<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AN ECHO FROM '98 IS HEARD IN ATLANTA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to rewrite throughout)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Scott Brosius follows form, the Atlanta Braves
better beware on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, the most valuable player in last year's World Series,
stroked three singles Saturday night, including one that ignited
the four-run rally in the eighth inning that propelled the Yankees
past the Atlanta Braves, 4-1, in Game 1 of this year's World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely hero rapped three singles in Game 2 of last year's
World Series against San Diego, then crushed the Padres in the
third game by lashing two home runs in successive innings and
turning a 3-0 deficit into a 5-4 Yankees victory. The Braves
wouldn't want to see Brosius perform in a similar manner against
them in the second game, then have to go to New York down, two
games to none.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Braves won the first two games in New York and went
home up by two games to none, but didn't win another game. It would
be too much for them to hope for an exact reversal of that World
Series this time, especially with Brosius in the batter's box
against them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the unassuming third baseman play a pivotal role in
the victories in the second and third games last year, but he also
singled home the second run in the 3-0 victory that completed the
four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   His World Series performance capped a terrific post-season for
Brosius. He batted .383 and hit four home runs in the three series
the Yankees won. He did not start out this post-season as well. He
had only 1 hit in 10 at-bats in the division series against Texas,
then had 4 hits in 18 at-bats against Boston, though half the hits
were home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the World Series began, Brosius was back on beam.
He led off the third inning tonight with a single to right field,
singled to center with two out in the fifth and opened the eighth
with yet another single, this one to left. At that point the
Yankees had four hits against Greg Maddux and Brosius had three of
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, on the other hand, had only one hit against Orlando
Hernandez, who continued his own dazzling post-season performance.
El Duque entered the game with a 4-0 record and a 0.97 earned run
average in five starts this year and last. The hit was a Chipper
Jones home run in the fourth inning, his first home run in a month,
since he destroyed the Mets in a three-game series here.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves were able to do nothing else with Hernandez. He
struck out the side in the first inning, and he struck out the side
in the third. He added four other strikeouts in his seven innings
of work, getting Gerald Williams and Bret Boone, the first two
batters in the Braves' lineup, in each of their first two times at
bat. He also struck out Eddie Perez twice.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was the Braves' leading hitter against the Mets in the
National League Championship Series, amassing 10 hits in 20
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had batted 59 times without a home run in 19 games
since his four-homer flurry against the Mets last month, did not
perturb Hernandez with his fourth-inning towering fly ball into the
right-field stands. Hernandez retired the next two batters, ending
the inning, then set down the Braves in order in the fifth and
sixth innings. He wisely walked Jones as the leadoff batter in the
seventh, then got Brian Jordan and Ryan Klesko on infield pops.
With Andruw Jones at bat, Chipper tried to steal second and was
thrown out, ending that inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius then led off the eighth inning with his third single. It
was Hernandez's turn to bat, but Manager Joe Torre decided this was
not the time for another sacrifice bunt. Hernandez had executed a
perfect bunt for a sacrifice in the third inning, putting his
countryman Rey Ordonez to shame.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez bunted five times in the Mets' series against the Braves
and popped up four times.
</P>
<P>
   Here was an American League pitcher who virtually never bats,
and he bunts the first pitch he sees for a sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had a different idea in the eighth, though. He sent up
Darryl Strawberry to bat for Hernandez and the Braves deployed an
exaggerated shift against him. The Braves had three infielders
between first and second for the left-handed batter and had Chipper
Jones playing at the regular shortstop position, though even he was
shaded toward second.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' strategy didn't work, though, because Maddux walked
him. Torre's strategy worked because the Yankees went on to score
four runs in the inning. Brosius scored the first on a single by
Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez pitched no more, but he ended the evening with his
fifth post-season victory against no defeats and a 1.02 earned run
average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
