<HEADLINE>
HEY, PAUL, TAKE ONE FOR THE TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Trojans can't hold 21-point leads and they
continue to take penalties at the darndest times. But we'll say
this for coach Paul Hackett; there's one area in which he has the
USC players impeccably schooled.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to a question of accountability, his athletes and
assistants don't cower. When the sword is presented to them, they
dutifully fall on it.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at the Coliseum, everybody from offensive
coordinator Hue Jackson to first-year linebacker Markus Steele bore
the humiliation for the Trojans' second disheartening
come-from-way-ahead loss in as many weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They all proclaimed themselves responsible for the Trojans'
35-31 loss to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   They all waded into the quicksand of culpability.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, that is, except for Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, inexcusably, the second-year Trojans head coach
had to be prodded into offering the weakest of branches to his
sinking players.
</P>
<P>
   While quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst, running back Chad Morton
and the entire special-teams unit but especially placekicker David
Newbury were in the locker room struggling to keep their chins up,
Hackett was in a nearby interview area saying, ``When you fumble on
(Stanford's) 5-yard line, shank punts, miss two field goals, that
hurts you. Those are momentum changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. But so is getting caught with 10 defensive players on
the field, a gaffe an observant Stanford offense exploited by
running Brian Allen through the hole where linebacker Sultan
Abdul-Malik should have been for a 13-yard gain on a drive that
begat seven points.
</P>
<P>
   So is getting caught with only six men on the line of scrimmage
on a down early in a series midway through the fourth quarter in a
situation that screamed ``MUST SCORE.''
</P>
<P>
   So is spending the 20-minute halftime devising ways to cork
Stanford's big-play offense and then watching the Cardinal offense
flow like champagne out of a bottle on the opening series of the
third quarter to pull within three points at 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   So is failing for two-and-a-half quarters to get a pass into the
hands of senior Windrell Hayes, who had caught two passes in each
of USC's first two possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is being paid handsomely to head off these kinds of
lapses, or at least treat them before they become a cancer that
kills a season.
</P>
<P>
   If professors of philosophy at USC are judged on how well their
students process the information fed to them, why should it be any
different for the resident professor of pigskin?
</P>
<P>
   After he stepped away from the cameras and the microphones and
the tape recorders, someone asked Hackett if his observation that
``we have to do some things better than we're doing them right
now,'' extended to the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said it did. When pressed, he prattled on about the
coaches needing to evaluate their preparation and improve the
efficiency with which they make substitutions and mete out
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Truer words were never spoken. The pity is he waited for an
audience of one to clear his throat and his conscience. If
Hackett's going to openly question the leadership of the seniors _
whom he conveniently didn't happen to recruit _ and not-so-subtly
point out the mistakes of specific players in public, why is it he
must be prodded before poking a finger at himself?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's your perception,'' Hackett said, spitting out his
words. ``You will say whatever you want to write, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   He then disappeared into the coaches' room, safely out of reach
of any more blitzing reporters.
</P>
<P>
   If only Hackett were a stand-up guy, we wouldn't have to chase
after him.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it would be hard not to feel a pang of sympathy if he
looked us straight in the eye, as did Jackson, and said, ``If
anybody should take the blame, it's me. I've got to get (USC's
offensive weapons) in better situations.''
</P>
<P>
   We'd be more inclined to cut Hackett some slack if he didn't act
like there was nothing left for him to know when it comes to X's
and O's. Asked if he considered utilizing Van Raaphorst out of the
shotgun formation to counteract the Cardinal's all-out ballfield
blitzing, Hackett curtly replied, ``We don't use the shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Next question?
</P>
<P>
   He talks about his players not all being on the same page, but
sometimes it seems Hackett is the one who is confused. He couldn't
explain why Hayes had four catches after 10 minutes and none for he
next 41. Hackett said Hayes fatigued but Hayes said he was
``perfectly fine'' and that he was getting open in the second and
third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' Hayes said plaintively.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: The man in the USC T-shirt who was
screaming expletives at the Trojan players as they trudged toward
the tunnel after the game was out of line.
</P>
<P>
   Any damnation of the USC football players ought to be directed
at Hackett. For better or for worse, it's his team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
