<HEADLINE>
SOWARD INJURY CAPS BAD DAY FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He wasn't included in the postgame report, but USC
wide receiver R. Jay Soward might have suffered the most
troublesome injury against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Soward strained his left hamstring early in the fourth quarter
and wasn't sure how serious it was after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I stand up and move, it hurts really bad,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would play next week, Soward said: ``We'll see. You
don't really know how it is until the next day. Right now, I'm
still on adrenalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Markus Steele sprained his left ankle but said he
would be OK, although he required crutches. Offensive lineman
Faasea Mailo badly bruised his right shin and was X-rayed, but no
damage was detected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's broken. I'm really fortunate,'' Mailo said. ``The
thing went numb on me. It's pretty painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Near goat: Stanford coach Tyrone Willingham almost looked silly
in the fourth quarter, when he decided to go for it on fourth-and-1
at his own 45.
</P>
<P>
   USC linebacker Zeke Moreno stuffed quarterback Todd Husak for no
gain and the Trojans took over with 2:08 left. Fortunately for
Willingham, USC failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought process was that if we could get one inch, we
could win the game,'' Willingham said. ``Was there risk? No
question. But we waived the risk. It wasn't about punting.''
</P>
<P>
   Star-crossed game: USC cornerback Antuan Simmons was everywhere
Saturday _ for better or worse. Simmons had two interceptions,
forced a fumble and recovered a fumble against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   He also had 15-yard personal foul and a defensive holding on
third down that gave Stanford a first-and-goal at the 2.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons' second interception was highly dubious, as replays
indicated he did not have control of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Record reception: USC wide receiver Kareem Kelly already owned
the freshman mark for most receptions in a season, and claimed the
freshman record for most yardage against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   He now has 632 yards receiving, which breaks R. Jay Soward's
freshman record of 507. Kelly has three 100-yard receiving games
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Local visitors: Chatsworth quarterback Matt Cassel and his
little brother, Justin, attended the game. So did Taft tight end
Gregg Guenther. Cassel and Guenther have already committed to the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Longest play: USC wide receivers Marcell Allmond and Soward each
had 64-yard touchdown receptions. Ironically, those are the
Trojans' longest plays from scrimmage this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
