<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-CATCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHERS: SIBLINGS, WITHOUT THE RIVALRY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The lockers in Fenway Park are a No. 2 pencil or two
wider than those found in most high schools, and after the Yankees
edged the Red Sox in Game 4 and took a commanding lead in the
series, the catchers Joe Girardi and Jorge Posada were crammed
together at their lockers, side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi played that night in Boston, as he has played most
nights in the post-season, vaulting over Posada for the majority of
the action; Girardi knew Posada was greatly disappointed about
this. Six years older than Posada, his crew cut speckled gray,
Girardi turned to Posada and spoke of Game 5, when Orlando
Hernandez would pitch and Posada would catch, just as happened
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be great, Jorge,'' Girardi said. ``I know you
didn't get to play as much as you wanted, but you're going to get a
chance to close it out and be the one who jumps into the arms of
the pitcher. I'm really happy that it worked out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   They are like siblings, except that they don't fight like most
brothers. ``I love working with Jorge, love working together, just
trying to improve and push each other,'' said Girardi. ``We want
the best for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   When Posada arrived in the big leagues for good, in the 1997
season, Girardi was the No. 1 catcher, Posada the heir apparent.
Girardi knew that Posada would eventually take over the majority of
the playing time in the regular season. Rather than resent Posada,
Girardi embraced him. Girardi has a belief _ seemingly out of date
in this era _ that he has a responsibility to do whatever he can to
help the team succeed, even if it means helping the guy who is
taking his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``No catcher could come to the big leagues could be treated any
better than Posada,'' said Don Zimmer, the bench coach. ``But
that's Joe Girardi; that's his style. Joe has done everything he
could to make the other guy better.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada deeply appreciates how helpful Girardi has been, and
cares a great deal about Girardi; he does not resent Girardi's
presence. Posada does have feelings, independent of Girardi, that
his own development was damaged because he was unable to become a
full-fledged front-line catcher this year.
</P>
<P>
   Posada recalled the final weekend of the regular season. ``You
come to the park and you're not playing and you sit down,'' he
said. ``After playing a couple of days, you sit down for two, three
or four days. When you get back in the lineup, you want to do so
well when you do play _ you're not relaxed. You're not doing what
you're supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurts when you go 0 for 4, and the next day, you're not
playing. A lot of negative things go through your head. You've got
a blurry situation and you don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada had a horrible start, a time when Manager Joe Torre was
recuperating from prostate cancer surgery and Zimmer was running
the club. Posada hit .210 in the first half of the season,
accumulating the bulk of his 17 passed balls in 1999 _ more than 24
of the 30 teams in Major League Baseball _ and had his eyesight
tested in June as a result. After spending the All-Star break
talking with his father and then seeing ultrasound pictures of his
unborn son, Posada relaxed and played better in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy coming into spring training,'' he said. ``I
had a lot of expectations, good things going in my head. And it
didn't turn out that way. I had two tough months, offensively and
defensively, and I had a lot of negative things going through my
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to put that aside. When Joe Torre came back, there was a
lot of relief. We talked a lot; nothing against Zim, but I didn't
know how to approach Zim. I always talked to Torre, and I didn't
know how to talk to Zim. When Torre came back, I started playing
like I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi was prepared to play elsewhere this season. General
Manager Brian Cashman informed Girardi that the Yankees would not
exercise their $3.4-million option for the 1999 season, and Girardi
was curious about playing elsewhere. He had grown up in Peoria,
Ill., attended Northwestern, broken into the big leagues with the
Cubs; word was the Cubs were interested in signing him. The Detroit
Tigers and Baltimore Orioles also intended to bid on Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   But in the hours before Girardi would become a free agent, Torre
persuaded George Steinbrenner to retain Girardi for one more
season. That ended any chance that Posada would develop into a
full-time catcher this year. Posada started 85 games at catcher in
1998, 98 in 1999; most everyday catchers work 125 to 130 games.
</P>
<P>
   There has been disagreement within the Yankees' organization
whether Posada's development should have been accelerated, whether
he should have caught more games and assumed more responsibility.
Some club executives maintained that Posada should have been given
a larger share of the playing time, while Torre continues to lean
on Girardi. Torre knows first-hand how pitchers prefer Girardi for
his experience, and he knows that a contented pitcher is more
likely to win.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's post-season, Posada teamed with Hernandez and
David Wells, while Girardi worked with Andy Pettitte and David
Cone. The playing time was split, Girardi starting six of the 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Girardi is teaming with Pettitte, Cone and Roger
Clemens, Posada with Hernandez. Girardi has caught five playoff
games, Posada three, and Girardi is scheduled to catch five of the
seven games in the World Series although Saturday night it was
Posada, going 0 for 4 with Hernandez starting.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi doesn't believe Posada's development has been damaged
because of Torre's reliance on both. ``I think he's been part of
something more important than playing every day,'' said Girardi.
``Playing 60 percent of the time and learning how to win and
playing important games can be just as important as playing 80
percent of the games. In the long run, it's more rewarding. He's
got another seven or eight years to play every day. What he's been
able to go through the last three years has been worth a ton of
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The path is clear for Posada to become the Yankees' No. 1,
full-time catcher next season, for at least one year. Posada will
be eligible for arbitration, and even with his diminished offensive
numbers, he remains a relatively low-cost commodity. But he will
have to establish himself once and for all in the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi is almost certainly going to play elsewhere next year;
the idea of playing every day intrigues him. The Cubs again are
said to be interested in signing Girardi, and he and Kim Girardi,
his wife, gave birth to a girl in September and recently built a
new home in the Chicago area. ``You go home and you weigh your
options and you do what's best for your family,'' said Girardi.
``Obviously, our family has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, will the relationship between the Yankees' catching
brethren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
