<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TRY TO RECOVER FROM LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The yelling was over by Saturday, but the work had
just begun.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 12 hours after the Kings' most embarrassing loss of
the young season, coach Andy Murray and his staff assembled the
club at Iceoplex to address tonight's opponent San Jose and
remember the mistakes against Phoenix on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who benched the first two lines for the final six
minutes of the 6-3 loss, had a one-hour meeting to remind the team
that its lack of effort was not acceptable. Murray then held an
exhausting 90-minute practice that included work behind both nets,
clearing pucks on defense and setting up scoring chances on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly the practice was about mental preparation. The Kings
had a 3-1 lead in the second period with a power-play opportunity.
But the Coyotes scored short-handed, the first of five consecutive
goals that included scores just 10 seconds apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were embarrassed,'' said benched winger Luc Robitaille, who
has not had a goal in four games after getting seven in the first
week. ``One thing that is very important to an NHL player is his
pride. We were hurt by the way we played and that is one thing we
have to change. We are much better than we showed last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who blasted his team after Friday's game, was a little
more subdued Saturday. A little. After discussing San Jose, which
has the most points in the league, Murray flipped over the
blackboard that still had the names of the Phoenix players from the
night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them if they really think the Coyotes are that strong
and that we are that weak,'' Murray said. ``I wanted them to look
at those names. We have a good team, but that effort was
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making major lineup changes, Murray is keeping the
group intact. Goalie Stephane Fiset, who by his own account let in
three bad goals, will be back for his 10th start in 11 games. Jamie
Storr, who started the only other game but left after one period
with a sore groin, will start Tuesday against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He let in some bad goals, but the team really let him down,''
Murray said. ``He has played very well this year and picked us up
many times when we needed a lift. Last night he needed to be picked
up and we just left him out there to get beaten up. I think you
just put him back there to show him it wasn't his fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said it was scary to think where the Kings might have
been without the production of their third line. Ian Laperriere
scored his first two goals of the season. Rookie Brad Chartrand did
an outstanding job tailing Keith Tkachuk until the Phoenix captain
scored a power-play goal at 13:49 of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who entered the game with the league's top power
play, went 1 for 4 with the man advantage. Ziggy Palffy scored with
17 seconds remaining in the first period, but it was his only shot
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the first line, we understand how important it is to set
the tone for the rest of the team,'' Robitaille said. ``We let down
and we know it. I've been benched before. But the message has
gotten through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
