A6625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     10-24 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EL DUQUE PROVIDES NEW WORLD SERIES MEMORIES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for rewrite throughout)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz still recalls the acrid smell of burning
automobiles. Jim Leyritz still tries to will Carlton Fisk's fly
ball foul. Kevin McGlinchy still shudders at the televised horror
of Mookie's grounder going under Buckner's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the World Series memories drive athletic little boys to
become major leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series is different. The 50 Braves and Yankees who
began the 1999 World Series last night were united in knowing that
the baseball season shifts a mighty gear after the league
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest feats and shocks usually happen late in a World
Series, but Saturday night's opener saw terrific pitching by
Orlando Hernandez, the Yankee from Cuba. A stirring sight the
moment he began to jog in the outfield to warm up, arms punching
forward like a prizefighter doing road work, El Duque struck out 10
Braves in seven innings and gave up only a home run to Chipper
Jones as the Yanks beat the Braves, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but El Duque, who does not bat in league games
because of the designated hitter gimmick, even laid down a perfect
sacrifice bunt. If his countryman, Rey Ordonez of the Mets, could
bunt at all, there might have been a Subway Series after all.
</P>
<P>
   If this was not a classic game, it was surely a gripping start
to the latest World Series, not merely ``the finals.'' No matter
how much television people yammer about ``post-season records,'' it
is just a case of having too many computers for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   It is irrelevant if modern players approach the records of
Berra, Mantle, Ford and Gibson, who earned their World Series
statistics when there was no league series, just the best teams
from the American League and National League deciding it all.
Nowadays a batter, or even a relief pitcher, could play 19
post-season games in October. Somebody please tell the networks
they are comparing kumquats to persimmons.
</P>
<P>
   Even with league playoffs, the World Series brings back the
little boy in these grizzled professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, only a few minutes after the Mets had lost a
crushing 11-inning decision to the Braves, Turk Wendell from
Pittsfield, Mass., was asked if he had been looking forward to a
Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I'm a Red Sox fan, and I was hoping they'd get in,''
Wendell blurted out.
</P>
<P>
   And Wendell was not alone. Last week, shortly before the Red Sox
went to their preordained defeat to the Yankees, Glavine of the
Braves, but originally from Concord, Mass., said, ``Yeah, I still
keep an eye on the Red Sox. Obviously, the kid in me is happy for
the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players insist they gave away those childlike fantasies
when they began earning major league paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rooted for the Reds and the Yanks when I was a kid, but that
kind of dies out,'' said Walt Weiss of the Braves, who grew up just
north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is the romantic concept of the Red Sox, those doomed
regional heroes, that stays alive longest in the hearts of a few
ball players.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger, the Dartmouth graduate and the Braves'
left-handed reliever, still quivers at the recollection of a
certain home run by Bucky Dent of the Yankees in 1978, not in a
World Series but in a special playoff with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the East Coast rivalries are more intense,'' noted
Remlinger, who grew up around Plymouth, Mass. ``I remember crying,
`How can he do that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger added, ``The World Series is what all kids grew up
on,'' but he admitted that post-season plays like the fantastic
stop and throw home by Weiss to help the Braves beat the Astros, or
the two extra-inning thrillers with the Mets are as good as
baseball gets.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the World Series stands apart. John Smoltz, the
bearded sage from Warren, Mich., recalls his father taking him to
Tiger Stadium for the fifth game of the 1984 World Series. The
Tigers wrapped it up, but fans burned cars and menaced the
neighborhood on that long and ugly evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad showed me how people react to victory,'' Smoltz said
the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he still rooted for the Tigers, Smoltz seemed to fight
a very human inclination to say yes. What he said was, ``I still
root for the three other Detroit teams. And since I live here now,
I root for the three Atlanta teams, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, the prodigal Yankee, knew where his boyhood heart was:
``I grew up near Cincinnati,'' he said. ``I remember staying up
late in 1975 to watch the sixth game. I remember Fisk's home run. I
was very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   To some children in Atlanta, he is the latter-day version of
Carlton Fisk _ or even General Sherman _ for the way he torched the
Braves with his three-run game-tying homer in the fourth game of
the 1996 World Series. McGlinchy, the fine young Atlanta relief
pitcher from Walden, Mass., remembers 1986, when he stayed up late
on a Saturday night to watch their New England team put away the
Mets, only to have the awful event take place. As it happens,
McGlinchy was the pitcher when the Mets staged their comeback in
the stirring 15-inning game last Sunday in that very same Shea
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed like an inhumane stretch for a journalist to bring up
that linkage to McGlinchy. Besides, Mookie's moment happened in a
World Series game whereas McGlinchy's bad inning took place in a
championship series. The Red Sox never recovered whereas the Braves
have moved on to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody will make baseball history, wonderful or hideous, in
the next week or so. What happens now is a season unto itself. It
is the World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
