passing on.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was able to do the job because she was able to take people
just as they were,'' says Donna Moffa, who worked with Eloise at
Hospice. ``You have to have a very special heart to pull that off.
That was Eloise.''
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Erie, Pa., though her friends in Arizona knew
little about her young life, other than the jokes Eloise made about
being a ``wild child.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Miller was close to her. &QL; 
`NO ORDINARY PERSON'
</P>
<P>
   ``This was no ordinary person,'' she says. ``This was an angel.
I mean, yes, she was a mom and a wife and a friend and a nurse, but
she lived, spiritually, on a level above the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   When she met her husband, Ernesto, he spoke no English and
Eloise spoke no Spanish. They helped each other be come bilingual,
and she used the skill to translate for Hospice families who needed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She refused to turn off the beeper she carried,'' Connie
Miller says. `` `Someone might need me,' she'd say. And someone
always did.''
</P>
<P>
   Eloise had two boys, one 7 and one 13. She had a husband and a
career and a house and a life. A future.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do work in a profession like this, however, you learn
about ap preciating the present because you don't know what will
happen,'' Donna Moffa says.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone who works at Hospice, Moffa and Miller often are
told, ``I could never do what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something people always say,'' Moffa says, ``but the
truth is many of them could do it. This is really the most
wonderful job in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller adds, ``Once this becomes part of your life, once you've
been able to help one family, one person, if only for a little
while, it's as if you can't see yourself doing anything else. I
know that's how Eloise viewed it. I used to joke with her that our
work was like taking out an insurance policy for the next life.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 2 p.m. on Oct. 19, Eloise Delgado was headed east
on In terstate 10, on her way to visit a family in need. It was a
sunny day. Traffic was light. Near Milepost 119, close to the
Jackrabbit exit, something happened to one of the tires on her 1993
Chrysler. A blowout, perhaps. Or the tread simply came off.
</P>
<P>
   A work crew from a local prison was clearing trash along the
road and saw her lose control. The speed limit on that stretch of
highway is 75 mph. The Chrysler drifted into the wide trough of the
median and flipped twice. She died instantly.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service is scheduled for 3 p.m. today at New Life
Christian Community Church in Peoria.
</P>
<P>
   Eloise Delgado was 34. &QL; 
HELPING EACH OTHER
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, those of us who help others deal with such
things had to help one another,'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   Only, unlike the usual Hospice case, there was no time to
prepare for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it a lot tougher,'' says Susan Goldwater, Hospice's
executive director. ``Most of us will die as the re sult of some
illness extending over a long period of time. In this case, there
was no time to come to grips with it. That can be very difficult to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   More than once over the years, Eloise told Miller that,
spiritually, she was pre pared for death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like she wanted it, because she had such a great
family, but she be lieved everyone should be prepared,'' Miller
says. ``Eloise was. Like I said, she was an angel on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tough job. And after reaching the highest level of
celestial efficiency a human can hope to achieve, she got pro
moted. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
