<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPE BACTERIA SPELL DOOM FOR FIRE SPRINKLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - What started five years ago as just a little drip in
the Tempe computer center of a major corporation has grown to a
flood of nationwide concern that fire-sprinkler systems are at risk
of being ruined by bacteria found in drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The pinhole-size leak discovered in May 1994 was one of many
that began turning up in overhead sprinkler pipes at the hub for
worldwide computer operations of AlliedSignal Inc., one of
Arizona's largest private employers.
</P>
<P>
   Colonies of industrious bacteria, generally categorized as
biofilms for the slimy shields they create to protect themselves,
had anchored along the pipe walls and, although not literally
eating the metal, were causing rapid decay.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is an ages-old affliction of countless water, gas,
petroleum and industrial pipe systems, but it hadn't been given
much attention in fire-safety systems until AlliedSignal pursued
the issue _ and an estimated $25 million in replacement costs _ in
federal court lawsuits blaming Phoenix and Tempe, its water
providers.
</P>
<P>
   That sent the nation's fire-safety industry, water utilities,
property insurers, scientists, lawyers and building owners
scrambling to examine sprinkler pipes as never before.
</P>
<P>
   What they have found in some cases is cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Bacterial corrosion of sprinkler pipes, often mild but sometimes
clogging an entire system, is ``very widespread and a very serious
problem,'' said Daniel Pope, whose consulting firm diagnosed the
problem for AlliedSignal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have fire-protection systems designed for 50 to 75 years
of service that in some cases are failing within months of
installation,'' said Pope, a former Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute microbiology professor who named the pipe-destroying
phenomenon MIC, for microbiologically influenced corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the problem is ``potentially life-threatening''
for anyone who relies on fire sprinklers to work flawlessly, Pope
said from his Bioindustrial Technologies Inc. office near Durango,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   When an electrical fire broke out last year in an Iowa nursing
home, the sprinkler system activated properly, but delivered no
water because every sprinkler head was plugged tight by MIC.
Patients were narrowly evacuated without injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have yet to lose a life to MIC,'' said Tariq Bsharat, the
top technical expert for the National Fire Sprinkler Association,
based in Patterson, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The odds against keeping that record intact are worsening daily.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a Phoenix corporation that specializes in cleaning
MIC-riddled pipes found that the fire-protection system of a
suburban Chicago bank was so corroded that it, too, would have
failed in an emergency, said Steven Carl, chief executive of
H.E.R.C. Products Inc.
</P>
<P>
   There was one startling difference from the nursing-home case,
though. In Iowa, the pipes had been installed for about 25 years;
the Chicago system was only 2{ years old, Carl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd bet the sprinklers in nearby hotels wouldn't work,
either,'' he said, observing that MIC often shows up in clusters of
buildings served along the same branches of water mains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at pipes from all over the country, and it's
happening everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Among jobs his company has handled with its patented cleaning
equipment and processes were 10-year-old sprinkler pipes that were
60 percent blocked at McCarran International Airport in Las Vegas,
and less-severe corrosion in one of AlliedSignal's more than 100
buildings near Sky Harbor International Airport in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The problem affects pipes of virtually any composition and is
found with regularity in water mains across the country. But MIC is
only one of many forms of corrosion, experts stress, and it often
is seen only in small concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix and Tempe officials firmly deny there is anything
defective about the cities' water. They point out that it complies
with regulations of the federal Safe Drinking Water Act, and argue
that even if it does contain pipe-corroding bacteria, there's no
way to safely and economically purify water to the degree
AlliedSignal seems to be demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the water systems must meet standards for anything
other than the health of the people who drink it is just a creation
of someone's imagination,'' Tempe City Attorney C. Brad Woodford
said.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal's lawsuits were ``the event that started shining a
light on the whole subject of MIC and sprinkler systems,'' said
professional engineer Roland Huggins, the top technical expert for
the Dallas-based American Fire Sprinkler Association.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins this month headed the first meeting of a
multidisciplinary task force looking for solutions to guide the
National Fire Protection Association in revising fire-sprinkler
standards that are followed nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco lawyer Peter Modlin, aiding in Phoenix's defense,
has argued in court that the litigation amounts to a demand by
AlliedSignal for the city ``to redesign its entire public water
disinfection program.''
</P>
<P>
   Several scientists and engineers agree that water utilities
ultimately may have to resort to costlier treatments and closer
monitoring because simply adding more chlorine creates byproducts
that cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the outcome of the lawsuits, water suppliers
everywhere could be subjected to similar litigation, the costs of
which would largely be borne by taxpayers and ratepayers, lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire-protection pipes are especially vulnerable to rapid growth
of corrosive bacteria because water sits stagnant in them for long
periods, usually at room temperatures highly conducive to
propagation.
</P>
<P>
   The MIC phenomenon could be widespread in the Phoenix area.
Pope's firm, which conducted numerous pipe inspections and water
tests at AlliedSignal installations in Tempe and Phoenix, said
evidence of MIC also showed up among the few samples taken for
comparison at an Intel building in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suggests that corrosion problems due to deposit formation
and MIC may occur in facilities throughout the Phoenix area
regardless of municipal water supply,'' the company reported. &QL; 
Although fire-sprinkler systems use drinking water, they do not
allow it to flow back into the supply pipes. Even severe outbreaks
of bacterial growth in sprinkler pipes will not contaminate the
rest of a building's water supply.
</P>
<P>
   MIC researchers and water-supply experts emphasize that any
water system is bound to contain a variety of microbes, but there
is no evidence that corrosion-causing bacteria are a direct threat
to human health.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not that type of organisms,'' said Charlotte Smith, an
Orinda, Calif.-based consultant to municipal water systems
nationwide and the head of a committee of the American Water Works
Association.
</P>
<P>
   A possible indirect danger, however, is that the MIC colonies
might provide safe harbor for human disease agents, said Anne
Camper, a researcher at the Center for Biofilm Engineering at
Montana State University in Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   Camper said the protective layer of slime made by biofilms could
shield other organisms because, in the words of Bill Costerton,
director of the National Science Foundation-supported center, the
membrane is ``phenomenally resistant to anti-bacterial agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ridges of corrosion also can create pockets that
chlorine has a hard time reaching, cities' regular testing of water
quality detects that problem, according to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   As MIC causes millions of dollars of damage to fire-sprinkler
systems across the country, methods of preventing or removing it
are both costly and relatively new.
</P>
<P>
   Once a colony establishes itself, treating the water won't
eliminate the bacteria, consultant Pope said. The pipes must be
cleaned, then refilled with disinfected water.
</P>
<P>
   One defense he recommends is to install an independent treatment
system to ensure that all water entering pipes is free of MIC
bacteria and as devoid as possible of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most common forms of MIC turns up when a small amount
of water is run into the system during quarterly testing and the
existing water runs dark and smells like rotten eggs. That hydrogen
sulfide odor is the product of sulfate-reducing bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   System experts say that draining and refilling pipes, often
necessary each time sections are replaced, likely compounds the
problem by providing fresh nutrients, a new oxygen supply and more
bacteria to already entrenched colonies.
</P>
<P>
   The prevalence of MIC is not disputed by sprinkler contractors'
trade groups, ``but the question is: `How often does it become
severe?','' said Bsharat, the expert for the national association.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of members 18 months ago turned up about 30 cases, he
said, and only a handful of new reports have come in since.
</P>
<P>
   Bsharat and spokesmen for the insurance industry emphasized that
fire-sprinkler systems are overwhelmingly reliable and remain the
most effective means of fire protection.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, his counterpart at the American association, agreed,
but said little data exist on how prevalent the problem might be
because the industry was so late in identifying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all `in-house' in the past,'' Huggins said. ``When a
system got pinholes, the contractor would just change out that
piece of pipe without recognizing the source of the problem. It
would just continue to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipe manufacturers are considering protective coatings to keep
microbes from settling in, Bsharat said, but a Teflon-lined pipe is
expensive and plastic linings are easily scratched or gouged.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the vast property-insurance industry, which has the
broadest exposure to the risk of sprinkler failure, has intensified
its own research. Also, a number of industrial or professional
groups are performing tests, sponsoring research or conducting
seminars on the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which homeowners' fire sprinklers are jeopardized
is anyone's guess, industry experts said, considering that even
large commercial installations were blind to MIC until the past few
years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
