<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6665 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BOX-AYALA-CONDO-TEX     10-24 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-AYALA-CONDO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANTAMWEIGHT CHAMPION AYALA CRUISES PAST TOUGH FOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Paulie Ayala's first world title defense
will not be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting before his hometown fans and fighting against an
opponent who refused to surrender, Ayala scored a unanimous
12-round decision against Saohin Srithai Condo to retain his World
Boxing Association bantamweight title.
</P>
<P>
   In a fight that featured no knockdowns but left Ayala with a
huge mouse under his left eye and the knuckles on his left hand
swollen, Ayala put away the game No. 1-ranked contender from
Thailand last night at Will Rogers Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Oscar Perez of New York had Ayala the winner by 117-111
under the 10-point must system. Jack Woodruff of Dallas and James
Cole of Garland each had Ayala winning 118-110.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very tough fighter,'' said Ayala, who improved to
29-1 with 12 knockouts. ``Look at my left hand. He had a hard head,
a very durable cranium. And he was strong. He was trying to the
very end. But I've been working on my defense and was able to duck
and dodge most of his punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Condo, however, did manage to slip through to land what could
have been a telling punch in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me in the left eyeball with a punch, and it really
bothered me,'' Ayala said. ``Hey, he was the No. 1 contender, a
former kickboxer; that's as tough as they come, bone on bone. Now I
see why everybody was dodging him. I would, too, but it was a
mandatory fight. This fight proved a lot to me, and I'd like to
dedicate it to the people of Fort Worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala earned a career-best $120,000. Condo, who came in having
won 14 consecutive fights and 10 by knockout, earned $40,000.
Condo's record fell to 25-7 with 18 knockouts, and 0-1 in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger was extremely active in the first round, showing
plenty of movement. Ayala snapped off a jab and backed Condo into a
corner. Ayala fired off a combination and as he escaped, Condo
nearly fell. The action returned to the middle of the ring when
Condo shoved Ayala to the canvas. No knockdown was called, and
Condo got a warning from referee Rafael Ramos of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Condo began to flash his right in the second, trying to dictate
the pace with his jab. Condo scored with a short right uppercut
that pushed Ayala into the ropes. His confidence boosted, Condo
continued to press forward, working almost exclusively to the head.
The area below Ayala's left eye began to swell in the last 30
seconds of the round, which closed with the fighters exchanging at
close quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Condo landed a big, roundhouse right to drive Ayala back early
in the third, and Ayala responded with a straight left. The two
countered each other most of the round, before Condo landed his
first meaningful body shot with a right to the midsection. Condo
was attempting to work the body when he walked into a short right
and overhand left combination at the bell.
</P>
<P>
   Condo stuck a slapping jab in Ayala's face at the outset of the
fourth, before a right and left combination by Ayala backed Condo
up momentarily. Working off his jab, Ayala landed a pair of lefts
to the head, and opened up a small cut in the bridge of the nose,
near the left eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala got the crowd excited early in the fifth with a short
right and left to the face. It hardly slowed Condo, who held his
ground and tried to work the body. Condo's crouching style made it
difficult for Ayala to go under and work the body, but Condo was
showing less movement than in earlier rounds. Ayala again excited
the crowd with a left hook at the end of the round.
</P>
<P>
   Condo began to bleed from the right cheek early in the sixth,
and Ayala finally was able to land his left under the challenger's
crouch. After Ayala connected with a straight left, Condo walked
into a short Ayala left and then absorbed a straight left. Ayala
began to sharpshoot for Condo's head, which was a ready target.
</P>
<P>
   Condo looked refreshed at the outset of the seventh, and once
again began loading up with his right. He stalked Ayala into a
corner but couldn't connect with either hand. Back in the center of
the ring, the fighters exchanged blocked punches as Ayala looked to
score off the upper. Ayala backed Condo into a corner and began to
unload, landing a left hook that rocked Condo momentarily with
about 10 seconds left in the round.
</P>
<P>
   Condo again began the round with no fear, loading up the right.
A right-left-right stunned Condo, who slowed his forward progress.
Ayala landed a another short left to keep the challenger on his
heels. Ayala landed a short right to the chin off a break and came
back with a left hook. Ayala scored with a right hook and then dug
a double left into Condo's midsection. Condo's punches were now
becoming fewer and less powerful, and by the end of the round he
was pawing at Ayala.
</P>
<P>
   The pace slowed in the ninth, with Condo still in less of an
attack mode. Ayala's jab scored and slowed Condo enough for the
champion to again dig in a couple of lefts to the body. Condo came
back with his right, and initiated an exchange. A welt appeared on
Ayala's left forehead as the round closed.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala scored with a left hook to start the 10th, and later a
short right. Condo tried to set Ayala up for his big right by
flicking his jab, but Ayala closed the gap and pushed Condo against
the ropes. Ayala backed Condo into a corner and with the crowd
howling, tried to finish him. But Condo landed a crisp right to
escape. Ayala started to bleed out of the left nostril with 20
seconds left, but Condo could do no more damage.
</P>
<P>
   The pace slowed considerably at the start of the 11th, the first
of the so-called championship rounds. Condo's punches were now more
wide and wild, and Ayala landed a combination to the head. Condo's
lunging style was now punctuated more than ever, but still awkward
enough that Ayala found it difficult to score cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   Condo again came out with plenty of steam, lunging and trying to
land to open the 12th. Ayala stayed clear with good movement, and
was content to keep clear of the right. Condo connected with a
short right but couldn't land a follow up. Ayala jabbed to keep him
at bay and with 10 seconds left began raising his arms in apparent
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the judges made it official.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
