<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECONOMY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA AND THE NEW ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   playing with blocks, first-graders at a west Phoenix elementary
school are snapping shots of spheres and cubes with a digital
camera and printing them from the classroom computer.
</P>
<P>
   In south Phoenix, drivers pull out of Swift Transportation's
terminal with keyboards in the cab and global positioning systems
on the roof. They used to check in with the office from truck stop
pay phones.
</P>
<P>
   At DeVry Institute of Technology, 28-year-old Johnathan Dady
just sweated through another batch of final exams. He went back to
school for a bachelor's degree in engineering because mentoring
from his engineer dad and four years of Navy avionics training
weren't enough to snag the cutting-edge jobs he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   These are the faces of the New Economy. It's a jittery,
fast-paced world where the way we do things is changing
dramatically _ and constantly.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is the current surging through it all, but the
implications reach far beyond the halls of Intel, Microsoft and the
latest dot-com Internet wonders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a company that's still trying to run your business
the old way, you will be left behind and probably be inefficient,''
said Tom Rex, research director for Arizona State University's
Center for Business Research. ``If you're an individual, and you
think a high school diploma is enough with no special skills,
you're being left behind.'' &QL; 
GUIDE FOR ARIZONA
</P>
<P>
   To help Arizona prosper in this daunting new landscape, often
compared to the Industrial Revolution, ASU's Morrison Institute for
Public Policy today will release a New Economy guide for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It details the potential benefits of this evolving economic
world _ higher-paying jobs, rapid growth and better productivity.
</P>
<P>
   And it spells out possible negatives: a non-stop, roller-coaster
ride for workers and businesses and, perhaps most threatening, a
bigger pay gap between skilled and unskilled workers due to the
increasing emphasis on brains vs. brawn and services and offices
over farms and factories.
</P>
<P>
   The institute delved into the topic because the round-the-clock
and round-the-world competition the wired world brings affects
students and senior citizens, laborers and lawyers, big business
and small business, and high-tech and low-tech ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so pervasive,'' said Mary Jo Waits, acting director of
the Morrison Institute. ``To still think we're just talking about a
few sectors of the economy is crazy.'' &QL; 
WHERE ARIZONA STANDS
</P>
<P>
   The report focuses on the tenets of the new economy, rooted in
technology, knowledge, people and competition, and Arizona's
standing in each.
</P>
<P>
   The state ranks pretty high in certain high-tech jobs and use of
the Internet and other technology, and is near the top in
fast-growing companies' share of the job market. But the report
suggests there is much work to be done if Arizona is going to be a
star of this new age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a mixed picture,'' Waits said, adding that the state's
relatively high rankings in a couple of recent national surveys on
the New Economy are somewhat misleading. &QL; 
MAJOR WEAKNESSES
</P>
<P>
   Among the major weaknesses cited in the ASU report: Low
education levels and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's young adults, especially those who grew up here, are
less likely than their peers nationally to have either a high
school diploma or a bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   The state also falls behind in investing in students from
kindergarten through college. Arizona's per pupil spending on
elementary and secondary schools was more than 20 percent below the
national average in 1995-96 and hit a 10-year low that school year.
</P>
<P>
   Spending for higher education was more than 20 percent below the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   Schools also are lagging in technology upgrades, such as
classrooms wired for the Internet and technology training and
e-mail accounts for teachers. Arizona ranked eighth among 10
Western states in this category.
</P>
<P>
   Students without proper training, and the businesses counting on
them as future workers, are doomed to fail in the New Economy,
experts say. Even factory workers need to have computer, science
and math skills today.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, the technology was not that sophisticated,''
Rex said. ``You didn't really need to learn much more than how to
do that particular job.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Humble, the first-grade teacher using cones and cylinders
and digital cameras at Richard E. Miller Elementary School, said
she's already prepping her students for careers, something that
used to begin around sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the technology,'' she said. ``They're exposed to
it sooner, and it's everywhere in their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Humble recently asked her 27 students if they had computers at
home. Only three or four said no. Just a few years ago, barely half
would have said yes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like overnight, it seems,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up with the kids, Humble, who primarily used her home
computer for word processing, has taken technology classes offered
by the Washington Elementary School District and now teaches some
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep up with the current times,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Humble's district is at the forefront of technology, thanks to a
1996 bond election that included $30.8 million to outfit schools
and teachers with state-of-the-art equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow high-tech cluster.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Phoenix area has been billed as the ``Digital
Desert'' and the ``Silicon Desert,'' a sister to California's
successful ``Silicon Valley,'' it is no high-tech hub.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the large high-tech employers are concentrated in one
area, hardware manufacturing. Intel makes computer chips at its
Southeast Phoenix area plants, for example, while Motorola makes
cellular phones and satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only ``knowledge-based industry'' in which Arizona
ranks above the national average in terms of the area's share of
such jobs. In contrast, Minnesota is strong in three areas:
computer/electronics, health care technology and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't like we've got the research and development sites and
the brains of the high-tech companies locating in Arizona,'' Waits
said. ``We think we're doing better than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   If Arizona wants to attract a broader base of New Economy
industries, such as software and communications services or
innovation services, it's going to have to change its economic
development approach, the report suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Luring companies in the 21st century won't be just about tax
breaks, low costs and an area's place on a map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies must locate the brains of their business in a
location that will provide them with a critical mass of
competitors, suppliers and customers, a strong talent pool, unique
institutions and desirable quality of life,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the amenities that cutting-edge companies and their
employers are looking for: top-notch university research;
telecommunications infrastructure; and community meeting places
such as coffee bars, parks and recreation rooms.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses can't afford to sit still if they want to get ahead,
or at least keep pace, in the frenzied competition the New Economy
brings.
</P>
<P>
   Swift Transportation founder Jerry Moyes says his customers, for
example, want up-to-the-minute information on their shipments so
they can pinpoint delivery times and prepare for any delays. Swift
responded with a new Internet tracking system.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a progressive company growing at 20 to 25 percent a year,
we've got to keep on the edge of what's going on,'' Moyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Swift is an established, good-size company with a stellar
financial record and hasn't had any trouble raising money.
</P>
<P>
   But fledgling companies, those that need the money most to get
their ideas off the ground, struggle to find investors in the
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local investment dollars to really jump-start the couple
guys in a garage, that's what's fundamentally missing,'' said Drew
Cohen, chief executive officer of NeoPlanet, a rapidly growing
Internet software firm that moved to Phoenix from New York earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, whose investors came from outside the Phoenix area, said
it goes back to the lack of a hub of emerging companies and the
suppliers and services they bring. Venture capitalists like to be
close to companies they invest in so they can keep tabs on their
investments and help entrepreneurs run their business. It's not
worth the effort to set up shop if there aren't enough promising
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cohen is optimistic about Arizona's chances in the New
Economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the opportunity for Phoenix to be one of the lead
cities is there. That's why we came,'' Cohen said. ``It's just the
execution.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at (602) 444-8617 or
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
