<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANTAMWEIGHT CHAMPION AYALA CRUISES PAST TOUGH FOE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Condo crumbles. Film at 11.
</P>
<P>
   In front of an adoring, rapping hometown crowd, Paulie Ayala
flexed his championship belt last night.
</P>
<P>
   As is his custom, Ayala plied patience and footwork and, in the
end, solved the lunging thrusts of Saohin Srithai Condo, the
night's international man of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   It was a unanimous decision, not only in the eyes of the judges
but in the hearts of the chanting Will Rogers Coliseum crowd.
</P>
<P>
   For the first defense of his World Boxing Association
bantamweight crown, Ayala was faced with a foe whose very name was
a riddle as recent as two days ago. Upon his arrival from Thailand,
we learned that Condo was really Anupong Srisuk, and that he was
brandishing not only a tough right hand but the name of his
sponsoring real estate company. In Thailand, we were informed, they
do this.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. How would Mike ``Mary Kay'' Tyson sound?
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday or thereabouts, Condo had never been to the
United States. His boxing career, in fact, had spanned 31
professional bouts, 30 of which had been in downtown Bangkok. The
other was fought in Cambodia _ a mere bus ride, presumably.
</P>
<P>
   Without a scouting report, Ayala fought the smart fight. He
probed, he waited, he found his chance.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Paulie Ayala fan, you don't sit and wait for the
Sammy Sosa home-run blow. Ayala, though, seems confident enough in
his basic boxing skills that he refused to accept the invitation to
brawl that Condo extended to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Condo's style made heavy use of a reach advantage that seemed
larger than the listed inch and a half. But maybe that was because
he was usually stumbling forward, trying to rain lunging right
hands on Ayala's elusive chin.
</P>
<P>
   The chin was there. Somewhere. But Paulie seldom let Condo find
it.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy who had scored a loud upset to snatch the title four
months ago from Johnny Tapia, Ayala looked easily at ease wearing
the championship mantle. The hometown crowd couldn't have hurt, but
here was a champ who arrived with his act together.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear who was the star of this night, Fort Worth's first
boxing title bout in 10 years. On the undercard, junior
middleweight Curtis ``Bull'' Durham of Fort Worth had been a
favorite and fellow local Chris Naya had been resplendent with his
red and gold, full-tasseled sombrero. And Ruben Nevarez of Wichita
Falls had briefly stolen the show by taking the ring for his
lightweight bout while wearing Goofy on the front of his trunks.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Paulie's night. The tables in the lobby sold T-shirts
emblazoned with Ayala's picture. One spot invited people to visit
the Y2K-compliant Paulie _ his Web site at www.paulieayala.com.
</P>
<P>
   The riddle of the night, however, was Condo, or Srisuk, or
whatever the rankings wanted him called.
</P>
<P>
   From his traveling companions, we had learned that Condo had a
background in kick boxing, as many Thai boxers do. We were told
that he had a powerful right hand and would look for the knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other tourist in town, he is still looking. Paulie
isn't on the Mapsco.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Condo's lunging style left him vulnerable. A
more thunderous puncher might have finished him off in the
mid-rounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Ayala's style is more patient, more tactical. When he opened
a nick above Condo's right eye, Ayala was able to peck away for the
kill.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
