<SLUG> BC-GOODY-TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX REWORK OF `LIFE' NOT ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - They are the three words no one in television wants to
hear: 
``Rework the pilot.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some tinkering is to be expected with any pilot, which is, after
all, a one-time ep isode meant to sell a network (and advertis ers)
on a show. By the time the show actually winds up on the air, some
changes usually have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the character of the sister's boy friend needed to be
recast. Perhaps the pro ducers couldn't secure the rights to a
certain song and had to find another one. Or maybe the all-knowing
troll who lives in the basement and serves as a narrator was such a
bad idea that he needed to be cut from the show entirely.
</P>
<P>
   These things happen. But when a pilot that has been in the works
for a while has to be not just fine-tuned but re worked, it smells
like trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with Time of Your Life, the Jenni fer Love
Hewitt spinoff of Party of Five that premieres Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the first episode, a question arises: If this is
the new, improved version, how bad must the original have been?
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to executive producers Chris Keyser and Amy Lippman,
the Fox Net work decided to pair Life with Ally McBeal instead of
Party of Five, as was originally planned. That's good news, but it
meant re working the show to make it a better fit for the Monday
night lineup.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to people who like to watch television, they should
have made a better show.
</P>
<P>
   Life finds Hewitt's character, Sarah, leav ing Bailey and the
rest of the Party clan be hind in California and heading to New
York City in search of her birth father (she is adopted, and her
mother died a couple of years ago).
</P>
<P>
   Apparently meant to be a sort of valen tine to both Hewitt, who
is also a producer of the show, and NYC, Life instead comes off as
overly fanciful to the point of ridicu lousness. Sure,Rudy Giuliani
has famously cleaned up Times Square and forced New Yorkers to be
more polite, but the Big Ap ple of this show makes Mister Rogers'
Neighborhood look like a housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the producers have made things more realistic than
they originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original pilot is a little bit like a fable about this
city,'' Keyser said this sum mer. ``It has a little bit of a
fabulous tone to it, and we've pulled back on that slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Extremely slightly. Having seen the first episode, all I can
figure is that the original pilot, which wasn't made available to
crit ics, must have co-starred the Muppets. (The human Muppet,
Rosie O'Donnell, has a cameo in the reworked version.)
</P>
<P>
   Or doesn't everyone who shows up at a strange building at night
in the heart of the city without her baggage (lost, naturally) end
up finding a roommate and friend be fore the sun comes up? By the
time a cou ple of days have passed, Sarah has several friends, a
job and reason to stay in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a strange city,'' she says near the end of the
episode, ``with no money and no plan and no one I know and say,
`Bring it on, whatever it is, I'll handle it and I'll figure it out
as I go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, well, if everyone's New York experience worked out like
hers, who wouldn't want the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   Just when you think the plot can get no sappier, the situations
no more ridiculous, it happens _ they do. Do events conspire to
allow Hewitt, who has a lower-profile ca reer as a singer, to belt
out not one but two tunes? Of course they do.
</P>
<P>
   Are the songs really New York, New York and It's the End of the
World as We Know It, two songs whose telegraphed messages are so
obvious no one could miss their meaning? Of course they are.
</P>
<P>
   When she finally meets the man she believes is her father, is
the only place she can catch a quiet moment with him in the men's
room as he stands at a urinal? Of course it is.
</P>
<P>
   And so forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played her (Sarah) for a re ally, really long time and I
feel re ally close to her,'' Hewitt said. ``And it's going to be
kind of fun to see what new stuff she gets to expe rience and do,
and how she sort of grows up.''
</P>
<P>
   If Life's first episode is any indi cation, those experiences
will in volve a wicked witch and a yellow-brick road.
</P>
<P>
   Keyser and Lippman said all the right things to TV critics this
sum mer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a show in trouble does not get awarded the best time
slot on the schedule,'' Lippman said.
</P>
<P>
   True enough. Though the way Fox's new shows have performed so
far this season, ``best'' may be a relative term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else we can say,'' Keyser said of rumors of
prob lems with the show. ``I mean . . . in some ways this is sort
of an exam ple of, if you ask the question enough times, it becomes
true, you know what I mean? It doesn't mat ter what answer we give.
</P>
<P>
   ``So there's nothing else we can do except to say we love this,
we love the script, we love our cast, we'll show you the episode.
Watch it. If you think it's bad, you'll write that.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at
bill.goodykoontz &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6674 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-SERIES-HNS &LR;      10-24 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Turner Field was sold out for a second straight playoff
game Saturday, which should end the ongoing questions about why
Atlanta fans don't show up.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for a no-show count, check the Braves' bat
rack.
</P>
<P>
   The anemic offensive showing that epitomized their performance
in the National League Championship Series won't get it done
against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves mustered just two hits in a 4-1 loss to Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez and New York in Game 1 of the World Series. The
two hits were the fewest in a World Series game since the Braves
held Cleveland to one hit in Game 6 of the 1995 Series.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's run came on Chipper Jones' first home run in a month.
It seems like it has been at least that long since the Braves
showed any consistency at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues, the Yankees could put the Braves out of
their misery in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez tried to do it by himself Saturday, outdueling Greg
Maddux, who filled in for flu-stricken teammate Tom Glavine. Maddux
had reason to feel sick himself after his excellent performance was
wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stuff was all right,'' Maddux said. ``But it's not about
pitching good. It's about winning. I pitched just good enough to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-time Cy Young Award winner took a shutout to the eighth
but did not retire a batter in the inning and lost when the Yankees
scored four times to make a winner of Hernandez, who ran his career
postseason record to 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Hernandez should trade ``El Duque'' for ``Senor
Octubre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He continues to just make you shake your head,'' Yankees
manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   If Torre was shaking his head, Braves manager Bobby Cox was
ready to stick his head in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Cox has been praised during the postseason for his knack for
pushing all the right buttons. But there isn't much a manager can
do to jump-start an offense when nobody can get on.
</P>
<P>
   Only six Braves reached base Saturday, and Jones was the only
one who advanced beyond first base until the Braves brought the
tying run to the plate against closer Mariano Rivera in the ninth.
Bret Boone's one-out single off Rivera, after a walk, was the
Braves' only other hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our club and the pitching we have, you always have a shot
to make a one-run lead hold up,'' Braves shortstop Walt Weiss said.
``But when you only have one hit going into the ninth inning,
you're very seldom going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves might as well have been playing Twister in the early
going. They could not have been more off balance than they looked
against Hernandez, who struck out eight of the first 11 batters he
faced and had 10 strikeouts in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, Braves hitters seemed to have trouble picking up the
ball out of Hernandez's high leg kick until Jones' homer in the
fourth inning ended early thoughts of a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no disrespect to the great pitcher that is Greg Maddux, I
knew one run wasn't going to win this game,'' Hernandez said
through an interpreter. ``Regardless of the situation, I had the
utmost faith that our team was going to come through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees ended Maddux's shutout bid when they loaded the
bases with no outs in the eighth _ using good hitting, a pitcher's
mistake and a defensive breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's single tied the game and ended Maddux's night, and
Paul O'Neill's two-run single off John Rocker through a drawn-in
infield put the Yankees on top. New York got an insurance run when
pinch hitter Jim Leyritz worked Rocker for a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have too many opportunities,'' O'Neill said.
``Lefthanders aren't going to make their living off Rocker. He's
too good, and he throws too hard. We got a break. I put the ball in
play, and it found a hole. Breaks are a part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the break goes their way, they turn two right there. But it
went our way and found a hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a few guys on, something can happen, and it did
tonight. The way our pitching has been all year, if we score a
couple of runs we're going to win. You can't say enough about what
Duque did.''
</P>
<P>
   The big inning was prolonged because of two errors by first
baseman Brian Hunter, who was sent in as a defensive replacement
for Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a first baseman had made two errors in the
same inning of a World Series game since Frank Torre _ Joe's older
brother _ did it in 1958 while playing for the Milwaukee Braves
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses,'' Hunter said. ``I just made two errors. You hate
to make errors any time, especially in a game like this. It makes
it even worse when you consider why I came into the game _ for
defense. I made myself look stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius' third straight hit opened the eighth, and Maddux
then suffered a rare lapse, walking pinch hitter Darryl Strawberry
and showing his frustration with a kick after ball four.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're in a close game and we get an opportunity, we know we
can win a game,'' said Strawberry. ``It's just about confidence.
We've got a very experienced ballclub, and we don't panic, and
that's a very big key for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch's bunt past Maddux was booted by Hunter to load
the bases. Jeter then singled between third and short, tying the
game and bringing on Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bases loaded and the 3-4-5 hitters coming up,'' Rocker
said. ``The odds weren't in my favor.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's hit between Hunter and Boone made it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't surprise us when we got a little crack,'' Joe Torre
said. ``We've been a very patient ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Jeff Nelson and Mike Stanton each retired one Brave in
the bottom of the eighth, and Rivera got the final four outs.
Rivera survived a two-on, one-out threat in the ninth by striking
out Brian Jordan on three pitches and getting pinch hitter Greg
Myers on a weak foul pop to Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   ``This loss will be really important if we don't win tomorrow,''
Hunter said. ``We have to leave home with a split.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
