<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CONTROL DRUGS: JUST SAY I DON'T KNOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States Olympic Committee has a drug problem. And it's
willing to pay through the nose, in a manner of speaking, to get
rid of it.
</P>
<P>
   At its board of directors meeting in Colorado Springs, Colo.,
this weekend, USOC officials debated a proposal that would, in
effect, get the organization out of the drug-testing business and
turn enforcement over to an independent agency.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the USOC would nearly double its funding _ from $12.6
million every four years to $24 million _ on behalf of drug-testing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing money at a festering problem is not a novel concept, of
course. Politicians try to do this all the time.
</P>
<P>
   What's hard to grasp in this case is whether the new plan is
rooted in sincere intentions, or it's the USOC's way of hoisting
the white flag.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Olympic world, you see, is convinced that we are
a nation of lawyers. In Johnnie Cochran Jr. we trust. Behind every
positive drug test by a U.S. athlete during the past 12 or so
years, the world is convinced, is an attorney with a briefcase full
of loopholes _ the sample was tampered with, the dog ate the result
sheets, etc.
</P>
<P>
   We are, after all, the land of the free. The words ``due
process,'' a sacred right in this country, don't translate well in
the power-is-power Olympic world.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, the responsibility for spot testing
Olympic athletes and enforcing those findings rests with the USOC
and the various national governing bodies.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture? Connect the dots.
</P>
<P>
   If, as an example, you're the head of U.S. badminton and a
badminton player tests positive for excess testosterone, this is
not good news. The incentive for impartial enforcement could be
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new plan, an independent, nonprofit organization would
take over all Olympic-related anti-doping matters in the United
States. The number of unannounced drug tests _ the only ones that
really work _ would increase from less than 1,000 to 4,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   The new group would forward all appeals to the Court of
Arbitration in Sport, a nonpartisan global panel that has the
blessing of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It could work. Until somebody sues the USOC for passing the buck
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is taking place in the same week when President
Clinton's drug czar, Gen. Barry McCaffrey, is chairing hearings on
Capitol Hill about the IOC's anti-doping plans. McCaffrey wants the
IOC's hands kept away from any new policies.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose, unfortunately, that it would be too late at this
point to ask the athletes to just say no. Let me naively offer the
viewpoint that most Olympic athletes don't use
performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But a lot of them always will. ``The Washington Post'' recently
ran a chilling story about Canadian runner Angella Issajenko, a
teammate of Ben Johnson at the 1988 Seoul Olympics. Now 40 and
coaching, Issajenko has admitted she took steroids and human growth
hormones and was never caught.
</P>
<P>
   She told a Canadian drug inquiry that she got the drugs from a
California doctor, Robert Kerr. The doctor says he gave
performance-enhancing drugs to 20 athletes who won medals at the
1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The most uncomfortable part of the Issajenko story is that she
doesn't think she did anything wrong. She claims that taking the
drugs ``in reasonable doses'' does not produce harmful side
effects. She sees them as an aid in training.
</P>
<P>
   Issajenko has four children, ranging in age from 6 to 13. Three
of them compete in track and are coached by Charlie Francis, the
same Charlie Francis who advised and coached Ben Johnson in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Spotlight on . . . Ice vice, arch acting and platform
sleepwalking
</P>
<P>
   It didn't make this week's episode of America's Funniest
Comebacks, but Tonya Harding returned to skating competition last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The belle of the 1994 Lillehammer Olympics finished second in
her first professional skating competition since the Nancy Kerrigan
kneecap incident that year. Before a crowd estimated at 3,000 in
Huntington, W.Va., Tonya nailed three triple jumps and dazzled the
judges with her free-skate routine.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, Harding wore a modest black-and-white
skating outfit, quite unlike the night in Lillehammer when she came
dressed as, well, Dance Hall Gal. Tonya, 28, blew kisses to the
Huntington crowd, bowed graciously and announced that she was
thrilled to finish in second place. (France's Surya Bonaly won.)
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the popularity meter, meanwhile, was Geena
Davis, aspiring archer. The Academy Award-winning actress was
invited by Australian officials to compete as a wild-card entry in
the Sydney Golden Arrow Tournament in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Davis apparently is serious enough about archery and good enough
that her participation at the U.S. Olympic Trials did not draw any
``Garth Brooks, third baseman'' comparisons. Despite being
relatively new to the sport, Davis reached the Trials semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   She won't make the Olympics this time, but give the U.S. archery
federation credit for knowing a publicity bonanza when it arrives
at its doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   The third female in the Olympic news is Houston native Tracy
Bonner, a diver who has been reinstated by FINA, the world aquatic
federation, after testing positive for a banned substance.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner, 26, is considered an odds-on choice to make the U.S.
Olympic team for Sydney in the new medal sport of synchronized
diving. She and partner Kathy Pesek are three-time gold-medal
winners in the U.S. championships.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner's suspension was lifted after the Court of Arbitration in
Sport ruled that the banned substance was prescribed medication
that Bonner took to combat narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   (Fill in your own joke about divers with narcolepsy here.)
</P>
<P>
   Quick Hits Trials rescheduled The dates of the U.S. Olympic
Triathlon Trials have been changed to May 27-28 at Las Colinas in
Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Locke, the savvy executive director of USA Triathlon, made
the announcement, explaining that the original dates (May 20-21)
conflicted with the Colonial golf tournament in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Triathlon makes its Olympic debut in Sydney. The triathletes
will swim 1,500 meters, ride bicycles for 40 kilometers (24.8
miles) then run 10 kilometers (6.2 miles). Texan sailing Paul
Foerster of Garland will be sailing for a place on the Olympic team
in the 470 class when the U.S. Trials conclude today at St.
Petersburg Yacht Club in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Foerster is teamed with Bob Merrick of Portsmouth, R.I., and led
the Trials after four races. Foerster won a silver medal in the
Flying Dutchman class at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics. Hatchell
considered Steve Hatchell, former commissioner of the Big 12
Conference, is among those being considered for the new position of
Chief Executive Officer of the U.S. Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The new title came about after the USOC underwent a detailed
review of its organizational structure. Departing executive
director Dick Schultz elected not to be a candidate for the
position.
</P>
<P>
   Hatchell reportedly has been prominently recommended to the
executive search firm of SpencerStuart. Super cycling The
Superdrome in Frisco has quickly gained a reputation as one of the
best venues in track cycling.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Trials are scheduled there April 25-29. Johnson
relaxes Baylor ex Michael Johnson says the pressure is off now that
he has added the world 400-meter record to his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I can go to Sydney and just concentrate on winning,''
Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   Some interesting flotsam from ``Track and Field News'', the
sport's bible, comes in the wake of Johnson's historic run Aug. 26
in Seville, Spain:
</P>
<P>
   Johnson ran the first 200 meters of the race in 21.3 seconds, an
amazing figure considering that he knew he had 200 more meters to
run. His 200-meter world record is 19.32. Johnson joins Tommie
Smith, Poland's Irena Szewinska and East Germany's Marita Koch as
the only ones to hold the 200 and 400 world records at the same
time. FYI The people who answer the phones in the sports department
would probably like you to clip this and keep it handy:
</P>
<P>
   Dates for the Sydney Olympics _ Sept. 15-Oct. 1, 2000
</P>
<P>
   Sports: 28 (and ballroom dancing is not one of them)
</P>
<P>
   To contact the Sydney Games, write:
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games
</P>
<P>
   GPO Box 2000
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, NSW 2001 Australia
</P>
<P>
   Phone: 011-612-9297-2000
</P>
<P>
   Fax: 011-612-9297-2020
</P>
<P>
   Web address: www.sydney.olympic.org
</P>
</TEXT>
