<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC WASTES ANOTHER BIG LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At least USC has made progress. The Trojans needed
just more than one quarter to blow a 21-point lead Saturday. Last
week, it took a full two.
</P>
<P>
   In this quickly disintegrating season, that's known as a baby
step ... backward.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it would be classified as just another mind-boggling
letdown, as Stanford overcame a three-touchdown deficit to defeat
the Trojans 35-31 in front of 57,494 at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be easy blowing a big lead. But it's even harder
explaining it _ especially on back-to-back weekends. So the Trojans
turned to a higher authority to interpret the latest debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it's out of our hands,'' USC free safety David
Gibson said. ``Someone is glancing down on us. Maybe it's payback
for the '70s. Someone is mad at us upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver R. Jay Soward concurred: ``It just seemed like
some force of nature was saying we will not win no matter how many
points we are up. It's a curse.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not really a hex that is causing USC to lose games, but
something more simple.
</P>
<P>
   Like the offense. And the defense. Plus the special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and it might even be the coaching, although players would
sooner blame the heavens than find that theory plausible.
</P>
<P>
   When you are under .500, things like luck and law of averages
don't really matter. The Trojans (3-4, 1-3) are simply not a very
good team right now. Honestly, they haven't been since they got
back from Hawaii after the season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our fault. Nobody's fault but the players,'' offensive
lineman Travis Claridge said. ``It's a tough feeling when you leave
everything on the field and it just wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost good enough, but not quite. That was the same feeling
last week against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, USC contributed heavily to its demise. It had some
pretty stats, like quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst's school-record
415-yards passing and tailback Chad Morton's 151 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   But underneath the surface, even those numbers were tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst threw three interceptions and had one returned 30
yards for a touchdown. He also fumbled in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Morton had the costliest turnover of the game. With USC leading
21-7 and facing a second-and-goal at the 10-yard line, he fumbled.
Stanford's Travis Pfeifer recovered at the 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't throw an interception for a touchdown, or fumble on
the 5-yard line,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``Right now, we
can't find the formula to pull us out of the funk we're in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting tired of these. There's not much to say.''
</P>
<P>
   This loss was a little different than the one at Notre Dame.
USC's defense wilted in South Bend because it was forced to be on
the field far too long.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense had no such excuse against the Cardinal. It
singlehandedly wasted the offense's 24 first-half points in about
2{ minutes.
</P>
<P>
   USC took a 24-7 lead with 1:39 remaining in the first half, but
the Cardinal needed just six plays to go 80 yards before
quarterback Todd Husak found DeRonnie Pitts on a 23-yard touchdown
pass to cut the lead to 24-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal (5-2, 5-0) required the first 72 seconds of the
second half to go another 80 yards, with Husak's 16-yard touchdown
pass to Dave Davis cutting the lead to 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   It was about this time that everyone started seeing visions of
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that creeps into your mind,'' Gibson admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, a clear favorite to make its first New Year's Day trip
to Pasadena since 1971, scored another touchdown and led 28-24.
</P>
<P>
   That's a 21-0 blitz, in case you had forgotten. The Trojans
briefly went ahead on Soward's 64-yard TD reception, but Stanford
came back to take a 35-31 lead when Husak scored on a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the play that typifies a bad team.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst found Soward wide-open for what would have been a
70-yard touchdown pass, but the ball bounced in and out and around
Soward's hands before he finally dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of season it is. I catch the ball, we win,''
Soward said. ``I take the loss. As a senior, I've got to take the
blame. I think I was too overzealous on the play.''
</P>
<P>
   USC made a vain effort to score at the end, but Van Raaphorst's
fourth-down pass was intercepted by Tim Smith at the 7-yard line as
time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're at a point where we don't know what's
wrong,'' said linebacker Zeke Moreno. ``I could never imagine this,
or thinking about this at the beginning of the season. I don't know
what we can do. Everything we've thought of we've tried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
