<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUMBLING BRUINS ROUTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ This summer, Oregon State replaced its aging
artificial turf with a new, $1.5 million carpet called AstroTurf
12/2000. It's bright green, it's thick and spongy, and it sits on
an inch of foam rubber.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, UCLA had a soft surface on which to bottom out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' Bruins receiver Freddie Mitchell said
after a 55-7 loss to Oregon State on Saturday in front of 33,427 at
Reser Stadium. ``I don't want to fly back to L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than embarrassing. It was the Bruins' worst defeat
in 69 years _ since a 52-0 loss to USC in 1930 _ and the most
points they've allowed since a 61-20 loss to Washington in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little lost for words,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most troubling for Toledo was the opponent. This wasn't
USC or Washington or even Michigan or Nebraska. This was Oregon
State _ !ital!last-place Oregon State.!off!
</P>
<P>
   On the surreal scale, this loss rivals UCLA's 66-3 victory over
Texas two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get beat like that, it makes you think we're sorry,''
Bruins tailback Keith Brown said. ``Oregon State wasn't supposed to
be a great team, but they were against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry? Perhaps. Desperate? Definitely. The Bruins (3-5, 1-4)
have lost four of their last five and must defeat Arizona,
Washington and USC to become bowl-eligible. To put that task in
perspective, consider that Washington defeated Oregon State 47-21
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season isn't over yet,'' Brown continued. ``The only time
it's over is when we can't go to a bowl game. As long as we still
have that, we still have a chance. If we lose again, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offense was as inept against Oregon State as it was last
week in a 17-0 loss to Cal. The Bruins could not run, could not
block and could not throw. They gained 10 yards in the first
quarter and 210 for the game. They averaged 2.5 yards per rush and
allowed seven sacks. Of their 15 possessions, seven gained zero or
negative yards; only two gained more than 30.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing to struggle against Cal, which has the
Pac-10's best defense. It's quite another to sputter against Oregon
State, which had allowed 30 points and 386 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's happened in the last two games,''
offensive coordinator Al Borges said. ``Our production is almost
zero. This is terrible. I have no explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   And after three credible performances, UCLA's defense regressed
to 1998 form. Oregon State's spread offense generated 559 total
yards and broke the game open with three touchdowns in 2:28 late in
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Most if the damage came on third down, when the Beavers
exploited UCLA's porous secondary and converted 8-of-9 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental errors killed us,'' UCLA safety Julius Williams said.
``They destroyed everything we tried to do. People were in thw
wrong places all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers led 7-0 late in the first quarter when they began to
take control. On third-and-8, quarterback Jonathan Smith hit
receiver Imani Percoats for 28 yards across the middle. Three plays
later, Smith found Roddy Tompkins for 23 yards, a touchdown and a
14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to take our shots downfield and spread them out to
get one-on-one matchups,'' Smith said. ``We had some success.''
</P>
<P>
   The first quarter ended with UCLA quarterback Cory Paus on the
bench with an injured left shoulder. Reserve Scott McEwan entered
the game and promptly threw an interception near midfield. The
Beavers needed nine plays to cover 39 yards and take a 21-0 lead.
The drive included _ what else? _ a 24-yard pass on third-and-12.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum appeared to shift with six minutes left in the
half, when Paus returned and directed an 80-yard touchdown drive _
UCLA's first in six quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that jump-started us,'' Toledo said. ``Then we
caved.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State regained control when reserve tailback Antonio
Battle charged around left end and raced 50 yards in nine seconds
for an uncontested touchdown. (Are there any other kind against
UCLA?)
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers followed with a seven-second touchdown. On first
down, Smith found Tompkins, who beat Ryan Roques and Lovell
Houston, for a 47-yard touchdown pass. Oregon State 35, UCLA 7.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence repeated. The Bruins gained four yards on their
ensuing possession, Nate Fikse punted, and OSU scored. It took
longer than seven seconds, but the result was just as humiliating
for UCLA: Smith hit Percoats from 10 yards out. Oregon State 42,
UCLA 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
