<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-COLONIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WORK TO OUTSMART WILY MICROBES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corrosion-causing bacteria, mostly unnamed but grouped generally
by what they eat and secrete, are extraordinarily wily creatures,
scientists have learned in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria are members of a category known as biofilms,
prolific microbes that attach tightly to a surface and fashion a
slimy film overhead that scientists say is unbelievably effective
in keeping disinfectants out.
</P>
<P>
   Given good growing conditions in pipes of virtually any
material, the microbes construct colonies that display ``almost
baroque levels of structural complexity,'' according to Bill
Costerton, director of the Center for Biofilm Engineering at
Montana State University.
</P>
<P>
   By releasing subtle chemical signals, the bacteria trigger
wholesale changes in their own cellular structures, depending on
the duties they perform in building and maintaining colonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot smarter than we used to think,'' said Anne
Camper, who researches biofilms in drinking water for the National
Science Foundation-supported center in Bozeman.
</P>
<P>
   The bacteria erect pedestal-like nodes that grow into ridges of
hard deposits called tubercles. Meanwhile, the pipe wall becomes
increasingly pitted and, eventually, pinhole leaks develop.
</P>
<P>
   A single community, sometimes containing several kinds of
bacteria working in harmony, can cover entire 10-foot lengths of
pipe, said Daniel Pope, whose consulting company's offices in Texas
and Colorado have worked widely with industry on the problem he
dubbed MIC, for microbiologically influenced corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still have a tough time making the connection between
corrosion and microbes,'' said molecular environmental biologist
Peggy Arps; but now, she is seeing ``at least 20 different types of
organisms'' that cause damage to one or another pipe material.
</P>
<P>
   Although corrosive bacteria have been studied for a century, it
has been little more than a decade since DNA testing started
shedding major light on them, said Arps, a research associate
professor in the Mackay School of Mines at the University of Nevada
at Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Corrosion is an electrochemical process that can be likened to
the operation of a battery, said Peter Fox, associate professor of
engineering at Arizona State University in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny current is produced between the pipe wall where there is
no oxygen and areas where oxygen exists, and the flow of electrons
strips away pipe material atom by atom, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be microorganisms in water,'' Camper and
numerous others emphasized, so instead of eradicating MIC, ``the
best hope is to try and control it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
