<SLUG> BC-BACTERIA-LAW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SUING CITIES OVER WATER QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AlliedSignal Inc. sued Tempe more than four years ago in U.S.
District Court in Phoenix and followed up the next year with a suit
against Phoenix. Both cases are far from trial.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits do not specify damage amounts, but in claims filed
before going to court, the aerospace company demanded $4.5 million
from Tempe and $20.75 million from Phoenix to pay for replacement
of fire-sprinkler systems in all its facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix case was dismissed by U.S. District Judge Paul G.
Rosenblatt in 1997 on the ground that municipalities are immune
from suits of this nature. The Tempe case, before District Judge
Roslyn O. Silver, was put on hold while the decision was appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In June, a sharply divided three-judge panel of the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco revived the Phoenix case, saying
dismissal was premature.
</P>
<P>
   Appellate Judge Warren J. Ferguson's scathing dissent said, ``In
this case, there is not even a hint anyplace that treating water
for human consumption creates an action for damages when the water
which is beneficial to humans is destroying the pipes that carry
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the complaint ``simply silly'' and ``frivolous
litigation,'' he wrote, ``It is this kind of case which fosters the
clamor for tort reform.''
</P>
<P>
   All three judges agreed that Rosenblatt was right in refusing to
order the city to treat water so bacteria wouldn't corrode pipes.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal contends that its corrosion problems stem from the
cities' inadequate disinfection of water supplies. It says the
cities also were negligent for never warning that some types of
bacteria could survive treatment and play havoc with pipes.
</P>
<P>
   The cities' attorneys attack the company's assertion that the
bacteria came from water, rather than any other source, such as
dirt or air entering the pipes during manufacture or installation.
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal outside counsel David B. Rosenbaum asserted in
court that a review of Tempe water test records revealed that ``on
numerous occasions, they were supplying water to AlliedSignal's
facilities in Tempe with inadequate chlorine (and) with excessively
high bacteria levels, under their own standards.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents are not yet on file in court, and AlliedSignal
would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Tempe City Attorney C. Brad Woodford discounted Rosenbaum's
comment as ``just an allegation.'' He and Philip M. Haggerty, chief
assistant city attorney for Phoenix, both emphasized that the
lawsuits say nothing about the purity of the cities' water for
human consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum, of the firm Osborn Maledon in Phoenix, countered that
``at the very same chlorination standards that the city is talking
about, . . . for all the balancing they do, if they do it right,
bacteria will not cause health problems . . . and it won't cause
corrosion to pipes.''
</P>
<P>
   No settlement discussions have been held, the cities' attorneys
said, but AlliedSignal, in the only comment it would make beyond
court filings, signaled a willingness to settle. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
