<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BIZARRE NIGHT FOR TYSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A disgusted woman who had paid God-knows how much to
see the fight summed it perfectly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that was a &AMP;%$ waste of time. And, of course, Mike Tyson
made it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This one, between Tyson and Orlin Norris, wasn't on par with the
ear-biting incident that ended the second fight with Evander
Holyfield. What could be? However, it had that remarkably bizarre
quality we've come to associate with Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The fight had gone only one round when Tyson landed a left hook
a split second after the bell, Norris fell awkwardly on his back,
wrenched his right knee and couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was ruled a no contest because of what officials
called an ``accidental foul.''
</P>
<P>
   That was that. Mike Tyson's latest comeback fight fizzled almost
before it started before a crowd of 12,081 at the MGM Grand on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The moment Jimmy Lennon Jr. announced the result, a tremendous
chorus of boos reverberated in the spacious indoor arena followed
by angry chants and nasty comments that shouldn't be printed here.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, convinced Norris could continue because he had walked to
his corner apparently with no problem, was himself disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have more to (complain) about than I do,'' he said
in a calm moment. ``The reality of the situation is that he
could've got up and continued to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the heat on him and he didn't want to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ... er, only round was largely uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson (46-3, with 40 knockouts) did some of the things his
trainers had hoped he'd do after a nine-month layoff, fight
relatively patiently, move his head, jab.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he also threw the big bombs we've also come to
associate with Tyson. None landed with any meaning, although it
seemed only a matter of time before one did.
</P>
<P>
   Norris (50-5, 27 KOs) also did what he set out to do: punch on
the move, don't stand in one place too long as Francois Botha did
when Tyson knocked him out in his last fight, in January.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if it might be an interesting fight ... and then it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Richard Steele, himself no stranger to controversy, had
warned Tyson early in the round about hitting on the break. And
then Tyson did it just as the first three minutes expired, knocking
Norris flat.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it appeared Norris was hurt by the punch but he
quickly got to his feet and went to his corner, where he sat down
on his stool.
</P>
<P>
   Steele then took !ital!two!off! points away from Tyson for the
foul, and it appeared the fight would continue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Norris' knee apparently wouldn't allow it and the fight
was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, perhaps not aware of exactly what transpired, reacted
angrily and was surrounded by his handlers, who calmed him down as
security guards _ ready for anything at a Tyson fight _ quickly
surrounded the ring to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen, Tyson's promoter, said he was uncertain what would
become of the fighters' purses, $10 million for Tyson, $800,000 for
Norris. The Nevada State Athletic Commission will decide that.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, convinced the world is against him, suspects he'll lose
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired, man. I'm just tired of all the (garbage),'' he
said. ``I don't even know if I want to fight any more.''
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary bouts, heavyweight contender David Tua showed
former Canadian champion Shane Sutcliffe why he's considered one of
the most dangerous fighters in the world, ending their scheduled
10-round bout with one left hook at 1:20 of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Sutcliffe (21-9-1, 12 KOs), who landed awkwardly on his hands
and knees, made it to his feet but referee Jay Nady spared him
further punishment by stopping the mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respect for the guy (Sutcliffe), but I had no respect
for his power,'' said Tua, a native of Samoa who fights out of New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee did a good job stopping the fight. He was
disappointed, but the referee ... didn't want to see him get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tua (35-1, 20 KOs) is seeking an opportunity to fight the winner
of the Nov.13 Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight but might not be
high on either's list of prospective opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Featherweight contender Augie Sanchez (23-1, 20 KOs) put down
Daniel Jimenez (27-8-1, 14 KOs) twice with body punches and Jiminez
stayed down the second time.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled 10-round bout was stopped at 1:41 of the sixth
round.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Dokiwari (15-1, 13 KOs) outpointed Agustin Corpus (7-4-2,
seven KOs) in a six-round heavyweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   And undefeated junior welterweight contender Zab Judah had an
usual evening: He fought two three-round exhibitions against
separate fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He dominated both Joaquin Gallardo, whom he dropped, and Manuel
Gomez. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
