<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-24 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ Sometimes you get the flu, and sometimes you just feel
sick.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the New York Yankees' swarming 4-1 win over the
Atlanta Braves to open the World Series on Saturday night, the
question is: Who's feeling worse today?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine? Or his Braves teammates?
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves were going to win this opener at Turner Field and
blast from the gate with a statement against their nemesis Yankees
counterparts, they needed to take advantage of what was staring
them in the face.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chance. It was a real chance to show the powerful
Yankees just how much of a heart is beating under their jerseys, a
chance to pull out a game in the nerve-rattling late innings.
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams can do those things. They can watch Greg
Maddux step in masterfully for the flu-ridden scheduled starter,
Glavine, and somehow give him just enough support to carry it to
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams can see Chipper Jones break out of his 1999
postseason doldrums, slamming a 403-foot home run just inside the
right-field foul pole, and back it up with solid late-inning
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Championship teams can go into the eighth with Maddux still
looking great, ace reliever John Rocker warming in the pen and the
crowd tomahawk-chopping in hopes of squeezing out the big win
against the Yanks, and somehow do just that.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves didn't. They couldn't take advantage of Maddux's
pitching or Chipper's clutch hit.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter Orlando Hernandez was pitching beautifully
through the night, but the Braves held the lead. As overwhelming as
he was, Hernandez had to be pulled for a pinch hitter in the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it seemed the Braves would manage to steal one and
send the Yanks off into the night in frustration, the Braves saw it
vanish in the most unlikely of ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never really hit the ball hard,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox lamented about the fateful eighth-inning collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, the normally reliable one who throws a mean fastball and
fidgets and squirms like a bad kid in church, spit the bit. The
defense collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of World Series opener the Braves did not need.
If there was a statement made on this night it was only by the
Yankees, who have won nine consecutive World Series games,
including five straight over the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees clearly know how to win these kinds of games no
matter the stakes; the Braves _ perhaps dominant in a league of
their own, the National _ haven't solved the New Yorkers on the
biggest baseball stage of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of game isn't unusual for us,'' said Yankees
outfielder Paul O'Neill, who hit the game-breaking two-run single
off Rocker in the eighth inning. ``We're used to close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go through enough of them and win enough of them, you
have the confidence that you're going to win them all. If someone
gives us a couple of outs or a couple of runs, we're going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks did indeed win because the normally steady Braves
flinched. Brian Hunter, a defensive replacement at first base,
committed a pair of errors in the eighth inning; Maddux gave up a
single to begin the rally and then lost what had been masterful
control.
</P>
<P>
   He walked pinch hitter Darryl Strawberry after Scott Brosius'
leadoff single. He left a pitch over the plate against Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the inning, the Braves misplayed a bunt by Chuck
Knoblauch and saw Hunter commit another error with a bad throw.
Rocker came on for Maddux and struggled through 30 pitches, giving
up the decisive two-run single and then adding to the Yanks' total
with a bases-loaded walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get the kind of play we needed,'' Cox said. ``Not
even close.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a meltdown in a game the Braves needed. Now, the Yankees
have gained the home-field advantage and have Andy Pettitte, David
Cone and five-time Cy Young winner Roger Clemens for the next three
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have one hit going into the ninth inning, you're not
going to win many ballgames,'' Braves shortstop Walt Weiss said.
``That's not how we wanted to start off.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering what lies ahead, it was the worst way for the Braves
to start. It could have been a night when the Braves stood tall and
showed the kind of grit and late-inning savvy that can make for a
World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Yankees made the early statement: They are the
champions, and this is why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we got a little crack,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said,
``it didn't surprise me that we opened it up. We made the most of
an opportunity. That's the way this team is.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how champions do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
