r s BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-24 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES COME BACK AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA---For seven innings Saturday night in the opener of the
final World Series of the 20th century, the Atlanta Braves seemed
as though they would be immune to the loss of their original
starting pitcher, Tom Glavine, sidelined by influenza.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, considering the flawless manner in which his
replacement, Greg Maddux, was working against the New York Yankees,
it seemed as though the Braves were fortunate Glavine had suffered
such an affliction.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Maddux was in his magical Cy Young Award form,
stifling the Yankees on a mere three hits with his dazzling array
of pitches that had New York's batsmen thoroughly bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Braves had only a 1-0 edge, but it seemed as though
the only hit they would manage against an equally stubborn Orlando
(El Duque) Hernandez---a fourth inning home run by Chipper
Jones---would be enough on a chilly evening when the temperatures
were dipping into the low 40s and Maddux was dispensing another one
of his masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   But these Yankees aren't to be confused with the New York Mets,
or any of those other ball clubs who have been foils for the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   And in the eighth inning, the Yankees would demonstrate
graphically why they've become the most feared team in baseball in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Before you could say Scott Brosius, Darryl Strawberry, Chuck
Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill, Jim Leyritz and Brian Hunter,
the Yankees stunned Maddux with a four run eruption that turned out
to be enough for a 4-1 win that also stunned 51,342 Turner Field
partisans.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter?
</P>
<P>
   He plays for the Braves---he was inserted as a defensive
replacement at first base for Ryan Klesko in the eighth---but the
1985 graduate of Paramount High School contributed mightily to the
Yankees' cause with two errors that led to two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Greg Maddux was as good as he's ever been,'' the
Braves' manager, Bobby Cox, would say afterward. ``The Yankees
really never hit him hard, and almost all their base hits just
found holes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played `little ball,' and it was enough,'' said the
Yankees' manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, the Yankees' overlooked third baseman, led off that
eighth with his third straight hit off Maddux. Then Strawberry,
pinch-hitting for Hernandez, walked. Then Hunter butchered
Knoblauch's bunt. Then Jeter singled in the Yankees first run. Then
Maddux exited and O'Neill singled in the next two Yankee runs off
the dreaded John Rocker on a play in which he advanced to second on
Hunter's second miscue.
</P>
<P>
   And then Leyritz, batting for Ricky Ledee, walked to produce
another score that would be more than his team would require.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, the Yankees, as they did against the Texas
Rangers and Boston Red Sox in the recent playoffs, had emerged
victorious on tight pitching---Hernandez would give up only that
homer to Jones and strike out 10 in seven innings---tight defense
and a few well-placed hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not an unusual game for us,'' said O'Neill. ``It
seems like we've been in so many of these type of low-scoring games
this season, and we just expect to win them. We've become pretty
used to them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Torre always is preaching to us when the door opens, we
have to take advantage of it---and that's what we did again
tonight,'' said Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   As good as Greg Maddux was---and he was so good that Cox
admitted he didn't even consider replacing him when he faced Jeter
in that eighth inning with no outs and the bases loaded---Hernandez
turned out to be even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy just continues to make you shake your head,'' said
Torre. ``He was sharp right from the get-go tonight. And yet in the
dugout he kept shaking his head after he gave up that home run to
Jones and said, `Mistake! Mistake! Mistake.' The guy makes one bad
pitch all night, and is down on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt all my pitches were working well, but what worked best
was my control,'' said Hernandez through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy gives you only one hit, you know he's pretty
overpowering,'' said the Braves' second baseman Bret Boone, who
fanned twice against Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's pitches were incredible and just so difficult to
hit,'' said the Braves catcher, Eddie Perez, who also went down
swinging twice against Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Maddux delivered the game's first pitch at 8:11
(EST) with the thermometer reading 49 degrees and the wind chill
factor at 34, hundreds of the literati gathered on the field doing
what they always do before World Series proceedings, exchanging
gossip with one another, complaining about the stadium food, giving
their predictions, and offering psychobabble insights on a variety
of subjects ranging from Glavine's sickness to Chuck Knoblauch's
mysterious throwing problems.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has a theory on Knoblauch's weird curse that has
resulted in his committing 26 errors this season, an outrageously
high total for a second baseman who once was a Golden Glove winner
as a member of the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   But the person who possesses the keenest understanding of
Knoblauch's defensive travails is Steve Sax, now a TV analyst for
Fox who experienced similar miseries in the early 1980s when he was
a second baseman for the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The throwing thing is all in Knoblauch's head,'' says Sax.
``Believe me, I know because it happened to me. You just get messed
up, and every time you throw the ball you start thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only way to get over it. And that's to keep practicing
throwing the ball to first base. I did that hour after hour, and
after a while the problem went away and I couldn't wait to throw
the ball to first.''
</P>
<P>
   Blessedly for ol' Chuck, El Duque Hernandez saw to it the Braves
didn't direct any balls in his direction, and Knoblauch didn't even
have a fielding opportunity until the ninth inning when Mariano
Rivera induced Gerald Williams to hit a routine grounder to
Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   This time Knoblauch threw flawlessly to first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did everything flawlessly Saturday night, except for
that one pitching indiscretion that Hernandez committed against
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Maddux pitched just as good as Hernandez,'' groused
Bobby Cox, who didn't hide his displeasure during the game with the
work of the home plate umpire, Randy Marsh. ``We just didn't get
any breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to get any breaks these days against these
remarkable Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 0205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
