<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6687 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-HNS &LR;      10-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LAS VEGAS _ Throw two-time ex-world heavyweight champion Mike Tyson
into the boxing ring, and controversy is certain to follow.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday night, in his first fight since being released from a
Maryland prison last spring, Tyson uncorked a punch to the head of
challenger Orlin Norris after the bell ending the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate result was an official no-contest that disappointed
the crowd of 12,081 at the MGM Grand Hotel-Casino's Grand Garden
Arena and left Tyson's future in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   But during the postfight news conference, Tyson (46-3) said he
is thinking about retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all this ,'' Tyson said. ``I really am. I really
don't know if I want to fight anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of all this political . I'm tired, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris, sent tumbling by the punch that landed almost a full
three seconds after the bell, suffered an apparent injury to his
right knee that left the Lubbock native unable to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Seated on a stool in his corner, Norris was examined by ringside
physician Dr. Flip Homansky, who informed referee Richard Steele
that Norris could not continue the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of an accidental foul after the bell rang,'' ring
announcer Jimmy Lennon Jr. said to the audience afterward, ``the
fight has officially been ruled a no-contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris (50-5) was taken to Valley Hospital for an MRI about 30
minutes after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the arena, he said, ``(Tyson) hit me after the
bell. I just went down wrong on my right knee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he conducted himself,'' said Tyson, ``he should be
ashamed of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't hurt enough that he couldn't keep on fighting. He
could walk back to his corner _ that's how hurt he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele, since working the world title fight between Julio Cesar
Chavez and Meldrick Taylor in 1989, has himself been the center of
some degree of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   He will probably be criticized again after assessing a two-point
penalty to Tyson for the late blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't say if it (the late punch) was deliberate,'' said
Steele. ``I don't know if he could hear the bell or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was supposed to have received $10 million. Dr. James Nave,
executive director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission, said
Tyson's purse will be withheld, pending a full investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Norris was supposed to get $800,000, but he was paid only a
little more than $200,000 because of his manager's share, an IRS
lien and a court order involving a lawsuit against him.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his troubled past and skills that had obviously been
on the wane since he was imprisoned for rape in 1992, Tyson entered
Saturday's 10-round main event needing to record an impressive
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Anything short of that, it was thought, might be the end of his
efforts to again become a world heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   How Saturday's result will affect his future is uncertain. There
is no question, however, the outcome meshes perfectly with a
star-crossed path that has been the life of the Catskill, N.Y.,
native.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the last three sordid incidents in boxing with which
Tyson has been involved have occurred at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1997 at the Grand Garden Arena, Tyson lost by
disqualification to Evander Holyfield when he bit each ear of the
World Boxing Association/International Boxing Federation
heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada State Athletic Commission later suspended his boxing
license for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   In the first fight after having the license reinstated, Tyson
took on former IBF champion Frans Botha at the Grand Garden Arena
last January.
</P>
<P>
   Though he won by fifth-round knockout, Tyson wasn't above
controversy. He twisted the arm of Botha during a clinch and, after
the bout, said his action was intended to break the South African's
arm.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, before throwing the ill-fated punch, Tyson looked far
sharper than when he landed a lucky right hand to knock out Botha.
</P>
<P>
   He had Norris backpedaling from the power in his left hook and
straight right hand.
</P>
<P>
   But it was of little consequence because of another
controversial incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
