<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNION-CHILD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE LEADS TO MOTHER, CHILD REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writers Charles F. Bostwick and Ian Hanigan contributed to
this story 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE _ A televised high-desert police pursuit Friday led to
a dramatic series of events Saturday when a 2-year-old boy caught
up in the chase was recognized as a child missing for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jacob Perez, who was found in a sport-utility vehicle abandoned
by his father, the suspect in the chase, was to be reunited with
his mother Saturday at the Los Angeles County sheriff's station in
Palmdale, sheriff's officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bianca Perez, 33, of Las Vegas had not seen her son since he was
allegedly taken by his father during a supervised custody visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in total shock,'' said Perez, a nightclub hostess who
caught the first glimpse of her son on a television news video at
the sheriff's station. ``I can't believe he's so big. He looks like
a 4-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   But after waiting six hours with Jacob's aunt, uncle,
grandmother and 12-year-old sister, Perez was told the meeting
couldn't take place until the boy's identity could be verified at a
procedure that could not take place until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand how they think they're doing better for the
child, but the baby should be with us, rather than passed from home
to home,'' said Perez, who brought with her custody papers and
other documents. In addition, a Nevada Attorney General official
told Los Angeles County officials she has custody. ``We're the best
interest of the child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The saga began Friday when sheriff's investigators received a
tip that a possible suspect in an armored car guard shooting in
Long Beach was going to be at a car dealership in Palmdale, 55
miles north of Los Angeles. Deputies saw the suspect, Desmond
Michael Mooreland, 33, of Quartz Hill, at the dealership, where he
was picking up a new window for his Chevy Suburban, sheriff's Sgt.
Mike Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   With authorities in pursuit, Mooreland sped off in the Suburban
with Jacob. Mooreland later abandoned the vehicle in the parking
lot of the Antelope Valley Mall, where he was eventually arrested.
Authorities plucked Jacob from the Suburban and placed him into
protective custody.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a relative of Mooreland's saw the pursuit on
television and contacted the suspect's maternal grandmother, who in
turn alerted the boy's uncle, Juan Caraveo of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who had been in Hawaii visiting her mother, didn't learn
of the news until she got off the plane Saturday morning and was
greeted by Caraveo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drove to my house and picked up my daughter and came right
down here,'' Perez said after arriving at the station. ``That's her
Tigger,'' she said, referring to her daughter's nickname for Jacob.
``We were just Winnie-the-Pooh fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez said Jacob _ the subject of a bitter custody battle _
disappeared one year and four months ago during a supervised visit
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, Perez and other family members have
struggled to find the toddler, offering monetary rewards and
working with five missing children agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two weeks ago, the faces of the boy and his
father were emblazoned on mailers distributed in Nevada and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no clues until Friday's high-speed chase.
Authorities said the boy and his father had been living with
Mooreland's uncle in a mobile home park in Quartz Hill for the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Residents from all over the Southland ``who recognize the kid
have been calling us and a national missing children's hotline,''
Sgt. Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   Mooreland was booked on suspicion of felony evasion and child
endangerment and was being held at the Long Beach jail.
</P>
<P>
   Mooreland and another of three men believed to be responsible
for shooting and critically wounding the armored truck guard during
a robbery in downtown Long Beach were in custody Saturday, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach police spokeswoman Nancy Tabing said authorities
found the 2-year-old boy, whom Mooreland later told police was his
son, inside the abandoned Suburban. She also said a ``significant
amount of cash believed to be part of the loss from the robbery''
was found on Mooreland at the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the money from the robbery was used to purchase the
vehicle,'' Tabing said.
</P>
<P>
   Mooreland is being held at the Long Beach Jail on suspicion of
premeditated attempted murder, robbery, child endangerment and
felony evading. In addition, he had been sought on a warrant out of
Las Vegas for unlawful flight to avoid prosecution. He is expected
to be arraigned in Long Beach Municipal Court on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach Police Sgt. Steve Filippini said suspect Keenan
Haywood, 26, was arrested in Carson early Wednesday morning, one
day after the shooting that left 24-year-old armored truck guard
Dwight Medrano near death.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are searching for a third suspect, described by
witnesses as a Latino male in his 20s, in connection with the
shooting and robbery Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have yet to determine which of the three robbery
suspects pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
