<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN     10-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL CHAPTER FOR TYSON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ No one was raped. No ears were chewed off. No
innocent motorists were roughed up. As atrocities go, Mike Tyson
certainly has perpetrated worse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
But one still got the feeling, Saturday night in Las Vegas, that
Tyson's bizarre boxing career finally took a blow from which it
will never recover.
</P>
<P>
   Or so we can hope.
</P>
<P>
   A once-great athlete who needed to show enough skill and wit to
prove he is worthy of our attention instead melted down in the ring
for the umpteenth time.
</P>
<P>
   A onetime superstar who needed to prove he remains boxer enough
to warrant a payday instead showed he can't follow the simplest
rules of the fight game.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson sucker-punched Orlin Norris a full second after the bell
to end Round 1 of their heavyweight fight at the MGM Grand Arena,
and it resulted in a ``no-contest'' ruling that perhaps was the
most infuriating episode yet in Tyson's singularly infuriating
career.
</P>
<P>
   Norris was dazed by Tyson's clearly late punch, went down in a
heap, and said he injured his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, television replays appeared to show Norris' knee
wrenching weirdly as it hit the canvas, and perhaps Tyson's shoe as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Norris' corner said he could not go on. The ringside doctor
agreed. After the obligatory Tyson post-fight chaos, which included
half the Las Vegas Police Department climbing in the ring, the
``no-contest'' came down.
</P>
<P>
   Fans were ticked. You could almost smell the slow burn of 12,081
suckers vowing never, ever to be suckered again by the prospect of
a Mike Tyson ``fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness, this one wasn't pay-per-view, but at least a few
of the 12,081 in the arena paid real money to watch this farce.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Tyson blamed someone else. Norris, in this case,
whom Tyson accused of seizing a chance to escape the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put the heat on him, and he didn't want to continue,'' Tyson
said. ``The way he conducted himself, he should be disgraced with
himself. A real fighter fights till he can't fight no more.''
</P>
<P>
   A real fighter knows you don't throw a jab after the bell.
Particularly when the referee is between you and your opponent
trying to break you up.
</P>
<P>
   The simple fact is, had Tyson not reached over referee Richard
Steele and slugged Norris after the bell, the fight would have gone
on.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, a blown-up cruiserweight, was carefully selected by the
Tyson camp because he represented an early-round knockout for an
extremely rusty fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tyson screwed it up. He couldn't even control himself long
enough to knock out the tomato can propped up for him.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson expressed frustration afterward, saying repeatedly how
``tired'' he is with boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go home,'' Tyson said. ``I'm tired of everyone
and everything. I'm tired. I don't even know if I want to fight
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold that thought, Iron Mike.
</P>
<P>
   We're quite certain we never want to see you fight again.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson already was verging on irrelevant. Because of his various
high crimes and misdemeanors, he was fighting for only the eighth
time in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   A man who once electrified the boxing world already was close to
putting it to sleep. Light ticket demand, no cable deal, limited
media interest.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before Saturday's ridiculous episode.
</P>
<P>
   So did Tyson's fourth comeback end ingloriously, in controversy
and frustration, with fans shouting insults at the former
heavyweight champion of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If we're lucky, we'll never have a chance to do it again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
