<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6691 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-BOS &LR;      10-24 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON LATE PUNCH RESULTS IN NO-DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ No mas. Please.
</P>
<P>
   Enough with Mike Tyson. Enough with bizarre behavior and
pathetic excuses. Enough with bitten ears and nearly broken arms
and blows thrown after the bell. Enough with false macho and what
has become a tired freak show.
</P>
<P>
   Enough is more than enough after Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's deplorable
performance by the former heavyweight champion at the MGM Grand
Garden Arena, where he went three minutes without hitting Orlin
Norris and then blasted him with a short left hand to the face
coming out of a clinch well after the bell had sounded to end the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   The bell tolled and referee Richard Steele was heard to yell,
``Stop punching!'' Apparently to Tyson that meant ``Open fire!''
Which he did.
</P>
<P>
   As the stunned Norris fell to the floor, his right knee buckled
under him and he lay flat on his back. As Norris started to rise,
Tyson stared menacingly at him, a bully on the loose. Steele
immediately deducted two points from Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   When the bell sounded to open the second round, Norris didn't
move and his chief handler, Abel Sanchez, told Steele his fighter
couldn't continue. Tyson stalked to the center of the ring, but
Steele directed him to a neutral corner where he paced like the
caged and frightened animal he has become in the ring since the
night Evander Holyfield first exposed him for what he has become.
</P>
<P>
   After a long discussion between Steele, Nevada State Commission
executive director Marc Ratner, and ringside physician Flip
Homansky, the bout was ruled a no-decision pending further review.
When that was announced, Tyson seemed to spin into a rage, but
promoter Dan Goossen rushed in with Tyson's cornermen and calmed
him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He quit,'' Tyson said as he was walking out of the ring. ``How
do I hit him in the jaw and he hurt his leg?''
</P>
<P>
   Probably because when he hit him it was A) after the bell; B)
coming out of a clinch; C) after Steele had ordered both men to
stop punching and; D) while he was still holding Norris with one
arm. Other than that, there was no reason Norris wouldn't have been
able to defend himself from an opponent who no longer has the
self-control to follow even the most basic rules of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hit me after the bell and I went down the wrong way on
my right knee,'' Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, boxing can be high drama and great art but not when
Tyson is painting the canvas. In the ring now he is what he once
claimed to be _ a street thug mugging old ladies in elevators after
saying he'd help them carry their groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Unsure of himself when under attack and showing none of the fast
combinations and head movement he had exhibited last week, Tyson
was once again winging wild rights and lefts and landing few of
them until the battle was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Only then was he the fearsome knockout puncher he once was. Only
then, with Norris' hands down and under orders not to punch, did he
unleash a knockout blow. What he has to worry about now is whether
he knocked out Norris or himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission will review the tape on Monday and decide if
the punch was intentionally late,'' commission chairman Elias
Ghanem said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner announced the commission would hold up Tyson's purse
until then while Norris would be paid immediately, although he
netted well below the $800,000 he had on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   After back taxes, manager's shares, a disputed claim, and
medical expenses were deducted, Norris netted $201,982.20 while
Tyson was slated to net $8,765,935.59 before his own managerial
fees and federal taxes are paid.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday night, Tyson may lose more than that. If the
commission rules he intentionally hit Norris after the bell, he may
lose his boxing license for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early last week it came to light that IBF junior lightweight
contender Diego Corrales's only title belt was being auctioned off
on eBay. Saturday &UR;  &LR; night he picked up a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Corrales made a stunning comeback from early trouble when he
sliced open the side of Roberto Garcia's right eye in the third
round and then followed up by dropping him in the sixth round. He
finished off the champion with a crushing straight right hand
behind a pawing left at :42 of the seventh round.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Garcia (32-1) was a bloody mess. He had been beaten
badly in the sixth round, sent to the floor with just under a
minute to go in the round, and then battered and beaten until he
voluntarily took a knee with 12 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the minute break was enough of a respite to allow
him to regain his senses, and when Garcia came out for what would
prove to be the last round of his reign, it was obvious his legs
were still unhinged and he was all but defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   Corrales (29-0, 24 KO) realized this and closed ground on the
tottering champion quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Almost the moment Garcia hit the floor, Cortez jumped in and
waved Corrales off.
</P>
<P>
   When Corrales left the ring, he was wearing the IBF belt Garcia
had brought, a belt he will surely guard more closely than the IBA
Continental lightweight title belt that disappeared from his house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
