<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SHARKS-BOS     10-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SHARKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FINALLY WIN ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ With half a second left on the clock and the
game clearly decided, Bruins defenseman Kyle McLaren gave a little
fist pump and broke into a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
<P>
   It took 10 games, but the Bruins finally made it into the win
column, beating the Sharks, 3-1, Saturday night at San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, which had matched its worst start in franchise history
with a nine-game winless streak (0-5-4), got strong performances
from goalie John Grahame (31 saves) and forwards Anson Carter and
Jason Allison on the way to the victory.
</P>
<P>
   There's a belief in hockey that the best time to play a club is
their first home game after a long road trip. The home team is
often sluggish and ripe for the picking.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly held true Saturday &UR;  &LR; night as the Sharks, who were
just back from a successful 4-2-0 journey and had the league's best
record, were slow out of the gate and the Bruins took advantage
with a pair of power-play goals in the first period and one in the
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play any worse or any better than we have in our
last four games,'' said coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it statistic-wise, we had just as many chances
in the other games. The only difference tonight was we found a way
to put it in behind the goaltender and bury our chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a question of time; it was a question of staying
positive with them and reassuring them it would happen someday if
they kept on working.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins went up, 2-0, in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Dave Andreychuk drew the penalty and then set up the
score at 12:36. Andreychuk relayed a pass to Carter, who was
positioned below the right circle. Carter found defenseman Darren
Van Impe in the left circle and Van Impe rocketed a shot that
sailed high into the net past goalie Steve Shields.
</P>
<P>
   Boston received a big boost with less than a second left in the
period when the team cashed in on its second power play. Allison
dished a pass to Joe Thornton, who relayed it to McLaren at the
point. McLaren moved it to left wing Sergei Samsonov in the left
circle and Samsonov gave it back to him with McLaren beating
Shields on a one-timer with just seven-10ths of a second remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long time coming,'' said McLaren. ``We played a pretty
good game tonight and our power play clicked and that's what we
need to win games. We shut down their top line and our goaltending
played great. The key guys got the points we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the second period, Sharks coach Darryl Sutter
pulled Shields in favor of Mike Vernon. Shields began the game with
the best statistics in the league.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle period, the Sharks picked up their game markedly
and outshot Boston, 12-8, but couldn't dent Grahame. Jeff Friesen,
Vincent Damphousse and Owen Nolan, the hottest line in the league,
put some decent pressure on the Bruins _ especially Friesen _ but
didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made it a three-goal cushion early in the third
period as Carter picked up his second goal of the season and second
in two games. Again the tally came on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, parked below the left circle, fed the puck to Carter in
the slot and he rapped it past Vernon at 3:07.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks responded at the 12:23 mark, spoiling Grahame's bid
for his first NHL shutout. Center Patrick Marleau, who was taken
with the No. 2 overall pick in the 1997 draft after Thornton was
grabbed at No. 1, made it 3-1 when he shoveled the puck past
Grahame from a bad angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell down funny,'' said Grahame. ``It was a bad goal. He was
on the side and I just fell down and it hit my side and went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that little blemish, Grahame was thrilled to celebrate
his first victory in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to know you can do it and be confident about
it,'' said Grahame. ``It's another thing to actually do it and get
that first win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big step for our team. Obviously it's good. It's one of
the best feelings you can have. It being the first time in the best
league in the world, obviously it's a tremendous feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
