<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES PUT ON A LATE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
 SERIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Muzzle John Rocker, the Mouth of the South?
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves manager Bobby Cox already was on record as saying
he'd like his lefthanded closer to ``calm down with the fans''
after Rocker decided he had to not only beat the New York Mets in
the National League Championship Series but also win a war of words
with their followers, whom he referred to as a ``tired act'' when
he wasn't calling them animals.
</P>
<P>
   Having already alienated Queens, Cox wasn't sure he wanted
Rocker to take on the Bronx, Manhattan, Brooklyn, and Staten
Island, too, in the 95th World Series against New York's other
team, the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But after Game 1 Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, the Braves may no longer have
to worry about abridging Rocker's freedom of speech. The Yankees
stuffed a sock in it, at least temporarily, by rapping Rocker and
stifling the Braves, 4-1, behind Orlando Hernandez, after it
appeared that the Yankees might lose (shades of Floyd Bevens) on a
night that their pitcher threw a one-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one said it was going to be easy,'' Braves second baseman
Bret Boone said after the Yankees scored all of their runs in the
eighth inning, turning three ground-ball hits, two walks, and a
botched bunt into four runs, Derek Jeter driving in the tying run
and Paul O'Neill knocking in two to break the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy all year. We had a tough series against
Houston, a tough series against the Mets, and we're going to have a
tough series against the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were behind, 1-0, after seven innings, the Braves'
only hit a home run by Chipper Jones off El Duque in the fourth.
New York finally stirred in the eighth against Greg Maddux, who to
that point had been composing one of the great pinch-hitting
performances in Series history.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, subbing for a flu-stricken Tom Glavine, had baffled the
Bombers on three singles and had not allowed an advance past second
base. But Scott Brosius, last year's Series MVP in the Yankees'
sweep of San Diego, led off with a ground ball through the left
side, his third hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre then sent up Darryl Strawberry to pinch hit
for Hernandez, who had 10 whiffs in seven innings, and Strawberry
worked Maddux for a walk, the third of the night by the Braves'
master craftsman.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees then made the Braves look as fumble-prone as the Red
Sox in the ALCS, capitalizing on two errors by first baseman Brian
Hunter, who had just entered the game for (ahem) defensive
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's first misplay came when he fielded Chuck Knoblauch's
sacrifice bunt, placed perfectly just past the mound, and had the
ball slip out of his throwing hand, allowing Knoblauch to reach
safely and load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to have a sinking feeling,'' Hunter said. ``No outs,
bases loaded, and Jeter coming up. I was hoping that maybe he would
hit a chopper back to Maddux. If we'd gotten an out on the bunt,
maybe we walk Jeter and try to get a double play.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jeter punched a ground ball through the shortstop hole
for a tying single.
</P>
<P>
   That ended Maddux's night. Asked if there was anything he would
have done differently, he said: ``Not really. I thought I pitched
Strawberry pretty good, even though I walked him, and I made a good
pitch to Brosius, and he hit it. The only physical mistake I made
was to Jeter. I wanted to throw it down and away, and it got too
much of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 51,342 at Turner Field roared as Rocker
emerged from the bullpen and sprinted toward the mound like a
spooked Clydesdale. Waiting at the plate was Paul O'Neill, who in
the face of Rocker fastballs hurtling plateward at speeds of 96
miles an hour, got ahead in the count, 3 and 1, then whacked a
ground ball to right through a drawn-in infield for two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pitcher's pitch,'' Rocker said. ``I couldn't have
made a better pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You put the ball in play,'' O'Neill said, ``and you hope good
things can happen, and they did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter cut off right fielder Brian Jordan's throw home and
attempted to nail Jeter at third, but he bounced his throw,
allowing O'Neill to advance to second.
</P>
<P>
   There were still no outs when Rocker issued an intentional walk
to Bernie Williams, reloading the bases. He fanned the next two
batters, Tino Martinez and Jorge Posada, but then faced another
Yankee pinch hitter _ and perhaps the most hated Bomber on
Peachtree Street _ Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz was last seen here crushing an inexplicable slider from
another Braves burner, Mark Wohlers, for a three-run home run that
turned the 1996 Series around. No such heroics from The King this
time, but he forced home a fourth run when he looked at a 3-and-2
off-speed pitch from Rocker for ball four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I got a lot of the plate,'' Rocker said of the last
pitch to Leyritz. ``I didn't get beat that bad tonight. I just
didn't get the breaks. Sometimes that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves started a rally of their own in the ninth, bringing
the tying run to the plate when Yankees closer Mariano Rivera gave
up a one-out single to Bret Boone and walked Chipper Jones on four
pitches. But Rivera righted himself quickly, striking out Brian
Jordan and retiring pinch hitter Greg Myers on a weak foul to third
baseman Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   The night, by Southern standards, was near wintry: game-time
temperature of 49 degrees, with a 15-mile-an-hour wind making it
feel like freezing.
</P>
<P>
   But the conditions were ideal for cafe Cubano _ strong, dark,
and rich _ and that's what Hernandez gave the Braves. El Duque, 5-0
in postseason play, struck out eight of the first 11 hitters he
faced before Jones turned on a fastball and launched it just inside
the right-field foul pole with one out in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after I faced (Hernandez) the second time,'' Maddux said,
``I knew we weren't going to score again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was right on as the Yankees won their ninth straight in
World Series play since the Braves beat them in the first two games
in New York in '96. They're 8-1 in postseason play this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
