<SLUG> BC-BB-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ NEW OCTOBER ACE 
</HEADLINE>
 SERIES-HERNANDEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ El Duque did it again Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, throwing seven
innings of one-hit ball in a 4-1 World Series Game 1 victory over
the Braves. He's emerging as the Bob Gibson of his generation.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, a Cuban refugee who is either 30 or 34 years
old, has a career postseason mark of 5-0 with a 1.02 ERA. The
Yankees have won all six of his playoff starts. Compare that with
Greg Maddux _ Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's loser _ who is 10-10 in the
playoffs. And need we remind you that Roger Clemens has won only
two of 11 postseason starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say if these are the best games I have thrown, but
they definitely make me happy and my teammates happy,'' said
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He continues to just make you shake your head,'' said Yankee
manager Joe Torre. ``He took control early, as did Maddux.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are so good, it's easy to forget they were
threatened once in the middle of the playoffs last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's true. The 125-win ``greatest team of the century'' New York
Yankees trailed Cleveland, two games to one, in the 1998 American
League Championship Series. Things turned around when El Duque went
to the mound at Jacobs Field and beat the Indians with seven
innings of three-hit pitching. It was his first postseason
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Since that Game 4 win, the Yankees have won an astounding 15 of
16 postseason games _ a monstrous streak interrupted only when
Pedro Martinez stuck it to Clemens and the Yankees at Fenway last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It looked for a time like El Duque might be a one-hit loser. The
Yankees trailed, 1-0, when Joe Torre sent Darryl Strawberry up to
hit for Hernandez in the eighth inning. It turned into a four-run
inning for the Yankees, making Hernandez a winner again.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about these Hernandez brothers in October. Two
years ago, Livan Hernandez was Most Valuable Player of the Florida
Marlins' World Series victory over the Indians. At that time, El
Duque was living in poverty in Cuba, unable to find a radio
broadcast of his brother's exploits.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out the side in the first, then did it again in the
third. With his high leg kick and impressive assortment of pitches,
he had the Braves off stride all night long, fanning four of them
twice. He is a worthy descendant of Cuban hurlers Camilo Pascual,
Mike Cuellar, and Luis Tiant _ all World Series veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought (Hernandez) and Maddux both threw great,'' said
Braves manager Bobby Cox, who was not happy with the work of plate
umpire Randy Marsh. ``Both pitchers were really throwing the ball
well and it was tough to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez made his only mistake in the fourth. After fanning
Bret Boone to start the inning, Hernandez grooved a fastball to
Chipper Jones. It was simple human error. Yankee catcher Jorge
Posada set up on the outside of the plate but Hernandez came inside
with a fastball and Jones sent it into the third deck in right
field. Hernandez immediately pointed to his own jersey, leaving no
doubt that he was at fault for the homer.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed only one base runner after the home run and
that was a walk to Jones in the seventh. Jones was erased
attempting to steal and the Yanks made Hernandez a winner with four
runs in the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
