<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6699 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-AZR &LR;      10-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO HAS WEIRDEST FIGHTS? IT'S NO CONTEST  
 PUNCH AFTER BELL ENDS TYSON'S LATEST FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ No contest.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   No more, please.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson's wayward path of anarchy continued to leave its
jagged scars on the remains of a proud sport Saturday night in a
fight with no result.
</P>
<P>
   The undisputed champ of nihilism proved again that there is no
end to all that is negative in a bout against Orlin Norris.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a Tyson comeback.
</P>
<P>
   It was.
</P>
<P>
   A self-proclaimed different man had come back as bad as ever.
</P>
<P>
   With referee Richard Steele standing between the two
heavyweights, Tyson threw a left hand after the bell sounded an end
to the first of a scheduled 10 rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Norris went down and apparently hurt his right knee as he fell.
That's how it ended, as boos and plastic cups poured from an angry
crowd of 12,801 at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Nevada State Athletic Commission, it was called
``no contest because of an `accidental' foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevada withheld Tyson's $10 million purse, pending an
investigation next week, according to Commission executive director
Marc Ratner. Norris was paid a reported $800,000 by Tyson's
promoter Dan Goosen.
</P>
<P>
   If the foul was accidental, why did Steele penalize Tyson by
deducting two points from a possible 10 on the judges' score cards?
</P>
<P>
   There was no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there never are explanations for the craziness that
Tyson (46-3, 40 knockouts) always seems to spawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He quit,'' Tyson yelled at the press section as he headed for
his dressing room. ``How did I hit him in the jaw and he hurt his
leg?''
</P>
<P>
   No explanation.
</P>
<P>
   But there also was no explanation from Tyson as to why he threw
a punch after the bell. Then again, Tyson never has been able to
explain why he bit Evander Holyfield's ears, or why he assaulted
two middle-aged men after a fender-bender in Maryland, or why, why,
who-oh-why.
</P>
<P>
   He always has lived by his own rules without any consideration
of conscience or cost.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Tyson expressed outrage about 30 minutes after the
last echoes of the last boo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody knows that, if you're competitive, you keep on
fighting, even if your leg is fractured,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson vowed there would be no second fight with Norris. But
Norris' contract also includes a clause for a rematch, which was
mentioned by Goosen moments after the latest chapter in the
unabridged, ongoing edition of Tyson trials and tribulations.
Believe it or not, Norris-Tyson II is a possibility for Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, Norris will have to recover from his apparent
knee injury. He was taken to Las Vegas' Valley Hospital, where he
was scheduled to undergo a magnetic resonance imaging test.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit me after the bell,'' said Norris, who, according to his
corner, had undergone surgery on his right knee a few years ago.
``I just went down on my knee the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   In another predictable reaction, neither Tyson nor Goosen
believed Norris was hurt at all. Goosen said it was clear from a
replay of the video that Norris walked back to his corner without a
limp after he climbed back to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have hurt himself when he sat down on his stool,''
Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   But ring physician Dr. Flip Homansky said Norris wasn't faking.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was swelling in the right knee, and it was stiff,'' said
Homansky, who examined Norris after trainer Abel Sanchez said his
fighter could not continue.
</P>
<P>
   Charge and counter-charge, examination and recrimination, and
all the rest would not have been necessary had Tyson not attacked
after a brief armistice had been declared.
</P>
<P>
   But the signs of anarchy were there all along. A couple of weeks
ago, Tyson announced he would bite all over again if necessary. He
didn't bite this time, but the effect was the same. His latest act
left a damaged sport looking a little more chewed up.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opening bell, drums pounded out a heavy, war-like
beat as Tyson marched to the ring dressed in his characteristic
black. The label on his sleeveless, Spartan T-shirt said Tyson
Gear.
</P>
<P>
   It rhymes with fear, which is what any fan of boxing should have
these days. This wasn't a requiem for a heavyweight. It was more
like an epitaph for a sport. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
