<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6700 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZ     10-24 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DOUBT ABOUT EL DUQUE'S GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - His life is a puzzle, full of high leg kicks and
side-arm deception. A true international man of mystery.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, he was simply Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   El Du-KKKKKKKKKK.
</P>
<P>
   You need no further proof. Orlando Hernandez may lie about his
age, prolong and proliferate a lie about his flight for freedom,
act like reporters are inquisitors sent by Castro. But he is a
remarkable big-game pitcher. One of the best ever to take the
mound, and you can look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Braves at Turner Field, Hernandez struck out 10
batters in seven innings. He gave up one hit, a solo home run by
Chipper Jones. He remains undefeated in the postseason, with five
victories in six career starts. And this is how dominant he's been:
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's virtuoso performance, Hernandez's postseason
ERA actually went up. All the way to 1.02.
</P>
<P>
   ``He continues to just make you shake your head,'' Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have been on cruise control for two seasons. But
there was one tenuous moment in the course of this dynasty, a
moment easily forgotten in the avalanche of victories.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's American League Championship Series, the Yankees
trailed the Indians 2 games to 1. Game 4 was in Cleveland. An upset
was in the air. Until Hernandez took the mound, shutting out the
Indians during seven innings. The Yankees have won 15 of 16
postseason games since.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say enough about El Duque tonight,'' the Yankees'
Paul O'Neill said. ``He pitched great. Again.''
</P>
<P>
   What to make of this man with a flair for the big stage and the
half-truth?
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows what happened the day after Christmas in
1997, the moment Hernandez and seven others fled Cuba. Originally,
the story placed Hernandez on a raft. Soon, he was holding an
orphan in one hand and fending off sharks with the other. Hollywood
was interested. A book-and-movie deal was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   That story was later amended. The raft became a boat. The kind
with a motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't know the size of the boat he came over on,''
Torre said. ``But whatever it was, it's still the fact that he had
to slide out of the country and hide somewhere and then be found.
It's not the way we got to the ballpark, I know that.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest: Hernandez claims he just turned 30. Except ``New
York'' ``Magazine'' unearthed court documents filed in Havana
regarding Hernandez's divorce, papers that say he was born in 1965.
Which makes him 34.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. The man can pitch. And at $1.85 million a season, he
could be the best bargain in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``His confidence is just so high right now,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   So Game 1 goes to the Yankees, a game that was all about
hurling. And not just because Tom Glavine was sick with a violent
flu strain that had his system working in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux, the Braves' surprise starter, was masterful for
most of the night. Hernandez threw 97 pitches, only one of them a
mistake. And if you ever needed proof that the designated hitter
needs to be abolished, this was the game.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott Brosius opened the pivotal eighth inning with a
single, Torre decided to lift Hernandez in favor of pinch-hitter
Darryl Strawberry. The move caught Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox
completely off guard. Cox had no reliever warming up, and
Strawberry coaxed a walk that blew the inning wide open.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful chess match. Even if it prevented Hernandez from
authoring a complete-game performance, the kind that could've
caught the attention of baseball historians. As it is, the effort
belongs on the second tier of World Series pitching gems. The shelf
right below Don Larsen's perfect game in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   There have been four one-hitters in World Series history, the
last in 1967. Hernandez could've had the fifth. Bob Gibson struck
out 17 in the 1968 World Series. Hernandez could've come close.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw good, I thought,'' a cranky Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Good?
</P>
<P>
   More like a mystery the Braves couldn't solve. A man who was a
nearly pitcher perfect. Again. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
