<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-BOX-TYSON-CASSTEVENS-     10-24 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON ONCE AGAIN CHEATS BOXING FANS WITH ANTICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS - The payoff at the ring toss booth is a Kewpie doll
or a big teddy bear.
</P>
<P>
   But what draws us to the seedy tent at the end of the midway?
The one painted with ornate illustrations of nature's oddities and
curiosities. Freaks. Geeks. Sword swallowers. Siamese twins.
</P>
<P>
   When the carny cries ````Hu''r-ry, ``Hu''r-ry, step right up!''
why do we?
</P>
<P>
   Curiosity. That's all it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, that's what Mike Tyson has become. A carnival sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked from his dressing room and into the glare of lights
Saturday night the rap music a pounding beat you could see the
anticipation on the grinning faces in the crowd. Among those at
ringside was actor Verne Troyer who played Dr. Evil's miniature
twin in the new Austin Powers movie. Looking up at Tyson, and down
at Troyer who is 32 inches tall, you thought of Dr. Evil's
admonition to his double.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Mini-Me, we do ``not'' gnaw on our kitty.''
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken question surrounding the ex champ hung above the
ring like the microphone the announcer used to introduce him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting out of the red corner. . .the youngest man ever to
win the heavyweight title. . .the explosive. . .the one and only. .
.''
</P>
<P>
   What was the glowering figure in a black trunks thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson's head has more rooms than the MGM Grand Hotel. What,
the audience wondered, will he do ``tonight''?``''
</P>
<P>
   What he did was give boxing which just thought it had run out of
black eyes another one.
</P>
<P>
   What he did was write another sorry chapter to a career in
decline and marked by endless controversy.
</P>
<P>
   What he did was cheat the public, again.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson hit Orlin Norris with a short left to the jaw ``after''
the bell sounded, ending the first round. Norris buckled, landing
on his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Richard Steele penalized Tyson, deducting two points.
</P>
<P>
   Norris returned to his corner. When he said his knee hurt and
couldn't continue the fight, three minutes old, was over, ruled a
``no contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Boos filled the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's $10 million purse is being withheld, pending an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The Baddest Man on the Planet is gone. He is mostly a curiosity
now, the lead actor in boxing's theater of the absurd. When it
comes to voyeuristic amusement the former heavyweight champion
isn't all that different from the carnival geek who bites the head
off a live chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in this same ring, Tyson lost his aura of
invincibility. He also lost _ forever _ the respect he once
commanded as a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   That summer night Tyson chewed off a piece of Evander
Holyfield's right ear, then took a bite of the left one. His
behavior was shocking, a low act, even for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Mills Lane only ``thought'' he had seen everything.
Biting? ``Once is bad enough,'' said Lane, now a black-robed TV
judge. ````Twice'' is dessert.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is a troubled soul. Tormented by demons. He assaulted a
beauty queen. Beat his ex wife. In and out of jail, he has made _
and lost _ millions.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nevada State Boxing Commission suspended him the
sanctioning body said Tyson was a ``disgrace to boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. A sport that sells public humiliation can't be disgraced.
Boxing is incapable of blushing. Tyson disgraced himself.
</P>
<P>
   What will he do next?
</P>
<P>
   What will he say?
</P>
<P>
   After the fight Tyson lay the blame for the fiasco on his
victim. In so many words he called Norris a coward. He said a
``real fighter'' would have continued. Tyson accepted none of the
blame, even though he threw the punch that was ruled an
``accidental'' foul.
</P>
<P>
   What next? What will he do? What will he say? History has taught
he may do, or say anything. At a recent news conference, Tyson
gazed out at his audience. ``I look up,'' he said in a soft flutey
voice that belongs in another body, ``and I possibly see perverts,
pedophiles, freaks and horrible fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   He called reporters ``dysfunctional drunks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I resent that,'' an Associated Press wit shot back, with mock
indignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not dysfunctional.''
</P>
<P>
   No, but boxing is.
</P>
<P>
   David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
