</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-GAME-1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT WITH SICK FEELING  
 BRAVES' BATS ALSO SEEM TO HAVE FLU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In what has become an all-too-familiar sight during
World Series games in the 1990s, the Atlanta Braves offense took
the night off again.
</P>
<P>
   Is it really any wonder why the Braves have just one World
Series championship to show for their otherwise fabulous seasons
during this decade?
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees hung around long enough to come back in the
eighth inning and beat the Braves, 4-1, in Game 1 of the World
Series on a crisp Saturday night at Turner Field. The home-field
advantage immediately shifted to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have to go out there and hit a little better,''
said Atlanta first baseman Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Using the simplest of street terms, ``No duh?''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Yankees starter Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez was as
sharp as ever, limiting the Braves to just one hit (a Chipper Jones
solo home run) while pitching seven magnificent innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hit against him the second time, I knew we weren't
scoring again,'' Atlanta starter Greg Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game that once again underscored the Braves'
inability to hit when it matters most, during the World Series.
Maddux, the surprise Atlanta starter after Tom Glavine came down
with a bad case of the flu, entered the game with a career 1.99 ERA
in four previous World Series starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' awe-inspiring trio of Maddux, Glavine and John
Smoltz now have a combined ERA of 2.01 in 19 World Series starts.
Despite those sterling numbers, Atlanta's big three starters have
just an 8-7 record to show for their World Series starts.
</P>
<P>
   What's it all mean? Mostly that Atlanta's offense isn't holding
up its end of the bargain in these Fall Classics.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, the fingers have to start being pointed toward
the offense, which managed just one other hit on this evening, a
one-out ninth inning single, against Yankees pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as though Atlanta's offense becomes lulled into a
false sense of security when one of their big three is on the
mound. It's a team that becomes much too pitching dependent once
the World Series starts.
</P>
<P>
   Once Jones hit his home run, a high arching drive down the right
field line in the fourth inning which also became the first World
Series home run ever hit at Turner Field, it was almost as though
Braves hitters said, ``All right Mad Dog (Maddux's nickname),
there's your run. Now go get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a game the Braves clearly let get away. They were six
outs from assuming a lead in the World Series when Maddux ran out
of magic and the Yankees bats came to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, pitching in a one run World Series game is mentally
tough, but not physically,'' Maddux said. ``If we win four more
games, then this one will be no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was definitely cruising along, holding a 1-0 lead, until
he hit some speed bumps in the eighth. He gave up a leadoff single
to last year's World Series MVP, Scott Brosius, before committing
what might have been his biggest mistake of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux walked pinch-hitter Darryl Strawberry, who entered the
game batting just .162 (6 for 37) against the four-time Cy Young
Award winner.
</P>
<P>
   An error then loaded the bases and Maddux, trying to waste a
pitch with an 0-2 count, didn't throw it poorly enough before Derek
Jeter lined a single to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's excitable closer, John Rocker, then gave up a two-run
single to Paul O'Neill, walked two of the next four batters and
finished the inning with the Braves trailing 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing unusual about a Maddux beating you 1-0,''
Yankees Manager Joe Torre said. ``It didn't surprise us once we got
a little crack there we were able to open it up. We've been a
patient ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's lineup, top to bottom, is not that intimidating. What
makes the Braves so difficult to beat is their pitching staff. But
when the offense isn't scoring, let alone hitting, it becomes a
much easier task to handle Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been tough to score in the post-season,'' Atlanta
shortstop Walt Weiss said. ``The ones who usually get here are here
because of pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   The clubs that win here, though, also mix in some offense, even
if it's a little, as evidenced by New York's six hits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
