<HEADLINE>
2ND-YEAR CENTER SENT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - At least he got to see his wife and kids for a week.
</P>
<P>
   But second-year center  &UR; Daniel Briere is headed back to the
minor leagues on Monday after officially being reassigned to the
Springfield Falcons on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny needs to get his ice time, and he can get that now in
Springfield,'' assistant general manager  &UR; Taylor Burke said.
``Hopefully, he can go there and dominate like he did two years
ago, which I'm sure he will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes didn't need to free up a spot on the roster. But
with
 &UR; Jeremy Roenick returning to the lineup Saturday after serving a
five-game suspension, the little ice time Briere was getting would
just melt away that much quicker.
</P>
<P>
   Briere, who started in the minors only a week after his second
child was born here in the Valley, was scoreless in five games with
the Coyotes. He was not available for comment, but he was expecting
the move. &QL; 
Moving up &QL; 
Left wing  &UR; Keith Tkachuk is two points shy of moving into third
place on the franchise's all-time scoring list. His third-period
assist Saturday night gave him 516, two behind  &UR; Paul MacLean.  &UR; Dale
Hawerchuk is the club's career leader with 929 points, followed by
 &UR; Thomas  &UR; Steen with 817.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk also is 12 penalty minutes shy of tying  &UR; Laurie Boschman
for the most in franchise history. Boschman ended his career with
the Winnipeg Jets with 1,338 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night in Edmonton, Tkachuk will move into sixth place
on the team's all-time games-played list, tying  &UR; Ron Wilson, now an
assistant coach in Springfield, who appeared in 536 games for the
Jets from 1979 to 1988. &QL; 
The Green light &QL; 
Center  &UR; Travis Green's point-scoring streak stopped at six games
and his goal-scoring streak, tied for the NHL high, ended at five
games.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's been quite a ride for the Coyotes newcomer, who says
he's ``just trying to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you're contributing, it's awesome,'' Green said.
``Winning is still the bottom line, but when you're winning and
contributing, it makes it even better. Like I've said, the puck
just seems to be jumping into the net right now.'' &QL; 
Getting untracked &QL; 
Defenseman  &UR; Teppo Numminen finally got his offense going. After
registering only one point _ an assist _ in his first seven games,
the ``Repo Man'' had three setups during the Coyotes' 6-3 win over
Los Angeles Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Bob Francis wants his blueliners to jump into the play
whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play against the other teams' top lines, I have to be
smart. I can't always think offense all the time. It's still
defense first,'' Numminen said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
