<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s BC-FBC-ARIZONA-OREGON-AZ     10-24 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-OREGON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DELIVER KICK IN TEETH TO ROSE BOWL HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - Arizona spent most of Saturday night flirting
with disaster, and the two finally left Arizona Stadium
hand-in-hand, whispering sweet lovelies in each other's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a mistake and the Wildcats probably made it in their 44-41
loss to Oregon in front of 55,251.
</P>
<P>
   It's a loss that will haunt the Wildcats (5-3, 2-2) for some
time, because it probably eliminates them from Rose Bowl
contention.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes ended about 11 p.m., when Oregon's Josh Frankel made
a 32-yard field goal with 1:04 left to give the Ducks (4-3, 2-2)
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had one last shot. Keith Smith barely missed receiver
Dennis Northcutt on a touchdown pass, forcing the Wildcats to try a
45-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McDonald, who had made just 1 of 9 field goals this season,
missed wide left with two seconds left. In contrast, Frankel,
playing because of starter Nathan Villegas' knee injury, made four
field goals Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats had more than 500 yards of offense (553) for the
fourth straight game, setting a school record. That's of no solace
now. The Wildcats know they started losing this game shortly after
kickoff at 7:24 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a mistake to be made, the Wildcats came up with
creative ways to do it. They gave up a safety on the first play of
the game and fumbled on the third. They missed an extra point and
drew numerous penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Their ``coverage'' teams never lived up to the title. Oregon had
207 yards in kickoff returns, a record for an Arizona opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon running back Reuben Droughns carried 45 times, a school
record, for 202 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that if Reuben ran that uch, we would have a good
chance,'' Oregon Coach Mike Bellotti said. ``We started to wear
them down in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all that, Arizona nearly won the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, who trailed, 21-7, in the first half, took a 34-27
lead early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Arizona could never contain the Ducks, who came back behind
the arm of backup quarterback Joey Harrington. He hit Tony Hartley
with a 36-yard touchdown pass that tied the game at 34 with 13:58
to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks later fumbled, giving Arizona possession at the Oregon
30. The Ducks stuffed Arizona on two plays, forcing a third-and-13.
</P>
<P>
   But running back Trung Canidate took a simple pass in the flat,
spun away from a defender and went 33 yards for the touchdown. The
extra point gave Arizona a 41-34 lead with 9:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected Oregon to be done, and the Ducks weren't.
Another long kickoff return gave them possession at their own 45. A
long run by Droughns and a 28-yard pass from Harrington to Hartley
set up a 3-yard touchdown run by Droughns, tying the game at 41
with 6:08 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats' problems arrived early and stayed late. On their
third offensive play, Northcutt set a Pac-10 record by catching a
pass in his 38th straight game. Then he fumbled the ball away to
the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats' special teams were awful and the defense looked
helpless early in the game trying to stop Droughns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they trailed the Ducks just 24-21 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The second half started nearly as badly for the Wildcats. Their
first drive ended when Smith was sacked, and the second one came to
an abrupt stop when Smith was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon started its first two drives of the half at Arizona's 35
and 25, but thanks to Arizona's defense, the Ducks came away with
just three points.
</P>
<P>
   They blocked a field goal on the first possession and limited
the Ducks to a 31-yard field goal on the second. Oregon led, 27-21,
but it could have been much worse for UA.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Arizona seemed prepared to regain the lead but
messed that up, too. Canidate took a pitchout and scored on a
60-yard run, tying the game at 27, with 7:06 left in the third
quarter. But McDonald missed his fourth extra point of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon threatened again on its next series, but cornerback David
Laudermilk came up with an interception at the Arizona 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats survived in the first half thanks to three big
offensive plays. Quarterback Ortege Jenkins scored on a 65-yard
run. Smith set up another touchdown with a 49-yard run. And
Northcutt took a reverse 80 yards for another score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
