<HEADER>
A6705 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-TYSON-WRITETHRU-L     10-24 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BIZARRE NIGHT FOR TYSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A disgusted woman who had paid God-knows how much to
see the fight summed it perfectly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that was a &AMP;%$ waste of time. And, of course, Mike Tyson
made it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This one, between Tyson and Orlin Norris, wasn't on par with the
ear-biting incident that ended his second fight with Evander
Holyfield. What could be? However, it had that remarkably bizarre
quality we've come to associate with Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The fight had gone only one round when Tyson landed a left hook
about a second or maybe two after the bell, Norris fell awkwardly
on his back, wrenched his right knee and said he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   It was ruled a no contest because of what referee Richard Steele
called an ``accidental foul'' before the end of four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   That was that.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's latest comeback fight fizzled almost before it started
before a incredulous crowd of 12,081 at the MGM Grand on Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The moment Jimmy Lennon Jr. announced the result, a tremendous
chorus of boos reverberated in the spacious indoor arena followed
by angry chants and nasty comments that shouldn't be printed here.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, convinced Norris could continue because he had walked to
his corner with little or no problem, was himself disgusted and
threatened to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired,'' said Tyson, whose $10 million purse was withheld
by the Nevada State Athletic Commission, while Norris received his
$800,000. ``I don't even want to fight no more, I'm tired of this
(garbage). I gave my best, I just came to give a good show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just tired of this, I'm just tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was serious about quitting, he said: ``I really
want to.''
</P>
<P>
   The first... er, only round was largely uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson (46-3, with 40 knockouts) did some of the things his
trainers had hoped he'd do after a nine-month layoff because of a
three-month stint in prison _ fight relatively patiently, move his
head, jab.
</P>
<P>
   He also threw the big bombs we've also come to associate with
him. Not one hit its mark, although it seemed only a matter of time
before one did.
</P>
<P>
   Norris (50-5, 27 KOs) also did what he set out to do: punch on
the move, don't stand in one place too long as Francois Botha did
when Tyson knocked him out in his last fight, in January.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if it might be an interesting fight. And then it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, himself no stranger to controversy, had warned Tyson
about hitting on the break. And then Tyson _ who said he didn't
hear the bell _ did it again moments after the first three minutes
expired, knocking Norris flat.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it appeared Norris was hurt by the punch, but he
quickly got to his feet and went to his corner, where he sat down
on his stool. If he had injured his knee, it wasn't immediately
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Steele then informed Tyson he took two points away from him for
the foul and it appeared the fight would continue.
</P>
<P>
   However, Norris and/or his handlers said the knee wouldn't allow
it and the fight was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, perhaps not aware of exactly what transpired, reacted
angrily and was surrounded by his handlers, who calmed him down as
security guards _ ready for anything at a Tyson fight _ quickly
surrounded the ring to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   In so many words, Tyson called Norris a coward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have more to (complain) about than I do,'' he said
in a calm moment. ``The reality of the situation is that he
could've got up and continued to fight. I put the heat on him and
he didn't want to continue. I heard he would come to fight. But the
way he conducted himself, he should feel bad about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real fighter fights until he can't fight no more,'' he
continued. ``Against Buster Douglas, I could've quit. Against
Evander Holyfield (in the first fight), I could've quit. I took my
beating like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Was Norris, who was taken to a local hospital and unavailable
for comment, really hurt?
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Flip Homansky, the ring doctor, said Norris told him after
he sat on his stool for several minutes that he felt pain and
stiffness. Homansky said the knee had begun to swell.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the fact Norris appeared to walk to his corner
with what he said was only a slight limp is consistent with
subsequent pain and swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time for the swelling to occur, then the pain comes
afterward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, executive director of the Athletic Commission, said
Tyson's purse was withheld pending review of the fight on Monday. A
commission meeting to address the situation will follow. The issue
is whether the foul was intentional or accidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was called an accidental foul,'' Ratner said. ``We just
want to look at the films, we want to make sure exactly what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   And what might be next for Tyson?
</P>
<P>
   Said Dan Goossen, Tyson's promoter: ``We just want to get past
this. Then we'll talk about what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In preliminary bouts, heavyweight contender David Tua showed
former Canadian champion Shane Sutcliffe why he's considered one of
the most dangerous fighters in the world, ending their scheduled
10-round bout with one left hook at 1:20 of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Sutcliffe (21-9-1, 12 KOs), who landed awkwardly on his hands
and knees, made it to his feet but referee Jay Nady spared him
further punishment by stopping the mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have respect for the guy (Sutcliffe), but I had no respect
for his power,'' said Tua, a native of Samoa who fights out of New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The referee did a good job stopping the fight. He was
disappointed, but the referee ... didn't want to see him get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Tua (35-1, 20 KOs) is seeking an opportunity to fight the winner
of the Nov. 13 Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight but might not
be high on either's list of prospective opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Featherweight contender Augie Sanchez (23-1, 20 KOs) put down
Daniel Jimenez (27-8-1, 14 KOs) twice with body punches and Jiminez
stayed down the second time.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled 10-round bout was stopped at 1:41 of the sixth
round.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Dokiwari (15-1, 13 KOs) outpointed Agustin Corpus (7-4-2,
seven KOs) in a six-round heavyweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   And undefeated junior welterweight contender Zab Judah had an
usual evening: He fought two three-round exhibitions against
separate fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He dominated both Joaquin Gallardo, whom he dropped, and Manuel
Gomez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
