<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MISS-MILLENNIUM25-COX     10-24 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-MILLENNIUM25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millennium concerns without weight, professor says
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Admit it.
</P>
<P>
   As you chuckle at TV reports of survivalists packing off to
their desert bunkers with shotgun shells and rations, you are
contemplating how much cash to withdraw from the ATM in late
December and whether you need a couple of extra frozen pizzas to
get through the New Year's Day football games.
</P>
<P>
   After all, surely the end of civilization as we know it won't
mean the end of football, too. Then you hit the remote, drift off
to sleep in your recliner and forget any doomsday thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas history Professor Howard Miller understands
your ambivalence. After at least three years of public
hand-wringing about a computer bug, Miller suspects as many
Americans are as Y2K complacent as they are compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long time for the American attention span,'' says
Miller, an award-winning teacher whose research includes pre-Civil
War history and American religion. ``We don't do attention span
well. I sense we're getting millennium fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller sees the intersection of secular society's Y2K fears with
America's religious history of expecting the apocalypse: the
ultimate triumph of Christian good over evil in a final judgment
and the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although Miller dreads another millennium list almost as much as
the apocalypse, we offer a list gleaned from his 75-minute lecture
to a university audience last week. If you're still not sure what
to think of the passing of another 1,000 years, here's everything
you need to know about the millennium in the Ultimate Millennium
List:
</P>
<P>
   10. The math is wrong. In the mid-sixth century, a monk named
Dionysius Exiguus, or Dennis the Short (seriously), created a
chronology of human history for a pope. It became the calendar for
Western Civilization, counting down time before Jesus Christ's
birth (B.C.) and then counting each year from the birth (A.D.).
Only problem is, Miller says, most historians believe Dennis the
Short missed Christ's birth by at least four years. ``The
millennium was 1996,'' says Miller gleefully. ``We missed it!''
</P>
<P>
   9. The math is wrong, Part II. Dennis the Short had no concept
of zero in his calendar. He called the first year after Jesus's
birth 1, not 0. So by Jesus' first birthday, the world was entering
its second year. Since then, the centuries ended in '00 as did the
first millennium, 1000 A.D. The second millennium _ 2,000 years
after the birth of Jesus _ actually ends more than a year from now,
Dec. 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   8. Pop culture rules. Despite the mathematical glitches, Miller
expects us to party like it's 1999. In his 1981 hit, The Artist
Formerly Known as Prince opted for a Jan. 1, 2000, beginning for
the millennium. Miller says pop culture _ and the news media that
celebrates it _ has fallen in line. He blames our fascination with
automobiles and their odometers: ``No intellectual explanation
about Dennis the Short's mistake is going to win out over the
fascination of seeing all of those nines turn into zeros.'' The
most notable exception in pop culture is Arthur C. Clarke's
futuristic movie _ ``2001: A Space Odyssey.'' It was made in 1968,
ancient history by pop standards.
</P>
<P>
   7. Pop culture rules, Part II. Hollywood already has had its say
on the subject. In the summer of 1998, ``Deep Impact'' and
``Armageddon'' made hundreds of millions of dollars with
end-of-the-world themes. ``For good or ill, folks, these two summer
flicks may be all we get in the way of marking the millennium,''
Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   6. An apocalypse is hard to predict. Since Jesus ascended into
heaven, Miller says Christians have been waiting for the Second
Coming when Christ is to judge the world. In the early 11th
century, a monk named Radulfus Glabor, or Ralph the Bald (another
monk-nomer), sensed a quickening in the religious life of western
Europe and believed there was an increasing number of floods,
earthquakes and volcanic eruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller says the church had paid little attention to the passing
of the first millennium, but Ralph speculated that the Second
Coming might come in 1033 _ the millennium of Christ's death. It
didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 19th century America, evangelist William Miller
predicted Jesus would return Oct. 22, 1843. As many as 50,000
Americans sold their earthly goods to prepare. When the Second
Coming didn't occur, many believers fell away in disbelief. Others,
however, accepted Miller's explanations for the failed prophecy and
founded the Seventh-day Adventist Church.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Miller says a young evangelist, Billy Graham, made
his reputation by focusing on the imminent return of Jesus. In
1968, a best seller, ``The Late Great Planet Earth'' by Hal
Lindsey, resurrected interest in apocalyptic language and thinking.
Miller says a basic fact of apocalyptic tradition is, ``It has over
the centuries been impervious to repeated failure of prophecy.''
</P>
<P>
   5. The Chinese think it's the Year of the Rabbit. Not everyone
counts time by Dennis the Short's calender and there are several
billion non-Christians who are not expecting a second visit from
Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   4. Our ancestors really didn't pay much attention to the passing
of centuries. Miller says the Catholic Church took little note of
the passing of the First Millennium: ``There were no church-wide
observances, no predictions that the world would come to the end.
In fact, the Pope took very little notice at all until the
millennial year was upon him.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, the first record of someone celebrating the turn of
a century, was on Jan. 1, 1701, Miller says. Judge Samuel Sewall of
Boston hired four trumpet players to blast in the 18th century in
the town square. About the same time, Americans began celebrating
their own birthdays. It was the French, at the end of the 19th
century, who raised thinking about the passage of time to a
movement. For about a decade, French intellectuals debated the
nature of changes in western Civilization as Jan. 1, 1901
approached. (The French elite remained fastidious about a century
actually having 100 years.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Thank God for Y2K. Before we modernists get too smug about
Dennis the Short's bad math, it should be remembered that a group
of Dennis the Menaces who created the first computers were a couple
of digits short. They programed their inventions to count the year
2000 as 00 _ or is that 1900? Without the Y2K debate, Miller
speculates that we only would take a bemused, detached notice of
the millennium's passing. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 12:00 midnight on Dec. 31, 1999, something real is going to
happen,'' Miller says. ``The clocks in those computers are going
either to turn over or they are not. And I bet you most of us are
going to be awake to see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says society's response will teach us more about
ourselves than just the turning of a millennium would have.
</P>
<P>
   2. Panic is possible. Miller says he fears less that the
computers won't work than that the news media will. Looking for the
next big story, the news media may focus too much on any glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K will then become a story that feeds on itself,'' Miller
says.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe that Americans can't panic easily. Miller points
to Orson Welles' 1938 radio broadcast of ``The War of the Worlds.''
Thousands sought refuge in cellars, jammed highways and tied up
telephone lines when they wrongly thought the dramatic program was
real news coverage of a Martian invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mass panic in a society tied together as firmly as we are
could get real messy real quick,'' Miller says.
</P>
<P>
   1. Stop the presses. In the end, all we may have are these lists
of the greatest this and the greatest that of the past 1,000 years.
If the computers work, the millennium may be poured out as quickly
as flat champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting bored with it,'' Millers insists.
</P>
<P>
   But he can't resist telling his audience of a cable channel's
designation of ``Person of the Millennium'' out of 100 nominees.
According to A&AMP;E, the Biography Channel, it's Johann Gutenberg, a
German printer who reputedly was the first European to print with
movable type.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares?'' challenges Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, professor, Gutenberg is a no-brainer. Have you ever tried
to do a list without a printing press?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
