<P>
   FALLING FROM THE SKY
</P>
<P>
   Part Two of a six-part investigative series by The Dayton Daily
News on the the recent rise in military air crashes and their
causes. The Daily News found that the U.S. military routinely sends
planes and helicopters in the air that it knows are plagued with
deadly safety problems. The series is based in part on
never-before-seen information from three databases from the Army,
Navy and Air Force safety centers.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-METAL _ A type of metal is in the middle of an
investigation involving a series of crashes of the Army's CH47
Chinook helicopter. The story came to light when a whistle-blower,
working at a former factory in Springfield, Ohio, found flaws in a
metal used to construct gears that power the helicopter's huge
rotor blades. Investigators now suspect that seven crashes may be
linked to the metal. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MISS-MILLENNIUM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ We missed the millennium, UT
Prof Howard Miller reminds us. Historians differ on when Christ was
born, but the most generally accepted date, historian Miller says
is minus-4 BC. That means we should have celebrated in 1996. Or in
2001. Anyway, Dec. 31, 1999 is definitely not the dawn of a new
millennium. But Miller, who has made a study of such things, says
that popular culture has taken a hold of this and that, along with
the Y2K computer bug and religious-based jitters about the end of
the millennium, has everyone in this tizzy. A step-back look at
what is about to befall us. (Copelin, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HAM-SHORTAGE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There's a worldwide
shortage of hams. Not those canned pork products, and not theater
bugs, but rather those amateur radio enthusiasts who, during
emergencies, are often the only links to ravaged areas. (Kleinberg,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-TRAINING _ WASHINGTON _ In a report from the American
Council on Education, college and university presidents say they
will start major reforms in teacher education programs. The report
coincides with the recommendations long pushed by Education
Secretary Richard Riley and comes less than a week after NCATE, the
organization that accredits teacher education departments, also
announces tougher tests for teacher licensing. (Mollison, Cox News
Service)
</P>
