<P>
   GERMANY-DIVIDED (Frankfurt an der Oder) _ A woman who moved from
west Germany to east Germany after the fall of the Berlin Wall has
written a book about the stubborn divide that still exits between
the two parts of the country. 1,800 words. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   TESTBAN-MONITORS (Undated) _ A case of international jitters has
broken out over whether the Senate's rejection of the nuclear test
ban treaty will end up pulling the plug on the half-built,
$250-million system of 321 monitoring stations meant to police the
treaty for clandestine blasts. 1,300 words. By William E. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Ingushetia) _ Interview with the leader of this
republic about the flood of refugees from Chechnya and what he
thinks the government of Russia is up to. 1,200 words. By Celestine
Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-GOVGEN (Ottawa) _ The fairy-tale rise of Adrienne
Clarkson, 60, from wartime refugee to the nation's first immigrant
governor general has captivated Canada, created a storm of
controversy, and pumped fresh blood into monarchism in Canada.
1,300 words. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ President Abdurrahman Wahid
presented his vision for Indonesia on Sunday as a tolerant,
democratic nation with rising living standards that can reclaim its
place of respect in the international community. 800 words. By Seth
Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-VOTE (Buenos Aires) _ With polls indicating that
Argentines are looking for some changes, presidential elections are
taking place. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S.-ASSESS (Nairobi, Kenya) _ As Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright visited six African nations last week, her twin
goals seemed to be to reassure Africans that the United States was
still interested in the continent's affairs and to persuade
Congress that Africa mattered. 1,200 words. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
