   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-BLACKS-EDUC (Providence, R.I.) _ At a time when many
colleges are cutting back on minority recruitment, Brown University
is going the extra mile to woo black students from the South with
free train rides, among other things. 1300 words. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BERKELEY (Berkeley, Calif.) _ In the midst of California's
latest gold rush, here's a city looking for lead. As high-tech
companies sprout on all sides, this city of 107,000 people and
roughly as many political causes is making a concerted effort to
preserve its low-tech core. In the process, Berkeley has managed to
deter the one industry that most of the nation's municipalities are
scrambling to attract. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-GROWER-WOES (Entiat, Wash.) _ Wide agreement about the
outstanding quality of this year's crop in the nation's top
apple-producing state belies the disturbing news: no one here seems
to be making any money growing apples. Hammered by factors that
include stagnant domestic demand, consolidation in the grocery
industry that gives large buyers the upper hand in determining
price, and a flood of imported apples from China, growers here say
they are facing some of the worst economic times in their memory.
1600 words. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-ED-EDUC (Undated) _ As the nation struggles to train
more than 2.5 million new teachers over the next decade, college
and university presidents must pay more attention and devote
increasing resources to schools of education, a leading
higher-education group argues in a new report. 850 words. By Jodi
Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S.-MURDER (Jerusalem) _ Maryland resident sentenced in
Israel to 24 years in murder. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   FISCAL-POLICY (Washington) _ All the arguing over the budget is
camouflage around a striking new feature of federal fiscal policy:
most of the prospective surpluses are going to go to paying off the
$5.5-trillion debt. It's almost a political accident, but it has
huge repercussions. Indeed, it's the most fundamental development
in fiscal policy of the past decade, dramatically reshaping
economic policy with hardly any explicit and substantive debate.
1500 words. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SPERLING-PROFILE (Washington) _ A profile of Gene Sperling, top
White House economic policy aide. 900 words. By Robin Toner.
</P>
