<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-TEACHER-TRAINING-     10-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TEACHER-TRAINING-1025 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE PRESIDENTS TOLD TO REVAMP TEACHER TRAINING
 &HT;    275&AMP;adds
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ College presidents should put their own houses in
order by improving or eliminating their teacher education programs,
according to a new report from the influential American Council on
Education.
</P>
<P>
   More public school students, especially in big cities, would be
taught by highly qualified teachers within five to 10 years if the
council's plan is widely adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public expects colleges and universities to prepare
teachers who are knowledgeable about what they teach and proficient
in how they teach,'' says the report, to be mailed Monday to the
presidents of some 1,800 colleges and universities who belong to
the council. ``College presidents must take the lead in fulfilling
this expectation,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   Many post-secondary institutions see teacher education as
profitable, but marginal programs ``to be treated with benign
neglect,'' the report said. It warned that the reputation of an
institution will suffer unless its teacher education program is
either ``moved to the center _ or moved out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is right on target,'' said Sandra Feldman,
president of the American Federation of Teachers. ``The reforms it
calls for are long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley, who summoned dozens of
college presidents to Washington last month to nudge them into
taking a bigger role in public school reforms, said he hopes they
will implement the new report.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared by the council's Task Force on Teacher
Education. Dominated by college presidents and chancellors, the
36-member task force also included a sprinkling of academic
leaders, school superintendents and state education officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The task force was blunt in spelling out signs that the teacher
preparation at the council's colleges and universities isn't up to
snuff:
</P>
<P>
   _ Too many teachers aren't competent to teach their assigned
subjects or to apply technology to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most education departments operate on their own, without
academic quality control. They don't seek outside review or
accreditation and don't get supervision from their parent
institution or cooperation from its other departments, such as
those within colleges of arts and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   _ Too many teacher education programs aren't coordinated with
the community colleges that feed in many of their applicants, or
with the school systems in which their graduates will work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most education majors who become middle or high school
teachers have only average academic records, and those who become
elementary teachers have poorer academic records than their peers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Only two-thirds of education graduates go immediately into
teaching, and half of all new teachers leave the profession within
five years.
</P>
<P>
   The report placed part of the blame on public schools. The
schools, it found, offer low teacher salaries, hire uncertified
teachers and assign unqualified teachers to more than half the math
and science classes in middle and high schools. It also criticized
federal government for not spending more on research into how to
better teach teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast bulk of the report called for the college
presidents to clean up their own school's problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the presidents were advised to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mandate a campus-wide review of the quality of students,
faculty, courses and accountability of their teacher education
program.
</P>
<P>
   _ Obtain public, independent appraisals of their teacher
education program at regular intervals from a national accrediting
body or an outside ``board of visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Require the arts and science faculty and the education faculty
to coordinate their curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   _ Craft agreements that mesh their education courses with those
at other colleges and universities, because most of today's
students transfer schools at least once.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create programs to support, monitor and mentor their recent
graduates, and strengthen professional development programs for
experienced teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report tracks what we've been doing and saying'' at the
nation's largest teacher union, said spokeswoman Kathleen Lyons at
the National Education Association. But, she said, ``the one thing
that's missing is any reference to NCATE.''
</P>
<P>
   NCATE, the National Council for Accreditation of Teacher
Education, is an established organization whose supporters include
the NEA. It accredits nearly half of the nation's 1,200 schools of
teacher education.
</P>
<P>
   Most don't seek accreditation, but a few dozen are considering
accreditation by a new rival group in which teachers would have
less of a say.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
