<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JUNKMAIL-AD-COLUMN-2T     10-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNKMAIL-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE THE INTERNET, DIRECT-MAIL MARKETERS GROW EVEN MORE
PROLIFIC
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Md., Ill.)  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``check'' is in the mail. So too are the ``important
national survey,'' the ``Priority Express Gram'' and other
``time-sensitive material'' that is ``personal and confidential''
as well as ``extremely urgent.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the phrase ``You've got mail'' evokes images of
virtual correspondence, the old-fashioned, ink-and-paper
counterpart _ replete with the plethora of puffery quoted above _
is alive and well as marketers keep waging war on consumers'
mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   The barrage of letters, catalogs and brochures that typifies the
advertising medium known as direct mail continues unabated,
peddling everything from magazines and computers to apparel and
political candidates. Alive and well? That's an understatement _
and something you rarely find in direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, direct mail, still widely dismissed with the sobriquet
``junk mail,'' is proliferating faster than it did before the
Internet, climbing to 44 percent of all pieces of mail handled last
year by the post office from 41 percent a decade ago and 32 percent
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming an information-loaded world and there's a
minimal amount of attention span,'' said Barbara Weckstein
Kaplowitz, editor of The DeLay Letter in Potomac, Md., a
publication that covers the direct marketing industry. ``But direct
mail is still working for many marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Direct Marketing Association, the industry's
trade organization, direct mail generated $421.2 million in sales
last year, an increase of 8 percent from $390 million in 1997 _ and
a gain of 62 percent from $260.2 million as recently as 1992. The
average compound annual growth rate of direct mail, at 8.4 percent
from 1992 through 1997, is projected to accelerate to 8.6 percent
from 1997 through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``If direct mailers go back to people who asked two years ago to
be removed from their lists and say, `We have something new; would
you like to hear about it?,' those are the best responders,'' Ms.
Kaplowitz said. ``They realize they miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most consumers, weary of the battle of the bulging mailbox _ and
disgusted with materials they deem misleading from companies trying
to sell magazine subscriptions _ might say they would miss getting
direct mail the way they would miss getting bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me started!,'' warned Bob Bulmash, founder and
president of Private Citizen Inc., in Naperville, Ill., an
organization that fights what he considers the considerable
excesses of direct mailers and telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk mail is not going to slow down,'' Bulmash asserted. ``As
long as a marketing channel is there, it will continue to be
abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the industry would take issue with that castigation.
Direct mail was once ``pretty intrusive,'' acknowledged Howard
Draft, chairman and chief executive at Draft Worldwide in Chicago,
the world's largest direct marketing agency. ``But now we're trying
to understand what a consumer's needs are and create an
invitational approach.''
</P>
<P>
   His agency, a unit of the  &UR; Interpublic Group  &LR; of Companies,
creates direct marketing campaigns for giant advertisers like
American Express, Compaq Computer, General Motors and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, direct mail seeks to communicate with consumers
who have bought a product in the first place,'' Draft said, ``to
build loyalty to encourage future purchases.'' That approach, meant
to keep the most profitable customers and minimize or even shed the
less lucrative ones, is a departure from the industry's onetime
ploy of blanketing consumers with mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion of mass mailings, which used to be the rule, has
become the exception,'' said Ian Baer, recently named president of
the Chicago office of Rapp Collins Worldwide, the agency owned by
 &UR; Omnicom Group &LR;  that handles direct marketing assignments for a
client roster that includes the online retail operations of Barnes
&AMP; Noble, Pfizer, the U.S. Navy and Western Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans receive more unsolicited mail than any other people
in the world,'' Baer said. ``They're jaded. They lack the time and
patience and inclination to go through mail they didn't ask for.
</P>
<P>
   ``So to get them to open a piece of mail, we have to take our
efforts to a whole new level of relevancy,'' he added, ``because
with all the clutter, people will focus only on what they consider
most relevant to them.''
</P>
<P>
   To make direct mail more relevant _ and thus more effective _
advertisers and agencies are intensifying their efforts to
customize the pitches they send consumers. The aim: to deliver
pleas as personalized and tailored as possible to appeal to the
intended recipients and minimize the anger generated by receiving
unwanted, unnecessary communication.
</P>
<P>
   That is, needless to say, also the goal of Internet marketing,
which many experts describe as an updated, high-technology version
of direct mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The common phrase we're hearing is that the Internet is
`direct marketing on steroids,''' said H. Robert Wientzen,
president and chief executive of the Direct Marketing Association,
which is based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet allows targeting in a more efficient way,'' he
added, ``but ink on paper still provides a sensory experience and
still does a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret is to build a relationship by providing people with
relevant information,'' said Wientzen, who is in Toronto this week
at the association's 82nd annual conference and exhibition, which
15,000 people are expected to attend. ``The fact we're growing at
more than twice the rate of retail sales says the consumer
appreciates the efficiency and convenience of shopping at a
distance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The computer technology that makes the Internet possible is also
helping direct marketers in their quest for the grail of relevancy
by making it easier than ever to compile extensive information
about consumers before any mail is sent.
</P>
<P>
   ```Data mining' is the term _ collecting, over time, information
that allows you to figure out what people want and like and do,''
Wientzen said. ``Our path in the information age is finding the
ability to market to niches, which was never economically feasible
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The data miners gather their information from the consumers
themselves, poring over records of what was already bought and
ordered: how recently, how frequently, how much was spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch what happens when you can accurately match an e-mail
address to a street address,'' said Ms. Kaplowitz, the newsletter
editor. ``They'll know not only how you act in the mail but how you
act online.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And direct mailers comb through data from outside sources like
mailing lists, postal records, government agencies and other
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we're doing is using information we have on our customers,
with overlays of demographic or psychographic information, to
enhance our knowledge of them and market back to them,'' said Draft
of Draft Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data bases are being used to target customers who really
have a need for a product,'' he added. ``What brings results today
is the unique selling proposition you're making to make the
consumer want this product.''
</P>
<P>
   Baer at Rapp Collins offered an example for a client, Western
Union, which differentiates campaigns aimed at Spanish-speaking
customers based on their countries of origin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominican-Americans are more established, often
second-generation, sending money to relatives back home,'' Baer
said, ``while Colombian-Americans are more likely to be
first-generation, sending money back to their families and then
going back themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But privacy advocates complain that data mining is more
insidious, the marketing equivalent of strip mining.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to fight back,'' Bulmash of Private Citizen said,
offering these tactics: ``Keep your name and phone number off all
documents, as best you can. Don't fill out sweepstakes cards. Don't
subscribe to magazines; buy them on the newsstand. Don't list your
address in the phone book.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumers seeking to have their names removed from mailing lists
can do so by sending their names, home addresses and signatures to:
Mail Preference Service, Direct Marketing Association, P.O. Box
9008, Farmingdale, N.Y. 11735-9008. (Yes, you must use the mail to
reduce the mail; about 3.4 million people have registered to date.)
</P>
<P>
   The association, sensitive to the rising tide of complaints, has
strengthened its privacy policies, with stipulations called the
Privacy Promise to American Consumers taking effect July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all industries, we do have shady operators who push the
line too far,'' said Weintzen, adding: ``We don't want to lose the
trust of the American people. If people don't like what you do,
they don't buy from you.''
</P>
<P>
   The new policies did not impress Bulmash, who dismissed them as
toothless because they involve the industry regulating itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dog says, `I'll be good,' but he's not going to hit himself
with a stick if he's bad,'' Bulmash said. ``You've got to teach him
to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other protests are being heard from the advertising research
industry, which is furious about a venerable direct mail gimmick:
cloaking a pitch as a survey, pretending that the purpose of a
letter is to seek opinions rather than sell a product or raise
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sham, it's dishonest and it does the survey-research
business a tremendous disservice,'' said Jim Spaeth, president of
the Advertising Research Foundation in New York. ``Refusals to
participate in legitimate surveys have been rising slowly and this
certainly is a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drives me crazy is sometimes these are organizations I'm
a member of and believe in,'' he added, referring to the
fund-raisers that sell under the guise of research. The foundation
even has a name for such trickery, ``frugging''; there's also
``sugging,'' for selling under the guise of research.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There's one consolation for consumers tired of make-believe
surveys, envelopes festooned with starbursts and addressed with
simulated handwriting and letters with underlined sentences and a
``P.S.'' at the end that looks to be an afterthought but isn't.
Those gimmicks are likely to begin fading away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we put material out there, that's the client's
brand in the home,'' said Draft of Draft Worldwide. ``You will not
see the kind of clients we work with allow us to negatively affect
the work they're doing in their general brand advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starbursts, underlining, the `P.S.' _ those don't affect
results that much,'' he added. ``If you come up with the big idea,
the big offer, that's what drives business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
