<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      10-24 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULING WOES END FOR `N.Y.P.D. BLUE' 
WRESTLING IS MAKING UPN A COMPETITOR  
 TIME PLANS TO BREAK ITS NEWS-ONLY SHELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Under pressure from the news media, fans and the outspoken
executive producer Steven Bochco, ABC Entertainment executives had
to make an almost Solomonic decision about whether the perennial
hit ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' should be knocked from its longtime slot on
Tuesday at 10 p.m. in favor of a promising new drama, the
touchy-feely ``Once and Again.'' They came up with what all sides
described as the best possible solution to the scheduling problem.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Bloomberg, the chairman of ABC Entertainment, announced on
Friday that, starting in January, ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' would be back
on Tuesday at 10, and `'Once and Again,'' which had played there
this fall, would move to Mondays at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' was supposed to move back in November, but ABC
had considered moving it elsewhere to keep ``Once and Again'' on
Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said, ``It just took some time to find the smartest
possible schedule.'' He noted that pushing ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' back
to a January start date meant the series would be able to run for
the rest of the television season without repeats. The show has
never repeated well.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco also pointed out that ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' now would face
repeats on other networks in March and April. Without repeats and
facing weaker competition, ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' stands an excellent
chance of scoring an improved overall rating for the season. ``It
may be a blessing in disguise,'' Bochco said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he made it clear that he had been extremely unhappy about
ABC's considering a move for his show.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg said ABC had only been concerned about fashioning the
best possible schedule and he denied that ABC's wrestling with the
decision had anything to do with a desire to protect ``Once and
Again'' because the network's parent company, Walt Disney, had an
ownership stake in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco, however, said, ``I can't believe that wasn't a factor,''
adding that he understood the nature of the television business
today demands that companies try to protect shows in which they
have a financial interest.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling Is Making UPN a Competitor
</P>
<P>
   ``Action'' may have been the most talked about, most publicized
and most debated new show of the television season, but when put in
the ring against a bunch of big, sweaty wrestlers, the new Fox
comedy has found itself slammed into submission.
</P>
<P>
   As it has so many times before, a wrestling program has defied
all expectations and proved to be a potent draw for young men. And
it has happened on the fledgling network, UPN, which was widely
being written off last year at this time as the one network too
many for the broadcasting industry.
</P>
<P>
   UPN's ``Smackdown,'' a weekly two-hour extravaganza of
wrestling, has so buried the new, heavily promoted Fox comedy that
it might soon be retitled ``In-Action.'' Last Thursday,
``Smackdown'' had its best rating ever, finishing third among six
networks, while ``Action'' fell to a level usually reserved for the
shows that do not make it on WB or UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Action,'' the comedy about a mean-spirited, high-strung
Hollywood producer, came in sixth and dead last among the six
networks on Thursday nights at 9 p.m. to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to ``Action'' would seem to be directly
related to how successful ``Smackdown'' has been for UPN. Fox, a
unit of the News Corp., consciously scheduled the comedy where it
did because last year the network had enormous success running
male-oriented specials like ``World's Scariest Police Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   But wrestling has spoiled all those plans. While UPN has been
recording increases in that time slot of 755 percent among male
teen-agers and 375 percent among men between the ages of 18 and 34,
Fox has seen its ratings drop every week. ``Family Guy'' was yanked
from the air after just two weeks, and ``Action'' was left to fight
alone, with two episodes (one a repeat) facing off against
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale, according to Fox executives, was that ``Action''
appealed to a more sophisticated audience than wrestling. Perhaps
so, but since when did Fox aim for the PBS audience?
</P>
<P>
   Now Fox executives have announced they will pull the comedy for
November, a ratings sweep month when the numbers are even more
important for the networks and their affiliated stations. It will
be back in December.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Time Plans to Break Its News-Only Shell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The future of the weekly news magazine may not lie in, well,
reporting weekly news. Beginning next Monday, in five special
issues whose theme is the future, Time magazine will publish a
serialized novel by Caleb Carr, a writer of historical thrillers.
Bertelsmann's Random House is currently negotiating with Carr to
publish the book in the fall of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Isaacson, Time's managing editor, and James Kelly, the
deputy managing editor, said they were fans of Carr's novels, both
of which _ ``The Alienist'' and ``The Angel of Darkness'' _ have
been set in the past. ``Walter and I decided it would be really
cool for a novelist to write a fiction series for us, just like in
Dickens' day, but about the future,'' Kelly said. He said that
Time, a Time Warner unit, had published excerpts from fiction
before, but had never published an entire novel in serial form.
</P>
<P>
   David Abrahamson, a professor of media studies at Northwestern
University's Medill School of Journalism, said he could not
remember the last time a weekly news magazine had published
serialized fiction. ``You'd have to go back two or three decades,
and you'd have to be somewhat generous in your definition of a news
weekly,'' Abrahamson said. ``You'd have to include things like Look
or Life or The Saturday Evening Post.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone of Carr's novel is decidedly more Raymond Chandler
than, say, Margaret Carlson, Time's political columnist. The first
chapter introduces the aggrieved widow of a media titan: ``From the
first it was obvious that she was deeply upset, and I tried to be
as gentle as possible as I led her to a chair. She asked in a
hushed tone if I was indeed Dr. Gideon Wolfe; assured that I was,
she informed me that she was Mrs. Vera Price, and I recalled
instantly that she was the wife of a certain John Price, who'd been
one of the theme-park industry's leading special-effects wizards
until he'd been murdered outside his New York apartment building a
few days earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr said he did not expect ``New Yorker-style'' literary
fiction to appear in Time.
</P>
<P>
   But with the proliferation of news on television and the
Internet, Carr said, ``news itself is now so immediately available
and disposable that if you are a news weekly, to stay vital and
exciting you need to add elements that can't necessarily be found
anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, `` What's nice about fiction is that it is keeping the
lines clear. You're not publishing speculation, or a mix of fact
and fiction. You just say, `We're going to publish fiction as a way
of drawing readers to the magazine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Given people's attention spans and the amount of time they can
devote, I think it's appropriate for installment fiction to make a
return right now,'' Carr said. ``And there are a lot of people who
are too smart or too grown-up to read comic books, but who don't
want to pick up a 500-page novel in an airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said it was premature to predict whether Time would
publish more serialized fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's wait and see Chapter Two,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
