<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHRISTIAN-FILM-2TAKES     10-24 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLEEPER MOVIE AWAKENED BY A HUNGRY AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The stylish couple getting their midmorning caffeine
blast on the sunbaked terrace of a Sunset Strip coffeehouse look
like any of the other black-clad power types in designer
sunglasses, cell phones resting on the table, giving every
impression of being in the middle of a lucrative deal that would
make other power types sick with envy if they only knew.
</P>
<P>
   Except in this case, it's true.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no one is more surprised than me,'' said Matt Crouch,
seated next to his wife, Laurie.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch is producer of ``The Omega Code,'' a $7.2 million
thriller starring Michael York, Casper Van Dien and Catherine
Oxenburg that blindsided Hollywood a week ago by sneaking under the
radar to earn $2.4 million during its opening weekend in only 305
theaters around the country, despite a national marketing budget of
only $600,000 and a smattering of reviews that were, well, not
particularly kind. The film took in an average of $7,869 a theater,
the highest for any of that weekend's films and a figure called
``eye-popping'' by The Hollywood Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Several studio executives said last week that the film had
caught them by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard of it until I saw it on the weekend box-office
list,'' said one production company executive. ``I thought, `What
the heck is this?' And I called some people up, and they didn't
know either.''
</P>
<P>
   What has drawn Hollywood's attention is not merely that yet
another little-heralded movie, a la ``Blair Witch Project,'' has
used an aggressively targeted grass-roots marketing campaign to
catapult into an apparent hit, but that the movie's core target
audience is the Christian right, known for its antagonism to movies
and to much of mainstream popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my belief,'' Crouch said, ``that there are millions of
people out there, we don't really know how many _ call them church
people, call them right-wing Christians, call them whatever you
want _ who are hungry for entertainment and who would love to go to
the movies. But they feel there are no movies being made for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Crouch is the son of Paul Crouch, a well-known preacher in
Orange County, Calif., and the operator of the Trinity Broadcasting
Network, a cable company geared toward the charismatic and
Pentecostal wings of the Christian right, with hundreds of outlets
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Omega Code'' is about an apocalyptic battle between good
and evil that draws its inspiration from prophecies in the Book of
Revelations, grafting onto them a standard-issue plot with a hero,
a villain and a pretty girl. The idea, Crouch said, was to make an
intense, traditional Hollywood thriller that would appeal initially
to conservative Christian audiences, but without being so
overbearing as to scare away those who do not normally tune into a
right-wing Christian message.
</P>
<P>
   With a marketing budget that allowed for only minimal newspaper
advertising and no billboards or television outside of the frequent
mention of the movie on his father's cable network, Crouch and
Providence Entertainment, a small San Fernando Valley company that
is distributing the film, were forced to rely on preachers and
conservative Christians from around the country to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were able to do was to utilize the loyalty of TBN
viewers,'' said Michael Harpster, vice president for marketing at
Providence. ``We had 2,000 local volunteers around the country _ I
mean volunteers _ who were instrumental in driving this film,
putting up posters in churches, organizing church groups, just
getting the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a page from ``The Blair Witch'' book, the Internet was
also heavily used. An ``Omega Code'' Web site (www.omegacode.com)
has been receiving 12,000 e-mails a day in recent weeks, Crouch
said, and Internet chat rooms devoted to religious topics have been
inundated with chatter about the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stunned with the Internet,'' Harpster said. ``One of the
things they did on the TBN Web page is they let people download
posters of the movie and a scriptural guide. One day we got 500,000
hits and 150,000 people downloaded that stuff. I mean, we had
people printing them out at home and then taking them to Kinko's
and having copies run off so they could plaster them all over their
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Several theater chains allowed Providence to sell tickets up to
a month in advance. ``We had pastors showing up to buy tickets for
their entire congregation,'' Harpster said. ``We've had busloads of
church people unloading outside the theaters. One businessman in
Oklahoma bought 1,000 tickets for all of his employees. A chain of
Christian bookstores bought hundreds of tickets for each of its
stores.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie remained on 305 screens in its second week, but will
expand this coming weekend to 30 more cities, then a bit more the
next weekend until by the end of November it is to be on 450
screens, Harpster said. Initially the movie was booked into those
cities where TBN's viewership was highest _ in the South, the West
and the Midwest _ in hopes that it could capture that core audience
and then gradually expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried initially to stay very closely in the TBN
footprints,'' Harpster said. ``We know where their people are and
in niche marketing like this you naturally have to go hunting where
the ducks are. I mean, you don't open a black film in Minneapolis
because, hey, there's nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is whether ``The Omega Code'' can
sustain its opening-week pace or turns out to be what Crouch calls
a ``church-bus bubble'' that pops once the church buses stop
arriving at the cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people in Hollywood are wondering the same thing,
because if there is a huge conservative Christian audience for
films _ anything like the audience that sustains hundreds of
Christian bookstores around the country _ and that audience can be
reached cheaply, then there might be a future for more movies like
``The Omega Code,'' maybe even better ones. It's still too early to
say for sure, several executives said last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have proven that there is a niche for these movies,''
said Nancy Utley, president for marketing at Fox Searchlight.
``What remains to be seen is how large the niche is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Crouch had been the head of Trinity Films, a subsidiary of his
father's cable empire, but broke away several years ago to form his
own company, Gener8Xion Entertainment. He said he was eager to make
movies that were not necessarily directed only at TBN's core
audience _ ``preaching to the choir,'' as he puts it _ but were
aimed at attracting a wider audience, making the choir bigger.
``TBN preaches to people 24 hours a day, but there is a whole lost
group of people out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So he began to knock on the doors of every movie executive. ``I
did the game,'' he said. ``I met with every potential funding
source, like an idiot, beating my head against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when he had the script for ``The Omega Code'' and doors
kept slamming in his face, he decided to take it back to his father
at TBN and was a little surprised when TBN Films agreed to make it
with him. Still, money was tight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the movie opened in 305 theaters,'' Crouch said,
``is that we only had enough money for 305 prints.'' And they got
that money, Ms. Crouch said, by mortgaging their house in the
Hollywood Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Now it seems to be paying off. Crouch said that since the movie
opened he has been interviewed by three television networks, two
wire services, The Times of London, Time magazine and The New
Yorker. He shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a headline on the front page of USA Today that said
`Omega-mania,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omega-mania!'' Ms. Crouch repeated, bursting into delighted
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I'm trying to tell people,'' Crouch said, ``is
that I appreciate the way newspapers are coining phrases, but what
I personally feel that I'm really good at is identifying a market
of people who for years had wanted to embrace Hollywood but
couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, he spends his time trying to figure out how best
to capitalize on the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want this to be just a flash in the pan,'' he said.
``I want it to be the beginning of something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
