<SLUG> BC-BANK-REFORM-PRIVACY-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED BANKING LEGISLATION RAISES CONCERNS ABOUT PRIVACY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala.)  (jw) 
 By JERI CLAUSING    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Congress votes as expected this week to overhaul the nation's
Depression-era banking laws, it will be doing more than paving the
way for the creation of one-stop financial supermarkets. It will
also be offering companies unprecedented opportunities to amass and
share reams of private data about their customers.
</P>
<P>
   The data-swapping opportunities, the bill's backers said, are
necessary for companies to be able to provide the integrated
financial services that the legislation aims to make possible.
</P>
<P>
   But in an age in which personal data have become an invaluable
marketing resource, consumer and privacy advocates fear that the
new law will give banks and insurance companies an unchecked
advantage over their customers. Financial institutions will be able
to share not only information on their customers' incomes,
investments, possessions and credit ratings, but also detailed
summations about where they go to dinner, where they buy their
lovers' presents and what medical expenses they have paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the privacy protections that were put into the bill
are a sham,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., who was on the
conference committee that negotiated the compromise last week. He
said he would refuse to sign the conference report that moves to
the full Congress where it is expected to be endorsed this week,
because ``it ignores a basic right for American people that I
believe shouldn't be ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charlotte Birch, a spokeswoman for the American Bankers
Association, said that the ability to share basic information about
customers' financial activities was a major requirement of the
banking overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is to be able to offer integrated financial
services to customers,'' she said. ``To provide that sort of
integrated customer service, be it through common account
statements, ease of loan applications, whatever, that kind of
information sharing between affiliates is a convenience for
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, she said, financial institutions would have incentives
to protect their customers' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is a bank's relationship with its customer is
built on trust,'' she said. ``The industry can't afford to come
down on this issue any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Birch said that the bill also required financial
institutions to establish comprehensive privacy policies and to
notify customers of those policies once a year.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over privacy protections in the compromise banking
bill was created by a tension that is increasingly moving to the
forefront of policy debates: how to balance the convenience that
new technologies offer consumers and businesses with the threat of
unprecedented intrusions into personal privacy.
</P>
<P>
   And how well that balance was struck remains the source of
fierce contention between the banking lobby and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the compromise financial services bill that was
tentatively endorsed by Congress and the White House last week
appears to offer consumers more privacy protections than current
law. It would require, for the first time, that banks in most cases
let their customers know if they are selling their personal
information to third parties. The bill would also require the banks
to remove an individual's data from such marketing lists if the
customer so requested.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the information that the new digital-age conglomerates
would be able to share unchecked among themselves that has consumer
and privacy advocates concerned.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever, the legislation would allow insurance
companies, brokerage houses, banks and credit card companies to
merge under one roof, enabling them to share with one another all
of the personal and financial information they have about each of
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders negotiating the compromise rejected
attempts to require that affiliated companies first get a
customer's permission before sharing that information.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted customers to be able to authorize the sharing of
information each and every time,'' said Ms. Birch, spokeswoman for
the banking group. ``It's just not practical and it would have the
effect of no information sharing whatsoever. In which case, just as
you are taking down legal barriers you are putting up new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   But the resulting compromise, privacy and consumer advocates
said, has left customers with little control over how their
sensitive personal information is used.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Torres, legislative director for the Consumers Union,
which was part of a diverse coalition of groups pushing for the
stronger privacy protections, said the long-term implications of
the bill were that ``banks can really use this this information to
manipulate their customers.'' He said that banks increasingly made
their profits from products and services rather than interest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``These aren't your fathers' banks. These are banks now in the
business of selling you things. How can you trust them if they have
all this information on you?''
</P>
<P>
   Torres said consumer groups were also concerned about the
implications for so-called digital redlining _ in which banks or
insurance companies could create a profile of a customer's credit
or insurance risk based on combined records of a person's banking,
insurance, credit card and brokerage transactions, and then use
that information to judge the person too risky a candidate to
receive a loan or line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, he said, if a consumer's bank and health
insurance company are affiliated, a loan officer might be able to
punch a button and see if the customer had any lingering health
problems before deciding whether to award a mortgage and at what
rate.
</P>
<P>
   And the bank would be under no obligation to tell the consumer
what personal data were used in deciding terms of a loan. Nor would
they be required to let the consumer check that information for
accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might go in for a loan, and I might go in for the same
loan and get charged different fees, based on this information in
the black box _ a box that you have no access to,'' Torres said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So in a nutshell, the privacy protections are anything but
private,'' he said. ``They aren't worth the paper they are printed
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, if the legislation is adopted in its current form,
consumer privacy in practice will depend on how the financial
institutions choose to approach the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two points of view,'' said David Komansky, chairman and
chief executive of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``As an individual and
consumer, I think that I am entitled to certain privacies. The
things that concern me are health records as they apply to
mortgages applications, for example _ I want to have those
protections.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``As a business person, having the option to
`data-mine' investment traits of clients can position us to be able
to more efficiently market our products. It's an important
advantage and something I value.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
