u f BC-TV-BOOKING-WARS-ART &LR; -     10-24 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOOKING-WARS-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORNING SHOWS BARE THEIR TEETH IN MANEUVERING TO BOOK GUESTS 
</HEADLINE>
 - 520(2TAKES)-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Friedman, the senior executive producer of CBS' new
``Early Show,'' which joins the network morning show competition
next week, was rather gleeful. He noted that ratings for the
longtime morning leader, NBC's ``Today,'' showed small signs of
slippage last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be using that in booking guests,'' Friedman said.
``We're going to tell people that `Today' is already showing signs
of erosion, and if you're tired of the `Today' show's arrogance in
the way they book guests, get on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the first of what promises to be innumerable salvos in
what Friedman calls ``the morning wars.'' Nowhere will the
infighting be more ferocious than in the behind-the-scenes daily
struggle to book the best guests on ``Early Show,'' ``Today'' or
ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   The bookings will be crucial because all three morning shows are
expected to follow basically the same format: male and female
co-anchors, hard news early, entertainment features and cooking
segments late. With the addition of CBS' new studio overlooking the
entrance to Central Park at 59th Street and Fifth Avenue, the three
shows will even display a similar window-on-Manhattan look. So,
executives with all three networks said, the three shows may depend
more than ever on distinguishing themselves by the guests they
bring on.
</P>
<P>
   Booking guests on the morning shows has long been a business of
horse trading and deal making, with shows often offering stars and
other valued guests some tangible benefit _ like multipart
appearances _ in exchange for getting the guest first.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a game of leverage. The total ratings dominance of
``Today'' over the last five years has changed the rules of the
game: ``Today'' has come to expect a certain advantage in booking
guests. Jeff Zucker, the show's executive producer, has declared
that his show is out of the deal business and will henceforth
depend only on its superior ratings position _ and of course, the
appeal of its hosts, Katie Couric and Matt Lauer _ to lure the best
guests.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman is sounding a call to any star representative who might
be just a bit fed up with the ``Today'' position as he takes on the
challenge of trying to build a successful morning show on CBS for
the first time behind Bryant Gumbel, the former longtime ``Today''
host, and the newcomer Jane Clayson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Today' show is quite particular about whom it puts on,''
he said. ``They do not take the co-star of movies. They do not take
somebody in a small movie that a studio may be pushing because they
won't make deals. People will start coming to me because they want
a contest. They really would like a show to challenge `Today' so
they can have some leverage. Jeff has all the leverage now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Ross, the executive producer of ``Good Morning
America,'' said much the same thing: ``The publicists are delighted
that they have somewhere else to go besides NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zucker said he was not worried. ``If we've proved anything
in the last five years it's that clearly we like to win, and we
expect to win,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-BOOKING-WARS-ART &LR; -     10-24 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BOOKING-WARS-ART </SLUG>
 - 2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: he said.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One reason for the welcoming of alternatives to ``Today'' is
that show's frank willingness to use the leverage of its big
ratings edge. ``I fully admit to being intense and competitive,''
Zucker said. ``Of course we want to capitalize on our strength.
You'd be derelict if you did anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker has engaged in some high-profile showdowns with
representatives of guests and is not shy about threatening to cut
off future bookings when he feels, as he put it, ``somebody isn't
straight with me.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, when George Stephanopoulos was making the rounds
earlier this year with his book about his White House years, Zucker
felt the publisher, Sarah Crichton of Little, Brown, had broken an
agreement by booking him on CBS the same day he was on ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker exploded, telling Ms. Crichton he would never book
another of her authors again. That situation was resolved after
Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS News, intervened.
</P>
<P>
   But a more enduring standoff has arisen over a booking
contretemps between ``Today'' and Pat Kingsley, one of the most
powerful publicity agents in Hollywood and a partner in the firm
PMK. The incident involved a Kingsley client, the actress Calista
Flockhart, who was touring to promote her movie ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream.'' Ms. Kingsley pulled Ms. Flockhart from ``Today''
after the show refused to accede to Ms. Flockhart's request not to
ask questions about her weight.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker reacted by canceling interviews with that movie's
co-stars, Kevin Kline and Stanley Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Today'' show then accused Ms. Kingsley of retaliating by
reneging on a deal the show had with Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman
for interviews about their movie ``Eyes Wide Shut.'' Ms. Kingsley
says there never was a deal and that ``Good Morning America''
simply came up with a better offer: five days of interviews as
opposed to three. Ms. Ross backed that version, saying the actors
``wanted to be on with Diane Sawyer because they know she's a great
interviewer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' executives said Ms. Kingsley was trying to rewrite the
facts and that they had backing from other PMK executives to prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the dispute was what both parties described as an
extremely heated phone conversation between Zucker and Ms.
Kingsley, which ended with Zucker telling her that her personal
clients would be banned from ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley said in an interview that she really does not have
personal clients; Zucker said ``Today'' knows who they are. The
fallout so far has included Chevy Chase, a Kingsley client who was
about the only former ``Saturday Night Live'' star not on ``Today''
the week before the 25th anniversary special of that show, and
Jodie Foster, who is still not booked on ``Today'' for her upcoming
movie ``Anna and the King.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' executives said that the movie's studio, Fox, has
pleaded that Ms. Foster be allowed on the show as long as Ms.
Kingsley has nothing to do with it, and they are now considering
whether the show will book the actress with that condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be a bully,'' Zucker said. ``But I'm very
serious about this.''
</P>
<P>
   The booking game is indeed very serious. Both Ms. Ross and
Friedman now say they, too, will refuse to take guests _ other than
figures in the news _ after they have previously appeared on
another morning show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ross said she was far less concerned about missing out on
guests than what she called ``incidents where the booking wars are
serious and dangerous.'' The example she cited involved a product
recall. She said Ann Brown, the chairman of the federal Consumer
Products Safety Commission, despite her status as a public
official, had an exclusive agreement to appear regularly on
``Today,'' where she was announcing the recall.
</P>
<P>
   What made this booking decision dangerous? Because, said Ms.
Ross, ``Good Morning America'' could not announce the recall at the
same time and give the widest possible distribution of the news.
Ms. Ross said she complained in Washington of the unfairness of
this arrangement and since has received some redress.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown even appeared on ``Good Morning America'' last week,
though Ms. Ross pointed out that the product recall she was
announcing was for dishwashers, some of which were manufactured by
General Electric, NBC's parent. ``I really don't know why Ms. Brown
became available to us on this particular product,'' Ms. Ross said,
leaving little doubt that she believed that NBC wanted to avoid
reporting negatively on its parent company.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives strenuously denied that they passed on Mn
because of the GE connection and said they had reported the recall
on the show's news segments.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Begala, a spokeswoman for the Consumer Products Safety
Commission, said Ms. Brown never had an exclusive arrangement with
``Today,'' but had come to prefer that show principally because of
its higher ratings and because it had been supportive after a
previous ``Good Morning America'' producer had decided he did not
want Ms. Brown on.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the sidelines watching the sniping, Friedman said he
hoped to take advantage of whatever ill feelings had built up among
guests booked and unbooked by the other two shows in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling people, if you help us now when we need help, we
have long memories,'' Friedman said. ``I'm there to help everybody.
I'm just this benevolent guy who's going to go in there and say:
Help me out.''
</P>
<P>
   But benevolence and booking really don't have much to do with
each other in morning television. Friedman made of point of adding,
``Of course, for those who don't help us out, we have long memories
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
