<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-MURDER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SENTENCED IN ISRAEL TO 24 YEARS FOR MARYLAND MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV, Israel _ Saying nothing and showing no emotion as he
stood before three Tel Aviv district judges and a gallery packed
with television crews, Samuel Sheinbein was sentenced to 24 years
in prison here Sunday for the murder of a neighborhood acquaintance
in Maryland in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The prison term, negotiated earlier in a plea bargain between
Israeli prosecutors and Sheinbein's lawyer, has already been
denounced as too lenient by Maryland prosecutors. But it was said
by lawyers here Sunday to be the harshest ever imposed in Israel
for a crime committed by a minor.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old Maryland native will be eligible for parole in
14 years, the prosecutor said Sunday. Within four years, a review
board could also begin authorizing furloughs from jail of up to
four days at a time, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges noted that there were few precedents for Sheinbein's
peculiar and politically charged case, which began when he fled
here after the murder two years ago to avail himself of the
protection he would enjoy as a citizen of Israel _ a country he had
never visited, but where both his parents were born.
</P>
<P>
   Under Israeli law, Sheinbein had full citizenship rights here.
And, under a law in effect at the time, no Israeli citizen could be
extradited on murder charges if the potential sentence abroad was
more severe than that which could legally be imposed in Israel. In
Maryland, Sheinbein could have faced a verdict of life without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with a defendant who forced himself upon the
Israeli judicial system,'' said Judge Uri Goren, the president of
the three-judge Tel Aviv district court panel, reading from its
19-page sentencing report. Sheinbein did not visibly react to the
recitation of the charges to which he had earlier confessed.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the back of the small courtroom, Sheinbein's parents
appeared numbed but relieved that the three-judge panel did not
reject the recommended plea in favor of a more severe sentence, as
Maryland prosecutors and others had publicly urged.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sheinbein, crying silently, and her husband listened to
Goren methodically detail the strangulation and subsequent
dismemberment by electric saw of Alfredo Tello, said to have been a
friend of Samuel Sheinbein and his accomplice, Aron Needle, who
later committed suicide in a Maryland jail cell. The ``shocking
acts of desecration of the deceased's body ... show us to what
depths the defendant sank and how inhuman he became,'' Goren said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge pointedly noted that it was Sheinbein's father who had
urged and assisted his flight to Israel, and that prosecutors here
had relied heavily on his father's admission to a Maryland grand
jury that Samuel Sheinbein had admitted to the strangulation in
conversations with him and with his brother. The Sheinbeins refused
to respond to reporters' questions, and left quickly when the
sentencing was over.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the brief proceedings Sunday, the judges, prosecutor
and even the defendant's lawyer displayed a seemingly visceral
distaste for the case, for Sheinbein himself, and for the
since-amended extradition law that effectively made it impossible
for Israel to deport Sheinbein to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Acidly rejecting one defense argument for the plea bargain _
that avoiding a trial would save the courts time and money _ the
judges noted that ``it was in the hands of the defendant in the
first place to avoid the entire procedure here in Israel, had he
not escaped here and had he been willing to face proper justice for
his acts in the right and proper place, i.e., in the state of
Maryland.''
</P>
<P>
   But the judges accepted the recommended sentence of 24 years,
pointing to punishments imposed in other murders by minors in
Israel and the inherent uncertainty about the penalty Sheinbein
would have received had he stood trial in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sheinbein was represented by David Libay, a former justice
minister, who said he had opposed the extradition ban that had
protected his client and ``welcomed'' the Parliament's decision
this year to change the law to preclude future such cases. But he
fought efforts to return Sheinbein to Maryland because ``the law is
the law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court imposed on the defendant in this case one of the
most harsh and severe punishments that has ever been imposed on a
minor convicted of murder in Israel,'' Libay said after the
sentencing Sunday. The court acceptance of the plea agreement
``shows that we have all done our best to act in a very reasonable
and responsible way in dealing with this very troubling case,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
