<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6809 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PREDICTORS-BOOK-REVIE     10-24 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDICTORS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PREDICTORS': IN CHAOTIC MARKETS, FANTASTIC RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Readers of an entertaining earlier book by Thomas A. Bass, ``The
Eudaemonic Pie'' (1985), will recall how from 1976 until 1981 a
group of California physicists worked to break the banks at Las
Vegas by predicting the outcome of the game of roulette. They
designed miniature computers that fit inside their shoes, walked
into a casino, punched into their computers the Newtonian numbers
that govern roulette, and started placing winning bets.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was just the beginning of their adventures in
forecasting. In his lively new book, ``The Predictors,'' Bass
reports how the two leaders of Eudaemonic Enterprises, Doyne Farmer
and Norman Packard, set about finding more complex things to
predict than the eventual resting place of a metal ball bouncing
around a rotating wheel.
</P>
<P>
   As pioneers in the arcane science of chaos theory, Farmer and
Packard saw possibilities of exploiting chaos as a predictive tool.
What you could do, it had been discovered, was send a probe into a
turbulent system, like two gases flowing next to each other, in
which coherent patterns called fractals could tell you about the
system in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   And what phenomenon would they model this time out? Not a
dripping faucet, a measles epidemic or smoke rising from a
cigarette in an ashtray, all of which are potential subjects of
chaos theory. No, instead the physicists would study what was in a
sense an extension of roulette, the behavior of financial markets,
which Bass, with his vivid introductory description of the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, makes seem the very paradigm of turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   By discovering the order within disorder of the markets, nice
money could be made, Bass asserts. ``How much money?'' he asks.
Take an initial $100 million investment, ``leverage it by a factor
of 5, secure a 30 percent return, collect 25 percent of this as a
fee for your services, and pocket a cool $37 million a year in
profit.'' He adds: ``This is a nice balance sheet for Year One.
After that, real money.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Predictors'' Bass describes how the two chaos
theoreticians tried to achieve these results; how they set up shop
in Santa Fe, N.M., and hired a scruffy band of Ph.D.s to think and
write software for them; how they sought out financial advisers and
investors, eventually contracting with powerful Swiss Bank Corp.
(not gnomes of Zurich but behemoths of Basel); and how they went
about decoding and modeling the commodities, currency and equities
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Bass has good narrative fun contrasting the loose-jointed
working style of the Prediction Company, as it came to be called,
with the Masters of the Universe who ended up financing the
project.
</P>
<P>
   He lavishes some of the richest prose on the scenery surrounding
the project's computer-crammed shop and on the local rituals in
which the predictors partook, like Fiesta and the burning of
Zozobra, also known as Old Man Gloom, a 40-foot puppet erected on a
hill nearby.
</P>
<P>
   More edifying, however, is Bass' use of his narrative to teach
readers about chaos theory as it relates to economics, about the
increasingly recondite instruments of investment in the age of
derivatives and, perhaps most important, about the evolution of
financial markets toward automation.
</P>
<P>
   As the Prediction Company approaches success, creating software
that models not only all markets but also all the world's stocks,
at least the ones traded with some frequency, you wonder
increasingly what the effect on those markets will be.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the company's employees wondered too, asking if ``to
make money this way is to be a parasite upon the financial system
rather than to serve it,'' as one person put it. ``Furthermore,''
he added, ``it is pretty clear that the only way to make money
consistently with such a technique is to keep it secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Packard's answer to these concerns was that ``finding
predictable structure and trading on it makes the markets more
efficient.'' He continued: ``Such trades reduce the overall
volatility of the markets, and thus the risk to participants is
reduced. The profits that go to the successful predictor are like a
fee that the markets pay for the service of making them more
efficient and less risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer's response was even more to the point. ``Making
predictions is fundamental to financial markets,'' he said. ``If
people didn't think prices were going to change, they wouldn't
trade. Price setting can be rational only insofar as the
predictions that drive it are sensible. By making predictions and
trading on them, we are indirectly helping society set its goals,
even if we're also trying to make a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the Prediction Company succeed? Although the answer is a
matter of public record, it will not be repeated here, out of
respect for Bass' energetic, serpentine narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, his story serves as a useful device for
describing the increasing abstractness of contemporary finances,
where markets derive from markets that in turn derive from derived
markets. (Some passages of ``The Predictors'' read like Greek in
their abstruseness, although Bass rarely uses terminology without
coming back to it and defining it further along.)
</P>
<P>
   But certainly you have doubts about the success of the venture,
given the recent growing volume of voices arguing that markets are
patternless and therefore unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the Prediction Company jokingly considered taking
as its motto Lux Solis Ex Cucumero, meaning Sunlight From Cucumbers
and referring to the academy in ``Gulliver's Travels'' where the
academicians engaged in such an absurd project of extraction have
to be protected from falling off cliffs or doing themselves other
bodily harm.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``The Predictors,'' you often feel that the computers
Bass' heroes try to get light from might just as well be cucumbers
hidden in their shoes. That they could eventually make money by
reading the madness of crowds bidding up the price of tulip bulbs
seems equally unlikely, until Bass gets through explaining in this
instructive and amusing book.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE PREDICTORS'
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas A. Bass
</P>
<P>
   309 pages. Henry Holt. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
