<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRAYN-PROFILE-ART-107     10-24 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAYN-PROFILE-ART-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBIGUITY FIRES A NOVELIST AND PLAYWRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ As an undergraduate studying philosophy at Cambridge,
Michael Frayn always attended his supervisor's lectures, an
academic experience so excruciating that after a few weeks he was
the only student there.
</P>
<P>
   One day he decided to stay in bed. ``At about 10 past 9 there
was a tap on the door, and it was my supervisor,'' he recalled the
other day. ``Since I was visibly not doing anything else, I had to
get up and get dressed. Thereafter, he would collect me on the way
to the lecture, and I remained his entire audience for the rest of
the term.''
</P>
<P>
   Frayn _ playwright, author, essayist, translator of Russian _
seems just as polite now as he was then, pouring tea in his airy
study in Camden Town in north London and talking about himself in
the manner of someone who revels in his work, not his biography.
</P>
<P>
   He has done a lot of talking about himself lately, in the United
States and Germany as well as Britain, as he promotes his latest
novel, ``Headlong'' (Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt).
</P>
<P>
   He certainly knows the drill. Years ago he wrote a dead-on
parody of a newspaper profile, featuring a supremely inarticulate
actor who plays the front legs of movie monsters and is interviewed
by a reporter with ``a lot of space to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Would you like a drink?' he asks, with simple, unforced
generosity,'' Frayn wrote. ``You watch him as he mixes it, and see
not the dreamer of `The Horror Crypt' but the practical man who
could have carved out a career for himself as a chemist or a soda
jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, though, the gentle and slyly funny Frayn, who at 66
is tall and lanky with white hair on the sides of his head and
almost none on top, is certainly far too well-mannered to boast
about the highly irregular double success he is enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, not only does he have a hit play on the West End,
``Copenhagen,'' about a deadly serious subject, but ``Headlong,'' a
wickedly clever novel with elements of the famous Frayn farce, is a
narrow favorite to win this year's Booker Prize, to be awarded
Monday night at a fancy ceremony in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``With nearly everybody you think that they're primarily a
novelist or primarily a playwright, but Michael's genuinely,
equally both,'' said Blake Morrison, the writer and critic. ``And
there are two sides to him, in both the theater and fiction. On the
one hand he has a real taste for farce, but he's also a very
serious-minded man, with an almost dry academic temperament and a
slightly professorial look about him.''
</P>
<P>
   In both these works, Frayn has thrown himself into real-life
intellectual disputes that can be dazzlingly abstruse.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Copenhagen'' Frayn investigates the unreliability of
memory, the ambiguity of human motives and the conflicting
loyalties of scientists in wartime by imagining what happened at
the famous, never-explained meeting in 1941 between Werner
Heisenberg, the father of the German nuclear program, and Niels
Bohr, the half-Jewish Danish physicist who had been Heisenberg's
mentor before the war.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which opened at the National Theater and moved to the
West End in February, is set to open on Broadway in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have found it exhilaratingly erudite without wearing its
ideas too heavily. ``This extraordinary play _ at once a historical
detective story, a lecture in morality and a lesson in advanced
nuclear physics _ shows that Michael Frayn, at his best, can blend
bogglingly cerebral material with the skill of a theatrical master
craftsman,'' wrote Nick Curtis in The Evening Standard of London.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``Headlong'' reads at times like a romp, albeit one
that poses moral and intellectual questions. An account of an
undisciplined, impecunious academic's growing attachment to his
theory that a picture in the house of an unsophisticated country
neighbor is in fact a missing Bruegel masterpiece, ``Headlong'' too
has drawn almost universally good reviews, with critics praising
its ability to work on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the novel has elements of thriller and elements of
farce, it also offers an anatomization of moral disintegration,''
said Caroline Moore, writing in The Sunday Telegraph of London.
``This, I should add hastily, is never grim, never merely
moralizing, far less dull: It is, indeed, horribly gripping.''
</P>
<P>
   Frayn, who is probably best known in the United States for his
farce ``Noises Off,'' became addicted to Bruegel-related issues
about three years ago, he said, when he was in Vienna, Austria, and
wandered, as he often does, into the Bruegel room at the
Kunsthistorisches Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, once again, looking once again at `The Hunters in
the Snow' and the two pictures next to it,'' he said. ``It's a
terrible admission because it makes me sound completely stupid, but
I'd never noticed before that they were part of a series.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign said that the pictures were part of a series of six,
illustrating times of the year, and that three were in Vienna, one
was in Prague, Czech Republic, one was at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art in New York, and one was ... missing. ``And even as I looked
at the notice, I thought, supposing you found that missing
picture?'' Frayn said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Clay, who thinks in ``Headlong'' that he has found the
missing picture, is motivated by a shifting mixture of greed,
altruism, deceit and guilt. As he immerses himself in Bruegel
arcana in an effort to determine whether the picture he has spotted
at his neighbor Tony Churt's house is in fact the lost masterpiece,
he becomes enmeshed in a complicated plot to extricate the picture
from Tony without telling him why.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protesting that he is basically lazy _ ``My idea is
always to do as little research as possible on anything,'' he said
_ Frayn became just as obsessed as Martin. ``I discovered, as
Martin discovers, that everything about Bruegel is vastly more
complicated than that notice suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, scholars don't even agree on how many
pictures were in the series, what months they actually represent or
whether the sixth picture was ever painted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more research I did, the plainer it became that there was
almost no documentation at all about Bruegel,'' Frayn said.
``Everything is theory or conjecture,'' he added. ``He's a very
ambiguous figure, and as soon as you find something ambiguous and
mysterious, it seizes your imagination.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguity and mystery lie, too, at the core of ``Copenhagen,'' a
play in which Frayn wrestles with two of his favorite subjects, the
philosophical implications of quantum mechanics and the mysteries
of human motivation.
</P>
<P>
   When he read an account of Heisenberg's murky trip to
Copenhagen, Denmark, in ``Heisenberg's War: The Secret History of
the German Bomb'' (Knopf, 1993), by the American author Thomas
Powers, Frayn said, he was struck by the incident's theatrical
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The tantalizing puzzle at the center of ``Copenhagen'' is that
no one knows exactly what happened at the meeting. Frayn begins the
play by struggling to make sense of a seminal moment in the lives
of the protagonists, who are long dead, and examining possible
scenarios. Was Heisenberg asking Bohr to join him in ensuring that
neither the Nazis nor the Allies would produce an atomic bomb? Was
he trying to recruit Bohr to the German side?
</P>
<P>
   All these underlie an even larger question: Was Heisenberg's
failure to develop a bomb for Germany a deliberate act intended to
thwart a war effort he abhorred, or the result of his own
scientific missteps?
</P>
<P>
   Although historians have deeply held positions on all sides of
these points, Frayn says he tried to be evenhanded, making the
point that Heisenberg's major contribution to science, the
Uncertainty Principle, applies just as much to understanding human
intentions as it does to measuring the physical world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you can't locate _ why people do or don't do
things,'' he said. ``What I'm saying in `Copenhagen' is that there
isn't an objective truth about people's motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Frayn's career has had its ups and downs. At Cambridge he edited
a literary magazine and wrote the script for one of the annual
shows of Footlights, the university's revue club, but then he
suffered the rare indignity of the production's failing to transfer
to the West End.
</P>
<P>
   He then joined The Manchester Guardian, writing articles for the
newspaper about things like ``the last clog maker in Bolton,'' he
said, and Prime Minister Harold Macmillan's trip to the Soviet
Union, before making his name with a Thurberesque humor column for
The Guardian and then for The Observer of London.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote novels (``Headlong'' is his ninth), and after
recovering from his Footlights disappointment, turned increasingly
to writing plays. After a series of theatrical successes, with
``Noises Off,'' ``Benefactors'' and ``Wild Honey,'' Frayn's
translation of Chekhov's first play, he went through an unhappy
patch when his next two plays flopped.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, sales of his novels were so anemic that when
``Headlong'' was put up for auction, some publishers declined to
bid.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn is not sure how to characterize himself _ ``I'm a novelist
when I'm working on a novel and a playwright when I'm working on a
play,'' he says _ but both guises present their own sets of
anxieties. When the opening of ``Copenhagen'' was put off until the
theater he wanted became available, Frayn said, ``I kept worrying
every week that someone else was going to come up with a play about
Heisenberg's visit to Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   And before ``Headlong,'' ``I was just waiting for somebody to
discover that Bruegel painting and completely shoot down my
novel,'' Frayn said. ``I hope they do discover it, but not until
we've got the paperbacks out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
