u f BC-MTV-INTERNET-GAME-600     10-24 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-INTERNET-GAME-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSIC-TRIVIA SHOW ENCOURAGES WEB AUDIENCE PARTICIPATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By EVELYN ELLISON TWITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the media industry's latest attempt to attain true
convergence of television and the Internet, MTV plans to start a
music-trivia game show in which viewers can play along by logging
onto MTV's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The program, ``Web Riot,'' has its debut late next month, but
MTV plans to begin ramping up promotion for it Monday and to let
potential players begin downloading the requisite PC software from
the MTV.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   As MTV prepares for the program's premiere on Nov. 29, media
executives _ particularly advertisers _ will be waiting for MTV to
prove that the time for convergence has finally arrived _ even if
the estimated 44 percent of American households with Internet
access is still far below the nearly 80 percent that subscribe to
cable or satellite television services that carry MTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can give us a good indication of the realities of
multitasking,'' said Bill Cella, executive vice president for
broadcasting and programming with the advertising firm of
McCann-Erickson Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Some 23 percent of U.S. households have a television and
personal computer in the same room, according to a survey of 1,166
households released in June 1999 by Paul Kagan Associates, a media
research and consulting firm. The survey was conducted with
Showtime Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   During the half-hour program each weekday afternoon, up to
25,000 ``Web Riot'' viewers, watching both their television and
personal computer screens, will be able to play along with four
on-air contestants.
</P>
<P>
   MTV will show clips from music videos and then multiple-choice
questions on television. Participants at home will use the numbers
on their computer keyboard to log their answers.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the game, the show will scroll the player
nicknames of the top 10 online contestants across the television,
and they will win prizes.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, a division of Viacom Inc., considers itself well positioned
to test this approach to convergence because of the demographic
profile of its audience: people 12 to 34 years old. (For legal
reasons, MTV is requiring viewers to be at least 13 years old to
play.)
</P>
<P>
   MTV's research indicates that 51 percent of its audience members
between 12 and 24 years old have Internet access, compared with 43
percent of the general public in that age group, and that many of
the networks' viewers often watch the cable channel while surfing
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two experiences seem to live comfortably together in
their lives,'' said Judy McGrath, president of MTV. ``So this is
the first time we're going to really try to shake that notion and
see if it's true in a very real way.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV is not the only company trying to make convergence work.
Since September, angling for a different demographic segment, Walt
Disney Company's ABC and ESPN networks have been offering Enhanced
TV, an online complement to the networks' coverage of National
Football League games. While watching the televised game on ESPN or
ABC, a viewer can also log onto the ESPN.com, ABC.com or NFL.com
Web sites for various forms of audience participation.
</P>
<P>
   One feature allows fans to predict the ball handler before each
live play from scrimmage. Players can compare their scores with
those of others nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Web Riot'' is successful, it could spur other television
game shows to create interactive components. ABC, for example, is
already exploring online options for its hit quiz show ``Who Wants
to Be a Millionaire?,'' said Jonathan Leess, vice president of
enhanced television at Buena Vista Internet Group, Disney's
Internet division.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MTV has been dabbling in convergent programming for more than
three years. The discontinued ``Yak Live,'' for example, allowed
viewers to chat online about videos as they played on television
and scrolled their conversations across the TV screen. Last May,
the network held a charity auction that was conducted on the Ebay
Web site but was coordinated with televised programming.
</P>
<P>
   MTV plans to place ``Web RIOT'' at 5 p.m. on weekdays, right
after the network's popular ``Total Request Live,'' a daily
countdown of the top videos as chosen by viewers who have voted by
telephone and on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The host for the new show will be Ahmet Zappa, who in the past
has been co-host for ``MTV Live'' and USA Network's ``Happy Hour''
with his brother, Dweezil Zappa.
</P>
<P>
   MTV's technology partner is Spiderdance Inc., an Internet media
company that creates mass-participation online programming, to
synchronize answers on television and computer screens. No special
software, beyond a standard Web browser, is required.
</P>
<P>
   If it catches on, combining television programming with an
Internet component, holds various implications. Advertisers, for
example, might benefit from the apparent ease of pushing consumers
to Internet links where they can register their interest or
immediately buy a product.
</P>
<P>
   ``It presents the product in a seamless manner,'' said Kristian
Magel, vice president for national broadcasting at Dewitt Media
Inc., who advised the automaker BMW to buy a banner ad on ESPN's
online program during ``Sunday Night Football.'' With an online ad
costing less than 1 percent of a television spot, Magel said, the
thinking was ``why not just do it?''
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Web interaction gives television programmers and
their advertisers a wealth of information about viewers who
participate, including how long and how often they visit the site,
whether they click on ads and whether they make purchases online.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the great boons of interactive media is that marketers
can learn a lot more about their customers than they ever could
before,'' said Aram Sinnreich, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   MTV says it intends to collect only the first names, ages and
e-mail addresses of contestants, but will also gather the addresses
and phone numbers of the prize winners.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to the privacy implications, the company does not plan
to sell this information to outsiders, said Rick Holzman, vice
president for programming and promotion at MTV Interactive Online.
</P>
<P>
   ```Web Riot' is just another way to get people to interact with
our brands in a meaningful way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
