<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6819 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-ROAD-SHOWS-NYT &LR;      10-24 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-ROAD-SHOWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELECTIVE ROAD-SHOW REVIEWS ON IPO OFFERINGS UNDER REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the two weeks before they issue stock to the public, company
executives often make an exhausting round of meetings across the
country, sometimes the world _ in what is called a road show.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers with billions of dollars at their disposal get a
chance to speak face to face to the people to whom they plan to
entrust some of that money. And in question-and-answer sessions,
they can see how well a chief executive knows the business and how
he performs in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But this longtime practice of giving sophisticated investors a
preview, and sometimes useful nuggets of information beyond the
public documents, is being challenged now that Webvan, an online
grocer, has postponed its initial stock offering. Webvan was forced
to delay its plans a few weeks ago after a reporter for
TheStreet.com listened by telephone to a road-show presentation and
reported the company had made significant statements not included
in its public filings.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is on the radar screen of the Securities and Exchange
Commission. In remarks last week, the SEC's chairman, Arthur
Levitt, said that road shows should not be forums for providing a
different look at a company than what is in its prospectus.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate is part of a larger issue: the unequal disclosure
of material information. In his remarks, Levitt stepped up an
attack on selective disclosure, a practice in which companies brief
some analysts about financial data, like earnings details, before
the public release. He urged companies to let all investors take
part in conference calls about important information.
</P>
<P>
   In the Webvan episode, the fact that it involved an Internet
company and Internet reporter is almost incidental. And yet the
Internet does figure into the rising debate over who should be
invited to these road-show meetings and what material should be
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   After all, online trading is encouraging more and more people to
take an active role in their stock-market investments. And use of
the Internet allows the distribution of financial information to be
quicker and wider than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, only so many people could fit into a conference room
for a road-show meeting. And even a telephone conference call, it
could be argued, might become too expensive and disruptive if a
large number of individuals were to chime in. But these days,
so-called Webcasting technology can enable anyone with an Internet
connection to listen in on a conference call, if the company wants
to make it public _ as many Internet-savvy companies have begun to
do with their quarterly-earnings calls to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of initial public offerings, securities law does not
preclude individuals from taking part in road shows. But it does
make far-flung participation virtually prohibitive, because SEC
rules permit more liberal discussion of a company in person than
they do when communication is by radio, television, phone or the
Internet. Companies that have filed for a public stock offering
must publish all information material to their business in public
documents. But they may clarify or elaborate in oral
communications. As a former SEC official put it, the companies add
``melody to the lyrics'' of the prospectus in the road show.
</P>
<P>
   Written communication is limited to what appears in the
prospectus _ hence the term ``quiet period'' to refer to the time
just before a new stock offering. And yet, some companies have
successfully appealed to the commission to let them broadcast their
road-show presentations by phone and on a limited basis over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Congress gave the commission broad power to change the rules
three years ago, and the SEC is now proposing that companies have
the same latitude in broadcast communications that they have in
oral communication during the so-called quiet period.The proposals
are part of a controversial overhaul of rules governing new stock
offerings, which has been opened to public comment. The proposals
would not require such public access, but would allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the current system say that opening road shows to
everyone could cause chief executives to clam up, for fear that
their comments may lead to shareholder lawsuits. This new wariness,
this argument goes, might be a subtle but key impediment to new
companies' ability to raise capital.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the debate pits an information-age drive to give all
investors equal access against many companies' desire to conduct
private forums with the sophisticated investors who dominate the
financial markets. ``What we're seeing is a collision between the
traditional idea of a quiet period and the pressure being put on
the system by technology,'' said William R. McLucas of the
Washington law firm of Wilmer Cutler &AMP; Pickering, a former SEC
enforcement director.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of more openness say individuals should have a chance
to perform exactly the same sniff test on a new stock that big
investors do.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Menlow, editor of the newsletter IPO Frontline, said
television interviews with chief executives after a company comes
out of its quite period, appearances that can often move stock
prices, are a clear indication that investors do place importance
on how a company's leader looks and sounds. And that, Menlow said,
is evidence they could gather earlier if they had access to the
road show.
</P>
<P>
   Menlow says it is not unusual for companies, as Webvan did, to
offer nuggets of information that could prove useful to any
investor. ``Why should the institutions have the advantage?'' he
said. ``I'm incensed the investment banking community has gone
unchallenged. It and the SEC have exercised complete control and
kept out the media and small investors.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of opening up the road show say the prospect
raises two practical considerations. First, individual investors
listening to the meetings may not have the sophistication to
distinguish salesmanship from salient material. In the prospectus,
the risks of the venture are completely laid out, but they
typically are not spelled out in a road show. This, in turn, leads
to the concern about the possible proliferation of lawsuits. If
investors feel misled during a road show by an executive's
implication, wink, nod, or other suggestion of success, and the
stock plummets, plaintiffs' lawyers could get plenty of extra work.
</P>
<P>
   That is why big investors tend to worry that opening up a road
show would force executives to stick to the script of the
prospectus, and hinder the ability of institutions to get the
information they need to make investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred R. Berkeley, president of the Nasdaq market, who says he
has attended several hundred road shows, generally favors broader
access. But he said any change had to be incremental, adding, ``My
concern is that the demand for mouths to open will actually have
the effect of causing mouths to close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
