</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRICHTON-MOVIE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JURASSIC PARK' AUTHOR TO GET BOX OFFICE PERCENTAGE FOR NEXT FILM 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Viacom's Paramount Pictures studio has made an
unusual deal with author Michael Crichton for his newest novel.
Instead of collecting millions of dollars by selling the rights to
the studio, Crichton has opted to take a sizable percentage of the
box office receipts.
</P>
<P>
   While film stars and top directors have, at times, signed such
deals, studio executives said they could not recall a similar deal
with a novelist.
</P>
<P>
   The book is ``Timeline,'' to be published soon by Alfred A.
Knopf, a unit of Bertelsmann. Galleys for the novel have circulated
for several weeks among Hollywood studios, which mostly passed on
the novel. The story involves an architect, a historian and a
medievalist who travel back in time and are in danger of being
stuck in the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton's manager, AMG Entertainment, whose owner, Michael
Ovitz, shaped the deal, also stipulated that another client,
Richard Donner, who directed the ``Lethal Weapon'' series, make the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Together the two, as well as Lauren Shuler-Donner, the producer
and Donner's wife, may share about 15 percent of the ``first dollar
gross,'' or initial box office receipts, for the movie, studio
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely how much the team will receive _ and earn _ was left
unclear. Some people involved in the arrangement said the
percentage might be higher. But studio executives said that once
Crichton and the Donners earned their customary fees _ Donner earns
as much as $10 million a film _ the box office percentage would
drop.
</P>
<P>
   Crichton has a generally strong, though not entirely successful,
track record in Hollywood. ``Jurassic Park'' and ``Disclosure''
were made into successful films. His last novel, ``Air Frame,''
about an imperiled female aerospace worker investigating a
cover-up, was sold more than two years ago for about $9 million to
Walt Disney Co., one of the highest sums ever paid for a novel. But
the project, after several scripts, seems to be foundering, studio
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   To top directors and stars, earning a hefty percentage of the
box office can turn into a financial bonanza. Tom Hanks and Steven
Spielberg, for example, received relatively little money at the
start of making ``Saving Private Ryan,'' which was seen as a
commercially risky film. But the movie has been a worldwide
success. Hanks earned $30 million or more, while Spielberg brought
home at minimum $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, but on a far smaller scale, the stars and director of
``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' earned millions of dollars each
when the film proved highly successful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CABLE-WIRELESS-NYT &LR;      10-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-WIRELESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE AND WIRELESS' WORLDWIDE REACH MAY BE SCARING OFF SUITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic and photo are is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Sitting pensive in his wood-paneled office here, Graham
Wallace dismissed the constant whispers among investors and
analysts around London's financial district _ the rumors that his
far-flung global telecommunications company Cable and Wireless is
ripe for a takeover and ready to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no interest in that,'' Wallace said, blithely waving
his hand. ``Sure I get calls every day. And I tell all of them the
same thing. I say that we have a completely viable stand-alone
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he paused, hedging his words and almost daring his
rivals to make a hostile bid. ``If those guys want to do different
things in the marketplace,'' Wallace continued, ``then that's their
affair.''
</P>
<P>
   Since February, when he was promoted to the top job at Cable and
Wireless after Richard Brown left to become chief of Electronic
Data Systems in the United States, Wallace has been busily trying
to put his company's house in order.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, the broader telecommunications industry has been
going through a whirlwind of merger-and-acquisition activity in the
United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom is in the midst of buying Sprint in the largest
acquisition in history. Mannesmann, Germany's fast-growing
engineering and telecommunications group, just announced it was
buying Orange PLC, Britain's third-largest mobile phone operator.
Global Crossing, the Bermuda-based upstart acquired Britain's Racal
Telecommunications two weeks ago. And France Telecom said it would
acquire 60 percent of the E-Plus wireless telephone network from
two major German utility companies, Veba and RWE.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, seeming to sit on the sidelines, has been
Cable and Wireless, the century-old British telecommunications
concern with a scattering of motley interests all over the world.
No wonder investment bankers here are quietly eyeing the company
and making lists of possible partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are probably the perennial favorite to be taken over or
broken up, but so far no one has bit,'' said Patrick Steiner, a
telecommunications analyst at Chase in London. ``Their varied
collection of assets makes it hard for a single buyer to justify
buying them.''
</P>
<P>
   That perception has plagued Cable and Wireless for years, not
only in terms of a potential acquisition, but even in terms of
assigning a value to the company. Cable and Wireless has major
holdings in at least 10 countries _ the largest being its stake in
Hong Kong Telecom, which remains a major question mark in the minds
of potential investors because it is partially owned by China's
state telephone company, China Telecom. The company also has its
own network in Britain and throughout parts of Europe, along with a
major Internet backbone in the United States that it acquired from
MCI last year.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a company with a global presence might sound
appealing to a telecommunications firm looking to expand its
worldwide network, but Cable and Wireless' holdings are almost too
worldwide. ``For a European player, they may have no interest in
Japan; the same goes for a Japanese player who has no interest in
Europe,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has been doing some major house-cleaning himself in
recent months as he tries to reposition the company away from its
consumer businesses toward a focus strictly on business customers,
which tends to be a market with higher profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   The most noteworthy divestiture was its sale in late July of the
consumer business of Cable and Wireless Communications, including
its telephone, cable and Internet properties, to NTL Inc. for $13.2
billion. And then about two weeks later it sold its 50 percent
stake in the British mobile telephone provider One 2 One for $5.78
billion, to Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   [On Sunday, Cable and Wireless said that it would sell its
holdings in Bezeq Ltd., Israel's state-controlled phone company, to
a local investor for $630 million.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to create shareholder value,'' Wallace said. ``The
business market is simply a better business. We lose nothing and
gain everything by making these sales. When we're finished we will
be the new-age telco.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts tend to think the strategy is on the right course,
though some believe the company must either acquire another company
or be acquired if it has any chance of being a major player in an
industry that continues to consolidate. At the very least, analysts
said, Cable and Wireless may need an alliance or partnership in
order to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts interviewed for this article spoke on the
condition of anonymity, because almost every major bank in London
is either doing some sort of work for Cable and Wireless or is
representing a competitor. ``They don't have enough cash to do a
big, big deal,'' one said. ``But by all means they've got to do
something sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the possible suitors for Cable and Wireless, many analysts
see Deutsche Telekom as a likely candidate because its other
options have begun to dwindle as many of Europe's major
telecommunications companies have already been gobbled up.
``Deutche Telekom may just decide to do a major transaction because
it wants to,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Other interested parties, analysts and investment bankers said,
could be MCI Worldcom, which is eager for a worldwide presence.
``MCI is busy doing the Sprint deal,'' another analyst observed.
``But when they finish, CW could be their next target.''
</P>
<P>
   Among British telecommunications companies, the mobile phone
player Vodaphone Airtouch, which already has an alliance with Cable
and Wireless, could be a front-runner to acquire the company as a
way to gain access to a worldwide land-line network. Analysts and
investment bankers also point out that, at least in Britain, the
companies could get regulatory approval because they operate
different businesses. British Telecommunications is also frequently
mentioned, but many analysts see major regulatory hurdles to such a
merger, because the two companies have overlapping and competing
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, at least, Wallace insists on sticking to his
go-it-alone script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm skeptical about alliances,'' he said. ``Give me stunning
example of a partnership in the telecom world, and I give you a
long list that haven't worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
