<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-FISCAL-POLICY-1155(2T     10-24 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISCAL-POLICY-1155(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET SURPLUS MAY GO TOWARD CUTTING NATIONAL DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all the political bloodshed over President
Clinton's spending proposals and attempts by Republicans to cut
taxes, the standoff this year over budget policy has led the two
parties into a third choice _ to slash the national debt _ that
could have equally enormous political and economic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Such a momentous decision, made almost by default as each side
blocked the others' proposals for allocating projected federal
budget surpluses, has consequences that are sure to eclipse in
importance the outcome of the current sparring over financing for
education, across-the-board spending cuts and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the magnitude of the decision, it was made without an
explicit vote or even a full debate in Congress and the country.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were trillions of dollars in projected surpluses
on the table in a town that has never had trouble parceling out
money, the two sides essentially battled each other to a draw on
what to do with it. There was no big tax cut. There was no big
surge in government spending. There was no expansion of Medicare,
and no agreement on how to shore up Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Yet gridlock in this case meant that the surplus was left more
or less intact. And because of the way the government's finances
work, running a surplus means that the excess revenues flowing into
Washington will automatically go to paying down the debt that the
nation ran up during decades of deficit spending, and to doing so
at a pace that would have been considered fantasy even a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Should the government stick to the course it is setting out on,
it could eliminate the most important component of the debt, the
$3.6 trillion in Treasury bonds owned by the public, within 10 or
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   While the approach was never put to a vote or even fully debated
in Congress, it yielded an outcome that most economists, including
Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman, consider to be
extremely positive for the economy over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing the publicly held debt would put downward pressure on
interest rates and free up capital for private enterprise to use in
building new factories or developing new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   It would reduce the government's interest expense, and increase
the government's capacity to borrow in the future if it needs cash
for looming problems like the projected shortfall in Social
Security's reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying down debt in large amounts is a truly momentous and
entirely salutary decision,'' said Carol Cox Wait, president of the
Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget, a fiscal watchdog
group. ``It is the one thing we can do in the short term to put us
in a much better position to do with the problems we face in the
long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Debt reduction was basically a fallback position for both
parties, embraced by them in its own right only after Clinton
blocked the Republican effort to cut taxes and Republicans stymied
calls by Democrats for higher government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party had debt reduction as its priority, but it ended
up being the common denominator they could agree on through
gridlock,'' said Van Doorn Ooms, research director for the
Committee for Economic Development, a business-funded research
group.
</P>
<P>
   Yet politicians of all stripes quickly found that debt
reduction, which they had long considered arcane and difficult to
sell to voters as an accomplishment, had a political appeal far
greater than they had anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton would return to the White House from speeches and tell
aides that he had been unexpectedly interrupted by applause when he
mentioned debt reduction. At town hall meetings, constituents would
tell their members of Congress that if a family were to receive a
financial windfall, it should go to cleaning up credit-card bills,
not to spending on a new car or a vacation _ and that government
should have the same attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a metaphor the American people instantly understand,''
said Rep. John Spratt of South Carolina, the senior Democrat on the
House Budget Committee. ``The American people get debt reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the consensus behind debt reduction in Washington remains
somewhat tenuous, and neither party sees continued gridlock as a
long-term strategy, particularly since Washington has only deferred
long-term problems like the solvency of Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative Republicans maintain that tax cuts would help
the economy more than debt reduction would. Some liberal Democrats
say higher spending in areas like education and health care would
be the best way to invest the surplus in the nation's future. If
divided government gave way to a situation in which one party
controlled both the White House and Congress, support for debt
reduction might dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, changing economic circumstances could lead to one
party or both reassessing their commitment to debt reduction as the
first fiscal priority.
</P>
<P>
   Should the economy turn down, both parties would likely support
some form of tax cut as a stimulus to recovery, and there could be
backing as well for increased spending, especially on social
welfare programs like unemployment insurance, job training and
assistance to families with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debt reduction isn't everything,'' said Robert Bixby,
executive director of the Concord Coalition, a fiscal policy group.
``It happens to be a very good and responsible thing to do at this
point in our nation's demographic and economic history, but in
other economic times it might not be true.''
</P>
<P>
   But especially given that both Clinton and Republican leaders in
Congress have pledged not to spend any of the portion of the
surplus generated by excess Social Security payroll tax revenues _
a promise that could bring swift political retribution if broken by
either side _ the fiscal debate in coming years seems likely to be
biased toward debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taboo against spending Social Security trust-fund
surpluses probably will be a continuing reality for some years to
come,'' Ms. Wait said.
</P>
<P>
   The national debt began surging in the early 1980s as Washington
began running huge annual deficits, forcing the Treasury to borrow
to make up the difference between tax revenues and spending.
</P>
<P>
   Debt held by the public went from $710 billion, or 26.1 percent
of gross domestic product, in 1980 to a peak of $3.77 trillion, or
47.2 percent of GDP, in 1997. Surpluses in the last two years have
allowed the government to reduce the debt to $3.6 trillion, or
about 40 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
   National debt can also be defined to include money the
government owes to itself, primarily in the form of promises to pay
future Social Security benefits. By that measure, the debt, now
about $5.6 trillion, will continue to grow for the foreseeable
future as the population ages and commitments to retirees continue
to mount.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, it was the political power of Social
Security that brought debt reduction to the top of the fiscal
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton started the process when he called in his 1998 State of
the Union address for the surplus to be left untouched until the
two parties had agreed on a plan to strengthen Social Security's
financial condition before the retirement of the vast baby-boom
generation.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy, which proved successful, was to block Republicans
on their signature issue by framing the fiscal choice before the
country as between saving Social Security and having a big tax cut.
At the time, White House aides said, debt reduction was considered
a nice byproduct of the strategy, but not the main goal.
</P>
<P>
   But by early this year, with the size of the projected surpluses
growing almost by the month, pressure was growing in both parties
to do something with the fiscal windfall. So Clinton set out a new
framework, saying that 63 percent of the total budget surplus over
the next 15 years should be used directly or indirectly for Social
Security, with the rest going to a variety of other programs, from
the military to education.
</P>
<P>
   Late last winter, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., chairman of the
Senate Budget Committee, saw a way to trump the White House. He
pointed out that Clinton's proposal would allow the government to
spend some of the portion of the surplus being generated by Social
Security, a practice the government had engaged in for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici put forward a budget framework that allowed Republicans
to claim that they would not spend any of the Social Security
surplus, which amounts to roughly $2 trillion of the $3 trillion
total surplus over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans like Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, the chairman of
the House Budget Committee, were reluctant at first, fearing that
the plan would limit their ability to press for an immediate tax
cut. But they eventually went along with Domenici's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, particularly in the House, were reluctant to sign on
to a program of austerity at a time of fiscal plenty. But by early
summer, Clinton had agreed that he too would leave the Social
Security surplus untouched, and most Democrats in Congress, not
wanting to cede the high ground as protectors of the New Deal
social-welfare legacy, reluctantly went along.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was a bipartisan consensus to allocate two-thirds of
the total surplus to debt reduction, a decision reached before
either party had fully thought through the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the two parties have been grappling with how to turn
their pledge into policy, starting with a budget for the fiscal
year that began on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It is still not clear that the two parties will be able to
completely make good on their promise. Republicans in Congress have
had to resort to all manner of budget gimmicks to pass spending
bills that leave the Social Security surplus untouched for this
year, and they are counting on spending cuts that Clinton has
already made clear are unacceptable to him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed a tax hike on cigarettes as an alternative
to spending Social Security money, but there is little support for
the idea in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they miss their goal of leaving the Social Security
money alone, it would not be by much in the context of a $1.8
trillion budget and a projected total surplus for the new fiscal
year of $160 billion. In any case, spending some of the retirement
system's money would have little or no direct effect on Social
Security's long-term financial condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
