<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO PUT YOUR FINGER ON A GREAT MEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you identify the most important aid to cooking excellence?
Nope, it's not the Cuisinart, the automatic bread maker, the
electric spice grinder or the industrial-size Mixmaster.
</P>
<P>
   You own one. You got it free. About the only maintenance
required is an occasional washup with soap and water.
</P>
<P>
   As any professional chef will say, the one essential to quality
control in the kitchen is the index finger.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, not the middle finger. That big digit can get you in a
whole lot of trouble, especially in Seattle, where road rage has
created a growth industry for insult specialists and kick-boxing
instructors.
</P>
<P>
   The index finger is the one next to your thumb. It's the finger
that chefs stick into a pot of simmering spaghetti sauce before
exclaiming, ``Dang, that's hot and, wow, that's tasty!''
</P>
<P>
   If they don't say, ``Wow, that's tasty,'' the sauce needs more
salt and a smidgen more oregano. But they wouldn't know this if
they hadn't stuck a finger into the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, you could use a tasting spoon. But chefs are busy
people and sometimes have to taste test garlic soup, chocolate
mousse and anchovy sauce in rapid-fire progression.
</P>
<P>
   They use an index finger (when the health inspectors aren't
looking) and after a few months in the profession they don't even
feel any pain when they stir-cook cheese fondue with the
indispensable digit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are exceptions to every rule. When you are
mixing up high explosives or the culinary equivalent _ like Thai
curries _ more than an educated finger is required. A foolproof
(and boom-proof) recipe is required.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor to Seattle, Nareerat Srisawat, has some excellent Thai
recipes, but she had a tough time selling them to her staff when
she owned and operated a restaurant in Thailand. Her background
also includes stints as an executive secretary, a merchandising
manager for a large luxury hotel and a facilitator in international
trade. And at one time she worked in Seattle for Thai Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Her restaurant experience was a continual frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thai chefs don't use recipes,'' says Nareerat, more commonly
known as ``Toy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They throw in some of this, some of that and then they
taste,'' she elaborated. ``Poor customer. If chief cook takes day
off, everything changes.''
</P>
<P>
   She took the logical remedial action, posting recipes on the
kitchen wall, and ordering the cooks to follow the instructions to
the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But to a Thai chef, a posted recipe is an insult to his or her
culinary expertise.
</P>
<P>
   `` `You must follow this recipe,' I tell them. They just look at
me. When I walk out of kitchen, they throw something else in the
pot. It is a big problem in Thai restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   The tasting finger is apparently not used to fine-tune the
cooking in Thailand. It is the accelerator, the brake and the
left-turn signal for the chef at the controls of the stove.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all else fails, read instructions,'' is North American
advice. When all else fails in Thailand, the chef throws away the
instructions, adds more curry sauce and tastes.
</P>
<P>
   If he is lucky, it might taste as good as this.
</P>
<P>
   Five Fingers Beef Skewers
</P>
<P>
   2 and one-half pounds sirloin steak
</P>
<P>
   5 teaspoons red chili flakes
</P>
<P>
   5 thin slices fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   10 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cup oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup teriyaki sauce
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Dump the chili flakes, ginger, garlic and curry powder into a
blender or processor. Lean on the button until you have a paste.
Mix this muck with the oyster and teriyaki sauces. Stir in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the sirloin into thin strips. Pour the sauce over all, moosh
around with all of your fingers, then cover and refrigerate 4 hours
or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Soak bamboo skewers in water for at least an hour. Then pierce
pieces of meat with the point of the stick three or four times as
you thread it onto each skewer.
</P>
<P>
   Cook briefly on a hot barbecue fire or under an oven broiler,
turning once. Don't overcook. The inside of the meat should be
pink.
</P>
<P>
   Thai Noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Asian noodles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red curry paste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound lean pork or chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 large carrot, peeled and cut matchstick size
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Asian fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 green onions, chopped, including green tops
</P>
<P>
   One quarter cup fresh cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup chopped peanuts
</P>
<P>
   We used buckwheat noodles, but you can substitute Hokkien or
Shanghai noodles. Cook according to package instructions in
boiling, salted water. If you refuse to read the instructions,
you're not going to get a job in Toy's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The red curry paste and Asian fish sauce can now be found in any
large American supermarket or _ probably at less cost _ in one of
the area's many Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   When noodles are done, drain, add a tablespoon of oil to keep
them from sticking, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon oil in a wok or large skillet. Add the garlic
and curry paste and stir-cook 1 minute. Add the pork or chicken,
which has been cut into thin strips, and cook 2 to 3 minutes, until
meat is no longer red.
</P>
<P>
   Add the carrot, fish sauce and brown sugar and half the green
onions and bring to a boil. Stir in the noodles and when everything
is hot, plop the ingredients of the pan into a serving platter and
scatter the remaining green onions, the cilantro and the peanuts
over the top. Serves four as a main dish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
