<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6844 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      10-24 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S TOUGHEST FIGHT FOR GOP NOMINATION COULD BE AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Texas, Mich.)  (Eds: 2nd take to be filed by 7 p.m.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Even as Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., enjoys a wave of
friendly publicity in his quest for the Republican presidential
nomination, he is struggling to prevent his great ambition from
collapsing in the most unlikely of places: His home state of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The state's most popular politician, Gov. Jane Dee Hull, has
defied political custom and endorsed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
instead of the home-state favorite. The reason, according to people
close to Mrs. Hull and McCain, is the senator's dismissive
treatment of her.
</P>
<P>
   While McCain easily won election to the Senate three times, his
temperament and sometimes prickly personality _ which rarely
surfaces in public _ may complicate his climb to the nomination.
Mrs. Hull's rebuff means that McCain may have to devote precious
resources to compete on his own turf, the first primary contest in
the West. And a struggle there could draw attention to a side of
the senator that remains largely out of view but which has
alienated other politicians, including those back home who know him
best.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hull described her relations with McCain as ``not
particularly warm.'' Pretending to hold a telephone receiver
several inches from her ear, Mrs. Hull explained in an interview
last week how she reacts to McCain's occasional eruptions at her.
``You've got to hold it out there for a while, and let him calm
down,'' she said. ``We all have our faults, and it's something that
John has to keep control of.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Woods, a former Arizona attorney general who was McCain's
first administrative assistant when he was elected to Congress in
1982, admitted that McCain had been ``heavy-handed'' with Mrs.
Hull. ``People come away with great respect and admiration for
him,'' he said. ``But it's kind of ridiculous to gloss over big
flaws and pretend they don't exist. John McCain likes being the
maverick but does not tolerate mavericks well. Gov. Hull was not
willing to be told how to do her job.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's victory in the state's presidential primary four months
from now is by no means assured; polls show he is in a tight
competition with Bush. By throwing her political organization
behind Bush, Mrs. Hull could cut into McCain's home-state base of
support. Sensing his vulnerability, Bush and Steve Forbes, his
other main rival, each plan to pump millions of dollars into the
state to try to topple him.
</P>
<P>
   While Arizona sends only a handful of delegates to the party's
nominating convention, the primary here, set for Feb. 22, is an
important test for McCain, the senior senator from the state that
gave Barry Goldwater to the Republican Party. The contest comes
only two weeks before the pivotal primaries on March 7 in
California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But far beyond Arizona, Mrs. Hull's spurning of McCain stands as
a telling example of how, despite his reputation as a war hero who
dares to speak his mind, the senator's personal style rankles many
politicians. Several people deeply involved in state politics said
the very attributes that many voters admire _ stubborn to the point
of rude, temperamental and cocksure in his maverick military way _
work against him with other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Already, advisers to Bush have seized on Mrs. Hull's endorsement
as evidence that McCain has flaws that may make him a
less-than-ideal presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a very good one-man performance,'' said Gov. John
Engler of Michigan, the Bush campaign's liaison to governors.
``It's not as clear how effective he is as part of a team.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Engler said, has made ``judgments in a negative way
about Jane and her abilities _ she wasn't his person.'' He added,
``Sometimes a leader needs to reach out a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hull insisted that her decision to back Bush was not
anti-McCain but pro-Bush. But she made clear she was rankled by the
senator's treatment of her.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether McCain ever forgave her when, as a state
legislator, she endorsed another candidate for Congress in 1982,
Mrs. Hull said, ``John has a long memory.'' And asked whether it
was true that McCain aggressively encouraged Mrs. Hull to fire or
demote her chief of staff, Rick Collins, the governor turned to
Collins and made light of the episode. ``Did he actually want me to
fire you?'' she asked, ``or just boil you in oil?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was fire,'' Collins replied with a smile.
``It was, `Just kill him!'''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain, in an interview, denied the accusations
and called them ``just bizarre.'' Asked if he ever tried to get
Mrs. Hull to punish or demote Collins, he said, ``I will take a
polygraph. I've never retaliated against anybody because that is
not my view of the way you go through life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're good friends,'' he said of his relationship with the
governor. ``I've never had a harsh word with her to my knowledge. I
endorsed her and campaigned with her in the last election.'' Told
of Mrs. Hull's comments about him, McCain said, ``Maybe something
has chilled since election night.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
