<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TIME-TV-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-24 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIME-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIME OF YOUR LIFE': AN INNOCENT ABROAD IN NEW YORK, FRESH FROM
FRISCO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is all this fuss about Jennifer Love Hewitt? Apparently she
became the beloved of teen-agers everywhere, playing Sarah,
girlfriend of the troubled but cute Bailey Salinger (Scott Wolf),
on Fox's hit drama ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a few months ago some Audrey Hepburn fans were horrified to
learn that she would be playing Hepburn in a forthcoming television
film. (Of course, having anyone play Hepburn seems sacrilege to a
lot of us. Julia Ormond's career still hasn't recovered from her
re-creation of Hepburn's character in the remake of ``Sabrina.'')
In comparison, Ms. Hewitt's starring in her own series, a ``Party
of Five'' spinoff, seems a relatively low-risk career move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time of Your Life,'' which has its premiere on Fox Monday
night, maintains the appealing romanticized realism of its parent
series. (If you'd watched them forever, do you think you would ever
have seen Ann Marie or Mary Richards, Sarah's
young-single-woman-in-the-city forebears, take off her bra while a
new guy watched appreciatively? That happens in the third episode
of ``Time of Your Life.'' Felicity, of course, is another story.)
The new series makes something of a case for the appeal of Ms.
Hewitt's post-modern vulnerability, an innocence that seems
dangerous when plopped down in Manhattan after hours.
</P>
<P>
   The show also does a good job of capturing the infinite
possibility facing a 20-year-old who has just moved to New York. In
Sarah's case the move began as a short trip to locate and encounter
her biological father. (Sarah was adopted and her biological mother
is dead.) Back on ``Party of Five,'' back in San Francisco, Sarah
assured Bailey that it was only a five-day trip and that she'd be
back in a flash. But viewers knew better.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah ends up, in an unlikely turn of events, living in the East
Village apartment that her mother lived in around the time Sarah
was born (January 1979). Her roommate, Romy, is a starving actress
who's ready to pack it in and go back home to her parents until a
couple of promising things happen to her.
</P>
<P>
   For Sarah there's a good-looking, sensitive guy (Johnathon
Schaech), a guitarist good enough to have played with Beck on the
scene. And he gets to be the one to inform Sarah that moving to New
York can be the beginning of a whole new life, if she wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be whoever you want to be, from here on out,'' he
explains, with the requisite Manhattan skyline at night twinkling
behind him. ``Invent yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Like lots of young people in the city, Sarah learns fast. When
she arrives, she strikes up a conversation with a stranger at the
airport luggage carousel, telling him her situation (which is
conveniently the spinoff's back story). He promptly suggests they
go to a hotel for ``sexual adventures.''
</P>
<P>
   A day or two later, when she meets the man she believes to be
her father _ and he turns out to be black and gay _ she coolly asks
if perhaps 20 or so years ago he had questioned or been uncertain
of his sexual identity. He hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   So Sarah continues her search. She drinks too much, gets
arrested for jumping a subway turnstile (well, the token booth was
closed; what were she and her friends to do?), sneaks into a
black-tie benefit at Lincoln Center by pretending to be with the
band and finally checks her e-mail, which gives her a hint of the
bad news from Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   When the judge pegs her as ``a sorority girl from the suburbs,''
one thing becomes clear: she does not want to be, she says, ``the
Marcia Brady of the new millennium.'' Future episodes are expected
to depict her fight against that kind of predictable niceness.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell has a cameo in Monday night's episode as the
receptionist of a theater impresario who may be Sarah's real
father. She's adorably obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   TIME OF YOUR LIFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Monday on FOX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 5 in New York)  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Created by Christopher Keyser and Amy Lippman; Keyser, Ms.
Lippman, Ken Topolsky and Mark Perry, executive producers; Michael
Engler, co-executive producer; Ivan Menchell, supervising producer;
Paul Marks, Shelley Meals, Darin Goldberg, Jennifer Love Hewitt and
Ellen Pressman, producers; Val Joseph, co-producer. A production of
Keyser/Lippman Productions in association with Columbia Tri-Star
Television.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jennifer Love Hewitt (Sarah Merrin), Diego Serrano (JB),
Jennifer Garner (Romy) and Pauley Perrette (Cecilia). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
