<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-8     10-24 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TURMOIL IN AN ENCLAVE WITH CHECHNYA AS A NEIGHBOR  (ART ADV: Map is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With each passing day, Ruslan Aushev, the president of the tiny
enclave of Ingushetia in Russia's Northern Caucasus, is becoming
more and more desperate with what he calls the ``imperial
thinking'' in Moscow and Russia's prosecution of war in neighboring
Chechnya, which has sent almost 170,000 refugees fleeing into his
impoverished republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't understand one thing,'' he said of the leaders in
Moscow. `'Even if we stamp out the bandits, dunk them, destroy them
_ and here too I have my doubts _ what will happen after that? Who
will come and run the Chechen republic?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we have to say clearly and succinctly, what is the
goal that the federal center has set for itself,'' he said in an
interview. ``That goal is known only to a few people and no one
else.''
</P>
<P>
   From his palatial premises in Magas, a cluster of glistening new
office buildings that form the new capital of Ingushetia, Aushev, a
former battalion commander in the Soviet army and a decorated
veteran of the Afghan war, who prefers military fatigues to suits,
tries to sway the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he was on the phone to Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev, arguing that the Russian military had neither the legal
nor moral right to usurp his authority as Ingushetia's elected
leader.
</P>
<P>
   He lost that argument, just as he has so far failed to persuade
Moscow authorities to resume a dialogue with Chechen President
Aslan Maskhadov. Aushev said Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin
was ``categorically'' against any such meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The war is close here _ so close that on Thursday evening, at
about 6:30 p.m., residents say they could literally hear it.
According to Aushev, people here reported what sounded like
low-flying planes or missiles heading eastward. Moments later, four
explosions went off in Grozny, the Chechen capital, where according
to Chechen officials, more than 100 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way to fight terrorism,'' said Aushev in an
interview in his office with The New York Times and Radio Liberty.
``There are other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he added: ``They should stop their imperial thinking. It
is imperial thinking that prevents the Russian leadership from
having a policy in the Caucasus.''
</P>
<P>
   The military campaign, he said, is cutting off chances for a
political region that has spent the last eight years slipping from
war to unruly peace and now to war again.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a month now, Ingushetia has had to cope with wave
upon wave of Chechen refugees, anxious and terrified families who
have clambered into cars, vans, buses and trucks, fleeing bombing
attacks by Russian federal forces.
</P>
<P>
   The various and diverse nationalities of the North Caucasus live
at close quarters. Ingushetia is itself a recently created region
that fought a bitter war with another neighbor, North Ossetia, over
disputed territory in the early 1990s. Grozny is only about 40
miles away from Magas, on the outskirts of Nazran, Ingushetia's
main city.
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, the Chechens and Ingushes lived uneasily
together in one nominally autonomous republic. Since the Soviet
Union broke up in 1991, the Caucasus region has been a maze of
bloody conflict, most notably in Chechnya, where Russian forces
battled rebels who sought independence for two years before
withdrawing in 1996 and leaving the breakaway region's status in
official limbo until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That uneasy peace dissolved in August, when Chechen guerrillas
became Russia's public enemy No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Russian government, Islamic militants based in
Chechnya not only carried out armed raids last August against
Dagestan, the Russian republic to Chechnya's east, but are also
responsible for bombing attacks, which killed almost 300 people in
Moscow and other Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, as Russian military vehicles lined the main
highway between Nazran and Grozny, the flow of Chechen refugees _
mainly women and children _was virtually stopped by order of
Russian military commanders. Even before blocking the only highway
out of Grozny, the Russians had set up a gauntlet of checkpoints
and roadblocks designed to filter out guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   With Russian forces now occupying Chechnya's northern tier, the
first glimmer of a national debate has opened up in Russia over
where the war should go from here.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military commanders have not ruled out the possibility
of an assault on Grozny, although many experts and a few
politicians predict that if Russian troops move deeper into
Chechnya, they will get bogged down in a hopeless war, where winter
and a mountainous terrain will give the advantage to well-armed
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ` &UR; ` &LR; There will be no quick, decisive victory,'' said Aushev.
``According to my information, there are about 26,000 guerrillas
all armed to the teeth, and now, after the explosions in Grozny,
there will be even more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here in Ingushetia, where the tide of refugees is overwhelming
the region's meagre resources, and straining the hospitality of
local families, Aushev says Moscow has to demonstrate that its war
is against Chechen guerrillas and not against the Chechen people.
</P>
<P>
   The same case is made, more passionately, by the refugees
themselves. ``What have we done to the Russians to deserve this?''
said one woman from Grozny, leaping out of her family's van as it
stalled in a mile long traffic jam at the border with Ingushetia
border on Friday. ` &UR; ` &LR; Tell us why this is happening to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other leaders in the region, Aushev has accounts to settle
with the Chechen bandit groups blamed for a wave of kidnappings and
violence that in the last two years has spread into Ingushetia. He
is also critical of the Chechen leader, Maskhadov, for letting the
situation inside Chechnya reel out of control after 1996, and for
failing to prevent or condemn the armed raids into Dagestan last
August.
</P>
<P>
   But Aushev said the real cause for the latest conflict was in
Moscow, where Russian political leaders are engaged in a bitter
power struggle in the runup to December's parliamentary elections,
and next summer's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in the Caucasus during the 1990s has always been
in the hands of forces which at any time, can be put into play,''
he said. ``Whoever solves the problems here becomes a hero of the
Russian federation, his ratings will go up, and he will have a big
chance to become president.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, a former KGB officer and former head of Russia's security
forces, was named prime minister in August, days after federal
forces made their first stand against the Chechen guerrillas in
Dagestan. Since launching the military campaign against men
routinely branded terrorists by Russian officials and media, his
approval ratings have soared.
</P>
<P>
   According to Aushev, the conflict in Dagestan was one that had
long been foreseen by leaders in the region, and yet no preventive
measures were taken by federal forces to protect Dagestan from
attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
