<HEADLINE>
`WONDERS OF THE AFRICAN WORLD': EXPLORING BLACK KINGDOMS OF
ANTIQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(ms) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Roots'' meets Kenneth Clark's ``Civilization'' as Henry Louis
Gates Jr., the prolific scholar, turns tour guide in a six-hour
series with the unscholarly title of ``Wonders of the African
World.'' Like other black Americans, he has been drawn to the
history of civilizations created and ruled by blacks in Africa
centuries before Europeans decided the continent was dark.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Afro-American Studies at Harvard University
makes a cheerfully informal companion on a journey that visits a
dozen countries where blacks made their mark. Monday night's
opening hour finds Gates _ he's the fellow in the Harvard shirt _
traveling from Egypt into Sudan, one of the world's less-frequented
tourist destinations. There he and the researchers he interviews at
sandy sites tell of Nubia, where, they say, for a thousand years,
from the rise of Greece through the fall of Rome, black kingdoms
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   There he sees the pyramids where generations of Nubian kings and
queens are buried (Sudan has more pyramids than Egypt), the remains
of Nubia's 4,000-year-old first capital and the descendants of an
ancient people.
</P>
<P>
   Present-day Nubians, he reports, are friendly, and so is their
visitor, whether he is buying a dozen oranges in a marketplace,
dressing up in white to be the guest of honor at a wedding, helping
to push a car out of a sand drift, climbing rocks on a rope or
allowing himself to be buried naked in the sand, reputed to have
healthful properties. ``I feel like a mummy,'' he says, but we
don't learn whether the treatment helped his arthritic hip.
</P>
<P>
   He is impressed by wall drawings showing that the earliest
pharaohs were black, but is distressed by the coming of huge
hydroelectric dams that are obliterating the evidence of a precious
history, along with the villages that today's Nubians call or
called home. (When villagers welcome the dams, he suspects that
they may be speaking more for the benefit of lurking government
security types than from their hearts.)
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the descriptions of African accomplishments
have a wishful quality, Gates' credentials and personality inspire
confidence as he proceeds on his odyssey into South Africa,
Zimbabwe, Mali and Ethiopia. In Ghana, Benin and Tanzania, centers
of the 19th-century slave trade, he finds evidence of the fate of
the many Africans who served rather than ruled, a painful contrast
to the glories that he reports were Nubia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   WONDERS OF THE AFRICAN WORLD With Henry Louis Gates Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday &UR;  &LR; nights on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Wall to Wall Television Ltd.; Henry Louis Gates Jr.,
host and writer; Ben Goold, series producer; Jonathan Hewes,
executive producer; Nicola Colton, Nick Godwin and Helena Appio,
directors; title music by Spiro, Wix, Legwabe.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
