<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUISIANA-POLITICS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPICY POLITICS ASIDE, LOUISIANA GOVERNOR WINS IN A LANDSLIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ In the end, all the campaign embarrassments and
miscues had little if any effect on Gov. Mike Foster's bid for a
second term. He proved himself to be one of the state's most
popular Republican officeholders in years and won going away in
Saturday's election, brushing off 10 challengers.
</P>
<P>
   A reform-minded conservative from Cajun country with a disarming
good-ol'-boy patter, Foster had concentrated during his first term
on three of Louisiana's most bothersome problems: a struggling
economy, inferior public schools and tort laws that made the state
one of the most litigious in the country. That concentration paid
off. Foster captured more than 60 percent of the vote, twice as
much as his nearest challenger, Rep. William J. Jefferson, a
Democrat from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   No other challenger got more than 3 percent of the vote on a day
when turnout was estimated at about 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We there,'' Foster declared in his best bayou-country accent
as he claimed victory at a late-night rally in Lafayette on
Saturday. ``So I'll be back in the office on Monday, ready to pick
up again running this state like a well-managed business,
continuing the good work that we've started. I told you all I'd get
us off the bad list of states and onto the good list, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while during the campaign, it seemed that Foster himself
might make a list of candidates who embarrass themselves.
</P>
<P>
   First, he was forced to acknowledge that in 1995, during his
first run for governor, he secretly bought a list of campaign
contributors and supporters from David Duke, the former Ku Klux
Klan leader, for $150,000. Then the state Ethics Board fined him
$20,000 for not reporting the purchase as a campaign expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a federal grand jury began looking into the purchase,
reportedly to determine whether Duke paid taxes on the $150,000 and
whether the money bought a promise from Duke, still something of a
political power in the state, not to run for governor (the governor
adamantly denies any quid pro quo).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the incident in which Foster found out that a
private detective was checking up on him, possibly for another
candidate. He sent for the detective and, after warning him that it
was not wise to ``mess'' with a governor, urged him to become a
``double agent,'' apparently without success.
</P>
<P>
   Politics can be like that here. One school of thought is that
voters who eat nothing bland do not want their politics bland,
either. Whatever the case, there was no evidence on Saturday that
they held any of it against the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, who had hoped to become the first black candidate to
win a statewide race here since Reconstruction, did not dwell much
on the governor's miscues and embarrassments during the campaign.
Rather, he focused on Foster's boasts about improving the state's
economy, schools and legal climate, arguing that they were mostly
self-serving fiction. Despite the progress the state has made, he
contended, too may poor people and too many students still are
being left behind.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the end, Jefferson, who has served five terms in the House,
carried almost all of the black electorate _ about 30 percent of
the entire vote _ but got very little of the white vote, proof that
while Louisiana is very much a state unto itself, it is still in
the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   For further proof of that, Ed Renwick, director of the Loyola
University Institute of Politics in New Orleans and one of the
state's leading political analysts, cited the fate of a proposal on
Saturday's ballot that called for giving tax breaks to people who
renovate blighted housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal affected only property in New Orleans, where
there is a great deal of blighted housing,'' Renwick said. ``But
the proposal required approval by a statewide vote. New Orleans is
about two-thirds black. The state as a whole is about two-thirds
white. The proposal was defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson did not mention the race issue in conceding defeat
late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did our best, kept the faith,'' he told a rally of
disappointed supporters. ``It's been a joyous journey. We tried to
make people understand there is a better way. I've had some ups and
downs in my life. Tonight has been a down. Now we'll have to wait
for another day.''
</P>
<P>
   When that day comes, some of Jefferson's friends say, he may run
for mayor of New Orleans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
