<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Oct. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The predominance of jet stream winds from the northwest across
the nation will lead to unusually dry and tranquil weather for much
of the week. While a series of fast-moving, but weak disturbances
will skirt across the northern third of the country, they will only
bring clouds and shifting winds as the moisture supply from the
Gulf of Mexico and Atlantic Ocean is sealed off by high pressure
covering the southeastern third of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The day will begin with record chill over parts of the Southeast
as the first frost ends the growing season in many sections of the
Piedmont plateau. Even northern Florida will notice readings in the
30s in rural locations. Abundant sunshine will raise temperatures
30 degrees above the gelid values at daybreak, but still not
reaching seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent clouds over New England and the central Appalachians
will slowly break allowing a few hours of sunshine in many interior
places during the afternoon. The winds will be noticeably lighter.
An active breeze will continue tonight along the Northeast Coast
and this will help keep temperatures from falling much.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure over Lake Superior will cause gusty winds and
broken clouds over the northern half of the Great Lakes. A few
showers may dampen northern Michigan. High pressure building south
from Saskatchewan will merge with a milder fair weather system over
the Rockies. Warm air will move northward into the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Northwest Coast will become unsettled with thickening
clouds and a little rain arriving during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TRANQUIL OCTOBER
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 15 airports in the United States that report hourly
weather observations were noting any precipitation early on Sunday
afternoon. This means that better than 98% of the over 1,000
weather stations were dry and nearly 70% of those had mainly sunny
skies. October is known as the tranquil weather month since the jet
stream which dips into the nation can leave a large ridge of high
pressure in its wake as it retreats. Indeed, high pressure will
stretch from the Carolinas to California on Monday and there may
only be a handful of sites that report any precipitation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
