<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      10-24 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's New &AMP; Notable reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``GODFORSAKEN SEA'' &QL; 
By Derek Lundy (Algonquin, $22.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The open ocean might look tranquil on any given day, but smart
sailors never forget what Herman Melville called ``the tiger heart
that pants beneath it.'' There have been many adventure-at-sea
books released over the last two years, but we hope you haven't had
your fill because this one is terrific. In Lundy's prologue, he
describes the deep fear that came to him during his first trip
across the open sea in a small sailboat, with just his wife along.
Their goal was to reach the Virgin Islands, but in his heart Lundy
knew that they would make it ``only if the ocean let us through.''
He admits that some of that fear lingers even today when he goes to
sea in a small boat, which makes the subject of his book seem
logical: the Vendee Globe round-the-world race, an astonishing
competition in which participants sail alone for 27,000 miles, more
than half of it through the most dangerous waters in the world (the
Southern Ocean), sometimes taking as long as five months to finish.
Lundy focuses on the 1996-97 race, in which 16 skippers _ 14 men
and two women _ faced severe storms and life-threatening
conditions. One disappeared altogether, and several were rescued
from the freezing water after their boats ran into trouble. The
most dramatic rescue was that of Raphael Dinelli, whose boat
capsized, then righted itself briefly before it went down (a
freezing Dinelli lashed himself to the awash deck, then jumped into
a life raft minutes before the boat sank). His only hope of rescue
from the icy water was Pete Goss, a British competitor who was
caught in the same storm 160 miles downwind. When race authorities
contacted him, Goss immediately abandoned the race and battled for
30 hours through ferocious conditions to reach Dinelli, without
even knowing if he was still alive (yes, but barely). This tale of
heroism, not to mention superb sailing, has a sweet ending: Dinelli
lived, and he and Goss became close friends. If you couldn't get
through Sebastian Junger's ``The Perfect Storm,'' try this one.
It's wonderfully written by someone who knows what it's like to be
alone in a wilderness of wind and waves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``ETHEL &AMP; ERNEST'' &QL; 
By Raymond Briggs (Knopf, $21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   See those people on the cover? You know them. They are Ethel and
Ernest, but you know them by other names. That's what makes this
book so enchanting. It's possible to read it in one sitting,
because it is _ don't panic, please _ a comic strip. Raymond Briggs
is a British illustrator of children's books (``The Snowman,''
``Father Christmas''). He is also the son of Ethel and Ernest
Briggs. Here he imagines his parents' lives from the moment they
first saw each other in 1928 (she was a maid, he was about to
become a milkman) to their deaths nearly 50 years later. Their
conversations over the years reflect world events, from the rise of
Adolph Hitler to the invention of television. They also reflect
things that are not so common today but that we remember in so many
people who are now gone _ modesty, simplicity, an appreciation for
what one has and a stoic acceptance of the troubles life delivers
to one's door. This is Briggs' love letter to his parents. It's not
overly sentimental, just real and wistful and true. Enjoy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE BOOK ON THE BOOKSHELF'' By Henry Petroski (Knopf, $26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petroski (``The Evolution of Useful Things'') is an engineer who
has carved a rather charming literary niche for himself by paying
minute attention to objects that don't seem to deserve it. Pencils.
Paper clips. Zippers. In keeping with that tradition, we read the
title of this book and thought that it might be about the physical
properties of books _ spines, paper, type. We were wrong. It's
about the physical properties of bookshelves. Think about it:
Books. Bookshelves. As subjects go, one suffers by comparison.
Petroski, however, is undeterred. He studies the function and
history of shelves because, he says, ``looking afresh at and
thinking anew about the bookshelf, like looking or thinking from
scratch about anything found or made, brings its own rewards, not
the least of which are fresh new ways of encountering and
experiencing the world.'' We preferred the view from Anne Fadiman's
delightful ``Ex Libris,'' in which the shelves are pretty but the
books get equal time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
``DIEGO RIVERA'' &QL; 
By Pete Hamill (Abrams, $49.50) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, Pete Hamill traveled by bus from New York to Mexico
City to study art under the GI Bill. He was 21 and, he says, ``in a
daily state of exhilaration.'' He sought out the work of the great
Mexican painters and found in the canvases of Jose Clemente Orozco
and Rufino Tamayo a reason to alter his plans _ within a year, he
had lost his nerve and decided to become a writer, too overwhelmed
by the Mexican artists to paint pictures of his own. But what of
Diego Rivera, the great Mexican muralist? The young Hamill found
him to be ``clenched and stiff . . . hopelessly dated, someone out
of the 1930s.'' Thirty years later, when Hamill visited an exhibit
in Mexico City that celebrated the 100th anniversary of Rivera's
birth, his interest was reborn. For the first time, he says, he
could see what a great painter Rivera had been. This handsome and
engaging book, with photographs and reproductions of Rivera's work,
is both a biography and an analysis of the painter's art and its
effect on an entire country. ``The daughter of an industrialist and
the son of a farmer could look at the work of Diego Rivera and
recognize Mexico,'' says Hamill. ``He is like some great writers,
from Charles Dickens to William Faulkner to Gabriel Garcia Marquez:
the insistence on the value of the local leads to the universal.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anne Stephenson can be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
