<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6858 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-POLITICS-2NDTA     10-24 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PHOENIX: election night.''   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Elizabeth Dole's withdrawal from the race last week, McCain
is certain to draw even more attention. Even McCain's backers say
that, inevitably, the public is likely to see a less appealing side
of the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``With any personality trait there's always a good side and a
bad side,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., co-chairman of the McCain
campaign. ``Obviously, somebody with his kind of intensity could in
certain situations upset people. But to some extent, as long as he
controls that strong-willed personality it is a positive factor in
terms of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain has made some enemies in Washington. In an example of the
hostility toward him _ as well as to some of his proposals _ three
of McCain's Republican colleagues grilled him for hours about his
campaign finance proposal in an unusually personal and vituperative
display on the Senate floor the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by Mrs. Hull's backing, Bush, who campaigned here
last week, said he intended to spend more than $2 million to
compete in Arizona. Last week, he appointed the governor's son,
Michael Hull, as his state campaign manager. Forbes, the wealthy
publisher who won the primary here in 1996, also plans an
aggressive effort.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of McCain in the state Legislature sought
unsuccessfully to delay the date of the primary so it would not be
as crucial in the primary calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a Hobson's choice,'' said Jay Smith, who was a media
strategist for McCain's Senate campaigns and also a consultant to
Mrs. Hull. ``He's got to spend money to win. He can't lose Arizona.
But then he won't have anything left.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Minnaugh, chairman of the Arizona Republican Party,
said, ``If you don't win your state it's not Doomsday, but it's
harder to convince people in other states to vote for you. Bush
doesn't have to win the state. He just has to be in there close.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Hull and McCain said the senator pleaded with the
governor to delay her endorsement because it came the same week he
announced his own candidacy. She said it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very, very calm conversation,'' Mrs. Hull
recalled of their talk. ``There was no yelling. He did ask if I
could delay it.'' Mrs. Hull said she told him the schedule was
already set.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe McCain's reaction, the governor said, ``Warm?
No. Clipped. But for John, that's warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hull, 64, was elevated from secretary of state in late 1997
after Gov. Fife Symington was convicted of fraud. She was elected
in her own right last year.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Phoenix, where he was stumping with Mrs.
Hull, Bush spoke respectfully of his rival, even as he made a
pointed reference to how he traveled here to hold a fund-raiser for
the senator's re-election last year. (Mrs. Hull said she first
heard Bush speak at that McCain fund-raiser.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Arizona are going to appreciate the fact that I
treat Sen. John McCain with respect,'' Bush said. ``I like him as a
person. He and I are friends. I actually came and helped him in his
Senate race.'' Insisting that he wanted to win Arizona, not
embarrass the home-state candidate, Bush said, ``I'm not in the
business of humiliating people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did his best to pull Mrs. Hull his way. He held
fund-raisers for her last year. Mrs. Hull said she never asked
McCain to hold a fund-raiser for her.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that although Mrs. Hull's decision was ``obviously a
disappointment,'' he still had the support of most elected
Republicans in his state. He insisted that he will not have to
spend as much money as Bush or Forbes because he is already so well
known in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see me buying ads,'' he said. ``If I do well in New
Hampshire and South Carolina, we will have no difficulty in our
home state.'' Dismissing surveys that show him to be in a tight
struggle with Bush, McCain said, ``Most polls in Arizona are really
bogus.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bruce Merrill, a professor of mass communication at Arizona
State University who was McCain's pollster in his 1982
congressional race, disagreed, saying, ``If McCain's people don't
spend money and Bush's people spend 2 to 3 million bucks, then the
endorsement could make the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's two top political advisers in Arizona, Wes Gullett and
Jeff Groscost, the state House speaker, offered no apologies for
the senator's manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rough-and-tumble world,'' Gullett said.
</P>
<P>
   Groscost put it this way: ``In Arizona, politics is a blood
sport. If you're not wearing some Band-Aids you're not playing. And
quite frankly, my office has had tourniquets on before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
