<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-VOTE-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXIT POLLS SHOW VOTERS REJECT PARTY OF PERON FOR ARGENTINE
PRESIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Buenos Aires Mayor Fernando de la Rua,
a somber centrist who campaigned pledging to clean up government
graft and breathe oxygen into a sluggish economy, appeared to win a
landslide victory in presidential elections Sunday, ending a decade
of rule under the flamboyant and unpredictable Carlos Saul Menem.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua's victory, forecast by exit polls on local television,
was widely expected, but significant for breaking the domination of
the populist party founded by Juan Domingo Peron, for decades the
most prominent politician in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers honking their horns loudly thronged the streets of
Buenos Aires Sunday evening, heralding what they hoped would be a
new era.
</P>
<P>
   Under Menem, the Justicialist party veered off its traditional
populist course and toward free market policies, creating a potent
coalition between the working class and an emerging upper middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   But the last year of deepening recession and a wide variety of
government scandals soured many Argentines toward Menem's rule,
busting the new coalition and leading to de la Rua's easy victory.
The capital's mayor appeared to coast through the campaign,
refusing to debate his leading opponent, Buenos Aires Gov. Eduardo
Duhalde, or to divulge many details of his policies.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial polls broadcast on local television stations
indicated that de la Rua, candidate of the center-left Alianza
coalition, had won 50.4 percent of all votes, enough to avoid a
second-round runoff. Total official results including counts from
small towns in the pampas and frigid Andean corners of Patagonia
were not expected until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in a distant second was Duhalde, the 58-year-old
candidate of Menem's party, who won 34.5 percent of the vote.
Domingo Cavallo, a former economy minister running on a
conservative third-party ticket, won 11.3 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes after polls closed, all major Argentine networks
declared de la Rua the winner, and his supporters poured into the
streets dancing across Buenos Aires' main thoroughfare, the Avenida
9 de Julio. Duhalde would not concede defeat early in the evening,
although several leaders in his party acknowledged that he had no
hope of winning.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua, an author of several law books and a lover of
gardening and golf, promised during the campaign to slice an
expanding budget deficit that he said would lower interest rates
and attract foreign investment. He pledged to grant incentives to
small and medium-sized business as a way to decrease the 14.5
percent unemployment rate, as well as narrow the gap between rich
and poor that has grown in recent years as the Menem government
sold off government agencies and enacted a slew of deregulatory
measures.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he would crack down on tax evasion and government
corruption, suggesting that at least some top officials in the
Menem administration could go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua, however, repeatedly promised during the campaign not
to touch the cornerstone of Menem's economic policy: pegging the
value of the Argentine peso one-to-one to the dollar, a policy that
ended a long history of hyperinflation and economic instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole country has high expectations,'' said de la Rua, 62,
wearing his usual blue blazer and ascot to his polling place in the
upper-class Buenos Aires neighborhood of Barrio Norte. In his
signature deadpan style, he added, ``I guess my life is going to
change a little tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   After voting, de la Rua talked amiably with reporters about the
recent baptism of a new grandson and predicted an orderly
transition. But he also made a special appeal to Menem to avoid any
costly last-minute pork-barrel projects leading up to the Dec. 10
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   As mayor of Buenos Aires, de la Rua was not known for any major
initiatives. But he put the city budget in the black, lengthened
the subway system, widened public health services and improved
services for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Duhalde managed to block Menem's attempts to contest a
constitutional ban against running for a third consecutive term,
but he never managed to unite and fire up his party. He veered
between distancing himself from Menem and embracing the successes
of the last decade, especially the end of hyperinflation.
</P>
<P>
   The election appears to mark the first time that the party of
Peron will lose power by popular mandate and not by military coup,
breaking an almost uninterrupted string of election victories that
gave it a domineering position in Argentina politics over the last
two generations.
</P>
<P>
   Its devastating defeat could have repercussions for years to
come, with what remains the country's largest political force going
through a probable power struggle to decide whether it returns to
its traditional left-wing direction or merely fine-tune Menem's
free market policies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, many analysts predict that de la Rua will not be a
forceful president. He will govern by leading an alliance of the
centrist Radical Party and the more liberal Frepaso Party, a group
that broke away from Menem's party in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The two parties, joined in the Alianza, appear to have picked up
a few seats in the lower house of Congress but they will not have a
working majority. Menem's Justicialists will continue to control
the Senate through at least the 2001 elections, and also to
dominate the Supreme Court and most of the provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a government that will have to negotiate, a big
break from the way Menem was able to govern,'' said Mariano
Grondona, a columnist for the Buenos Aires daily La Nacion. ``It's
the end of the era of the `caudillo,''' he added, referring to the
Spanish term for the traditional ``strongman.''
</P>
<P>
   As voters went to the polls at an elementary school on Avenida
Eva Peron in the lower-middle class neighborhood of Parque
Chacabuco, they appeared in the mood to reject Menem even though he
was not on the ballot himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two teen-age daughters and they are going crazy trying
to find work,'' said Nilda Savastano, a 52-year-old social worker.
``This used to be a middle class neighborhood until Menem, who
brought stability for the rich and the politicians but not for the
rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 24 million people voted in what was the fourth
presidential election since civilians replaced a military
dictatorship in 1983. There were reports of only minor
irregularities and no violence, underscoring the political
stability that has replaced what once seemed like chronic
turbulence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
