<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NORRIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON FORCED TO WAIT AS PANEL REVIEWS FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson's boxing fate and $10 million purse are
in the hands of the Nevada State Athletic Commission until it can
determine whether he intentionally threw a late punch Saturday
night that caught Orlin Norris on the jaw and caused him to fall in
an awkward manner and injure his right knee. Norris could not
continue, and the bout was ruled no-contest because it was stopped
on an accidental foul.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Richard Steele, who ruled that the punch was accidental,
deducted 2 points from Tyson's total at the end of the round. Dr.
Flip Homansky examined Norris' knee in his corner before the second
round began and determined that it was injured. Homansky said there
was swelling and stiffness.
</P>
<P>
   Norris left the ring with an ice pack on his knee and was later
taken to Valley Hospital for a magnetic resonance imaging test.
Homansky told The Associated Press on Sunday that the test revealed
that Norris had dislocated his kneecap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MRI clearly shows the path his kneecap took when he went
to the ground,'' Homansky said. ``When he stood up it popped back
in. There's no way he could have continued. He very well might need
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada commission, said
the five-member commission would review a tape of the fight on
Monday. Later in the week, the panel will determine whether Tyson's
purse should be forfeited and whether any other sanctions should be
imposed against the former two-time heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada commission restored Tyson's boxing license last
October after the fighter went through a battery of psychological
tests and the commission was convinced that he would not again do
anything outrageous in the ring. Tyson's license had been revoked
because he bit the ear of Evander Holyfield during a bout on June
29, 1997. Tyson was disqualified and was fined $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson and his promoter, Dan Goossen of America Presents, thought
Norris was faking the injury. ``It would be one thing if he limped
over to his corner or had to be dragged over there,'' Goossen said.
``But he didn't. He walked over there. He looked more hurt after he
sat down. As far as I'm concerned he had the ability to go back out
there and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson agreed with that statement. ``He could have got up and
continued,'' Tyson said of Norris. ``I put that heat on him and he
didn't want to continue. I was hearing all this stuff _ he's a
tough guy, he's not going to lay down, he's not like everybody
else, he's going to come to fight, he's a good boxer. I don't care
what you say about me, good or bad, you've got to have heart to get
in the ring with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he conducted himself, he should feel bad about
himself, he should feel disgraced. Real fighters fight until they
can't fight no more. When I fought Buster Douglas, I could have
quit that fight. When I fought Holyfield that first fight I could
have quit that fight. I took my beating like a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said he did not hear the bell, even though it sounded five
times. His punch came about two seconds after the bell. When the
bell sounded for the start of the second round Tyson came out, but
Norris did not move from his corner. Norris' trainer, Abel Sanchez,
and one of his managers, Sterling McPherson, were telling Norris to
stay put and to not continue to fight. At one point, Tyson had to
be restrained by Goossen and his trainer, Tommy Brooks. The fans
booed Norris for not continuing, and they booed him when he left
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Norris received his $800,000 purse, but the Internal Revenue
Service took $135,000 for back taxes and $266,667 went into escrow
because Norris' former promoter, Frank Warren, has sued Norris,
alleging that the boxer broke a promotional contract with Warren.
Warren says he is due one-third of Norris' purse. Goossen said they
would try to make a rematch of Tyson-Norris for Dec. 11, provided
that Norris has recovered from his knee injury. Norris first
injured his knee in a fight against Bert Cooper on Feb. 17, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   At Saturday's postfight news conference, which neither Norris
nor anyone from his corner attended, Tyson sounded frustrated and
didn't appear to want to get anywhere near a ring any time soon.
''I'm tired of all this stuff,'' Tyson said. ``I don't want to even
fight no more. I'm tired. I'm just tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
