<SLUG> BC-SWITZERLAND-VOTE-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT-WING PARTY LEADS IN SWISS ELECTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Switzerland's most right-wing political party surged to
stunning gains on Sunday in the country's parliamentary elections,
apparently capturing the largest share of the vote nationwide and
raising fears that this middle-of-the-road country is following its
neighbor Austria into political conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Televised exit polls from the nationwide elections showed the
Swiss People's Party captured some 23 percent of the votes cast for
Switzerland's lower house, up from 15 percent in the last elections
in 1995. If the trend holds, the People's Party, an anti-immigrant,
anti-tax and anti-European Union group dominated by outspoken
industrialist Christoph Blocher, could remake Switzerland's staid
political map.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-election polls had predicted that Blocher's party, which is
centered in the German-speaking portion of Switzerland, would
overtake the left-leaning Social Democrats and the two center-right
parties to become Switzerland's pre-eminent political party.
</P>
<P>
   But the size of its victory appeared to stun the political
establishment. Final results are not expected until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss elections came two weeks after Joerg Haider led his
far-right Freedom Party into second place in Austria's national
election, endangering his country's coalition government.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the success of Switzerland's ardent nationalists
threatens this country's so-called ``magic formula'' _ the
governing coalition of the country's four political parties which
has balanced regional interests and its four language groups _
French, Italian, German and Romansch _ since 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on Swiss television, Blocher said the party would
demand a second seat on the seven-member Swiss federal council, the
Cabinet-like body that runs the country. Until now, his party had
one seat, with the remaining slots shared among the Social
Democrats, the centrist Christian Democrats and the free-market
Radical Party, all of which appeared to lose support on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Blocher's demand could mean that traditional Swiss consensus
politics will unravel into polarization and confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   If projections hold, the People's Party could gain some 17 seats
in the 200-member lower house. Predictions for the 46-member upper
house were not yet in. ``This is a real surge to the right,''
Claude Longchamp, director of a major political polling group, said
on Swiss television. The Social Democrats were the big losers, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   The jump in the nationalists' popularity is credited to Blocher,
a controversial millionaire businessman who heads the party's
Zurich section. Like Haider, who opposes immigration and says he
puts Austrians first, Blocher has campaigned on an anti-European
platform, opposing membership in the United Nations _ whose
European headquarters is in Geneva _ and the European Union and in
favor of maintaining traditional Swiss neutrality.
</P>
<P>
   He discounted comparisons with Haider, whose past praise of Nazi
employment policy and Waffen SS members as men of character has
made his popularity in Austria a cause of major concern abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same,'' Blocher insisted. ``We are for an open
Switzerland, but not for attachment to any international
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Controversy however erupted around Blocher last week with
publication of a March 1997 letter he wrote to the author of a book
called ``The Decline of Swiss Freedom.'' The author, Juergen Graf,
has repeatedly denied that millions of Jews died in Nazi Germany's
gas chambers. Blocher insisted that he was merely praising the
title and had not read the book itself.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, polls indicated, Blocher made gains even in the
French-speaking part of Switzerland, which is traditionally seen as
more outward-looking than the German-speaking areas in the center
and east of the country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although record unemployment of over 7 percent has been dropping
in the past two years and Switzerland continues to have a high
standard of living, the vote appeared to reflect concern over jobs
and swelling immigration, particularly from Kosovo, the Yugoslav
province over which NATO went to war last spring.
</P>
<P>
   With the Balkan wars, Switzerland experienced its biggest influx
of refugees since World War II, registering more asylum seekers per
person than any other European country. However, a great number of
Kosovars have returned to their province now that U.N.
administration has replaced what the Kosovo Albanian majority
viewed as the oppressive rule of Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Blocher attributed his gains to clear policies, not
``wishy-washy'' statements, in his interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
