<HEADER>
A6877 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LAD     10-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES, CONFIDENCE AMONG THE MISSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As he lost the game, UCLA coach Bob Toledo also
lost his team. The Bruins, as they existed two weeks ago, have
disappeared. Their confidence has vanished, their best players are
hurt, and the tiny senior class seems helpless to stop the descent.
</P>
<P>
   Only USC and fading bowl hopes separate the Bruins (3-5, 1-4)
from throwing in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the towel couldn't be any worse than UCLA was
Saturday in a 55-7 loss to last-place Oregon State. Wait, check
that. The Beavers were in last place before the game. Now, UCLA is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have confidence in the team,'' senior tailback Keith
Brown said. ``But I don't know where that level is for a lot of
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   First, the logistics. The Bruins must defeat Arizona, Washington
and USC to become bowl-eligible. There's no guarantee UCLA gets a
bid at 6-5, but it seems reasonable given the Hawaii bowls'
reliance on TV ratings. The problem, of course, is winning games.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive captain Pete Holland ruled out a players-only meeting,
saying that would be a sign of panic. Another good week of practice
isn't enough, and don't even think about a quarterback change. The
coaches are committed to freshman Cory Paus _ as they should be _
and he's only the sore throat, not the infection.
</P>
<P>
   What can be done? First, the drawing board is about to get busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go back and evaluate every player and every
scheme,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the players were demoralized, Toledo added: ``We'll
find out Monday. We're hurting pretty bad. It's no fun to work hard
and get embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, some tweaking is required _ here's one vote for
throwing more on first down early in the game _ but it's too late
to change the offense or revamp the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the systems aren't the problem. The Bruins are using
the same offense that averaged 40 points a game in 1997-98, but
instead of seniors there are freshmen and sophomores. The defensive
problems result from personnel _ or lack thereof in the secondary _
not strategy.
</P>
<P>
   If they can't change tactics, can they change talent? Not
really. Most teams in this predicament would bench upperclassmen
who aren't performing and give younger players a chance. But the
Bruins are using their young players. Of the 60 players in uniform
Saturday, there were 12 seniors and eight walk-ons.
</P>
<P>
   If healthy, sophomore tailback DeShaun Foster would be playing
ahead of Brown, a senior, and junior Jermaine Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   All the able-bodied receivers are playing.
</P>
<P>
   There are two seniors among 10 offensive linemen (Matt Phelan
and Jim Ghezzi) and both are reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Holland is the only senior in the defensive-line rotation.
Gifted freshman end Sean Phillips and rookie linebacker Marcus
Reese are getting all the snaps they can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Lovell Houston's insertion into the lineup _ he replaced
fifth-year senior Eric Whitfield _ completed the youth movement in
the secondary. The only healthy underclassman not in the rotation
is safety Jason Stephens, who lost his starting job earlier in the
year because of poor play.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins can't change their strategy and they can't change
their lineup. All they can do is change their minds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
