<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-ART-(TRI     10-24 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOOD-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICO, A RISING TIDE LIFTS ALL POLITICAL RESENTMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico _ As his windshield wipers beat against a
relentless gray rain, Eduardo Gomez pulled his car up to the edge
of a swampy lagoon littered with plastic bottles and broken chairs.
He gestured toward a cluster of houses that stood, dark and silent,
in the middle of the waters. ``My house is in there,'' Gomez, 52, a
taxi driver, said mournfully.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he had seen his living room was on Sept. 16, when
one of the several rivers that course around this delta city rose
up and filled his ground floor and four inches of the upstairs. His
losses include his refrigerator, stove, television, living room
sofa and dining room table, most of the fruits of a lifetime of
work.
</P>
<P>
   But Gomez does not regard himself as the victim of an act of God
or the wrath of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dams _ that's what caused it,'' he said. ``They
miscalculated the water in the dams.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Gomez, many residents of Villahermosa (pronounced BEE-ya
er-MO-sa), capital of the Gulf state of Tabasco, are convinced that
the monthlong floods that turned their streets into canals and
their suburbs into marinas were caused by a demon of human origin
that they have loathed and battled for years: the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, like its neighbor to the north, is a federation of
states, 31 in all, with distinctive regional identities. Just as
Americans have grown suspicious of the goings-on inside the
Beltway, many Mexicans in the provinces harbor an abiding distrust
of the national authorities in Mexico City, known here simply as
``el centro,'' the center.
</P>
<P>
   It happens that the flow of water on the Grijalva and Carrizal
Rivers, which wind around Villahermosa, is governed by a
hydroelectric system of four dams located far upstream. They are
run by the National Water Commission, a federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Tabasco, along with most of central Mexico, has
been drenched in recent weeks with rainfalls heavier than any seen
since the country has kept records.
</P>
<P>
   Many flood victims here contend that the flooding is the result
of decisions by the National Water Commission to deluge them in
September by opening the dams' floodgates without telling anyone
and to continue to pump huge amounts of water through the dams'
turbines. Residents say the hidden purpose was to maintain a supply
of electricity to industries in other states.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens of Tabasco also have a theory for why President
Ernesto Zedillo and his officials would not mind drowning their
state. Roberto Madrazo Pintado, a much-liked politician who stepped
down as governor in June, is running hard to win the governing
party's nomination as its presidential candidate for elections next
year. His main opponent, Francisco Labastida Ochoa, is believed to
be Zedillo's choice for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have reason to be upset. Neighborhoods all around the
edge of Villahermosa, both poor districts and upscale communities,
have been immersed for nearly five weeks. As people moved out of
their homes, snakes and crocodiles moved in. More than 186,000
people in the state lost their homes and 24,000 people are living
in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300 inmates of the overcrowded men's state prison were
forced to retreat to the roof, fleeing cells filled with two feet
of fetid wash. Their relatives have had to wade chest-deep in mire
to bring them what food they can.
</P>
<P>
   (On Friday the prisoners rioted for the fourth time since the
jail was flooded. Prison officials said that nine inmates were
killed in attacks by other inmates, and that 350 were moved to
jails in other states.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The release of water from the federal dams does have something
to do with the high waters around Villahermosa. The engineers who
run the dams say that the heavy rains have filled the dams to
capacity and they are in danger of rupturing. The engineers said
that they never opened any floodgates in September. But they did
continue to pump water through the turbines rather than close them
down, as some officials in Villahermosa demanded. They say it had
nothing to do with supplying electricity to other states.
</P>
<P>
   (At 2 a.m. on Saturday, engineers opened four of the eight
floodgates of the Penitas Dam, the one farthest downstream of the
four dams on the Grijalva River. It was the first time the gates
had been opened since the dam was built in 1987, officials said,
and they warned that the water around Villahermosa would rise one
and a half feet. Thousands of residents fled lowland homes while
army troops rushed to finish sandbag barricades along the
riverbank.)
</P>
<P>
   But the increased flow from the dams does not explain why the
waters sat and stagnated around Villahermosa instead of draining
away, as they did in past hurricanes and floods.
</P>
<P>
   In this decade several Tabasco governors, including Madrazo,
built ambitious highways, housing projects and shopping malls by
filling in waterways around the city that were crucial to the
rivers' drainage. Silvia Whizar, an ecologist from Tabasco, said
the state government mapped key drainage areas in 1987 and
prohibited development in them. But Madrazo, among other state
leaders, ignored the bans.
</P>
<P>
   In the drive to lay blame, nasty accusations have flown between
state and federal officials. On Oct. 10 a local foundation that is
in charge of raising money for Madrazo's presidential campaign told
Zedillo in an open letter, ``The perception of the majority in this
state'' is that the opening of the dams ``was designed and carried
out for political reasons and in bad faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo retorted by rebuking Madrazo for politicizing a natural
disaster. The interior minister, Diodoro Carrasco, said Madrazo and
his allies in Tabasco had shown ``a total lack of ethics.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pro-Madrazo lawmakers in Tabasco have kept up their attacks on
the federal government. ``What they are telling us is that we can't
be right,'' said Manuel Andrade Diaz, the leader of the state
Congress, who is also Madrazo's campaign manager for the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying that the officials who manage Mexico's water
are federal, so they must be right. That's what our people do not
accept: that kind of arrogance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
