<HEADER>
A6893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-NYT &LR;      10-24 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA AND REBEL GROUP BEGIN PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ After nearly a year of false starts, dashed
hopes and spiraling violence, the Colombian government and the
country's principal Marxist guerrilla group began formal
negotiations Sunday aimed at ending more than three decades of
violent civil conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting at a site deep in a rebel-controlled zone, a government
team and leaders of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia,
known here by the Spanish-language acronym FARC, met to discuss a
12-point agenda likely to be as contentious as the preliminaries.
The rebels are demanding an overhaul of virtually every aspect of
national life as a price for a negotiated settlement and have
resisted demands that they give up kidnapping and drug-trafficking,
their main sources of income.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are being held in Uribe, one of five rural
municipalities in a south-central region of savannah that President
Andres Pastrana declared a demilitarized zone last November and
handed over to the insurgents in a good-faith gesture intended to
get negotiations started. The rebels were not required to declare a
cease-fire in exchange, and no mechanism was created to monitor
their activities in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Initial discussions about a negotiating agenda began in January,
but were almost immediately suspended, after guerrilla leaders
accused the government of collusion with right-wing paramilitary
units and demanded the death squads be brought under control. Talks
resumed again in the spring, though, and early in May the
government announced that agreement on an agenda had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   But the formal start of negotiations was suspended days later
and then again in early July in a dispute over the role that
international observers would play in the process. After the
guerrillas launched a military offensive in mid-July that briefly
brought them near the outskirts of Bogota, the capital, the future
of the peace efforts seemed to be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the Pastrana government has dropped its
demand for some form of foreign monitoring of the
guerrilla-controlled zone. At the same time, the U.S. Congress is
considering an emergency aid package for Colombia, which the rebels
have strongly criticized, that could entail as much as $1.5 billion
in assistance, much of it to the military, over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace is a long process that is not achieved from one day to
the next,'' Pastrana cautioned Friday while on a visit to Spain,
adding that while he hopes an agreement can be reached before his
term expires in 2002, he cannot guarantee success. ``The important
thing is to take the first step and that there exists political
will to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite expectations the talks will be slow-moving, Pastrana
clearly hopes his political standing will be strengthened by having
finally brought the rebels to the table. He has been castigated by
many Colombians _ three quarters of those who responded in a recent
poll said they believed the rebels were not negotiating honestly _
and some American officials for having ceded so much without
getting anything in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``This territory no longer belongs to the Colombian state, but
to the narco-terrorists of the FARC,'' Gen. Harold Bedoya, a former
minister of defense, complained in an interview here earlier this
month. ``The government has removed the last vestiges of public
authority from this area and handed over 200,000 Colombians to this
mafia, which has taken advantage of this absurd decision to build
drug laboratories and bring in arms.''
</P>
<P>
   The formal start to the peace talks coincided with a series of
protest marches in 700 cities and towns across the country Sunday,
demanding respect for human rights and an end to the violence that
has killed 35,000 in the last decade and displaced another 1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations, in which several million of the country's 40
million people were said to have taken part, were organized by a
civic group called ``No Mas,'' or ``No More'' and had the support
of the government, which welcomes pressure on the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before the protests were to begin, however, three
powerful bombs exploded in Medellin, traditionally one of
Colombia's most violent cities.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the blasts caused extensive damage but that no
one was killed and that while guerrillas, drug traffickers and
right-wing paramilitary units were all possible suspects, no group
had yet claimed responsibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
