<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      10-24 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, Oct. 25. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) _ If you go by Emmy standards, Ally McBeal,
which makes it season premiere Monday, is TV's best comedy. If
that's the case, shouldn't it make you, you know, laugh? By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NEW&AMP;NOTABLE (undated) Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new
books. BY ANNE STEPHENSON. Story will move in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCCAIN (Phoenix) _ Arizona Sen. John McCain is trying to run a
presidential campaign and at the same time reform the U.S.
political system, rather like trying to shoe the horse as he rides
it. But McCain is determined to turn that apparent disadvantage
into an opportunity, his aides say, by taking the issue on the
campaign trail and spearing his political opponents with it every
chance he gets. On Wednesday, McCain will take his first stab,
challenging his GOP competitors on the eve of a debate in New
Hampshire to support a plan to fund an education voucher program by
eliminating subsidies for oil, sugar, gas and ethanol. By KRIS
MAYES. Story will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANTIAGING CLINICS (Phoenix) _ Like most people, Bobbie Clift
doesn't enjoy growing old. Unlike most, she's doing something about
it. ``There's nothing better than to feel like you're not growing
old,'' said Clift, 39, a Nashville businesswoman. It's such a good
feeling, in fact, that Clift now flies to Phoenix three times a
year and pays thousands annually for treatments at an anti-aging
clinic opened recently by Valley millionaire John Sperling.
Sperling, 78, founder of the University of Phoenix, plans to open
nine upscale ``age-management'' clinics in Arizona and California,
and to invest at least a million dollars a year into aging
research. The first Kronos Clinic _ named for the Greek god of time
_ opened in Phoenix; the second is scheduled to open in Scottsdale,
Ariz., in the spring. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ``A''
and ``L'' categories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
