<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 10/24/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   First photos of Game 2 of the World Series will move by 9:00
p.m., EDT, and then continue to move throughout the evening. A
separate budget listing the additional photos will move by 10:15
p.m., EDT.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) VIDA NUEVA, Honduras -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
MITCH-VILLAGE-4-HNS, 10-24 -- Jesus Mercado, left, and his brother
German are helping to build a house in the new development of Vida
Nueva outside the Honduran city of San Pedro Sula. A year into the
recovery from its worst natural disaster in decades, Honduras
swirls with talk of a new society that will rise from the rubble.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
MITCH-VILLAGE-3-HNS, 10-24 -- Jose Victoriano Aguilar, his wife
Maria Hernandez and their three-year-old son Victor Aguilar still
live atop the mud left in their home by Hurricane Mitch a year ago.
A year into the recovery from its worst natural disaster in
decades, Honduras swirls with talk of a new society that will rise
from the rubble. (Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
MITCH-VILLAGE-2-HNS, 10-24 -- Eight-year-old Estella Jirot Sanchez
attends class in a school set up for the young occupants of
shelters in the Honduran capital. About 25,000 Hondurans made
homeless by Hurricane Mitch last year still live in shelters.
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
MITCH-VILLAGE-1-HNS, 10-24 -- Marta Palma lives in a partitioned
section of a volleyball court in the Honduran capital one year
after Hurricane Mitch destroyed her home. About 25,000 Hondurans
made homeless by Mitch still live in shelters. (Andrew
Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- MTV-INTERNET-GAME , 10-24
-- Judy McGrath, president of MTV and Van Toffler, general manager,
playing the video trivia game ``webRiot'' in their Time Square
office last week. In the media industry's latest attempt to attain
true convergence of television and the Internet, MTV plans to start
a music-trivia game show in which viewers can play along by logging
onto MTV's Web site. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
FBN-GIANTS-SAINTS, 10-24 -- New York Giants' Amani Toomer (81)
beats New Orleans Saints' Tyronne Drakeford for a touchdown on a
twenty-seven yard pass in the second quarter on Sunday. New York's
usually inept offense looked spectacular in handing Mike Ditka's
team its fifth straight loss. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LONDON -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- CABLE-WIRELESS, 10-24 --
Graham Wallace, chief executive of Cable &AMP; Wireless, in his London
office in front of a portrait of Lord Inverforth who founded the
original company that became what it is now. Wallace dismisses the
constant whispers among investors and analysts around London's
financial district that his far-flung global telecommunications
company is ripe for a takeover and ready to sell out. (Jonathan
Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- IBM-PC-PROFITS, 10-24 --
David M. Thomas, head of I.B.M.'s personal computer systems group,
thinks that thin profit margins can still amount to good business.
Last week, IBM announced a tactical retreat on the PC front, saying
it would pull its desktop computers off store shelves and let
customers buy them only over the Internet. (IBM/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- TV-BOOKING-WARS, 10-24 --
From left, Steve Friedman, excecutive producer of the CBS ``This
Morning,'' Shelly Ross, producer of ABC's ``Good Morning America,''
and Jeff Zucker, producer of ``The Today Show'' for NBC. With all
three network morning shows using the same format, male and female
anchors, news followed by variety as well as studios with a view of
Manhattan streets, the three shows will depend more on their
producers coming up with hot guests in order to distinguish
themselves from each other. (CBS, ABC, NBC/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- CHRISTIAN-FILM, 10-24 --
Makeup artist Trent Cotner works on Matt Crouch, right, producer of
``The Omega Code,'' before an interview on CBS's ``This Morning.''
The movie has blindsided Hollywood by sneaking under the radar to
earn $2.4 million during its opening weekend. (Edward Carreon/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LONDON -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- FRAYN-PROFILE, 10-24 --
Michael Frayn, a playwright and novelist, at his desk last week.
Not only does he have a hit play on in London's West End,
``Copenhagen,'' but his latest novel, ``Headlong,'' a wickedly
clever novel with elements of the famous Frayn farce, is a narrow
favorite to win this year's Booker Prize, to be awarded Monday
night in London. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- TIMES-SQUARE-FLOATER, 10-24
-- A police officer stands next to a statue of Daffy Duck selling
stolen watches outside the Warner Bros. store last week in Times
Square. Following extensive construction and renovation of the
area, as well as the installation of a police satellite station at
the center of the bustling square, just steps from the store,
behavior such as the one the statue alludes to has significantly
been reduced. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNITED NATIONS -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- U.N.-HEADQUARTERS-3,
10-23 -- A general view of United Nations headquarters last week.
At center is the General Assembly Building. Towering at right is
the Secretariat. Fifty years after construction on the complex
began, the facility is in dire need of repair and upgrade. (Chester
Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNITED NATIONS -- Oct. 24, 1999 --
U.N.-HEADQUARTERS-2-B&AMP;W, 10-23 -- Secretary-General Trygve Lie
spreads cement as the cornerstone of the United Nations building is
set in 1949. Fifty years after construction on the U.N.
headquarters began, the complex is in dire need of repair and
upgrade. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNITED NATIONS -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- U.N.-HEADQUARTERS-1,
10-24 -- A patch fills a hole on the aging roof of the Conference
Building at the United Nations last week. In the background is the
Secretariat Building. Fifty years after construction on the U.N.
headquarters began, the complex is in dire need of repair and
upgrade. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- TRUMP-POLITICS, 10-24 --
Real estate developer Donald Trump during a news conference last
week at City Hall about a millenium fashion show of which he is
chairman. Calling Republicans ``too crazy right,'' Trump said
Sunday he is quitting the Republican Party. The move is seen as a
key step in any bid for the Reform Party nomination for the 2000
presidential election. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- SPERLING-PROFILE, 10-24 --
Gene Sperling, director of the National Economic Council and
assistant to the president for economic policy, in his office
during an interview last week. Sperling is enmeshed in his seventh
season of budgetary combat. Sperling's job, previously held by
Robert Rubin and Laura D'Andrea Tyson, puts him in the center of
the administration's economic agenda and he brings a deeply
political background to it. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ENTIAT, Wash -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- APPLE-GROWER-WOES-2,
10-24 -- Bruce Grim with Trodoro Paz as they wait for a bin to
finish being fully loaded last week at Grim's fuji apple orchard.
Wide agreement about the outstanding quality of this year's crop in
the nation's top apple-producing state belies the disturbing news:
no one here seems to be making any money growing apples. Hammered
by factors that include stagnant domestic demand, consolidation in
the grocery industry that gives large buyers the upper hand in
determining price, and a flood of imported apples from China,
growers here say they are facing some of the worst economic times
in their memory. (Jackie Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ENTIAT, Wash -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- APPLE-GROWER-WOES-1,
10-24 -- Fuji apples are picked last week from an orchard owned by
Bruce Grim. Wide agreement about the outstanding quality of this
year's crop in the nation's top apple-producing state belies the
disturbing news: no one here seems to be making any money growing
apples. Hammered by factors that include stagnant domestic demand,
consolidation in the grocery industry that gives large buyers the
upper hand in determining price, and a flood of imported apples
from China, growers here say they are facing some of the worst
economic times in their memory. (Jackie Johnston/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- BROWN-BLACKS-EDUC,
10-24 --Students catch up on their homework on a train ride to
Providence for a visit to Brown University. At a time when many
colleges are cutting back on minority recruitment, Brown University
is going the extra mile to woo black students with free train
rides, among other things. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PRAGRAM, Germany -- Oct. 24, 1999 -- GERMANY-DIVIDED,
10-24 -- Gabriela Mendling outside her her house in a suburb of
Frankfurt-an-der-Oder in August. Mendling moved from west Germany
to east Germany after the fall of the Berlin Wall and has written a
book about the stubborn divide that still exits between the two
parts of the country. (Hans Scherhaufer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
