<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-BLACKS-EDUC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1085(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES ARE WOOING BRIGHTEST MINORITY STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Inserts 2 grafs, beginning ``What they do not ...'' as new
4-5th grafs in 2nd take.)  
 (ATTN: R.I., Md., Pa., Va., Minn.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ It was not yet 8:30 on a Saturday morning,
but as soon as Kara Beverly climbed aboard Amtrak train No. 84 in
Washington, she had Ralph Ellison's ``Invisible Man'' open on her
lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long is this train, eight hours?'' wondered Ms. Beverly, a
17-year-old senior at Elizabeth Seton High School in Prince Georges
County, Md. ``Great. I can finish this book and write my essay.''
Then she scanned the seats in the car reserved by Brown University
for this special recruitment trip to its campus here. ``Are there
any chemistry people here?'' she asked no one in particular.
</P>
<P>
   There were, indeed, plenty of thick chemistry textbooks tucked
inside the backpacks that crowded the overhead bins. Physics, too.
And calculus. It was a train full of students balancing Advanced
Placement courses with responsibilities for the National Honor
Society, teen-agers who had scored 1300 (out of a possible 1600) on
their SATs but were retaking them this fall in hopes of even higher
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There was another thing that stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' marveled Joe Williams, as he boarded the train in New
Carrollton, Md. ``Everybody's black.''
</P>
<P>
   In the increasingly competitive environment of applying to elite
colleges, the still small number of high-achieving African-American
students are among the most coveted _ wooed with free trips to
campuses, personal attention from administrators and alumni, and a
bevy of scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   The battles over affirmative action that have led many
institutions to back away from giving preferences to minority
applicants have intensified these recruiting efforts as colleges
seek ways to eir campuses racially mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top minority students are recruited like rock stars,
they're really courted,'' said Esther Hugo, coordinator of
multicultural affairs for the National Association of College
Admissions Counselors. ``They are treated in a way they were never
treated before.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 100 students hopping aboard this train as it trudged up
the East Coast for a weekend of getting-to-know-you programs called
the Black Experience at Brown, the free ticket is flattering and
flirtatious, part of a courtship that began during junior year and
will stretch into spring.
</P>
<P>
   Some had already been eyeing the institution for its open
curriculum or eight-year medical program, while others had never
even considered it until the invitation arrived. Many aboard the
train will be the first in their families to attend a selective
college, and said that the chance to see what Ivy League life was
like, to camp in dormitories and tromp through late-night parties,
was an invaluable opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But as the foliage outside the windows grew more colorful, it
became clear that the trek north, in itself, was a key part of the
experience. A few students recognized one another _ from last
month's free plane trip to Washington University in St. Louis, or
last summer's minority student program at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology _ yet it was the camaraderie among total
strangers that was striking.
</P>
<P>
   They traded calculators and compact discs, mixing talk of
homework and hip-hop, exulting in the rare experience of being
together for who they are: smart, overachieving and black. Talk of
race was blatant and honest, as young people who had never met
before shared the same language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only black male in all of my classes,'' said Taylor
Keitt, 17, a football player at Central High School in Philadelphia
who was counting on scholarships for academics, not athletics.
``It's good to see so many of us trying to set ourselves high.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are plenty of qualified blacks out there,'' Taylor added
with a nod toward the affirmative-action debate. ``You don't have
to lower standards, just go and find them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like having to choose at all,'' Chantel Lee, 17, who
has one white parent and one black, said to another light-skinned
girl, Elizabeth Todd of Silver Spring, Md. ``I am what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not `other,''' added Elizabeth, referring to a racial
category on forms.
</P>
<P>
   The search for these youngsters begins with the first round of
standardized tests, when alongside the overall list of National
Merit Scholars come targeted lists of black and Hispanic students
with high scores. Those are the ones that Brown, and other schools
with similar programs, singles out for special perks like this
trip.
</P>
<P>
   The students hail from fancy private schools like Hotchkiss and
Spence and from magnet public schools, like Stuyvesant in New York
and Eleanor Roosevelt in suburban Washington. Few are from
low-performing inner-city public high schools where the vast
majority of black Americans attend school. Most are from working-
or middle-class families and are worried far more about financial
aid than about getting admitted.
</P>
<P>
   While Ivy League schools offer financial aid based only on need,
historically black colleges, state universities with honors
programs, and other select institutions also flood these students'
mailboxes with information about special scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Humphries, the president of Florida Agricultural and
Mechanical University, has personally flown to visit individual
applicants in his quest to lure more of these students than Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started her 10th-grade year,'' said Laura Nichols of
Manassas, Va., as she dropped her daughter, Tiffany, at Union
Station in Washington to catch the train. ``We get phone calls all
the time, maybe six or seven a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Admissions officers say students are much more likely to apply
to, and eventually attend, campuses they have visited. Ms. Hugo,
currently the outreach counselor at Santa Monica College, recalled
that when she worked at Westchester High School in Los Angeles, a
student who had already decided to go to a local women's college
nonetheless accepted free plane tickets to several campuses,
including Carleton College in Minnesota, which spends about $20,000
a year subsidizing visits by minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her why she took the trips,'' Ms. Hugo said. ``She
said, `Well, it's free travel, free food, so I thought I'd try it
out.''' The young woman ended up at Carleton (Ms. Hugo helped raise
money to buy her a winter wardrobe).
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose student body is about 7 percent black, started its
program nine years ago. Over the last five years, 75 percent of
those who attended the weekend and applied for admission were
accepted, compared with 32 percent of black applicants overall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On this year's train, there were students like Etsub Berhanu of
Silver Spring, Md., who is putting the finishing touches on her
application for early admission to Brown, due Nov. 1. ``I've
written it all, I just have to fit this in,'' Etsub explained,
referring to the present trip. ``I'm going to talk about how this
experience has helped me want to go to Brown. I hope it does.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Shaun Koiner, who attends a Roman Catholic
school in Washington and had already visited 22 campuses (after 15,
he said, they started to blur together); a certain campus in
Providence was not exactly prominent on his list.
</P>
<P>
   Two black Brown seniors trolled the train to answer questions.
Are there black engineering students? Do they have classes in
Capoeira, a Brazilian martial art? Is it colder than New York?
How's the food? (``Remember, it's known for its health,'' one
student said unconvincingly. ``There's salt and pepper on every
table,'' offered the other.) One girl wanted to meet the track
coach, another was interested in singing. Why did you decide to go
to Brown, they asked over and over.
</P>
<P>
   What they do not discuss is the persistent performance gap
between black and white students that spans the socioeconomic
spectrum. They barely hint at questions of black isolation in the
ivory tower, with oblique inquiries about Providence nightclubs,
and about whether tables in the dining halls tend to be segregated.
</P>
<P>
   They are used to being lonely, teased by friends from their
neighborhoods about ruining the curve on tests. One student says he
has already been in the local paper dozens of times for this
African-American honor or that, which makes him wonder whether he
is the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of pressure,'' said Maya Martin, who lives in
Philadelphia, and spent the train ride being distracted from her
book, Aldous Huxley's ``Brave New World,'' by friendly boys.
``They're really depending on me to get a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Leah Tucker, Maya's seat mate, said she felt guilty because her
parents had already paid for her tuition at Philadelphia's
Germantown Friends School. ``If I get in everywhere that I apply,''
she asked rhetorically, ``do I have to go where I get a merit
scholarship?''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the weekend, the students were to be entertained by
various cultural groups on campus, invited to parties at a black
sorority and at Harambee House, a dorm where black students gather,
and to a discussion of the ``racial and sexual politics'' of ``He
Got Game,'' a Spike Lee movie. Brown's minority community was out
in force, putting on its best face, and the nervous high school
seniors were struggling to see where they would fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to visit Yale _ I was planning on applying early _ the
diversity just wasn't there,'' said Diana Bradshaw, who goes to New
Rochelle High School in New York state. ``If they have a minority
weekend, you know they care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
