<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BERKELEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKELEY STAYS THE COURSE FOR LOW-TECH CORE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KATIE HAFNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ In the midst of California's latest gold
rush, here's a city looking for lead.
</P>
<P>
   As high-tech companies sprout on all sides, this city of 107,000
people is making a concerted effort to preserve its low-tech core.
In the process, lost in a Zeitgeist all its own, Berkeley has
managed to deter the one industry that most cities are scrambling
to attract.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, executives at Ask Jeeves, an Internet
start-up that has expanded so rapidly it outgrew its offices here,
began looking for a new building. The company's preference was to
stay in Berkeley but, unable to find a suitable spot, Ask Jeeves
moved to Emeryville, a half mile south.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wondered if someone from the city would try to contact
us,'' said Curtis Vredenburg, a company executive who led the
search for a new site. ``But no one did.''
</P>
<P>
   Other local high-tech companies do not even bother with
Berkeley. When Pixar, the animation studio of ``Toy Story'' fame,
began looking for new space three years ago in anticipation of a
growth spurt, Berkeley did not make the short list, in part because
of the lengthy permit process. Pixar plans to move next year to
Emeryville from Point Richmond, just north of Berkeley,
leapfrogging Berkeley in the process.
</P>
<P>
   No one here is surprised. But even those who say that Berkeley
has recently grown less hostile to business are exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're stuck in the '60s,'' said Mayor Shirley Dean, speaking
about those who stand firm on the city's manufacturing-friendly
policies.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, the mayor pointed to last year's Colgate
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if Hollywood were looking for a spot to film an urban
bomb scene, it would find a ready-made set in the abandoned
Colgate-Palmolive plant, whose 10 acres of buildings have steadily
deteriorated since the company left nearly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a developer proposed an office complex for the site.
The complex would have drawn multiple software, multimedia and
biotech firms to the city. But when the city decided that 20
percent of the site had to be used for manufacturing, the proposal
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was breathtaking in its stupidity,'' said Patrick Kennedy,
a developer. ``Here's the whole Bay Area booming, and what we've
done is snub the whole world, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the policy say that unless the city preserves its
manufacturing base, social and economic diversity will suffer. They
argue, too, that the city simply does not have the space to serve
as much more than an incubator to high-tech start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Landau, a senior planner with the city, credits the
policy for a small increase in manufacturing companies over the
last decade. He said the issues surrounding manufacturing were
widely misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are parts of the economy that are often different from
the university-based economy that a lot of us in Berkeley are used
to, and I think it's not always necessarily visible,'' he said.
``But that doesn't mean it's not happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The part of the city most mired in dispute, known as West
Berkeley, is an eclectic assemblage of manufacturers, warehouses,
parking lots and residences, with a smattering of upscale
retailers, eateries and offices.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, when city planners and residents began working on what
came to be known as the West Berkeley Plan, which calls for a small
number of choice parcels to be set aside for manufacturing,
leftists and left-leaning moderates alike were in favor of it. When
the City Council approved the plan in 1993, people began to think
it might be flawed. Now those same people are sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Berkeley is being held hostage to the sentiment on the
part of some activists that the city has to return to the good old
days of lunch-pail jobs and blue-collar industry,'' said City
Council member Polly Armstrong. ``They're a group of people who
appear to be waiting for General Motors to come to Berkeley to
launch a new Saturn plant.''
</P>
<P>
   The stagnation stems from a classic case of Berkeley's most
earnest residents getting ``lost in their own Berkeleyness,'' as a
longtime Berkeley fixture named Wavy Gravy once described it when
running for City Council on a platform of lightening things up. (He
lost.)
</P>
<P>
   The feather in the city's hard hat is the biotechnology center
of the Bayer Corp.'s pharmaceutical division. Bayer, the city's
largest manufacturer, is now buying the Colgate site, partly to use
for parking.
</P>
<P>
   In stark contrast, Emeryville, a swatch of a place, is the most
direct beneficiary of Berkeley's restrictive policies. Thanks to
its lenient zoning and speedy permit process, Emeryville has an
impressive roster of computer and biotech firms. The 300 or so
employees at Ask Jeeves, up from 50 a year ago, occupy 50,000
square feet in a building on the site of a defunct Westinghouse
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Alameda, another relatively obscure city south of Berkeley, is
nurturing a high-tech boomlet of its own. And Mayor Jerry Brown of
Oakland, hardly a capitalist tool, is promoting his city as this
side of the bay's newest ``high-tech settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   And so high-flying Internet companies continue to leave Berkeley
when they grow beyond a certain size.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Cybergold, another high-tech company, moved from
downtown Berkeley to Oakland in July, the chief executive, Nat
Goldhaber, got a call from an official in Berkeley's economic
development office asking why the company was leaving. Goldhaber
said he needed a building big enough to accommodate substantial
growth and wired for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person from the city said: `Oh. Have a nice time in
Oakland,''' Goldhaber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COWBOYS-     10-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-COWBOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS HEARS THE TALK, THEN WALKS THE WALK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Talk may be cheap, but for the Dallas Cowboys,
for Deion Sanders, it was like a bur in the saddle, a bee sting, a
lightning bolt.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys did not like what they heard from the Redskins
before Sunday's game here at Texas Stadium, that Washington was
really the better team even though Dallas had already won the first
match in overtime in Washington. The idea from Redskins receivers
that Sanders could be attacked and beaten from the onset.
</P>
<P>
   That last thought came personally from Washington's Albert
Connell. He said Sanders could not cover him one on one. Connell
said that his team would throw at Sanders all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Connell he played a good game,'' Sanders said after
Dallas spanked Washington, 38-20, claiming a first-place tie with
the Redskins in the National Conference East division. ``But I also
let him know that if he is going to hunt rabbits, sometimes it
ain't no fun if the rabbit has a gun, too. If you're going to talk
the talk, you had better be able to walk the walk. Their receivers
are young, and they have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Defiant Deion. Delicious Deion.
</P>
<P>
   He took the challenge and turned it into a spectacle before
64,377 spirited fans in a manner that only he can. He made the
game's first tackle (Deion, tackle?), a jarring blow by the
198-pound cornerback on the 234-pound running back Stephen Davis
that threw Davis for a 4-yard loss. Sanders helped the Dallas
defense limit Washington to six plays on its first two drives while
Dallas, on its first two, built a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He gathered a punt in the first quarter and suffered a
concussion on a piercing blow, a punishing head-to-head collision
with Redskins center Dan Turk. He left for the locker room. He
returned with 11 minutes 49 seconds left in the third quarter and
simply ran on the field, assumed his position. And then _ would it
be dazzling Deion if there was not a finale? _ he ended the game's
scoring with 9:03 remaining on a 70-yard punt return and spurt for
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Dominating Deion.
</P>
<P>
   It was his league-record 18th touchdown off returns (eight on
interceptions, one on a fumble, three on kickoffs and six on
punts).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember half the game,'' Sanders said. ``I did just
run back on the field. I knew the doctors wouldn't clear me, but it
was important to get back on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the kind of intensity Dallas showed all day as it
matched Washington's 4-2 record, won its fifth straight in this
series and snapped a two-game losing streak against divisional
opponents where both losses (to Philadelphia and the Giants) were
by 13-10 scores. The Cowboys held Connell to two catches for 52
yards and a 44-yard score when Sanders was not in coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to go out and show something, and they thought
about it all week,'' Dallas Coach Chan Gailey said of his team. ``I
thought we'd get after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas scored the game's first 17 points. Ahead by 17-13 early
in the third quarter, Dallas snatched the game with Troy Aikman's
passing, with its defense forcing Washington punts and with Sanders
igniting his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman threw amazing passes _ long, short, medium-range, to his
right, to his left _ and kept making big plays en route to a
244-yard, two-touchdown passing day. He passed for 11 first downs.
Rocket Ismail caught six balls for 76 yards including the game's
first score, a 13-yard touchdown pass eight minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Washington converted on only four of 12 third downs (33 percent)
and rushed for only 61 yards. Dallas safety Darren Woodson led his
team in tackles with six.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not match their intensity,'' Washington Coach Norv
Turner said. ``We had a chance to take the lead in the East and we
didn't, and that's extremely disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington could not live up to its talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have other chances,'' Connell said. ``They won this
round.''
</P>
<P>
   He also hinted that Sanders plays a dirty brand of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he loves me,'' Connell said of Sanders. ``Ain't no
love here. When you take cheap shots and claim you're a man of God
... God don't like ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brian Mitchell, the Redskins' veteran special teams ace,
warned: ``You're not going to get trash talking out of the game.
When you do it and succeed, you're great. But if you talk and lose,
you shouldn't have said anything. If you're going to do it, you've
got to keep your focus and do your job. If you can't do that, maybe
you shouldn't say anything at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
