<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BAGELS VS. DOUGHNUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Words in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARPER'S FERRY, W.Va. _ A sea change in American taste took
place at the beginning of this decade: The bagel overtook the
doughnut in popularity. Today we spend three-quarters of a billion
dollars a year on bagels, only a half-billion on doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Although these baked goods are similar in shape, they are wholly
different in character. Doughnuts are sweet and crumbly, with over
10 grams of fat; bagels are chewy and low in fat. Doughnuts are
fun, with sugary smiles, sales peaking at Halloween; bagels are
serious, ethnic and harder to digest.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in taste reflect shifts in other opinion. The triumph of
bagelism in the '80s and early '90s meant that tough munching was
ascendant; the decline of doughnuttiness meant that soft sweetness
was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing now. The bagel explosion at the bakery level has
begun to level off; A.C. Nielsen reports only a 2 percent increase
over last year (frozen bagels are in actual decline), while
doughnuts have been rising at a 3.2 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Isn't Dunkin Donuts now selling bagels in its 2,100 stores
to compete with McDonald's penetration of the world McBagel market?
Hasn't the bagel (rooted in the Indo-European  &UR; bheugh &LR; , ``bend'')
become even more American than apple pie?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but. In the bagel's adaptive triumph lies the poppyseed of
its self-destruction. For the bagel has moved toward the center,
and that center has no distinctive hole; its crust has lost its
hard-boiled nature.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching for an ever-wider audience, the bagel has gone soft and
spongy. Although sourdough and caraway and sesame seed were
permissible variations, the lust for new markets has turned the
flavoring frenetic. The low point was reached with the introduction
of the  &UR; blueberry &LR;  bagel _ sweet, soft, inky-colored and hard to
tell from a stale doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, its open-faced purpose is being corrupted. The bagel was
never meant to be used in a sandwich; the towering production is
too wide for the human mouth. It is arrogant and wrongheaded for a
thick half-bagel to masquerade as a thin slice of bread.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the guiltily gulped doughnut has held fast to its
liberal essence. Despised by dieters, it remains deliciously
feminine, sinfully sweet and outrageously hedonistic.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the doughnut _ like excess in art and hypersensitivity
in sexual relations _ is staging a comeback. Its most
mouth-watering variation, frosted chocolate, is leading the way.
(Krispy Kreme, now going public, loftily calls its crumbly
concoction ``chocolate-enrobed.'')
</P>
<P>
   Today's doughnut knows what it is and defiantly asserts its
fattening identity. But today's phony bagel vacillates between a
confection and a tunafish-salad holder. Call it a ``doughgel'' or a
``banut'' _ this middling moderate, this triangulated toroidal,
this product of a foggy focus group is neither here nor there.
</P>
<P>
   The formerly chewy morsel that once had to be separated from the
rest of its ring by a sharp jerk of the eater's head is now devoid
of character _ half-baked, seeking to be all pastry to all men.
</P>
<P>
   What lessons does the coming end of the bagel boom teach us
about America at the  &UR; fin de millenaire &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   1. When you score a breakthrough and surge far ahead, never
forget the reason for your success. In the bagel's case, that
reason was a certain quality of tasty toughness against a crumbling
opposition of sustained sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   2. When you open up a long lead against the competition, never
let up and freeze the cake, lest hungry runners-up eat your lunch.
</P>
<P>
   3. When greed for an ever-growing market share causes you to
sacrifice your authenticity and compromise core principles, repent
and take a stand _ or your flavor will disappear into the mealy maw
of moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Americans profited from a clear choice when our breakfast rested
securely on a two-pastry system. But now the two poll-driven
pastries have become indistinguishable. That's why alien third
pastries _ from flaky croissants to nutty bran muffins _ vie to
attract voter-buyers who are bored with the bland, and who hunger
for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, in the teeth of the doughnut resurgence, let bagels
be bagels. Character counts. Authenticity attracts. Unless the
overconfident bagel learns this quickly, it will be toast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
