<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORBES SPENDS TIME AND LOTS OF MONEY IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Steve Forbes, the multimillionaire publisher who
is again running for president, brought his anti-tax crusade here
this past weekend, spending his own money lavishly in order to
promote his view that the government should have less and spend
less.
</P>
<P>
   On a weekend that displayed the scenic autumn beauty of this
state and before crowds that shared his fiscally conservative
views, Forbes, who is running for the Republican presidential
nomination, came to unveil what he _ and his staff _ had promoted
as the ``Forbes New Economy Plan.'' But the plan was largely based
on the same views that he has long advocated: shrinking government,
shrinking taxes, shrinking the federal deficit and increasing
individual wealth.
</P>
<P>
   He promised that if his conservative economic plan were enacted,
the decade ahead would be ``dazzling'' _ workers would see their
wages increase by 62 percent, 24.5 million new jobs would be
created and the U.S. economy would double its current growth rate
and expand by 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to cut taxes and return the money to the people who
earned it,'' said Forbes in his stump campaign speech, and wherever
he said it, that line drew large applause. At a campaign stop at
the Oakledge Country Club in Sunapee, N.H., a listener named Steve
White agreed: ``We're overtaxed. We're unfairly taxed. Taxes are
confiscatory. In New Hampshire, we are very fiscally conservative,
and we don't like our money to go to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' plan, amplified with some additional economic
statistics, consists of his basic message, which is that enacting a
17.3 percent flat federal income tax, replacing Social Security
with individual retirement accounts for younger workers and making
the government smaller will bring about a supply-side economic
boom.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to get his anti-tax message out, Forbes is spending heavily
here. Forbes television commercials flood the airwaves, direct mail
brochures blanket doorsteps and phone banks work constantly. And
Forbes is crisscrossing the state in a two-bus caravan filled with
sophisticated electronic equipment that enables him to
instantaneously broadcast campaign events to his Web site.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign pays such close attention to detail that even the
pumpkins at his Manchester campaign headquarters were carved with
Forbes 2000 logos. Altogether he is spending money at the rate of
$3 million a month, according to his campaign manager, William Dal
Col.
</P>
<P>
   In spending, Forbes is running almost neck-and-neck with
Republican front-runner George W. Bush _ Bush has spent $20 million
since January, compared to $19 million by Forbes, who has a net
worth of over $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference, however, is that while Bush's campaign cash
comes from donations, the bulk of Forbes' spending is from his own
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Dal Col, the campaign manager, said that the Forbes
campaign anticipates big spending ahead. With 113 people on the
Forbes payroll and campaign offices in states as far-flung as
Alaska, Louisiana, Arizona, Iowa and Delaware, among others, Dal
Col said the campaign has sufficient resources to ``engage'' Bush
both on the ground with grass-roots organizations and in the air
with television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col said the Forbes campaign will not hesitate to use the
same kind of hard-hitting television ads against Bush that Forbes
used against Republican front-runner Bob Dole in the 1996 primaries
_ ads that many Republicans criticized for being overly harsh on
Dole and for causing his support to drop in key electoral states.
</P>
<P>
   But Dal Col maintains that spirited attacks are what campaigns
are all about. When asked about the negative reaction to Forbes'
ads, Dal Col responded: ``It doesn't matter. You have to remember
this is an election. To be bold and spirited in the primaries is
what it's all about. I'm sure that when they see our ads that some
in the party will like them and others will get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign is currently airing ads in New Hampshire,
and just finished airing ones in Iowa. These ads promoted Forbes'
views on taxes and Social Security, and were biographical.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the money Forbes is spending, he also engaged in
traditional meet-and greet sessions, often laced with humor.
</P>
<P>
   At the Belmont Restaurant in Manchester, Forbes turned to a
table of four men and, on a rainy morning, promised: ``If I'm
elected, I'll do something about this weather.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as 7-year old Maxwell Lawrence of Manchester listened,
Forbes added: ``And if I'm elected, you won't have homework.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
