<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     10-24 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ALL-CENTURY PLAYER WHO HAUNTS BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the lovely things to look forward to next New
Year's Day _ when the world does not, after all, come crashing down
on our heads _ is an end to the plague of lists.
</P>
<P>
   You can be absolutely sure that 10 years from now, when Sammy
Sosa's Chicago Cubs play Hideo Nomo's Yomiuri Giants in a real
World Series, nobody is going to be blathering about the team of
the decade. Just play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these millennium and century and decade lists are
arbitrary and sometimes cruelly exclusive, creating their own
mischief. The latest list is baseball's all-century team, announced
Saturday, 30 undeniably great players, including Pete Rose,
currently suspended from the business he says he loves.
</P>
<P>
   Rose showed up for the introduction of the all-century team on
worldwide television Sunday night, receiving a more raucous welcome
than the loud cheers for Henry Aaron, Ted Williams and the rest. He
came straight from the diamonds (and hearts and clubs and spades)
of Atlantic City. To baseball officials, he was as welcome as
garlic breath in the subway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a baseball person, I'm a teacher, I love the game,'' Rose
said, showing his old self-involved charm in a news conference more
crowded than anything the players would see after the second World
Series game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Manson can get a hearing,'' Rose noted, adding, ``I
hope they don't wait till 2060 to review my case.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has been hoping Rose would go away ever since he was
banished for gambling on sports, including, apparently, his own
sport. He makes it hard on baseball by remaining in serious denial,
and is ineligible for the Hall of Fame, although he has the highest
total of hits in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked pitching against him because he didn't hit home
runs,'' said Bob Gibson, one of the 30. ``But he was a great
ballplayer. When you get to the World Series the way he did, you
can say you are a winning ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   When the promoters of this all-century team started handing out
computer ballots to fans this past summer, nobody could figure out
a way to ban Rose from the poll. Wouldn't you know it? Charlie
Hustle finished ninth among outfielders, just inside the cutoff.
Right behind Rose (629,742 votes) were Roberto Clemente (582,937)
and Stan Musial (571,279).
</P>
<P>
   This was such an embarrassment that the officials created a
panel of ``experts'' to add five players to the squad. This is
where it gets sticky.
</P>
<P>
   Clemente was one of the great right fielders, plus a proud and
vocal early representative of Latino ballplayers, plus a hero for
the way he died in a plane crash while ferrying goods from Puerto
Rico to Nicaragua following an earthquake. Clemente also suffers
somewhat from the unfortunate fact of remaining dead. If his
burning, handsome presence were still among us, Roberto Clemente
would be in the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   Musial, who has been unfortunately eclipsed by the reasonable
veneration of the dynamic Ted Williams in recent years, is still
among us, and thank goodness for that. Stan the Man was the
laughing cavalier, Wayne Gretzky in floppy flannels. Even the
dems-and-doses denizens of Ebbets Field loved the guy. The experts
put him on the all-century team.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Stan Musial belonged on that team because of what he
has accomplished in his life, and just player-wise, the ability to
do a lot of things,'' said Joe Torre, a lodge member and hardly a
spreader of controversy. ``I didn't think it was fair to put Pete
in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose arrived Sunday afternoon straight from one of those
ubiquitous card and autograph shows, for big bucks, at a certain
gambling den in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a show of 3,000-hit players,'' he explained. ``You can't
have one without me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the selection of Atlantic City was a coincidence _
``It could have been Detroit'' _ and besides, he said, he doesn't
even like casinos because he prefers gambling on the horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slot machines are for 70-year-olds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose did thank Commissioner Bud Selig for ruling that he could
appear on the ballot. Selig is locked into intransigence toward
Rose because of the untimely death of Commissioner Bart Giamatti in
1989, days after banishing Rose, who said he thought he had merely
been suspended indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   There is the sentimental notion that all Rose must do is
apologize for whatever it is that he did and he will be welcomed
back into the business. Rose raised the tantalizing suggestion
Sunday night that if Giamatti were still alive, he would have
reinstated Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know I'm sorry,'' Rose told reporters, asking Selig to
``give me a second chance. I won't need a third.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose took advantage of his first official appearance at a
baseball function in 10 years. If we take this list seriously for a
nanosecond, it might have been better to arbitrarily ban active
players, giving us more time to judge them. With all due respect,
my guess is that Cal Ripken Jr. and Roger Clemens would not make
such a list 10 years from now, but that Mark McGwire and Ken
Griffey Jr. probably would. And while Nolan Ryan is a totally
admirable Hall of Famer, his selection as the century's top pitcher
is _ how else can one say this? _ ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 50 to 60 guys who could be, should be, on
this team,'' Gibson said. ``All I know is that I'm on it, and thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibson said his St. Louis Cardinals of the late 60s could beat
the top 30. I like his style. Personally, if I could borrow Jackie
Robinson from the top 30, I would take my chances with the Brooklyn
Dodgers, circa 1946-1957.
</P>
<P>
   But enough of memories of other ages. The Yanks are playing the
Braves in real time. The clock is ticking on this century, and Pete
Rose is now on two opposite lists _ the all-century list, and the
suspended list. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
