<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON AGAIN BACKS HIGHER MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With two economists and the head of New York's
largest coalition of labor unions by her side, Hillary Rodham
Clinton implicitly attacked Mayor Rudolph Giuliani on Sunday for
not supporting an increase in the federal minimum wage and
suggested that he had not done enough to help the poor in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the wonderful news about the national economy in
general, poverty has gone up here in New York City,'' she said, in
a visit Sunday afternoon to the headquarters of Local 3 of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers in Queens. ``Now
there are those who have opposed an increase in the minimum wage,
arguing that it will cost jobs, and there are some people who say
that we need still more studies. Well, they are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a customary tactic in her exploratory
campaign for a U.S. Senate seat, the first lady did not mention the
mayor, her likely Republican opponent next year, by name. Instead,
she left the direct attack on Giuliani to Brian McLaughlin, a state
assemblyman from Queens who is also president of the New York City
Central Labor Council.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton listened attentively as two economists for the
Fiscal Policy Institute, a nonprofit group in Albany supported in
part by unions, challenged Giuliani's assertions that raising the
base wage could result in jobs being lost and could hinder
welfare-to-work policies. Then she quickly launched into her own
veiled attack.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has repeatedly said he would like to see more
studies on the effect of raising the minimum wage, did so again on
Sunday when asked about Mrs. Clinton's comments. He also repeated
his statement that he expects to support the wage increase
eventually. ``My stand on the minimum wage is that I have asked a
study to be conducted to determine the impact it would have on poor
people getting jobs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the impact is minimal,'' the mayor said, ``I'll support it.
If the impact is substantial, then I'll try to find ways to
ameliorate that, which is what I have done in the past. So I think
what I am doing is actually much more caring and much more
compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he had asked the city's Human Resources
Administration to study the proposed increase in the minimum wage
now being considered in Congress, to $6.15 from $5.15, over two
years. ``I anticipate that I'll eventually support it, but first I
have to see what their study shows,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the union headquarters in Queens, Mrs. Clinton stood by
McLaughlin, a Democrat, as he criticized the mayor by name, just as
she has stood by on other recent occasions as Rep. Charles Rangel
of Harlem, Borough President Fernando Ferrer of the Bronx and other
Democratic elected officials rebuked Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have often heard that we live in the greatest city on
earth,'' McLaughlin said, an apparent reference to Giuliani's habit
of calling New York the capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greatness is measured in how well we treat the less fortunate
among us,'' he said. ``And with 25 percent of this city living in
poverty, we must strive and can do better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
