</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GIANTS MAKE A STAND, RELATIVELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Don't take the Giants' 31-3
excommunication of the Saints too seriously. Don't assume that the
Giants suddenly are off and running and passing toward Super Bowl
XXXIV, or even the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the National Football League, as if it had studied
under Albert Einstein, operates on a theory of relativity. Each
week the ability of every winning team is relative to the ability
of the losing team it opposed. And the Saints, now desperate and
disorganized at 1-5, just might be pro football's worst team this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Giants, who edged the Dallas Cowboys, 13-10, last
Monday night, have won two in a row for a 4-3 record, but they
haven't really proved their worth as a playoff contender. So don't
make any airline and hotel reservations for Super Bowl XXXIV in
Atlanta, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   For now, just enjoy the fun of Sunday's virtually unopposed
rout, as all those Giants loyalists did. Especially in cheering the
two ``dee-fense, dee-fense'' goal-line stands late in the fourth
quarter, which prevented the Saints from the consolation of scoring
a touchdown or two long after the outcome had been decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just fought for them,'' Jessie Armstead was saying now,
referring to the fans shouting from the stands behind the west end
zone. ``We didn't want to let 'em score.''
</P>
<P>
   From the decibels of the ``dee-fense, dee-fense'' chant, you
would have thought that the playoffs were at stake, that a Saints
touchdown would have ruined the Giants' season. But an opportunity
to roar ``dee-fense, dee-fense,'' which originated with the staunch
Giants' defenses of the early 60's in Yankee Stadium, is all that
Giants fans ever ask.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all those Giants loyalists appreciated the offense's
finally waking up, notably Kent Graham's 53-yard pass that Joe
Jurevicius caught in the back of the end zone on the last play of
the first half for a 24-3 lead. But in Giants Stadium there is no
chant or cheer with the ancestral spirituality of ``dee-fense,
dee-fense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a kick out of the goal-line stands,'' defensive end
Michael Strahan said. ``It gave the fans something to stay for.''
</P>
<P>
   With about four minutes remaining, the Saints had a third-and-1
at the Giants' 3-yard line, but Sam Garnes and Corey Widmer stuffed
Ricky Williams for no gain. On fourth down, Billy Joe Tolliver
misfired on a pass to Andre Hastings, who was covered by Jason
Sehorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some guys nicked up,'' Strahan said, ``but those were
the guys, like Jessie Armstead, that made the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan was talking about the second goal-line stand. Armstead
had sustained bruised ribs earlier, but defensive tackle Robert
Harris and safeties Percy Ellsworth and Shaun Williams were on the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Peter had replaced Harris and Jeremy Lincoln, a
cornerback throughout his eight years in the NFL, was playing
safety for the first time since 1986 when he was in a Toledo, Ohio,
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not want to let 'em in the end zone,'' Lincoln said.
</P>
<P>
   With about two minutes remaining, Saints cornerback Fred Weary
recovered the rookie running back Joe Montgomery's fumble at the
Giants' 3-yard line. Ricky Williams gained 1 yard, then was stopped
for no gain. On third down, quarterback Danny Wuerffel rolled out
for no gain. On fourth down, Wuerffel's pass to Lawrence Dawsey was
incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go out on the field and play that way,'' Coach Jim Fassel
said of the two goal-line stands, ``that had pride written all over
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But stuffing the Saints in two goal-line stands isn't the same
as stuffing some of the NFL's better offenses.
</P>
<P>
   With their victory, the Giants moved within one-half game of
both the Cowboys and the Washington Redskins, whose 4-2 records
share the National Football Conference East lead. Now the Giants go
to Philadelphia next Sunday for what could be a 5-3 record. After a
bye week, they play the Indianapolis Colts here, then go to
Washington before returning against Arizona and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a winning record,'' Armstead said, ``but we're not
going to pat ourselves on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Not after drubbing the Saints, perhaps the NFL's most drubbable
team. And not if they also drub the Eagles, another drubbable team.
The Giants don't deserve to be taken seriously as a playoff
contender unless they go to Washington and reverse their
embarrassing 50-21 loss to the Redskins this season.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the Giants' defense will be tested much more than it
was in those two goal-line stands against the Saints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
