<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family feud: Jeff Burton tops brother
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKINGHAM, N.C. _ For the third time this season, Jeff and Ward
Burton battled it out to the end at a Winston Cup race on Sunday.
For the third time, Jeff got the best of the brotherly rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton maintained his dominance over his older brother to
win the Pop Secret 400 at North Carolina Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say that I feel really bad that Ward didn't win the
race,'' said Jeff, 32. ``I know nobody believes that, but it's hard
to go out there and one of your goals has to be to beat your
brother. That's the hardest thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, whose lone career victory was at Rockingham in
1995, was in control of the race until a caution flag was raised
after Dale Earnhardt and Wally Dallenbach wrecked on lap 322.
</P>
<P>
   When Ward entered the pits three laps later, he had been in
front for the previous 23 laps. But the advantage was lost after
Jeff narrowly beat his brother back out to the track, and the
younger brother kept the upper hand over the final 68 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically mad as hell, really,'' said Ward, 37. ``I don't
know where that anger is directed at, it's just circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers were slowed late in the event by Jeff Gordon, who
made a futile attempt to avoid being lapped. Ward appeared to be
more affected by Gordon's aggressive driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have got Jeff (Burton) if we had more time,''
Ward said. ``I'm not going to say names, but we had a lapped car
race us really hard. Jeff (Burton) got about 200 yards in front of
me and from there I was playing catch-up. I ran it with all I
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward eventually caught up with the rear of his brother's car on
the final lap and gambled with an inside pass on the third turn.
Jeff held off the challenge to post his sixth victory of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only chance I had,'' Ward said. ``I couldn't go
high because of lapped traffic. I just drove it in there and, of
course, it didn't work. But if I had drove it in there easy it
wouldn't have worked either. I was just trying with everything I
had to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burton brothers also finished 1-2 at Las Vegas and
Darlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like having to beat Ward,'' Jeff said. ``It's a
difficult situation to be in. Any time you are in a business
situation with a family (it's) always pressing. And then when
you're in a business that competes with a family member, that's
even worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, that's what I do. I mean, my job and what I love to
do is to win races, so whoever I'm racing against, my goal is to go
beat 'em. It's a shame it had to be Ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
