<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS25-COX     10-24 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many whys to Falcons' demise
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ It was never a problem last year when injured
Falcons running back Byron Hanspard parked his car outside the door
to the locker room of team headquarters in Suwanee, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   He'd finish his rehabilitation, get in his car and leave. It was
like clockwork, every day.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, Jamal Anderson didn't have it so easy. After
parking in the spot apparently reserved for injured players,
Anderson had to be careful not to hit a golf cart donated to coach
Dan Reeves, which had been left behind Anderson's car by Reeves'
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Small thing? Of course. But it's just another little reminder
that everything is out of whack this year for the Falcons, who
continue to be a story of contrasts as they play at Pittsburgh
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons went 14-2 last season and shocked the professional
football world by advancing to the Super Bowl. This year, they're
1-5.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an ambitious and hard-hitting Falcons defense led the
NFL in turnover ratio at plus-20. This year, they're lethargic,
tied for last at minus-11.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, they were No. 6 in rushing, No. 2 against the run.
This year, they're No. 28 rushing, and No. 29 against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling; it's the anti of everything you did,''
said free safety Eugene Robinson, who had his shining moment at
Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami turned into a fleeting 15 minutes of
fame. It's worth noting that Robinson's arrest for solicitation of
prostitution on the night before the Super Bowl against Denver
seemed to cast a pall from which the franchise has not recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But there have been other, more tangible reasons, for the
Falcons' demise:
</P>
<P>
   _ The team was weakened by the decisions to release wide
receiver Tony Martin and weak-side linebacker Cornelius Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, released in a cost-cutting move, led the Falcons in
tackles last season, but he apparently brought much more to the
defensive unit. In Indianapolis, he has become a team leader and an
inspiration for the Colts defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons saved roughly $2.4 million by releasing Bennett. His
replacement, second-year player Keith Brooking, has played well.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves cut Martin during the offseason, when he wouldn't agree
to postpone a $400,000 roster bonus past March 1 to give the team a
chance to gauge the outcome of Martin's five federal charges of
money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on it until the last minute to try to get them to
delay payment until we could see when a trial was set,'' Reeves
said. ``Mr. Martin (Tony's father, Hal) was dead set on him not
doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still felt like if ... becomes a free agent, we'd have a
chance to sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was acquitted on all charges, signed with the
Dolphins and is leading the team with 28 receptions for 481 yards
and two touchdowns. He's averaging 17.1 yards per catch.
</P>
<P>
   Martin led the Falcons last season with 66 receptions, but he
was valuable for much more than statistics. His speed changed the
way teams defensed the Falcons, helping Anderson rush for a
franchise-record 1,846 yards because teams had to honor the deep
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, of course it changed,'' said Vikings cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock, whose team lost to Atlanta in the NFC title game, then
defeated the Falcons in the 1999 opener. ``He's a guy who can
stretch the field. Stretching the field meaning getting downfield.
This year, I don't think they're able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Falcons sent a dubious message on draft day when they
discussed the possibility of moving Anderson in a trade with the
Patriots. The story shocked Anderson and his teammates, and might
have factored in Anderson's lengthy holdout during training camp.
It was a big distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so big to this team, such a huge factor; when you heard
the trade talks it was a shock,'' wide receiver Jammi German said.
``I guess that was the business side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest fallacy,'' he said. ``Calling and seeing
what somebody might be willing to give for somebody doesn't mean
he's going to be traded. If you don't call, you have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On draft day, the Falcons traded next year's first-round pick
to Baltimore for a second-round pick, and used it to draft Reggie
Kelly, one of four tight ends on the roster. Reeves said at the
time it wouldn't be a bad trade unless his team had a poor season,
which would make the lost pick occur earlier in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what?
</P>
<P>
   If the Falcons were determined to go through with the trade,
they might have been better advised to draft a wide receiver or a
running back. Or they should have pursued backs and receivers
through free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves defends the trade by saying he felt good about the team's
receivers and running backs, even though Byron Hanspard, Anderson's
backup, missed the 1998 season with a knee injury. Ken Oxendine
carried 18 times as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like Byron was going to be back, Kenny was the backup,
and we felt Jamal was going to be there,'' Reeves said. ``We
thought we had plenty of running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Anderson has not been replaced, and Reeves points to
the loss as the key to the Falcons' downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``You miss (Anderson) as a receiver, a blocker and as a
runner,'' Reeves said. ``You look at film from last year, and Jamal
made a awful lot of people miss. Plus, he was a great leader, a
tough guy. He gave guys inspiration. He was always fired up, and
you miss that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The timing of contract extensions created ill-will among
players.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons still have 10 starters whose contracts expire after
this season, nine who will become free agents. But the extensions
last month for starting defensive tackle Travis Hall, who still had
three years left, and reserve defensive tackle Ed Jasper, who got
two more years even though he had just joined the team, didn't sit
well with everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Starting defensive ends Lester Archambeau and Chuck Smith and
starting defensive tackle Shane Dronett are up for new contracts
after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can do is take care of myself, but definitely it shows
what the team is thinking,'' Dronett said. ``I take that back.
We're losing, and I wouldn't give anybody any more money, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Hall and Jasper got extensions because they happened
to agree to terms sooner than the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we haven't tried to sign Lester and the
others,'' Reeves said. ``If you have success like we had last year,
and have that many free agents, you can't keep them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't keep people from thinking whatever they want to
think. But a lot of guys see what everybody else is getting. We
can't pay everybody necessarily want they perceive they're worth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The juggling of offensive linemen has hurt. When Reeves moved
last year's second-round draft choice, Bob Hallen, into Calvin
Collins' starting left guard spot before the season, he explained
it was a move for the future. It hasn't worked. Greg Bishop will
start at left guard tonight.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little cohesion on the offensive line, and for
much of the season guards have been shuttling in and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob at times plays really well, but it hasn't been there
consistently,'' Reeves said. ``We thought ... six weeks into the
season, he would have gotten that down. It hasn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Can the Falcons turn it around? History suggests it's possible,
but not likely. The team began the 1997 season with a 1-7 record
before finishing 7-9. They rode that momentum to a wonderful 1998.
But that was then.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Falcons officials seemed to go against an
age-old adage: If it ain't broke, don't fix it.
</P>
<P>
   The tinkering has taken a heavy toll.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
