<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-SAINTS-NYT     10-24 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-SAINTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS PRODUCE A MONTH'S OFFENSE IN ROUT OF SAINTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The offense scored four touchdowns,
which is normally a month's worth. It got 7 points on one of those
desperation passes that almost never work. In the game's final
minute, even though it no longer mattered, the defense put up a
goal-line stand, just to be obstinate.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five days after giving up 50 points at home and two weeks
after a miserable 3-point performance at Arizona, the New York
Giants won a laugher Sunday, running away from the New Orleans
Saints, 31-3.
</P>
<P>
   Routing a bumbling team like 1-5 New Orleans may not mean much,
but the outcome does: the 4-3 Giants are one of three teams near
the top of the National Football Conference East. Dallas and
Washington have &QC; 4-2 records.
</P>
<P>
   Two games after the Giants appeared in descent, the division
race is on. Remarkably, they are in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great to be 5-2,'' said Giants quarterback Kent
Graham, who had a serviceable day with two touchdown passes, one
interception and 239 yards while completing 19 of 29 passes. ``But
considering where we were, right now, we'll take 4-3.''
</P>
<P>
   The only negative for the Giants was injury related. Although
they were buoyed by the debut of the rookie running back Joe
Montgomery, who brought a little spirit to the team with a
skillful, determined 12-yard touchdown run, Montgomery also broke a
bone in his left foot and will be sidelined three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Safeties Shaun Williams (pulled hamstring) and Percy Ellsworth
(foot sprain) left the field on carts. Neither may play next week
at Philadelphia. Linebacker Jessie Armstead also bruised his ribs,
and defensive tackle Robert Harris left the locker room on crutches
with a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries aside, the Giants finally had a day when they looked
accomplished and adept. Most notable was a daring offense that
attacked in several new ways.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end Pete Mitchell's expertise as a third-down receiver was
finally used as Graham threw to him five times, three times to
convert on a third-down situation.
</P>
<P>
   A double reverse sprung wide receiver Ike Hilliard for 24 yards
that led to the Giants' first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   And Graham threw downfield frequently, forgoing the cautious
approach so routine to the Giants. With 70 seconds left in the
first half and the ball at the Saints' 27-yard line, the Giants did
not settle for a field goal. Instead, Graham threw a touchdown to
Amani Toomer in the corner of the end zone for a 17-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the Giants got the ball back with 32 seconds left in
the half, they quickly moved 25 yards. From their 47-yard line, on
the last play before intermission, Graham launched a pass into the
Saints' end zone, where three Giants receivers waited. The ball was
tipped by Toomer and safety Sammy Knight and caught in the back of
the end zone by wide receiver Joe Jurevicius, giving the Giants a
24-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a Hail Mary work before,'' Giants Coach Jim
Fassel said. ``But there was no question in my mind we should go
for it. I told Kent, `Just make sure it gets all the way to the end
zone.'''
</P>
<P>
   The game was, in effect, over as soon as Jurevicius came down
with the ball because the Giants' defense continued to play at a
level that makes the unit among the elite in the National Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   They controlled and dominated the Saints, harassing quarterback
Billy Joe Tolliver into three interceptions. Ricky Williams, the
Saints' rookie running back, rushed for 111 yards on 24 carries,
but most of them were in the second half when New Orleans
threatened to cross the Giants' goal line only in the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Even that sequence was revealing. Montgomery's fumble had given
the Saints the ball on the Giants' 3-yard line. But twice the
linebackers stuffed Williams as he tried to bull into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   On third down, a play-action bootleg by the reserve quarterback
Danny Wuerffel failed when safety Sam Garnes ran him down and made
a spectacular open-field tackle. A fourth-down pass was incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plays like that is how you judge a defense,'' Armstead said.
``We could let them score and they really wanted to score. But we
never want anyone to score.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstead left the game in the third quarter after a freakish
play that also sent Ellsworth to the sideline. Chasing Williams,
Armstead dived for the ball carrier, landing on Ellsworth's left
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth's foot knocked the wind out of Armstead and left a
deep bruise on his rib cage. Ellsworth came off the field limping
on his left foot. Four plays later, with the Saints driving,
Ellsworth's backup, Shaun Williams, pulled his left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Ellsworth back into the game, his foot hastily
taped. He intercepted Tolliver's next pass.
</P>
<P>
   Ellsworth did not return to the game after his interception,
which left cornerback Jeremy Lincoln to play free safety because
the Giants' usual third safety, the rookie Lyle West, is also
injured.
</P>
<P>
   On the next New Orleans possession, it was Armstead's turn to go
from injury to interception. He picked off Tolliver's pass in the
flat and appeared to be on his way to the end zone when his
teammate Keith Hamilton accidentally got in his way, enabling the
Saints to catch Armstead from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery scored his touchdown on the next play, giving the
Giants their 31-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed something like this,'' Fassel said. ``I don't know
that I've ever had a laugher. Every game is tense. But a win is a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time this season, Fassel was not required to
apologize for the play of his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that feels pretty good, too,'' the Giants' coach said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
