<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CABLE AND WIRELESS DENIES IT'S READY FOR A TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   As the telecommunications industry goes through a whirlwind of
merger-and-acquisition activity in the United States and Europe,
there is constant speculation that Cable and Wireless of Britain is
ripe for a takeover and ready to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, Graham Wallace, dismisses that
notion. He is trying to shift the company's focus away from its
consumer businesses toward its business customers. That has meant
selling some operations, including a deal announced Sunday to shed
its holdings in Israel's state-controlled phone company for $630
million.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN THE PRODUCT IS THE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The desire to cash out big is not a new motivating force in the
technology industry. But what is striking about today's Internet
economy is how many entrepreneurs are focused on selling business
plans for their own sake rather than planning viable businesses.
And the ability to pull cash out of companies quickly and with
impunity may soon begin to crumple those Internet businesses that
can no longer get money from investors or the public markets.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA REJECTS NISOURCE OFFER
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Energy Group rejected a $6.1 billion takeover bid from
the utility Nisource and said it would begin exploring
alternatives, including a merger with another company. The
announcement came one week after Nisource sweetened its bid.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGER TENT SOUGHT FOR ROAD SHOW
</P>
<P>
   The road show, the longtime practice of giving sophisticated
investors a preview before an initial public offering, is being
challenged by people who say all investors should be allowed to
take part in conference calls about important information. In
essence, the debate pits an Internet-age drive to give all
investors equal access against many companies' desire to conduct
private forums with the investors who still dominate the financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   WORD-OF-MOUTH OPINIONS GO ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   A handful of companies are hoping to take advantage of the
age-old effectiveness of word-of-mouth recommendations by creating
independent Web sites that give common folks and bona fide experts
a forum to voice their opinions, and users a way to rate the
pundits.
</P>
<P>
   PC SHIPMENTS UP 23 PERCENT IN 3RD QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   The personal-computer industry is continuing to show significant
global growth, with third-quarter shipments increasing by 23.2
percent compared with those in the quarter a year earlier,
according to a report to be issued Monday by Dataquest, a market
research company.
</P>
<P>
   MTV SHOW TO HAVE WEB PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   In the latest attempt to attain true convergence of television
and the Internet, MTV plans to start a music-trivia game show in
which viewers can play along by logging onto MTV's Web site. The
program, ``Web Riot,'' will have its debut late next month, but MTV
plans to start promoting it Monday and to let potential players
begin downloading the required software. Media executives _
particularly advertisers _ will be waiting for MTV to prove that
the time for convergence has finally arrived.
</P>
<P>
   CRICHTON MAKES BOX-OFFICE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The author Michael Crichton has made an unusual deal with
Paramount Pictures for his newest novel. Instead of collecting
millions of dollars by selling the rights to the studio, he has
opted to take a sizable percentage of the box-office receipts.
Executives said they could not recall a similar deal with a
novelist.
</P>
</TEXT>
