<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SAINTS AND DITKA, A MISMANAGED CLOCK IS TICKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ With two minutes left in the shambles of
a rout by the Giants, a flock of reporters rushed to the New
Orleans Saints' interview room Sunday and jockeyed for position. It
is rare that the coach of a team that loses by 31-3 is this highly
sought. But this was Mike Ditka, the volatile coach whose reaction
to the Saints' deepening morass this season has taken him to the
brink of a meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in New Orleans, with his own fans showering him with
boos and jeers during what would become a 3-point loss to
Tennessee, Ditka cursed, made an obscene gesture and grabbed his
crotch as he left the field at halftime. The fans were angry
because the team had bungled a chance to score from the 1-yard line
at the end of the first half. The Saints fined Ditka $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   There was no outburst Sunday, just a tight-lipped, red-faced
soliloquy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were totally confused on defense, disorganized
offensively,'' Ditka said. ``Nothing else out there was really
respectable enough to call it Saints football, or any other kind of
football.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday another time-management blunder _ again at the end of
the first half _ opened the floodgates in what may be a benchmark
game for the Giants. Trailing by 17-3, with the Giants back on
their 22-yard line, Ditka stopped the clock with 17 seconds left.
Four plays later, Kent Graham threw a 53-yard desperation touchdown
to Joe Jurevicius to boost the Giants to a 24-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   William Roaf, the Saints' veteran offensive tackle, lamented:
``They go down there a minute before the half, they go down and get
a touchdown. See what I mean? We got beat. I mean, something's got
to give. I can't take it too much longer. They stopped everything
we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka said of his clock management, ``It was poor. My fault. Not
good. We've done a poor job before; we did it again. Thank you.''
With that he left.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka was hired in 1997 and predicted that the Saints would
reach the Super Bowl. But the relationship between the good-time
city and the intransigent coach soured. A year after he was hired,
Ditka complained about the filth on Bourbon Street, the lack of
places to shop for clothes and the city's attitude. He complained,
``The people in this city are negative, and that bothers me.'' He
said, ``Before you can win, you have to believe you're worthy.''
When an increase in ticket prices was criticized, Ditka said: ``If
everybody is going to complain, maybe New Orleans doesn't need a
franchise. Ever think of that?''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Saints are headed for their third consecutive
losing season under Ditka, the team has become a potion for teams
in need of a lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're the elixir that makes everybody happy,'' he
said. ``When we show up, everybody seems to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka is a relic, skating on thin ice and suffering from
comparisons: Dan Reeves, in just his second year as the coach of
the Atlanta Falcons, led the team to its first Super Bowl. Bill
Parcells guided the Jets to the conference championship game only
three years after inheriting a 1-15 team. Dick Vermeil, who
returned to coaching the same year Ditka returned, has led the St.
Louis Rams to a 5-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints' last winning season came in 1992. In a recent survey
conducted by The Times-Picayune, respondents predicted by a 2-to-1
margin that Ditka will not lead the Saints to the playoffs. By a
3-to-1 margin, those polled predicted that the Saints would post a
losing record for the third straight season under Ditka.
</P>
<P>
   As his teammates scurried out after Sunday's game, Ricky
Williams, the Saints' rookie running back, remained behind,
patiently answering questions about his milestone day. Williams,
the 1998 Heisman Trophy winner, had rushed for 100 yards for the
first time in his pro career, all of six games old.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just numbers, that's all,'' he said. In Williams'
case, numbers matter. A lot. The Saints, on Ditka's recommendation,
effectively mortgaged their future by trading a number of draft
picks for the chance to select Williams. In turn, Williams signed
an incentive-laden contract with the Saints. He is guaranteed $11
million, but his four-year contract can be worth as much as $68
million if he reaches all of 26 incentives written into the deal.
One incentive is reached if Williams averages 1,600 yards a year
over four years, a staggering figure. He'll have to average nearly
120 yards a game the remainder of this season to be on pace. He
hasn't been healthy enough to even make a dent.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams' fortunes have been as dismal as the Saints'. He
reported to camp out of shape, then injured his ankle, twice, and
injured his forearm. Sunday he gained 111 yards on 24 carries. He
scored once, but the touchdown was called back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been injured and banged up a lot, so I haven't had a
chance to really be myself out there,'' he said. ``For the first
time I felt more like myself.''
</P>
<P>
   As Williams left for the team bus, someone asked how he felt
about Ditka's explosions. Did he feel linked to his coach?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``We're on different levels _ he's been
in football so long and this is my first year, so I can't really
understand what he's been going through, but I know it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the rookie, is watching a coach near the end of his
career do a slow burn; it's all part of the business, but not fun
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels like everything is his fault,'' Williams said. ``It's
really sad. I wish we could play better to make him feel better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
