<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENT DEFENDS FAIRNESS OF PARTY'S 1ST PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Speaking two weeks before Mexico's first
presidential primary, President Ernesto Zedillo on Sunday defended
the fairness of the process and renewed his pledge to remain
neutral.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo denied accusations that the primary for his governing
party has been rigged to favor Francisco Labastida Ochoa, his
former interior minister. His three rivals have complained
repeatedly that Labastida, the only member of Zedillo's Cabinet in
the primary, is the president's preferred candidate and has been
given unfair advantages by his Institutional Revolutionary Party,
known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not during the process up to now, nor in what remains of it,
have I had, nor will I have, a preferred candidate,'' Zedillo said
Sunday in a speech to hundreds of party leaders. ``Nobody can point
to a single action, not even the smallest sign, to suggest that I
have failed in my commitment to strict neutrality.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's address to governors, members of congress, mayors,
union chiefs and other party leaders broke a seven-month silence.
He has not spoken publicly about the primary since March, when he
publicly renounced the tradition under which Mexican presidents
have handpicked their successors and urged party leaders to
organize the party's first primary, scheduled for Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, opinion polls have suggested that Labastida has
taken a significant lead over his closest rival, Roberto Madrazo
Pintado, a former governor of Tabasco. Two others seeking the
party's nomination, Manuel Bartlett Diaz, a former governor of
Puebla, and Humberto Roque Villanueva, a former speaker of the
House, are running far behind. The winner of the primary will
compete against two opposition-party candidates in presidential
balloting on July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's three primary election adversaries have all
complained in recent days about what they say has been unfair
support given to him by governors and other officials, including
verbal endorsements as well as logistical and material help. But
Zedillo brushed aside those assertions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the candidates, I repeat: Have confidence in
democracy,'' Zedillo said. ``Have confidence in the PRI. Don't
waste your time and campaign resources inciting fears that are not
warranted. In short, don't cast aspersions on our party for unjust
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo has been especially aggressive in impugning the
impartiality of party leaders. Earlier this month, he accused the
governing party chief, Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez, of working
to rig the primary in favor of Labastida, and demanded that
Gonzalez resign. A party panel established to referee the primary
campaign rejected Madrazo's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints by Labastida's rivals have grown so vehement that he
has acknowledged that the party could rupture after the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo urged the four contenders to maintain party unity. ``In
elections as competitive as we expect next year's to be, unity is
simply indispensable,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
