<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SCOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDY SCOTT, 50, WHO FAKED ILLNESS FOR ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (lb) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wendy Scott, who had one of the most severe cases on record of a
syndrome in which people feign illness or make themselves sick to
get medical treatment, died on Oct. 14 at a hospice in South
London. She was 50.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was intestinal cancer, said Mary Jane Lang, a friend
of Miss Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Scott, who lived in London, spent 12 years traveling from
one hospital to another in Britain and elsewhere in Europe,
pretending to be ill so that she could become a patient. She was
admitted to hundreds of hospitals and underwent 42 operations,
nearly all of them unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Miss Scott recovered from the condition, called
Munchausen syndrome, which many doctors consider untreatable.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in The New York Times on July 20, Miss Scott
said she had not faked her way into a hospital in 20 years. She
credited her devotion to a pet with helping her recover. She became
so attached to a kitten that she gave up hospitals for fear the
kitten would be neglected in her absence.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, she tried to help other people with Munchausen
syndrome, communicating with them by mail, telephone and the
Internet. She also approached Dr. Marc Feldman, a psychiatrist at
the University of Alabama at Birmingham and an expert on Munchausen
syndrome, who said she had helped a number of patients.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Ms. Scott became increasingly ill but had
difficulty obtaining medical care in London because of her
notorious record. While visiting Miss Lang in the United States
last summer, she sought help from Feldman, whose colleagues in
Birmingham discovered that she had advanced intestinal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Scott remained in the hospital in Birmingham until last
month, and then returned to London.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Scott was born in 1948 in Wemyss, in the Fife region of
Scotland near the North Sea. Information about survivors was not
available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONNERLY25-COX     10-24 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNERLY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ward Connerly fights image issues
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each word is spoken with increasing
anger. Ward Connerly is ticked off, and right now, race matters.
</P>
<P>
   A Palm Beach Post editorial comment that he considers dismissive
of his African-American, Irish, French and Indian ancestry, ``is
very demeaning of my heritage,'' says the man who wants Floridians
to end race-based affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's racist. Your damn paper gets away with it
because I'm a black.''
</P>
<P>
   If Connerly is aware of the irony of his statement, he never
lets on. Instead, he calms down and spends the next 45 minutes
talking about how we should have a society where race doesn't
matter.
</P>
<P>
   To his critics, Connerly is a political fraud. ``He wants to
tell blacks that race doesn't matter, but when he got angry he
didn't say he was Irish,'' says Tony Welch, 34, a Tallahassee
Democrat who shares much in common with Connerly except his
political beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly sees himself as a crusader who believes that the next
logical step in improving race relations is to end affirmative
action and replace it with programs that help the poor regardless
of color.
</P>
<P>
   He does more than talk about it. His movement succeeded in
changing the laws in the states of California and Washington so
governments and universities can no longer use racial preferences
in choosing students or awarding contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly wants to do the same in Florida. His organization here,
the Florida Civil Rights Initiative, has already collected more
than 50,000 signatures. Plenty to send a proposed 37-word amendment
to the state Constitution to the Florida Supreme Court. Soon, the
court will decide if those words are clear enough and limited in
scope enough to be put on the November 2000 ballot. Early polling
suggests that if the amendment makes it to the ballot, it will win
overwhelming support.
</P>
<P>
   He has been called a ``house slave'' and a ``puppet for the
white man.'' Gov. Jeb Bush urged him not to come to Florida, saying
he is ``too divisive.'' When Connerly, who had the help of former
California Gov. Pete Wilson in passing Proposition 209 last year,
asked to speak at the Florida Republican convention this month, he
was told, ``No.'' Ditto to his request to set up a hospitality
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The establishment in Florida from the governor on down don't
seem to give a damn about free speech and open discussion of
ideas,'' Connerly complains. ``The politicians and minorities in
Florida play hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   COMMON BONDS, UNLIKE IDEALS
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing Bush's concerns, Connerly asks, ``What issue isn't
divisive? You don't think a proposal for school vouchers isn't
divisive?'' For Connerly, getting rid of racial preferences is the
next logical step toward a time when his three grandchildren will
live in a society where race is no longer the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my grandkids to have to go through the crap of,
'What are you?''' he says. ``You know if I say I'm anything other
than African-American, I get grief. Why should there be this
intimidation?''
</P>
<P>
   Welch says, welcome to reality.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are black. Their wives are white. Their children
biracial. Connerly has two grandchildren who have a Vietnamese
mother. With as much as they have in common in their homes, they
have little in common on the issue of race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Ward Connerly really believes the bile he's
spewing,'' says Welch, a former Pensacola newspaper reporter who is
now a spokesman for the state Democratic Party. He spoke for this
story as a private citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that race should not matter, but it does, and I
have already had to explain to my 4-year-old daughter why it
mattered one day in preschool,'' Welch says. ``And Connerly knows
that the reason he is the chosen leader of that movement is because
of the color of his skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action and other preference programs must remain to
continue the effort begun with the 1964 Civil Rights Act to end the
racism embedded in both government and private industry, Welch
argues.
</P>
<P>
   'WELFARE FOR THE MIDDLE CLASS'
</P>
<P>
   Connerly believes the Civil Rights Act never intended preference
programs. Instead, it was a call to treat all people equally. The
only preference programs that should exist are those that help
people in poverty regardless of race.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs have become like welfare,'' Connerly says.
``People have become dependent on them. And there are some serious
problems in Florida with cronyism and favoritism that abuse this
system. I believe the sole reason for the government to use
taxpayers' money to benefit anybody is to help people who need
assistance. Affirmative action is a form of welfare for the middle
class.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Connerly says, he experienced the callous racism of
the Jim Crow era where ``coloreds'' were often denied service in
restaurants and hotels and were forbidden to use ``white''
restrooms and water fountains.
</P>
<P>
   He went to community college in Sacramento and then went on to
get his four-year degree. A few years later he wound up working
with Pete Wilson, then a state legislator in California. At
Wilson's urging, Connerly got a job dealing with housing and
community development in then-Gov. Ronald Reagan's administration.
He now has a consulting business based in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   None of his jobs or clients was the result of any type of
affirmative action program, says Connerly. ``Say I'm a crony of
Pete Wilson. Say I'm appointed because I gave him $130,000 for his
campaign. But instead, we would rather believe a black person got
something because he is black. That stigma is not helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG READY TO MOVE FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   Welch suggests Connerly is being conveniently naive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he really believe that Ronald Reagan didn't consider the
color of his skin when he appointed Connerly?'' says Welch. ``I
don't doubt that his connections to Pete Wilson helped. I also
don't doubt that Connerly's race helped.''
</P>
<P>
   It is among the people who are half his age, such as Welch, that
Connerly sees the most promise for the future. He says younger
blacks do not want to cling to slavery or the days of Jim Crow
laws. He says younger whites do not want to be held responsible for
the past. Both, he insists, are ready to move forward in race
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a Democrat, I would probably have more credibility
with some people about this issue,'' Connerly says. ``But then I
would be seen as a race traitor and as a traitor to the Democrat
ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is viewed by his rivals as someone who is trying to
make a name for himself, put a few dollars in his pocket and win
respectability among conservative whites at the expense of
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I ask myself why I keep doing this,'' says Connerly.
``But I have an absolute belief that if you feel something strongly
enough, you have a moral obligation to follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
