<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY MARTIN EARNS CARD FOR PGA TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By BILL FIELDS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOTHAN, Ala. _ Casey Martin's golf wasn't pretty, but when the
Nike Tour Championship ended Sunday, his tie for 37th place was a
beautiful thing to him.
</P>
<P>
   That was because despite closing with a 78 and finishing at
11-over-par 299, 16 strokes off the pace, Martin concluded the Nike
Tour season 14th on the money list. And as one of the top 15 money
earners on the Nike developmental circuit, he secured his PGA Tour
card, giving him playing privileges on the Tour next year.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is a disabled golfer who sued the PGA Tour for the right
to use a golf cart in competition and won; the Tour has appealed
the case in Federal Court, and a ruling is expected any day. He
began the week 12th on the money list. When he shot 77-78 in the
final two rounds, he was vulnerable to falling out of the top 15,
but he got help when three golfers immediately behind him on the
money list had off weeks as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a struggle, every week is a struggle,'' said Martin, who
was born with a circulatory disorder that has caused his right leg
to deteriorate and forced him to deal with constant pain. ``My life
can definitely be a struggle, but it's a fairy tale too at the same
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the other 14 golfers who earned their 2000 PGA Tour
rights, Martin was handed his player's card by the PGA Tour
commissioner, Tim Finchem, after Bob Heintz had defeated Marco
Dawson in a playoff for the championship. As Finchem has done
throughout Martin's legal battle with the PGA Tour, he applauded
Martin's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased and excited for Casey,'' Finchem said afterward.
``He's overcome a lot to get to this point. Whatever the court
does, it does. We believe strongly in the rules we have regarding
walking in the sport, but at the same time you have to a great deal
of admiration at how far he's come. You have to take your hat off
to him, and we do.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Tour wins its appeal, it would be up to the Tour policy
board to decide whether to make an exception in Martin's case,
something it has not chosen to do before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what the court does,'' Finchem said. ``And then
we'll talk about that. Right now, our posture is, we have a rule on
the books. If the courts don't disallow us from implementing that
rule, it would be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Repeating a pattern from the third round, Martin began to
struggle in the middle of Sunday's final round. He bogeyed the
first three holes of the back nine, setting the tone for an
incoming 42. Finishing about two hours before the final group, he
had time to eat lunch, check the computer leader board and watch
the leaders finish on television. His mother, Melinda, sat with
him. His father, King, retreated to Martin's courtesy car to be
alone with his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying this trip wouldn't be in vain,'' King Martin
said. ``We don't do anything easy. We get there the hard way. I
wish I could just box the way I feel right now, because it's a
treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's legal case has created a fissure in professional golf,
but after playing two seasons on the Nike Tour, he has won over
some players after they have seen the difficulty he has just moving
from his cart to the ball. His right leg has gotten worse in recent
years and is unlikely to get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey's a friend of mine, and I've got chills thinking about
it,'' said Carl Paulson, who finished first on the Nike Tour money
list and will be joining Martin on the PGA Tour. ``It's a dream
come true for him. He can't play without a cart. The way I look at
it, it's more unfair if he didn't get a cart than unfair if he has
a cart. It's a perfect script that he makes it this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
