<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LAMBORGHINI-LEMON25-C     10-24 1780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMBORGHINI-LEMON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lamborghini lemon case shifts to plantiff's past
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Who knows, maybe the Lamborghini Diablo
Roadster is the world's most extravagant lemon. But in a lawsuit
intended to prove just that, questions about the $238,000 sports
car's reliability are suddenly beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, attorneys for the Italian automaker will appeal to a
federal magistrate in West Palm Beach to throw out a suit against
the company filed by a Fort Lauderdale man, John Martin. They say
Martin is holding ``straw title'' to the car for its true owner,
Brian Neiman, a paralegal and felon who has become notorious in
South Florida legal circles for his role in several high-profile
discrimination lawsuits _ and for an aggressive style that
sometimes crosses the line.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of testimony about leaky doors, sudden engine stalls
and blinking dashboards, the case has now cast a spotlight on
Neiman's checkered career: From his convictions three years ago for
insurance fraud, to more recent accusations that he practiced law
illegally and has used ``blackmail tactics'' to extract
million-dollar settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense to the case is to try to make me the highlight
of the case, which I am not,'' Neiman said. ``There's really one
question: Is the car defective?''
</P>
<P>
   It all began in June 1998, when John Martin v. Automobili
Lamborghini was filed in federal court. In the suit, Martin said
the company promised him that the low-riding purple sports car,
which can reach speeds of 200 mph, could take the wear and tear of
everyday driving. Instead, the car scraped over speed bumps, leaked
when it rained and stalled for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin would not have purchased the Diablo if he had been
advised of the existing design and manufacturing defects,'' the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   When the lawsuit was filed, Martin, 32, a jet engine mechanic
and pharmacy student, told The Palm Beach Post that his parents
helped him buy the 1997 car from a North Miami Beach dealership.
</P>
<P>
   But that turned out not to be so. Lamborghini lawyers found that
Neiman negotiated the deal for the car, and money from a bank
account in Neiman's name covered the difference after they traded
in a Ferrari (also held in Martin's name).
</P>
<P>
   READING THE FINE PRINT
</P>
<P>
   In initial court papers, Martin was described as Neiman's
roommate. It has since been disclosed in court papers that they
were lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin may have been asked to hold straw title as a front, but
to have claimed in this suit that he was the purchaser and owner
... was a rank fraud on this court,'' Lamborghini lawyer John
Dotterrer wrote in court papers
</P>
<P>
   Neiman, 30, is the paralegal for Saul Smolar, the lawyer who
filed the suit. With Smolar and another attorney, Norman Ganz,
Neiman has helped collect millions of dollars in out-of-court
settlements from discrimination claims, many of them against large
employers and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Among their targets have been the Boynton Beach police, the
cities of Lake Park and Port St. Lucie, the St. Lucie County School
District and the Martin Correctional Institution.
</P>
<P>
   But the legal team's tactics have been criticized more than once
by opposing lawyers, judges and even some of their own clients. The
Lamborghini case has been no different.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning the ownership of the car, the Lamborghini
lawyers attacked the lawsuit itself. They found that Neiman, not
Smolar, was the one who signed the complaint, as well as several
other court documents. Court rules say only lawyers should sign
such records.
</P>
<P>
   When handwriting samples were demanded, Neiman and Smolar
admitted it was Neiman who signed Smolar's name. Smolar said he's
often out of the office and can't always sign documents, but he
reviewed them with Neiman over the phone, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   The defense wants Smolar and Neiman fined for the infraction.
And it's not the first time it's happened. Last month, a magistrate
in Fort Pierce recommended $10,000 fines each for Neiman and Smolar
for allowing Neiman to sign court papers. The judge also wants
Smolar barred from practicing in federal court for a year. Smolar
and Neiman have filed objections.
</P>
<P>
   DID THE COMPANY KNOW?
</P>
<P>
   To Lamborghini, it's further indication that the case against
the company is: The man who signed the complaint was the one who
bought the car, and he often drove it. Neiman has been ticketed
while driving the car, he paid for repairs, and he took tax
write-offs for it, court records show. Neiman's probation officer
said he even bragged about his new car, though Neiman said he
doesn't remember it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you not make the case about Neiman when every rock we
pick up comes back to Neiman?'' said John Mullin, a Fort Lauderdale
lawyer with Lamborghini's distribution company.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman and Martin say none of this matters. Martin holds the
title to the car, his name's on the warranty, and he holds the
insurance. It was Martin, they say, who was trapped inside the car
when the doors jammed shut; he was the one who got smacked in the
head when the sunroof swung free.
</P>
<P>
   They also have statements from more than a dozen former
Lamborghini employees who say the company knew the car was a lemon,
and repair records showing the problems with the Diablo are
chronic, Neiman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real facts of this case will eventually bear out that the
Diablo is defective,'' Harris Solomon, a lawyer for Martin and
Neiman, said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   BIG MONEY BRINGS BIG PROBLEMS
</P>
<P>
   Lamborghini denies the Diablo Roadster is faulty, and lawyers
for the company say the ex-workers are disgruntled. Neiman says the
defense strategy has been to portray him as ``a fag and a felon,''
rehashing his convictions for grand theft and insurance fraud and
forcing him to disclose his relationship with Martin (they broke up
late last year after six years together).
</P>
<P>
   Neiman said he gave the car to Martin as a gift, and the
$145,000 check that covered the difference from the Ferrari
trade-in came from an account the two men still share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to reconcile the relationship with him, and
this certainly hasn't helped it,'' Neiman said. ``The only thing he
left this relationship with was that car.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman said he bought Martin about six cars over the years, paid
for with the money he made working with Smolar and Ganz.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Neiman and Ganz handled several high-profile
lawsuits from Miami to Fort Pierce, usually alleging race or sex
discrimination. They won big settlements, including $1.4 million
from the St. Lucie County School District, $1.6 million from
BellSouth and $1.3 million from the Broward County clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   But opposing lawyers and some judges have said the team's
negotiating tactics were akin to blackmail. In one case, U.S.
District Judge Kenneth Ryskamp said Neiman, Ganz and two other
lawyers should share a $180,000 fine for using the threat of action
by the NAACP to try to get a large settlement. Ganz was the general
counsel for the civil-rights group's Fort Lauderdale branch at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   These issues eventually caught the notice of the Florida Bar.
Last year, while the bar was investigating Ganz's conduct in two
cases, Ganz resigned from his law practice, citing medical reasons.
His cases were then taken over by Smolar, who now is also under
investigation by the Bar.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits made Neiman a wealthy man wealthier, it seems, than
the lawyers he's worked for. Until recently, the law firm worked
mainly out of a $1 million waterfront home Neiman owned in Fort
Lauderdale. According to bar investigators, Ganz's law practice
made about $4.1 million in 1995 and 1996 _ nearly 70 percent of
which went to Neiman.
</P>
<P>
   But lately the courts have not been so kind to Neiman. He's been
prosecuted for practicing law without a license, the Florida Bar is
after him, and opposing lawyers have waged vitriolic
counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   THE `LAWYER' WITH A RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Neiman pleaded guilty in August to the misdemeanor charges of
practicing law illegally for negotiating settlements for clients.
He was sentenced to five years' probation, but it was suspended
while he appeals. He says he did it in an effort to clear up the
law: An appeals court has been asked to draw clear lines regarding
what paralegals can and can't do when working on a case.
</P>
<P>
   To the Florida Bar, the lines are obvious. Its 22-count
complaint, filed in January, says Neiman, not Ganz or Smolar, met
with clients, orchestrated the complaints and negotiated most
settlements, sometimes using ``coercive tactics'' to get their
clients to agree to the terms. The complaint also says Neiman
occasionally held himself out as an attorney; one client said she
didn't know Neiman wasn't a lawyer until she read about him in a
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman has been in trouble before. In 1996, he was convicted of
filing false insurance claims, saying he couldn't work for a year
because of complications from a tonsillectomy. He's also been
charged with taking part in bogus ``slip-and-fall'' schemes (one
involving his mother), leading to convictions for grand theft and
organized fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Neiman's recent civil cases have also soured. In one
suit against a skating rink, the rink's lawyers accused Neiman of
racketeering, saying he bribed witnesses to essentially set up the
case, court records show. Neiman dismissed the accusations as
``impertinent and scandalous,'' and the suit was later settled for
$15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman and Smolar were also sued in Broward County by some
former clients who say their legal fees were excessive.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW HE'S A WITNESS
</P>
<P>
   Neiman dismisses all this as distractions from questions about
the Lamborghini's faults. He's busy working with Smolar, gathering
more evidence for future cases against the famous automaker.
</P>
<P>
   However, Smolar has withdrawn as Martin's lawyer because Neiman
has become a witness. Solomon, the lawyer who took over the case,
has filed a motion asking that evidence of Neiman's criminal record
be banned from the trial, which is set for April.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman sold his oceanfront home and now lives more modestly. (He
tried to argue to Fort Lauderdale zoning officials that he had to
work out of his house for health reasons. His condition?
Incontinence.) And though he insists the Lamborghini is still
Martin's to have, the violet vision that started the whole mess is
sitting in Neiman's garage. Martin, he says, can't keep it at his
condominium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worthless,'' Neiman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
