<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REDSKINS-     10-24 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REDSKINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ Washington receivers Albert Connell and Michael Westbrook
boasted last week that they weren't afraid of Dallas cornerback
Deion Sanders. They were confident, they said, that the future Hall
of Famer couldn't stop them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What they failed to consider, however, was the Redskins stopping
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with a concussion suffered early in the game, Sanders
got his first punt return for a touchdown this season, running 70
yards to cap a 38-20 Cowboys victory over the Redskins on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Connell and Sanders tied with one touchdown apiece, Connell's a
44-yard reception late in the third quarter that still left the
Redskins playing catch-up. He finished with two catches for 52
yards. Westbrook was even less of a factor, catching three balls
for 38 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him (Connell) he played a good game and got his big
play, but it ain't no fun when the rabbit's got the gun, too,''
Sanders said. ``I know a lot of guys want to make a name for
themselves off me because I'm a big-game player, but I've got the
gun also.''
</P>
<P>
   At 4-2 each, Dallas and Washington are now tied atop the NFC
East, although the Cowboys obtained the tiebreaker edge by virtue
of a regular-season sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who didn't play when the teams last met in the season
opener, suffered his concussion on a punt return toward the end of
the first quarter. He barreled forward, head down, and met Dan
Turk, helmet on helmet. Shaken, Sanders got up slowly, then was
taken to the locker room for tests.
</P>
<P>
   He emerged from the locker room in the third quarter, bypassing
the sideline and heading straight onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the doctors weren't going to let me go out there,''
Sanders said. ``So I came right out of the tunnel, right onto the
field. I wouldn't hear no for the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither would his teammates, who had much to prove after 13-10
losses to the Eagles and Giants over the previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas offense, in particular, was desperate to show it was
better than the unit that was limited to one touchdown at both
Philadelphia and New York. It struck early and often, scoring 17
points on its first three trips down the field. In all, the
Cowboys' offense amassed 352 yards and crossed the goal line four
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We executed better, no turnovers, and did well in the red
zone,'' Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman said. ``We had big plays and
touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was responsible for three of those, connecting with
Rocket Ismail on a 13-yard pass on the opening drive and with tight
end David LaFleur on a four-yard pass late in the third quarter.
Aikman later carried the ball one yard himself, barely getting into
the end zone on an ugly but successful bootleg keeper early in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to throw it,'' Aikman said. ``It should have been an
easy touchdown. I made it more dramatic than it should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith plunged in from a yard out for the Cowboys' other
touchdown. Smith, who rushed for only 26 yards Oct. 18 against the
Giants, struggled on his outside attempts but was fairly successful
running north and south, finishing the day with 80 yards on 24
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very important after the way we played the last
two weeks that we come out early and establish ourselves, either on
the ground or in the air,'' Smith said. ``I think we did a good job
of that. We were more intense today. We did better flying around
and just trying to have fun playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to have fun as Dallas surged to a 17-0 lead thanks
to Ismail's catch, Smith's run and a 32-yard field goal by Richie
Cunningham. The Redskins were held to 23 total yards in the first
quarter, which included Washington drives of nine and minus-13
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played horribly in the first quarter, and the Dallas
Cowboys played with a lot of intensity,'' Redskins coach Norv
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas defense also came in with a mission, determined to
prove it wasn't as bad as it looked in Week 1 when it allowed the
Redskins to score 35 points. It made its point quickly as Sanders
leaped out on the opening play to nail Stephen Davis four yards
behind the line of scrimmage. Greg Ellis took the lead on second
down, hitting Larry Centers at the line for no gain. It was Chad
Hennings' turn on third-and-14. He drilled quarterback Brad Johnson
at the line of scrimmage to force a punt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very impressive,'' Dallas coach Chan Gailey said of
Sanders' initial hit. ``It looked like he shot out of a cannon. It
showed everyone we were going to get after them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins were eventually able to get the NFL's No. 1 offense
going. Johnson hit Mike Sellers with a 33-yard scoring pass to
narrow the gap to 17-7 with 6:52 remaining in the second quarter.
Brett Conway's second field goal made it a 17-13 game at the 10:35
mark in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But for the remainder of the game, Dallas came up with an answer
every time Washington threatened. After Conway's second field goal,
the Cowboys held the ball for nearly six minutes, driving 75 yards
and scoring on LaFleur's touchdown catch.
</P>
<P>
   After Connell caught his 44-yarder late in the third to again
pull Washington within four, the Cowboys drove 90 yards for
Aikman's one-yard score to increase the lead to 31-20. Sanders'
70-yard punt return was icing on the celebratory cake.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins finished with 272 yards total offense, a far cry
from the 504 they amassed in Week 1 against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was a little bit of a measuring stick,'' said Dallas
defensive coordinator Dave Campo, ``because of the fact that we
helped them to their No. 1 offensive ranking in that first
ballgame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
