<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-QUINN-NYT &LR;      10-24 0216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-QUINN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT QUINN, JOHNNY CARSON'S DIRECTOR, DIES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Quinn, the longtime director of NBC's ``Tonight'' show
when Johnny Carson was host, died on Thursday at his home in
Malibu, Calif. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, known as Bobby, was the director of the show from 1968 to
1992, when Carson left the show and he retired.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 Quinn won a Directors Guild of America award for his
work on Carson's second-to-last ``Tonight'' show, with Robin
Williams and Bette Midler as guests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 Quinn was nominated for an Emmy for his directing of
``Tonight,'' ``after doing five shows a week for 25 years,'' as
Carson put it at the time.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Brooklyn, Quinn graduated from high school there and
served in the Marines during World War II and the Korean War. He
joined NBC in the 1940s as a mail clerk in Manhattan and rose
through its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   His marriages to Nancy Kyle and Tangley Lloyd ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving are his wife of 14 years, the former Charlotte
Micheli; three daughters, Patricia Hilton, Kathleen Gorlitz and
Demarest Quinn; six sons, Douglas, Kevin, Brian, Colin, Robert Jr.
and James; 13 grandchildren and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
