r s BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-24 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAY HEY KID WAS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Where's Pete Rose? Why isn't he here? Oh, he'll be
here later in the day before Game 2 of the World Series when they
introduce the living members of the All-Century Team.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Peter Rose? Oh, he's doing a card show in Atlantic City.
What do you think, should he be in the Hall of Fame?
</P>
<P>
   The assemblage of writers went on and on about Pete Rose this
and Pete Rose that, but on this particular early Sunday afternoon I
wouldn't have cared had Pete Rose remained in Atlanta City and
gambled to his addictive heart's delight late into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   To be honest with you, I didn't give one damn bit about Pete
Rose, even though I happen to like Pete personally and believe that
he should have his plaque hanging in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   My childhood idol, Willie Mays, was present at an All Century
Team press conference at the Marriott Marquis, along with other
icons of his sport like Hank Aaron and Sandy Koufax and Stan Musial
and Bob Gibson and Warren Spahn and Mike Schmidt and Brooks
Robinson and Nolan Ryan and Yogi Berra.
</P>
<P>
   They stuck the players in three ballrooms for interviews, but I
was interested only in talking to the man who was the greatest
baseball player I've ever seen perform on the ball diamonds around
America.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, the immortal Say Hey Kid, with his thrilling style of
playing a game that he so often turned into a private recital of
his joyful skills.
</P>
<P>
   No one could make a catch more exciting than Mays, and no one
seemed to have more fun on the field than the hyperactive center
fielder of the San Francisco Giants who played 22 major league
seasons and wound up with 660 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   There have been passionate arguments among people who care about
such things about who the best living baseball player is since the
death of Joe DiMaggio, and the names mentioned most often are those
of Mays, Ted Williams, Pete Rose, Koufax, Musial and Gibson.
</P>
<P>
   But I, admittedly biased, think the arguments are specious.
</P>
<P>
   I thought Mays ranked No. 1 even when DiMaggio was living.
</P>
<P>
   But for some reason, in the wake of the New York-inspired
hysteria accompanying the deaths of DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle and
the on-going controversy surrounding Rose, Willie Mays has lapsed
into the public shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why haven't you received as much recognition in recent years
as some of your contemporaries?'' I asked Mays, as he sat at a
podium engulfed by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I'm not going to go there,'' said Mays defensively. ``I
think I'm as well known now as I've ever been. I really don't think
of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays is stylishly dressed in a custom-made tan suit, and he's 21
pounds heavier at 210 than he was during those glad days when he
was chasing down fly balls and loosing his cap in parks around the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I weighed 189 my entire career, and had a 32-inch waist when I
retired,'' he says proudly.
</P>
<P>
   He is 68 years old now, and the hair has receded slightly and
the face is puffier than it was when he was the most entertaining
athlete in this country.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter from New York reminded him of that famous picture of
him playing stickball with kids on a street in New York when the
Giants still played there, and what an impact it had on the young
men of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way an athlete could do that today,'' says Mays, who lives
in San Francisco and works part-time for the Giants and Bally's.
``The streets are a little more dangerous. You might get in some
trouble if you tried it now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where exactly did you play stickball with the kids?'' Mays was
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was at 155th and St. Nicholas right near the Polo
Grounds,'' related Mays, shaking his head in fond remembrance.
``The police used to close off the street, and we'd have a blast.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Mays how many more home runs he would hit had he not
played at Candlestick Park, where the wind blew in from left field
and forced Mays to change his batting stance and drive the ball to
the opposite field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I probably would have hit a few more,'' he said. ``But I'm
a guy who never cared about records. What I cared most about was
winning. If I concentrated on hitting just home runs, I'm sure I
could have hit 50 many times. If I concentrated on stealing bases,
I'm sure I could have stole more than 50 many times. But I was
never about numbers. I just cared about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays refused to say anything about Pete Rose other than
extolling his virtues as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a terrific player,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose later in the day would hold a lively press conference at
Turner Field, reiterating that he was sorry for his past gambling
deeds, saying how passionately he wanted to return to baseball,
saying there was no greater goodwill ambassador of the game than
himself and saying that he hasn't been treated fairly and that even
Charles Manson gets a hearing every year.
</P>
<P>
   Rose understandably commanded the most media attention among the
All Century Team members, but not for an old sports columnist who
remembers what Willie Mays defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the baseball scouts I've spoken to say you're the greatest
player they've ever seen,'' I say to Mays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you hear those things,'' he says. ``It's nice. They're
always touting someone as the `next Willie Mays.' They're saying it
about Andruw Jones. Once it was Cesar Cedeno. And then it was Eric
Davis. I'm sure one day one will come along.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so.
</P>
<P>
   But I doubt I'll be around to witness it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
