<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHICAGO-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE U.S. CITIZEN FROM MOROCCO SETS MARATHON RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Six years after emigrating from Morocco, Khalid
Khannouchi is chasing the American dream. He has a Web site and a
sport utility vehicle. He hopes to win a gold medal for the United
States in the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   If only he were a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi ran the fastest marathon in history on Sunday,
surpassing the old record by 23 seconds.. On a blustery morning, he
blew through a pack of Kenyan champions to win the LaSalle Banks
Chicago Marathon in 2 hours 5 minutes 42 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   A slight 27-year-old, Khannouchi came 3,500 miles from the city
of Meknes to Brooklyn in 1993. He married an American citizen in
1996, but his citizenship application has moved slowly through the
Immigration and Naturalization Service. After he moved to Ossining,
N.Y., his congresswoman, Rep. Sue Kelly, tried without success to
get congressional action in his case.
</P>
<P>
   Without action by the INS or Congress, Khannouchi will not be
able to compete in the U.S. Olympic trials next year. He said he
will not race for Morocco but wants to win a medal for his new
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my dream,'' he said after the race. ``I want to give
something back. I'm so grateful. `Thank you' is nothing. I really
want to do something for the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's resolution was rebuffed by a fellow Republican, Rep.
Lamar Smith of Texas, the chairman of the House Judiciary
Subcommittee on Immigration and Claims. ``It would be unfair,''
Smith wrote, ``to expedite naturalization for someone to allow them
to compete against American citizens for the small amount of slots
on the U.S. Olympic team.''
</P>
<P>
   But without Khannouchi, the United States will have fewer slots
in the marathon. Runners need times under 2:14 to qualify for the
Olympics. Only one U.S. runner has made that time during the
qualifying period. So, unless two other Americans slip under 2:14
by Sept. 11, 2000, Khannouchi would be adding a runner to the team,
not taking someone else's slot.
</P>
<P>
   The first American to break 2:14 did so Sunday in Chicago, and
he set a national record. David Morris, originally of Eagle River,
Alaska, finished a surprising fourth in 2:09:32. His time broke the
American record of 2:09:35 set in Chicago by Jerry Lawson in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Other Americans have run faster than Morris, including Alberto
Salazar in the Boston Marathon and the New York City Marathon and
Bill Rodgers twice in Boston, but their times are not recognized as
records because the courses were too downhill, too windy or too
short.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a perfect day for a marathon: 36 degrees by Lake
Michigan, with a wind of 8 mph. But the field of 30,000 was packed
with world-class runners who came to Chicago for the flat, fast
course and the $400,000 purse. They included Ronaldo da Costa of
Brazil, whose record Khannouchi broke.
</P>
<P>
   The race directors did everything imaginable to get a world
record. They hired three rabbits, runners who run fast
half-marathons before quitting. The pace car displayed not only the
race time but also the finish pace, so the lead runners could see
how close they were to the record.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbits did their jobs, pushing the leaders to a halfway
time of 1:03:00. In the 15th mile, da Costa dropped out. In the
18th mile, Moses Tanui, a Kenyan who has won the Boston Marathon
twice, assumed the lead. Tanui moved 26 seconds ahead, but
Khannouchi did not follow him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a chance,'' Khannouchi said. ``The point today was to
stay relaxed. It was cold, a little windy. That's not my weather.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first marathon, Khannouchi won in Chicago two years ago
in 2:07:10. It was the fastest debut in history and the
fourth-fastest marathon at that time. Last year, with an injured
heel, he considered quitting but limped to second place.
</P>
<P>
   With three miles to go in this, his third marathon, Khannouchi
began to close quickly on the more experienced Tanui.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about running a record today,'' he said. ``It
was more important to win. So I just decided to run a very relaxed
first half of the race, not to take any chances and pull away the
last three miles. That was the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   With a mile and a half to go, the pair entered a tunnel by the
lake-front, with Khannouchi three strides in the lead. When they
emerged 30 seconds later, he led by 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the point I decided,'' Khannouchi said, ``if I'm going
to get him, I have to move.'' He ran the last 3.1 miles at a pace
of 4:40 a mile.
</P>
<P>
   After chesting the tape, Khannouchi cried and embraced his wife
and coach, Sandra, a 2:42 marathoner and naturalized American
citizen from the Dominican Republic. Then he blew kisses with his
white-gloved hands.
</P>
<P>
   Tanui said that he had confused the distance, thinking the race
was further along when he moved ahead. He finished 33 seconds back,
in 2:06:15, a personal best.
</P>
<P>
   The women's race was closer but not near a record, with two
Kenyans finishing a stride apart. After falling just before the
middle of the race, the defending champion, Joyce Chepchumba, 28,
finished in 2:25:59, just ahead of Margaret Okayo.
</P>
<P>
   Each winner received $65,000, and Khannouchi added $100,000 for
the world record.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday afternoon he had updated his Web site, at
www.khannouchi.com, with a new headline, ``World Record 2:05:42.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
