<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-RAIDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS LET A LEAD, A RAIDER AND A SEASON SLIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It got worse for the New York Jets on Sunday,
and it comes at a point in the season when they have time on their
hands. They blew a 20-3 lead, blew a mini-revival by Rick Mirer at
quarterback and all but officially blew their season.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 15{ minutes of the game, the Raiders produced
touchdown drives of 72, 83 and 90 yards to generate a stunning
24-23 victory and drop the Jets to 1-6. The final touchdown came
with 26 seconds remaining. Quarterback Rich Gannon scrambled,
eluded Mo Lewis and drilled a 5-yard touchdown pass to James Jett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I got my arms around him,'' Lewis said. ``But it wasn't
enough. It wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But until that moment, a Jets' victory had seemed imminent, and
it appeared to have arrived just in time for Coach Bill Parcells
and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have to say it every week _ I thought it couldn't get
any more disappointing,'' Parcells said. ``We collapsed under
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Jets have two weeks off to think about Sunday because
of a bye week, time to wonder if there is something seriously wrong
in the underpinning of a team that had every right to expect a trip
to the Super Bowl only seven Sundays ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now players will be thinking not only about the loss. Some have
been surprised by the news that the wide receivers' coach Todd
Haley has been demoted to assistant and the offensive coordinator
Charlie Weis is taking over Haley's role.
</P>
<P>
   But these types of problems are often magnified in losing.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets have a lot to magnify at the moment. From the
moment Vinny Testaverde was lost in the opening game, the Jets have
rarely demonstrated a spark on offense.
</P>
<P>
   This latest loss marks the fourth time this season they have
blown a lead in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for much of the game, Mirer (13 of 22, 158 yards) was making
third-down plays and the defense was covering the Raiders' speedy
receivers with clever schemes.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were opportunistic, too, with 13 points from three
turnovers. They got the better of the former Giant, Tyrone
Wheatley, who had found success here in silver and black. Instead,
he was knocked out of the game with a back injury following his
second fumble _ fumbles which had led to 10 Jets points.
</P>
<P>
   This was Mirer's fifth start. And, thanks to his own diving
touchdown and a John Hall field goal, the Jets led by 10-3 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy, though; Mirer seemed almost too pumped up at
first. After a while, however, he began to make plays. He had been
benched after the Monday night loss to the Jaguars, which marked
the second time in four starts he had failed to direct a touchdown
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday he quickly found Keyshawn Johnson to convert a third-down
pass. He also found Wayne Chrebet for a 34-yard pass play.
</P>
<P>
   But often, the Jets dug themselves into a hole on penalties.
They were flagged nine times, with seven accepted. They committed
three in the first quarter, including pass interference by Aaron
Glenn on Jett. Along with a 36-yard scramble by Gannon, it set up a
25-yard field goal by Michael Husted for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, mixing the run and pass well, got solid rushing from
Curtis Martin, a 28-yard reception from Johnson and tied the score
on Hall's 32-yard field goal. Martin went on to produce a 123-yard
game on 26 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense now was forcing Gannon to scramble. His
receivers were cloaked by white-jerseyed Jets. Then came the
strange series that led to a Jets' touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   From midfield, Mirer sought a sprinting Dedric Ward near the
goal line. Ward had a step on the defense, but his pass floated so
high and so long that it was easily picked off by cornerback Erie
Allen on the Raiders' 5-yard line. But on the next play, Wheatley
was hit by Jason Ferguson, the ball came loose, and Bryan Cox
recovered on the 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets immediately deployed five receivers. First, though, the
Raiders asked for a review of the Wheatley fumble. The call stood
and Mirer got back in formation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of passing, though, he took the ball and ran straight up
the middle. At the 2, he dived over the goal line for the touchdown
and a 10-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Dwight Stone, who hadn't carried the ball
since 1995, produced the Jets' longest run of the season, 36 yards.
Martin ran and caught the ball for 51 yards on the drive. Finally,
Eric Green, who had two catches for 5 yards all season, caught
another short one _ but it was a 2-yard pass from Mirer that was
good for a touchdown and a 17-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Again the Raiders began a drive that was ended by a Wheatley
fumble caused by Roman Phifer and recovered by Victor Green.
</P>
<P>
   The tackle also knocked Wheatley out of the game. He had been
the Raiders' leading rusher, but had totaled only 18 yards on eight
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Wheatley's fumble led to a 37-yard field goal by Hall. The Jets,
for only the third time this year, had produced 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders, who haven't been going deep, were forced to. So
Gannon found Tim Brown, who beat Glenn for 45-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   And then in the final period, they mounted a powerful 83-yard,
11-play drive capped by Zack Crockett's 3-yard run. The Jets lead
fell to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Glenn, the Pro Bowl cornerback, intercepted Gannon near
midfield on the next Raiders' drive. It set up another field goal
as the Jets took a 23-17 edge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
