<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-PISCATOR-NYT &LR;      10-24 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PISCATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIA PISCATOR, 101, THEATER ARTS TEACHER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ill.)  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maria Ley Piscator, a theater arts teacher and director and the
widow of the theatrical director Erwin Piscator, died on Oct. 14 at
the Jewish Home and Hospital for the Aged in Manhattan. She was
101.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Vienna, Ms. Piscator began her theatrical career as a
dancer in Berlin and Paris and later turned to choreography. She
helped stage several productions with Max Reinhardt, including his
renowned production of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   She met Piscator, her third husband, in 1936 while studying for
a doctorate in literature at the Sorbonne. The two immigrated to
the United States and founded the Dramatic Workshop at the New
School for Social Research in Manhattan. Their students included
Stella Adler, Harry Belafonte, Marlon Brando, Tony Randall and
Anthony Franciosa.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Piscator also directed theatrical productions off-Broadway
and in Europe and was the director and founder of small theater
programs in New York for the elderly, children and others. Her
teaching also included work in the 1970s at the University of
Southern Illinois at Carbondale and at the State University of New
York at Stony Brook. She began working with the Elysium Theater
Company of Munich in the 1980s and in 1993 became the honorary
artistic director of Elysium _ Between Two Continents, a
Munich-based organization devoted to cultural exchange between the
United State and Europe, particularly Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Piscator wrote books including ``The Piscator Experiment:
The Political Theater,'' which was published by James H. Heineman
in 1967, a year after her husband's death. Her autobiography,
``Mirror People,'' was published in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
