<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: DUTCH ART IN CLEVELAND; GERMAN ART IN WASHINGTON;
NEW MUSIC IN NEW YORK; BELLINI'S CAPULETS AND MONTAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 16th and 17th centuries, when the riches and power of the
Netherlands put the country at the forefront of the Western world,
its great artists turned their talents to ``stilleven,'' or ``not
moving materials,'' known in English as still lifes.
</P>
<P>
   Vibrant flowers, tantalizing fruit and sumptuous banquets,
sometimes rendered in almost microscopic detail, became the
subjects of artists like Rembrandt, Samuel van Hoogstraten and
Joseph de Bray.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Sunday, 70 of these paintings are to go on view at
the Cleveland Museum of Art in ``Still-Life Paintings From the
Netherlands, 1550-1720.'' Assembled from more than 50 museums and
private collections, the exhibition will continue through Jan. 9.
Information: (888) 262-0033 or (216) 421-7350.
</P>
<P>
   Masters' Touch
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the late 15th century, many of the best artists of
Germany and Switzerland expressed themselves most powerfully and
completely through their drawings.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday nearly 200 master drawings and watercolors by these
artists went on display in the West Building of the National
Gallery of Art in Washington. ``From Schongauer to Holbein: Master
Drawings From Basel and Berlin,'' reflecting the artists'
development, style and variety of subject, also includes works by
artists like Albrecht Duerer and Lucas Cranach the Elder. It runs
through Jan. 9. Information: (202) 737-4215.
</P>
<P>
   Musical World Tour
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New music from around the world will be featured in
six piano recitals to be presented under the collective title
``Solo Flights 99'' on three consecutive nights, beginning at 7 on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Presented by the Composers Collaborative at Here, the arts
center at 145 Ave. of the Americas, the opening program features
Claudia Ruegg of Switzerland in works by Lois V. Vierk, Justine
Chen and Kaspar Ewald, followed at 9 by Beatriz Roman of Brazil in
works by Gilberto Mendes, Sorell Hays and Coelho de Souza.
Information: (212) 647-0202.
</P>
<P>
   At It Again
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The families better known as the Capulets and the
Montagues will be at each other's throats once more on Monday night
at 8 at Avery Fisher Hall, but the drama is not Shakespeare's. The
vehicle is ``I Capuleti e i Montecchi,'' the Vincenzo Bellini
opera. This is the season-opening concert performance by the Opera
Orchestra of New York. Information: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
</TEXT>
