<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-49ERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INEXPLICABLY, VIKINGS LOOK LIKE GEORGE'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 (ms) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The oddness of this strange, quirky season, in
which the traditionally good teams are bad and the bad teams are
good, crystallized perfectly at the Metrodome on Sunday. This
simple statement sums it all up: Quarterback Jeff George saved the
Minnesota Vikings from falling into the abyss by leading his team
past San Francisco, 40-16.
</P>
<P>
   There are head coaches who would rather eat their playbooks than
accept that George is capable of saving any team. He is known as
selfish, arrogant and, oh yeah, ditzy. Especially ditzy.
</P>
<P>
   But talented is a word that also describes George, mainly
because he can flick a pass on a dime 50 yards with little effort.
That arm strength helped to put a little cockiness back into the
Vikings' offensive step, something that had been missing all season
with Randall Cunningham as the starter.
</P>
<P>
   How long their success will last is unknown. Even though the
Vikings' 40 points was the most they have scored this season (their
previous high was 23 against Detroit) it was against the 49ers, who
have the league's 30th-ranked defense. Still, Minnesota, thanks to
George, may be at the beginning of a serious run that would put
them back in playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way our offense is supposed to be,'' said wide
receiver Randy Moss, who had only one catch for 24 yards because of
the 49ers' double- and triple-teaming. ``It's just a start, but it
was good. The last couple of weeks, we've struggled.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers were the cure. That team no longer resembles the
proud, brilliant franchise that dominated football over the past
two decades. Instead, they are a confused, aging and injury-riddled
group. Minnesota totaled 395 yards, averaged 6.6 yards a play and
outhustled the 49ers, part of the reason why San Francisco had 15
penalties for 104 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings were able to pick on San Francisco's secondary,
maybe the most porous in the league. The 49ers concentrated on
stopping Moss, but unlike in the recent past, the Vikings were able
to take advantage of that single-mindedness. Cris Carter (7 catches
for 84 yards), Jake Reed (3 for 42) and Matthew Hatchette (2 for
88) combined for 12 catches for 214 yards and 2 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   This is where George is more effective than Cunningham. George
is better at finding where a speedy receiver is single-covered.
Sometimes the coaches often literally told Cunningham where to
throw the ball before the play.
</P>
<P>
   That difference was apparent in the second quarter. Minnesota
trailed, 10-7, after a Leroy Hoard fumble was returned 71 yards for
a touchdown by San Francisco cornerback Darnell Walker. On the
first play of the Vikings' next offensive series, George saw
immediately that Hatchette was single-covered by Walker on the left
sideline. He let Hatchette outrun Walker and threw a deep strike
for an 80-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it was a perfect throw,'' Green said. ``It was,
`run with the safety.' And no one had help because they were
working to stop plays towards Randy's side. It was a perfect strike
right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter Wade Richey made a 26-yard field goal to
pull the 49ers to 24-16. But George, working mostly from the
shotgun, again picked apart the secondary. The final play of that
drive was a 9-yard run up the gut by Moe Williams, who scored
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   Many 49ers were puzzled to explain how they stumbled into their
troubling 3-4 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never dealt with a situation like this,'' said Jerry
Rice, the all-universe receiver, ``but I think if we were able to
come out of this it will make everything even sweeter, going
through all of this and still somehow finding a way to win and make
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings are thinking the exact same thing. Only now, with
the strong-armed George at quarterback, they have a much more
realistic chance of doing it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
