<HEADLINE>
FISHER CONTENT WITH ROLE IN NEW OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ It seems this short message isn't getting
through to Derek Fisher, not that he hasn't heard the refrain
enough.
</P>
<P>
   People keep saying how new Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson
likes to have tall guards on the floor in his vaunted triangle
offense, particularly in the starting lineup. Fisher stretches in
at 6-foot-1.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher knows Jackson also used plenty of smaller guards
while in Chicago _ guys like B.J. Armstrong, Steve Kerr and John
Paxon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys made huge contributions,'' Fisher said. ``The only
thing you can control is your play. You can't really get into who
the coach is going to play, who he likes. You definitely have to do
what the coach wants on the floor, but don't worry so much about
who they want you to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go out there and play and have confidence in yourself. That's
what I've been trying to concentrate on. I can't grow to 6-4 all of
a sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher believes the new offense might actually be helping his
play. Certainly, he looked like he belonged Sunday afternoon in the
Lakers' 97-79 exhibition victory over the Miami Heat at the
Centennial Garden. In 23 minutes, he contributed 13 points, five
rebounds, two assists and two steals.
</P>
<P>
   With the trade of Nick Van Exel last season, Fisher was expected
to give the Lakers leadership at point guard in just his third
season. And often, Fisher looked like a young player trying to
provide leadership. But as the 1999-2000 season opener draws near,
Fisher looks like a guard playing more naturally. Fisher credits
simply being more comfortable as a player and running a
team-orientated offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't give us a lot of rules or say, `You can shoot, you
can't shoot, we want to give this guy the ball more than you,''' he
said. ``It's an offense where everybody shares the basketball and
the guy who is open can take the shot. It's really done wonders for
me as far as my confidence level.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, I always felt like there was a glass ceiling over
what the coaches wanted me to do out on the floor. My priorities
were to allow everybody else to play, then if I get a chance, then
play. Now I feel like the coaches are OK with me going out and
displaying my abilities within the framework of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Tex Winter said the Lakers won't restrict Fisher
because of his size.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what Derek is,'' Winter said. ``He's a fine NBA guard,
but he's certainly not the exceptional guard at this point. He'll
be a great complementary player for us. We're not worried about
him. He'll fit in very nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Forward Robert Horry sat out Sunday's game with his sore
left knee and is expected to miss exhibition games tonight in
Albuquerque and Tuesday in Las Vegas. Horry, bothered by tendinitis
in both knees, said he felt the knee lock up in Friday's game
against the Suns. It's the same knee Horry injured three years ago
when he first came to the Lakers. Said Horry: ``It's never really
been the same since. It's a lot looser than it's supposed to be.''
Jackson said it was not serious: ``I've been assured he'll be
fine.'' ... Shaquille O'Neal, always up for going against Alonzo
Mourning, led the Lakers with 14 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
