<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MODERNIZING MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Oct. 25:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee voted last week to put off
consideration of legislative measures that would give Medicare the
same tools that private health insurers commonly use to control
costs and the quality of care. That probably means that debate on
this crucial issue will be delayed to next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had proposed a comprehensive plan to
improve Medicare, including a new prescription-drug benefit. Unless
Congress acts, Medicare will not have the flexibility to create new
choices of coverage for beneficiaries that will help reduce costs,
for them and for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1997 Balanced Budget Act, Congress greatly expanded
the ability of Medicare enrollees to join health maintenance
organizations. In three years the number of beneficiaries in HMOs
has doubled, to 7 million _ about 18 percent of the entire Medicare
population _ largely because HMOs can offer lower deductibles and
co-payments, more preventive care and drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Medicare still functions under the traditional
fee-for-service approach that is rapidly disappearing in the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of Medicare HMOs has been a significant step
forward in modernizing the program. But up to now, Medicare has not
been able to offer beneficiaries much access to preferred provider
networks, the dominant form of managed care now in the private
marketplace. These networks, usually called preferred provider
organizations, or PPOs, have become so popular that they surpass
HMOs in number of enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   PPOs are less restrictive than HMOs because they typically
eliminate gatekeeping functions that prevent patients from seeing
specialists and generally allow patients to see doctors outside the
network for a higher fee. PPOs control costs by negotiating lower
fees with doctors who want to be part of the PPO panel and
selecting doctors who have a record of providing good-quality,
cost-effective care.
</P>
<P>
   Patients gain by paying lower out-of-pocket costs if they choose
a preferred provider. With the private sector moving to this
managed-care hybrid, Medicare enrollees should be allowed the same
cost-saving option.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also wants to offer special payment rates to
competitively selected hospitals that have demonstrated expertise
in complex medical procedures. Beneficiaries would not have to go
to these centers, but they could be offered lower cost-sharing and
other benefits if they do. The designated centers would benefit by
being able to increase their market share in certain procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures would increase Medicare's use of competitive
bidding in purchasing goods and services, and establish a voluntary
case management plan for beneficiaries in fee-for-service Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and hospital groups are nervous about giving Medicare
any ability to pick and choose among providers. But ultimately,
these strategies will give patients new incentive to select
cost-effective care. The private sector has adopted these
approaches. It is time that Medicare caught up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-CHILDCARE-765&AMP;ADD-     10-24 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILDCARE-765&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD-CARE FUNDS GOING UNSPENT IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When New York state's new budget was passed in
August, it appeared to throw an $800 million lifeline to New York's
low- and moderate-income parents, roughly doubling the amount of
money previously available to them to pay for child care.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, anyway, that money is no more than a promise. Tens
of thousands of New Yorkers who need subsidized child care are
unable to find it, advocates for the poor say, and providers of
such services have long waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   More state money, the advocates contend, will make little
difference as long as there are too few places to spend it in.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, though, the state has no detailed plan for getting
the new money into the hands of low- and moderate-income parents.
Instead, it will simply give the money to local governments,
leaving crucial details, like deciding who is eligible for the
money, to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are glad to have the additional money, we are very
concerned that parents who need help with the cost of child care
may never get it,'' said David Hunt, executive director of the New
York State Child Care Coordinating Council. ``There's all this
money, but it doesn't appear to be getting into the hands of
parents who need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in fact, under a far smaller program to give
child-care subsidies to parents, the state was unable to spend much
of the money that it had devoted to that purpose. To date, roughly
$75 million remains from last year's $406 million allocation for
child care, state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The state's inability to spend its child-care money is
apparently not a result of a lack of need. A recent study by the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services found that 82 percent
of the New York families eligible for government-subsidized child
care were not receiving it. Nationally, the figure was even higher.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason that the money has not been spent in New York,
advocates for the poor and some government officials agree, is that
there are not nearly enough day-care providers to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   New York City was one of the few localities to spend all of its
allocation _ more than half the statewide total of child-care money
_ in the last fiscal year, yet even there, day-care providers had
waiting lists totaling between 35,000 and 40,000 people, according
to public and private estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The severe shortage of licensed day-care slots in New York,
experts say, is aggravated by efforts undertaken by local
governments, most notably New York City, to require parents on
welfare, most of them single mothers, to work for their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the state comptroller, Carl McCall, has estimated
that an additional 109,000 children will need day care by 2001,
largely as a result of workfare.
</P>
<P>
   There are other causes for the state's failure to spend the
money. The advocates say many local governments have not focused on
the issue, grappling instead with other pressing and complicated
aspects of the continuing national effort to overhaul the welfare
system, like reducing the public assistance rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates go so far as to say that many counties do not
care about providing day care. Just as important, though, many poor
families are unaware that subsidized day care is available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Parents now receive subsidized day care in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   The most common is to have their children placed in day-care
programs that receive direct government payments.
</P>
<P>
   The other method involves parents receiving vouchers, which they
then give to providers as payment. Depending on local guidelines,
eligible providers can range from state-licensed centers to
relatives, neighbors and baby sitters, as long as they meet minimal
health and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to gauge the disparity between supply and demand
in New York's child-care system with complete certainty. In part,
that is because no one agency keeps track of how many people
actually need affordable child care, or how many providers of the
service exist, experts on child care say.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is known: About 881,000 children are eligible for
subsidized child care in New York under the federal eligibility
guidelines, though only 158,000 children, or 18 percent, receive
such care. The number of children eligible under the state's
eligibility standards, which are stricter than federal standards,
is 631,000, meaning that about 25 percent are actually receiving
subsidized care.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, large numbers of children are not getting the
subsidies they are eligible to receive, child-care experts say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the same time, only 485,000 day-care slots are being provided
by state-licensed operators. While they acknowledge New York's
shortage of licensed day-care slots, some state officials say the
gap is being filled by informal providers of child care, like
relatives and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But even these officials concede that they have no idea how many
informal providers operate in the state. Just as important,
advocates say informal providers are often unreliable and cannot
take the place of professionally licensed child-care operators.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some state officials assert that it is not the
state's obligation to build and operate day-care slots. Rather,
they say that the state should provide subsidies to people who need
them and that this in turn will create a demand for child care that
providers will try to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Terry McGrath, a spokesman for the state's Office of Children
and Family Services, pointed out that state expenditures on
child-care subsidies have increased to roughly $800 million this
year from $269 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he said, the number of children in
government-subsidized child care has risen to 138,000 this year
from 76,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath noted that the money allocated this year should provide
subsidies for an additional 40,000 children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-24-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991024.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
