u a BC-OBIT-DIAMOND-NYT &LR;      10-24 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DIAMOND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGMUND DIAMOND, PROFESSOR WHO INVESTIGATED THE FBI, DIES AT 79
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Fla., Md.)  (jw) 
 By ERIC PACE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sigmund Diamond, a Columbia professor of sociology and history
who studied American business titans, female industrial workers and
FBI information gathering, died on Oct. 14 in Norwich, Conn. He was
79 and lived in Salem, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was esophageal cancer, said his wife, Shirley.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond began his career at Columbia in 1955 and retired in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Compromised Campus: The Collaboration of
Universities With the Intelligence Community, 1945-1955,'' Diamond
wrote about the FBI's attempt to gather information from university
employees. In The New York Times Book Review, Herbert Mitgang wrote
that the book asserted that for at least 10 years after World War
II, J. Edgar Hoover's agents ``enlisted administrators and
professors and planted them as subagents in place.'' Diamond said
in the book that those university officials and teachers were
prepared to give the FBI information on coworkers they thought were
disloyal to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier book, ``Reputation of the American Businessman,''
published in 1955, Diamond chronicled titans like John Jacob Astor,
Cornelius Vanderbilt, J.P. Morgan and John D. Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond worked for the United Auto Workers during the 1940s,
compiling reports about women who worked during the war and what
happened to them after it ended. The report found that by early
1945, women who had been laid off were having trouble returning to
work, partly because of prejudice. While he a UAW staff member,
Diamond advocated that women get equal pay for equal work.
</P>
<P>
   During his time at Columbia, Diamond founded and headed the
history department's social history program and was a consultant
for an American Jewish Committee oral history project about the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond was born in Baltimore and received a bachelor's degree
from Johns Hopkins University in 1940 and a doctorate in American
history from Harvard in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   He said he suffered for his political beliefs before teaching at
Columbia. According to a 1977 article in Newsweek, he said he had
been a Communist Party member from 1941 to 1950. After leaving the
party, he said, he was turned down for a job as a part-time
lecturer in history at Harvard because he had refused, under
pressure from McGeorge Bundy, who was then a Harvard dean, to
identify other former party members.
</P>
<P>
   Bundy said in 1977 that he had opposed hiring Diamond partly
because he thought that Harvard's governing board ``would not want
an ex-Communist with these attitudes in any administrative job.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Diamond is survived by a daughter,
Betty Ann Diamond of the Bronx; a son, Stephen, of Coral Gables,
Fla.; four granddaughters, and two brothers, William of Washington
and Alvin of Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
