<SLUG> BC-GLF-RENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS FIRST IN 19 YEARS TO ACHIEVE 6 TOUR VICTORIES IN YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Instead of being spoiled by success,
Tiger Woods seems motivated by it.
</P>
<P>
   As darkness fell Saturday night after the third round of the
National Carl Rental Golf Classic, Woods was on the driving range
hitting golf balls until he could no longer see where they landed.
He remains hungry, driven to improve, driven to win, despite being
the world's No. 1-ranked player.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how much better Woods can get, how much
more distance he can put between himself and his peers. But Sunday
he added another victory to his growing collection, finding a way
to win when he was not at the top of his game. He became the first
player to win six times in a season on the PGA Tour since Tom
Watson won six times in 1980. And at age 23, the best for Woods may
be yet to come, a chilling thought for the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming early troubles and avoiding mistakes on the back
nine, Woods held on to win at Walt Disney World Resort by one
stroke over Ernie Els, who shot a 71 Sunday. Woods shot a
one-over-par 73 Sunday to finish 17 under par for the tournament at
271. Three strokes behind Woods were Bob Tway and Franklin Langham,
who tied for third.
</P>
<P>
   Woods continued a remarkable year _ he has won seven times
worldwide, including once in Germany _ that some of his peers are
having difficulty putting into context. After challenging Woods,
but failing to beat him, Els did not bite his tongue when asked to
evaluate Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is 23 years old, and he's already this good,'' said
Els, a two-time United States Open winner. ``There can't be anybody
in the world who hits the ball that pure. It's unbelievably long
and straight. Nobody can touch this guy at the moment. He has gone
to a level where I don't think the rest of us can really find right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods earned $450,000 Sunday to surpass $4.71 million for the
season, a tour record. He is almost $1.2 million ahead of David
Duval, who is No. 2 on the money list. And with next week's Tour
Championship and the World Golf Championship event in Spain left to
play, Woods could become the first player in tour history to
surpass $5 million or $6 million in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won six times in his last nine starts, including the
PGA Championship. By refining his swing and improving his short
game, Woods has matured into a player who can win with power, with
finesse or with his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Is Woods anywhere near his peak? He would rather not think in
those terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put any kind of limit to where I think I can
go,'' said Woods, who has won 13 times on the tour in 68 starts.
``I believe I can win golf tournaments. I take a lot of pride in
what I do. I love to practice more than I like to play. It's hard
to get complacent when you love to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Woods and the rest of the field faced a challenging
Magnolia Course with greens much firmer than they had been during
the first three days of the tournament. Starting the day tied with
Tway at 18 under par, Woods fell two strokes behind with three-putt
bogeys at Nos. 6 and
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens were just incredibly fast,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods adjusted. He made a 10-foot birdie putt at No. 10 to
get within one stroke of Tway, then hit a beautiful 9-iron approach
shot at No. 11 within 3 feet of the hole, setting up another birdie
to tie Tway.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tway self-destructed with a triple-bogey at the par-3 No.
12, hitting his tee shot into the water and his second tee shot
into a bunker. That left Els, playing a group ahead of Woods, as
the last pursuer with a realistic chance to win. But Els made two
crucial mistakes at No.s 14 and 17. Tied with Woods at 18 under
par, Els bogeyed No. 14 after hitting a terrible 5-iron shot into
the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the worst swing of the year there,'' Els said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods made another three-putt bogey at No. 14 to fall back into
a tie with Els, but Els bogeyed the par-4 No. 17 after hitting his
second shot onto the worst possible part of the green, the left
side. He was left with a 35-foot putt straight downhill that was
impossible to stop close to the hole if he missed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was done when I was lining up my putt, `' Els said.
``I was going to three-putt.'
</P>
<P>
   Els was right. His first putt raced 12 feet past the hole, and
then he missed the uphill putt that would have saved par. The bogey
gave Woods his one-stroke lead again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year,'' Woods said. ``When I was in junior
golf, I thought I could never love the game as much as I did then.
But I can honestly say I love it more.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
