<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELMONT REPORTS DECLINES IN ATTENDANCE AND WAGERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Belmont Park ran its final races of the season
Sunday before giving way to Aqueduct for the next six and a half
months, and reported that its average attendance for the 32-day
autumn meeting had dropped by 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The final Belmont meeting produced mixed results, somewhat in
keeping with the trends in recent racing. Attendance dropped to an
average of 6,757 a day, but the total betting handle rose by 14.6
percent, to an average of $10.3 million a day, for the 32 days
since Saratoga ended its summertime run and the horses returned to
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   One day of racing was lost because of Tropical Storm Floyd, but
the betting totals probably reflected the spread of simulcast
betting to and from other outlets. However, on-track betting
slipped with the attendance by 3.3 percent, to an average of $1.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with the total handle,'' said Terry
Meyocks, president of the New York Racing Association. ``Meanwhile,
we would have hoped for a better meet on track, so naturally we're
disappointed. But with the weather not on our side, it took its
toll. Also, when you add in all the competition for the attention
of the New York sports fan this fall, it makes it even more
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't let a 32-day period dampen our enthusiasm. We've been
very fortunate, and the weather was on our side this year until
now. We had a very high-quality stakes program this fall, and
hopefully a lot of the horses that competed in this year's fall
championship meet will do well in the Breeders' Cup and in Eclipse
award balloting.''
</P>
<P>
   For the short autumn season at Belmont, the leading jockey was
Jorge Chavez and the leading trainer was John Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont gave a dramatic farewell with a pair of $100,000 stakes
on the turf for 2-year-old horses. In the Miss Grillo Stakes, Gary
Contessa's Wolf Alert outdueled Windsong by the length of her nose
with Jerry Bailey riding. In the Pilgrim, it was John Campo Jr.'s
29-1 long shot Kachemak Bay, with John Velazquez riding, running
down Bailey and the favored King Cugat in the final strides.
</P>
<P>
   New York racing will be staged at the Aqueduct track starting
Wednesday at 12:30 p.m. and carrying on until Belmont opens next
May. This will be the 40th anniversary of racing at Aqueduct, and
the track will mark some history of its own with an opening-day
feature, the Discovery Handicap, a race that was won during its
eventful past by superstars such as Kelso and Forego.
</P>
<P>
   The fall portion of the Aqueduct meeting will run through Dec.
31, with no racing generally on Mondays and Tuesdays. The track was
originally built in 1894 but was reopened in 1959 before a crowd of
42,473. The most noticeable improvement installed since last spring
is a $4 million paddock, which replaces the old underground
facility and gives fans a clear view of the horses as they are
being saddled. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
