u s BC-FBC-DRAPE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-24 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DRAPE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DADGUM IT, FLORIDA STATE STILL STRUGGLES WITH
WARRICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON, S.C. _ Who would have thought that the man who has
returned the expression ``dadgum'' back to metropolitan sports
pages and national airwaves would believe in something as cosmic as
karma? But there was Bobby Bowden, a homey 69-year-old, suggesting
just that after a milestone 300th victory captured in a historic
coaching confrontation with his second son, Tommy.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden didn't invoke it to explain how his Florida State
team outlasted Clemson by 17-14 Saturday night. Or why his son, of
all people, ended up on the opposite sideline on the night he was
trying to join Joe Paterno, Bear Bryant, Amos Alonzo Stagg and Pop
Warner in the record books.
</P>
<P>
   No, Bowden reached for the notion of
what-goes-around-comes-around justice to describe the performance
of his prodigal wide receiver, Peter Warrick. The senior rejoined
the Seminoles here Saturday after a two-week suspension that was
lifted when he pleaded to a misdemeanor count of petty theft on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, the team had been caught up in a saga that
began with Warrick's felony charge for accepting an illegal
discount on designer clothes _ getting more than $400 worth of
clothes for $21.40 _ and ended with Warrick, the president of the
university, a state legislator and countless Florida State fans
looking, well, foolish.
</P>
<P>
   The whole mess detracted from the Bowden family's big night and
the family patriarch appeared to understand that. He wasn't bitter.
He acknowledged that the distractions of the Warrick situation
spilled over to his star receiver's performance and he was was not
that sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick caught 11 passes for 121 yards, but dropped a couple of
big ones and seemed rattled by the boos and ``jailbird'' chants
that followed him throughout the game. Bowden said flatly that
Warrick dropped some passes that could have won the game earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen Pete play like that since he was a freshman,
and maybe that is the way it should be,'' Bowden said, tipping his
hat to karma.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick wasn't talking afterward. Bowden put the blame squarely
on Warrick. But from the beginning, Bowden said he believed that
this was a minor offense and he wanted Warrick back on the field.
When it first broke, he said he ``was praying for a misdemeanor''
settlement. When he got it on Friday, the coach called it ``a
miracle from above.'' On Saturday, he proclaimed the settlement _
which includes one year probation, 300 hours of community service,
$579 in restitution and $295 in court costs _ was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got drug addicts that we let out of jail,'' Bowden said.
``The kid is trying to get an education. He's going to dadgum
graduate and some want to hang him. I say you punish him and let
him go become a citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   But that message was terribly diluted by the uproar that
preceded the settlement in Florida last week. It began with
Warrick's lawyer, John Kenny, offering state attorneys a deal (not
a very good one for his client) where the receiver would serve jail
time in the spring in exchange for a reduced charge.
</P>
<P>
   When Florida State University President Talbot ``Sandy''
D'Alemberte said he would not allow Warrick to rejoin the team now
and serve time later, there was an outcry from some boosters and
alumni _ including state Sen. Jim King who sent a letter to the
university president criticizing his handling of the Warrick
matter.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alemberte cut short a trip to Barbados and, on his return, was
reportedly the target of 600 e-mails, many of them hostile and
accusing him of everything from grandstanding to embarrassing the
athletic department. To counter charges that he failed to
communicate the university's policy to the athletic department, he
released a copy of an Oct. 11 e-mail to Athletic Director Dave
Hart.
</P>
<P>
   In it D'Alemberte wrote: ``Please caution Bobby about raising
expectations too high for Peter Warrick's return. I have an open
mind but I am inclined to think that Warrick must not only
negotiate a plea bargain but also get all contact with the criminal
justice system behind him (including any community service or other
sentence handed down).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Saturday, Warrick was back as a starter, guilty of a
misdemeanor and facing community service in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Those aren't exactly the ideal circumstances for a proud
institution of higher education or an accomplished coach to salute
a successful football program or celebrate an impressive career
milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, the season's first Bowl Championship Series ranking
will be released and Florida State (8-0, No. 2 behind Penn State in
the New York Times computer ranking and No. 1 in the ESPN/USA Today
and Associated Press polls) will likely hold the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS rankings factor in the news media and coaches' polls,
eight computer rankings (including The New York Times') and
strength of schedule to come up with the Nos. 1 and 2 teams to
ensure that they play each other in the national title game in the
Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking does not matter until the end of the season when the
nation's two best teams will show themselves. But with four games
left and his team not playing well, coach Bowden has got plenty of
reasons to be aware of that dadgum karma. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
