<SLUG> BC-CONN-ROWLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT GOVERNOR'S FUND-RAISERS SCRUTINIZED
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ They were the nation's youngest governor and
the nation's youngest state treasurer, glad-handing contributors
eager to be associated with a popular administration.
</P>
<P>
   At fund-raising receptions in New York and the posh suburbs of
Hartford as he geared up for last year's re-election race, Gov.
John Rowland of Connecticut sipped drinks and shook hands with
representatives of funds that had just received _ or were about to
receive _ investments of state pension money.
</P>
<P>
   The receptions seemed routine at the time, but they are now
being scrutinized by federal and state investigators. The parties
were organized by Paul Silvester, whom Rowland appointed as state
treasurer when the incumbent resigned. Silvester pleaded guilty
last month to racketeering and money laundering during his 17
months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Silvester, 37, who left office in January after losing an
election and now faces up to six years in prison, admitted cooking
up an ambitious scheme to enrich himself, his relatives and his
friends through the placement of state pension funds, and is now
freely talking to investigators about who else was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, 42, said he knew almost nothing about the fund-raisers
and who was giving them. He has adamantly denied any wrongdoing and
has said that Silvester betrayed him just as he betrayed the other
citizens of the state.
</P>
<P>
   But as what is likely to be a long, ugly scandal begins to play
out, the overriding question is whether prosecutors have built a
tight case against one greedy former officeholder, or whether they
have found the thread that could unravel the state's political
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   No one has more on the line than Rowland, who was Silvester's
political patron. It remains unclear whether the investigation will
find that Rowland did anything illegal as he engaged in the
aggressive fund raising that is now being closely scrutinized. But
at the least, the governor runs the risk of his administration's
being darkened _ and perhaps defined _ by scandal, and his judgment
is sure to be called into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connecticut has remnants of old machine politics, but it was
always done with a wink and a nod, with self-imposed limits,'' said
Scott McLean, a political science professor at Quinnipiac College.
``This was on a grand scale, with rich New Yorkers helping to
manipulate state investments. Whether he personally did anything
wrong or not, the rest of Rowland's term is going to be a
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a plea bargain, Silvester was to receive four to six years
in prison. But his sentencing was not set until March 20, and
prosecutors said he could reduce his sentence by giving information
about other possible crimes. Lawyers involved in the investigation
said Silvester had provided voluminous information about possible
illegal activity by politicians in both parties, several of whom
were showered with ``finders' fees'' that Silvester demanded in
return for investment of state pension money.
</P>
<P>
   Silvester has contended that lobbyists acting as intermediaries
for Rowland pressured him to invest more than $100 million with
fund managers who had promised payments to allies of the governor,
or had made contributions to his campaign. Rowland has repeatedly
denied any wrongdoing, and simply making investment recommendations
would not be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has said that Silvester's statements are lies from a
criminal seeking to curry favor with prosecutors. ``Frankly, he'll
pretty much say anything to have his sentence reduced,'' the
governor told reporters earlier this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
