<HEADER>
A7000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANUCKS-N     10-24 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' SCORELESS STRING REACHES THREE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time the New York Rangers had been shut out
in three consecutive games, Harry S. Truman was president. That was
Oct. 19, 21 and 22, 1950 _ at the beginning of some of the bleakest
years in team history.
</P>
<P>
   Those Rangers did not make the playoffs in five straight
seasons. These Rangers are at two and counting. And Sunday night at
Madison Square Garden, these Rangers were blanked for the third
consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was by 3-0, to the Vancouver Canucks and their
24-year-old goaltender, Kevin Weekes, who stopped 19 shots for his
first National Hockey League shutout. He has defeated the Rangers
twice this season after entering it without a victory in 15 NHL
games.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Schaefer scored the first two goals as the Canucks handed
the Rangers their fourth consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 234 minutes 31 seconds _ nearly four hours _ since
the Rangers' last goal. They have not scored since 5:29 of the
first period on Tuesday night in a 2-1 loss at the Garden to San
Jose. The Rangers lost in Philadelphia, 5-0, on Wednesday night and
again to the Flyers, 2-0, on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Messier, the former Rangers captain, scored his 613th
career goal into an empty net, tying him with Mario Lemieux for
sixth in NHL history. And that brought some of the biggest cheers
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Messier, who led the Rangers to their first Stanley Cup in 54
years in 1994, was making his third trip back to the Garden as a
member of the Canucks. It was obvious he was still a fan favorite.
Messier jerseys could be spotted throughout the stands, and there
was a loud ovation for No. 11 when he was introduced before the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Could it have been the 38-year-old center's final trip to the
Garden? Doubtful. Messier is in the final guaranteed year of the
three-year contract he signed with Vancouver. But Messier said
before the game that he was optimistic about the progress that the
rebuilding Canucks had made this season. And regardless whether the
Canucks pick up his option, Messier said he wanted to play
somewhere after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Messier said it was difficult coming back to the Garden
to play. Both he and Wayne Gretzky had said the same thing about
playing in Edmonton earlier this month, as the Oilers prepared to
retire Gretzky's number against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially tough playing against all the guys I spent a
lot of time with here,'' Messier said, referring especially to Adam
Graves, Mike Richter and Brian Leetch. ``I never got used to
playing against Wayne. And I feel the same way about Gravy, Ricky,
Leetchie and all the guys that were really soldiers for me when I
was here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the guys who believed in me and what we were trying
to do and were the sole reason we won the cup here. So when you
experience something like that with players, it's hard to compete
against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Leetch, Graves and Richter, however, only Darren
Langdon remains on the Rangers from the Messier era. The Rangers
have not made the playoffs since Messier left as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their revamped lineup and their N.H.L.-record $58.8
million payroll, the Rangers have struggled offensively this season
without Gretzky quarterbacking their power play. After going 0 for
4 on the power play Sundayl night, the Rangers are 4 for 55 this
season, easily the worst in the league. Over their last seven
games, the Rangers are 1 for 27.
</P>
<P>
   To add insult, the Canucks scored the game's first goal while
the Rangers had the man advantage. Schaefer scored it for the
Canucks _ who swept the two-game season series with the Rangers _
at 16:50 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Mathieu Schneider had jumped into the play along the right-wing
boards in the Canucks' zone, but when he could not pinch the puck
in along the boards, it freed Vancouver for an odd-man rush.
Schaefer finished it with a wrist shot from the right circle that
clanged off the post and into the net's top right corner.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could not even muster a shot in the second period
until more than 15 minutes had been played. By then, the only other
cheers came each time the scoreboard flashed a Yankees run in the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   And when Weekes made a miracle save on Theo Fleury with just
over 13 minutes left in the final period _ Weekes, lying on his
stomach, reached up to glove the shot _ Fleury could not even break
his stick over the boards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
