A7008 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN     10-24 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S COLLECTIVE SLUMP SIMILAR TO '96
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC freshman wide receiver Kareem Kelly turned on
the TV in his hotel room Saturday morning and became intrigued by
what he heard on a college football pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said (Florida State coach) Bobby Bowden hasn't lost more
than two games in one season since '88,'' Kelly said. ``I thought
that could be us in a couple years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, youthful optimism. Kelly has done everything possible to
help USC this season, already setting two freshman records for
receptions and yards. But not even his efforts are enough to lift
the Trojans out of their current malaise.
</P>
<P>
   People might feel like Saturday's 35-31 loss to Stanford was
deja vu, the second straight week USC blew a 21-point lead. But
this season is really a re-occurrence of 1996. The Trojans have
lost three consecutive games for the first time since '96, and the
program seems in similar shape.
</P>
<P>
   Just like three years ago, there really isn't one person who can
be blamed for the misfortunes but rather a collective slump that
has engulfed the team. Whether it's the defense or the offense's
fault, it doesn't really matter. You just seem to know USC will not
protect its lead. Or make a sufficient comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone will play hard, but plays will not be made. It's about
performance, not blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of heart. We don't know what's going
wrong,'' free safety David Gibson said. ``We've reached deep.
Things are just not going our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither on nor off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this week had a sour taste just as it got
started, when Trojans coach Paul Hackett singled out his seniors
and upperclassmen for their inconsistent play. That's one thing
that certainly didn't happen in '96.
</P>
<P>
   It grew worse in midweek, when Hackett gathered the seniors
together and scolded them for not accomplishing anything their
first three years. This is hardly the stuff that inspires the
troops to turn in a morale-boosting victory.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost predict that USC would find a way to fall
apart, with the mixed messages that were being sent during the
week.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Trojans are on the verge of missing a bowl for the third
time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   USC needs to win four of its final five games just to be
considered for a bowl berth. The Trojans' schedule is supposed to
be easier in the second half, but nearly everyone assumed before
the season that USC would beat Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, one day we'll get it together, but we have to start
very soon because we don't have many games left,'' linebacker
Markus Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   USC (3-4, 1-3) is facing real stress this week as it prepares to
go to Cal. The Trojans could easily pack it in and have a season of
disastrous proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of pressure on us,'' Kelly said. ``I can handle
it, but can everybody else is the question?''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be USC's real problem. Individually, each player
thinks he can do the job. It's just when the team as a whole is
considered that a lack of confidence becomes an issue. It better be
addressed soon, or USC will be taking the month of December off.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward (left hamstring) and offensive
guard Faasea Mailo are listed as probable against Cal. Linebacker
Markus Steele (ankle) and linebacker Troy Polamalu (concussion) are
listed as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
