</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-FILM (Hollywood) _ ``The Omega Code,'' a
Christian-themed film, becomes a surprise hit. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   PREDICTORS-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt
reviews ``The Predictors,'' by Thomas A. Base (Holt).
</P>
<P>
   TIME-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Anita Gates reviews Fox's ``Time of
Your Life,'' which premieres Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   GATES-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Walter Goodman reviews ``Wonders of
the African World with Henry Louis Gates Jr.'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FISCAL-POLICY _ All the arguing over the budget is camouflage
around a striking new feature of federal fiscal policy: most of the
prospective surpluses are going to go to paying off the
$5.5-trillion debt. It's almost a political accident, but it has
huge repercussions. Indeed, it's the most fundamental development
in fiscal policy of the past decade, dramatically reshaping
economic policy with hardly any explicit and substantive debate. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDICARE-DRUGS President Clinton is opening a new attack
on the drug industry, saying that drug companies are charging too
much and have grossly misrepresented his proposal to offer drug
coverage to all Medicare beneficiaries, White House officials said
Sunday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
