<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-N     10-24 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 2: YANKEES DEFEAT BRAVES, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos _ NYT22-37 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves juggled their lineup for Game 2 of
the World Series on Sunday night hoping for more offense. What they
got, as a result, was terrible defense and very little offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had no trouble scoring runs on Sunday night, but the
Braves gave them more, anyway, and by thrashing Atlanta, 7-2, the
Yankees now are poised for a World Series wipeout. They lead by two
games to none, as the series shifts back to New York for the next
three games _ or two, if the Braves can't avoid the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta managed just one hit against the Yankees' David Cone on
Sunday night, and has accumulated seven hits and three runs in the
first two games of the series, batting 7 for 58 (.121)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will be Manager Joe Torre, or outfielder Paul O'Neill,
or Cone, who didn't allow a hit until the fifth inning on Sunday
night. But after the Yankees gained a stranglehold on this series,
someone was sure to remind everybody else how another team came
back to win the World Series after losing the first two games at
home _ the 1996 Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Don Baylor, the Braves' hitting coach, approached Keith Lockhart
after Atlanta's defeat in Game 1 on Saturday and suggested that
Lockhart stay ready, he might play in Game 2. What Lockhart didn't
know was that Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox planned major lineup
changes for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez had embarrassed the Braves' right-handed
hitters with his slider _ in particular, the second baseman Bret
Boone, the catcher Eddie Perez and the left fielder Gerald
Williams. Knowing that Cone is similar to Hernandez, who throws his
slider from different angles to confoundright-handed hitters, Cox
stacked his lineup with left-handed hitters. Lockhart started at
second in place of Boone, who had 144 starts in the regular season,
Ozzie Guillen was the shortstop instead of Walt Weiss and Greg
Myers opened at catcher rather than Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just throwing it out there,'' Cox said, ``and seeing if
they won't change things.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some risk to Cox's strategy: Guillen and Lockhart are
vastly inferior to Weiss and Boone on defense. But Cox could have
assumed, with justification, that the shortcomings of his
substitute middle infielders would not have manifested themselves.
Kevin Millwood is a fly ball pitcher of the first order, who
averaged 0.88 ground balls for every fly ball this season.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, the Yankees' left fielder, studied videotape of
Millwood on Sunday afternoon, like a student cramming for a final
exam. What he saw was Millwood whipping his fastball 93 to 95 miles
an hour, overpowering hitters before dropping in his sharp
curveball or a slider.
</P>
<P>
   The Kevin Millwood who pitched on Sunday night was nothing like
the pitcher whom Ledee studied. His fastball in the first inning
was 90 to 91 mph, his slider was inconsistent, and he didn't really
use his curveball. He had no weapons with which to finish off the
Yankees' batters. Chuck Knoblauch, the first batter of the game,
fell behind no balls and two strikes and Millwood leaned back and
pumped a high fastball, a neanderthal approach that might have been
effective if he had better stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch slammed a single into left-center field, and time
and again this was Millwood's pattern in the first inning. After
Derek Jeter pulled a single into left field _ the Yankees had first
and second and nobody out _ O'Neill fell behind by no balls and two
strikes and fouled off three two-strike pitches, before he hit a
single to center field, Knoblauch scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams grounded into a double play, Jeter taking third,
and it appeared Millwood might get out of the inning allowing just
the one run. But Tino Martinez fell behind by 1 ball and 2 strikes
and then smashed a line single to left, scoring Jeter. Ledee drew a
walk, and like those before him, Scott Brosius fell behind no balls
and two strikes, before grounding a ball toward the middle, to the
left of Guillen.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, the Braves' regular shortstop, may or may not have
reached the ball; Guillen did not, and Martinez scored as the slow
roller reached center field. The Braves had two hits in all of Game
1, they were facing a tough pitcher with a revamped lineup, and
they were down three runs before their first at-bat. Millwood
required 38 pitches to get through the first inning, and more
telling is the fact that of those, the Yankees' swung and missed
just one time.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood slogged through the second inning, throwing another 18
pitches. But Bernie Williams led off the third inning by falling
behind in the count by 1-2, then bouncing a ball to Lockhart's
right, and past him _ a ball Boone would have easily reached.
Martinez singled and Ledee crushed a double between the outfielders
in left and center, Williams racing home with the Yankees' fourth
run. Cox figured there was no point in waiting for Millwood's spot
in the lineup to come around in the bottom half of the third; Terry
Mulholland relieved Millwood and retired the next two hitters, the
runners holding at second and third.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Cone was next, his hitters' senses dulled by
years of playing in the American League. But he waged a surprising
battle with Mulholland, fouling off five pitches; the Yankees would
foul off 24 pitches in the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Then Cone reached out and poked a ball with the end of his bat,
the pain of imperfect contact slicing through his hands as his
little pop fly spun at Guillen. The shortstop took a couple of
steps to his right, held out his glove, an easy chance _ and he
dropped the ball. Martinez went across home plate to make the score
5-0, and Cox put both hands on the top of his head in frustration,
in a Homer Simpson pose. Guillen and the Braves were booed heavily
as they ran off the field at the end of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be more follies. Jeter doubled to lead off the
fourth, took third on a fly ball and after the Braves intentionally
walked Bernie Williams, the Atlanta infield played back, looking
for a double-play. Sure enough, Martinez grounded to Guillen, who
flipped to Lockhart, who bobbled the ball for a moment before
stepping on second and, in fear of losing the doubleplay, fired the
ball high and wide of the first baseman Ryan Klesko. More boos. The
Yankees now were in command, 6-0, and half their runs were a direct
result of the play of the Braves' middle infield.
</P>
<P>
   Fans would begin quietly fleeing Turner Field and the cold
shortly thereafter, not hanging around to see the outcome of the
only remaining drama of the evening: Could the Braves get a hit off
of Cone?
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander had stymied the Atlanta left-handers with his
split-fingered fastball, and he was so very careful. He threw 35
pitches in the first three innings and only two were on the inside
half of the strike zone. An outside slider to Brian Jordan hung in
the bottom of the first inning and the Braves' cleanup hitter
crushed a high drive to left field, certainly a home run on most
days. But the wind was gusting from left to right and Jordan's fly
fell about five feet short.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked three in the first four innings, but Atlanta had no
hits. When Myers skipped a single through the middle to start the
fifth, the fans roared sarcastically. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
