<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-24 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-24 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS? BRAVES HAVE GOT TO BE, BASED ON THEIR ANEMIC HITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Derek Jeter, who in a moment would bat with the bases
loaded in the eighth inning of a game the Yankees were losing, 1-0,
looked at a spectator in the first row of the box seats next to the
Yankees' dugout and posed a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nervous?'' the young shortstop asked George Steinbrenner on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving no audible reply from his employer, Jeter proceeded to
step into the batter's box and rap a single between shortstop and
third base, tying the game. The Yankees would score three more runs
in the inning and defeat the Atlanta Braves, 4-1, and take a 1-0
lead in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now it should be the Braves who are nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Yankees' 7-2 romp on Sunday night in Game 2, the
Braves are in a perilous position, down two games to none and
heading to New York for the next three games. Hmmm, now where have
we heard that before?
</P>
<P>
   That's it, the Braves' grand scheme is to play this World Series
in the exact opposite pattern as they played the 1996 World Series.
In that one, they beat the Yankees twice at Yankee Stadium and then
went home and lost three games before returning to New York for one
more game and one more loss. Turnabout is fair play, is it not?
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the real world, the Braves are braced by the
reality that they haven't defeated the Yankees in a World Series
encounter in their last six attempts and the Yankees haven't lost a
World Series game in their last 10 late October outings. But the
Braves have even more serious problems than patterns and
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   They can't hit. They have amassed a grand total of 2 hits in 14
innings against the Yankees' starting pitchers, and they have
scored a total of three runs in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a psychological barrier standing in the way
of winning and a pitching barrier positioned in the way of their
hitters is making this a more difficult World Series than the
Braves had envisioned. Not that they planned on breezing past the
Yankees, but they did expect to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Before the World Series began, the Braves said no link existed
between this one and the one they lost in 1996. This team, they
noted, is not the team that lost that Series, so that one should
have no effect on this one. But the Braves still haven't won a game
since Game 2 three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   To have any chance against the Yankees, the Braves knew they had
to hit better than they did in Game 1 and better than they did in
the National League Championship Series against the Mets. But Don
Baylor, the hitting coach, rejected any suggestion that the Braves'
two-hit effort Saturday night was a continuation of their
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in that cold stuff or whatever,'' Baylor said
as the Braves took batting practice on Sunday evening. ``That
wasn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, he said, was Orlando Hernandez, the baffling Cuban,
who allowed one hit, a fourth-inning home run by Chipper Jones, and
struck out 10 in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy pitched good last night; he pitched great,'' Baylor
said. ``We never came close to having an attack. We didn't have
good swings at all. We never were in the good offensive counts,
2-0, 3-1, where he made a mistake. David Cone is going to do pretty
much the same thing as El Duque did _ change speeds, throw his
cutter, his slider.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone did exactly what Hernandez did Saturday night, allowing one
hit in seven innings. But the Braves didn't score against Cone, who
permitted only a leadoff single by Greg Myers in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to change the Braves' fortunes, Bobby Cox, their
manager, made wholesale changes in the lineup. ``After you get two
measly hits,'' Baylor said, ``you better think about something
else.'' They did, and they got five measly hits.
</P>
<P>
   Myers caught in place of Eddie Perez, Keith Lockhart replaced
Bret Boone at second base and Ozzie Guillen played shortstop in
place of Walt Weiss and batted second in place of Boone. Cox
dropped Andruw Jones from sixth to eighth in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he's not swinging good,'' Baylor said of Jones. ``He
realizes it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones didn't swing well from the No. 8 slot either. He popped to
short, grounded into a double play after Myers singled and took a
third strike for the third out after Cone had walked two of the
first three batters in the seventh inning. In the games in New
York, when the designated hitter will bat instead of the pitcher,
Cox could drop Jones even lower, to the No. 9 spot.
</P>
<P>
   Cox explained that with the lineup changes he was trying to
``generate a little offense.'' Brian Jordan, who retained his
cleanup spot in the batting order, said that it was ``unusual for a
World Series to change the lineup so dramatically'' and that the
players who did not find their names in the posted lineup were
``pretty surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jordan added: ``I guess Bobby's trying to mix it up, make
things happen. We only got one or two hits yesterday, so we need to
get something going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves better get a lot going quickly or they could go home
later this week with no more games to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
